WEBVTT

00:00:20.700 --> 00:00:24.760
Frankenstein or The Modern Prometheus by Mary Wollstone-Craftshelly

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:28.060
The Letters

00:00:29.120 --> 00:00:30.360
Letter 1

00:00:31.060 --> 00:00:38.840
To Mrs. Seville, England, St. Petersburg, December 11th, sometime in the 1700s.

00:00:40.040 --> 00:00:47.400
You will rejoice to hear that no disaster has accompanied the commencement of an enterprise which you have regarded with such evil forebodings.

00:00:48.320 --> 00:00:56.200
I arrived here yesterday, and my first task is to assure my dear sister of my welfare and increasing confidence in the success of my undertaking.

00:00:57.040 --> 00:01:08.140
I am already far north of London, and as I walk in the streets of Petersburg, I feel a cold northern breeze play upon my cheeks, which braces my nerves and fills me with delight.

00:01:08.500 --> 00:01:18.000
Do you understand this feeling? This breeze, which has traveled from the regions towards which I am advancing, gives me a foretaste of those icy climbs.

00:01:19.340 --> 00:01:29.380
Inspirited by this wind of promise, my daydreams become more fervent and vivid. I try in vain to be persuaded that the Pole is the seed of frost and desolation.

00:01:29.920 --> 00:01:34.400
It ever presents itself to my imagination as the region of beauty and delight.

00:01:35.500 --> 00:01:43.160
There, Margaret, the sun is forever visible, its broad disk just skirting the horizon and diffusing a perpetual splendor.

00:01:43.980 --> 00:01:49.600
There, for with your leave, my sister, I will put some trust in preceding navigators.

00:01:50.240 --> 00:02:02.960
There, snow and frost are banished, and sailing over a calm sea, we may be wafted to a land surpassing in wonders and in beauty every region hitherto discovered on the habitable globe.

00:02:02.960 --> 00:02:13.200
Its productions and features may be without example, as the phenomena of the heavenly bodies undoubtedly are in those undiscovered solitudes.

00:02:14.220 --> 00:02:18.020
What may not be expected in a country of eternal light?

00:02:18.920 --> 00:02:31.340
I may there discover the wondrous power which attracts the needle, and may regulate a thousand celestial observations that require only this voyage to render their seeming eccentricities consistent forever.

00:02:32.040 --> 00:02:41.800
I shall satiate my ardent curiosity with the sight of a part of the world never before visited, and may tread a land never before imprinted by the foot of man.

00:02:43.500 --> 00:03:00.480
These are my enticements, and they are sufficient to conquer all fear of danger or death, and to induce me to commence this laborious voyage with the joy a child feels when he embarks in a little boat with his holiday mates on an expedition of discovery of his native river.

00:03:00.480 --> 00:03:28.560
But supposing all these conjectures to be false, you cannot contest the inestimable benefit which I shall confer on all mankind through the last generation by discovering a passage near the pole to those countries to reach which, at present, so many months are requisite, or by ascertaining the secret of the magnet which, if at all possible, can only be affected by an undertaking such as mine.

00:03:29.620 --> 00:03:49.500
These reflections have dispelled the agitation with which I began my letter, and I feel my heart glow with an enthusiasm which elevates me to heaven, for nothing contributes so much to tranquilize the mind as a steady purpose, a point on which the soul may fix its intellectual eye.

00:03:49.500 --> 00:04:04.200
This expedition has been the favorite dream of my early years. I have read with ardor the accounts of the various voyages which have been made in the prospect of arriving at the North Pacific Ocean through the seas which surround the pole.

00:04:04.980 --> 00:04:13.260
You may remember that a history of all the voyages made for purposes of discovery composed the whole of our good Uncle Thomas's library.

00:04:13.260 --> 00:04:33.920
My education was neglected, yet I was passionately fond of reading. These volumes were my study day and night, and my familiarity with them increased that regret which I had felt as a child on learning that my father's dying injunction had forbidden my uncle to allow me to embark in a seafaring life.

00:04:35.180 --> 00:04:57.200
These visions faded when I perused, for the first time, those poets whose effusions entranced my soul and lifted it to heaven. I also became a poet, and for one year lived in a paradise of my own creation. I imagined that I also might obtain a niche in the temple where the names of Homer and Shakespeare are consecrated.

00:04:57.940 --> 00:05:10.720
You are well acquainted with my failure and how I heavily bore the disappointment. But just at that time I inherited the fortune of my cousin, and my thoughts were turned into the channel of their earlier bent.

00:05:12.100 --> 00:05:34.220
Six years have passed since I resolved on my present undertaking. I can even now remember the hour from which I dedicated myself to this great enterprise. I commenced by a nearing my body to hardship. I accompanied the whale fishers on several expeditions to the North Sea. I voluntarily endured cold, famine, thirst, and want of sleep.

00:05:34.220 --> 00:05:49.180
I often worked harder than the common sailors during the day, and devoted my nights to the study of mathematics, the theory of medicine, and those branches of physical science from which a naval adventurer might derive the greatest practical advantage.

00:05:49.180 --> 00:06:09.380
Twice I actually hired myself as an undermate in a Greenland whaler and acquitted myself to admiration. I must own I felt a little proud when my captain offered me the second dignity in the vessel and entreated me to remain with the greatest earnestness so valuable did he consider my services.

00:06:09.380 --> 00:06:23.020
And now, dear Margaret, do I not deserve to accomplish some great purpose? My life might have been passed in ease and luxury, but I preferred glory to every enticement that wealth placed in my path.

00:06:23.720 --> 00:06:42.280
Oh, that some encouraging voice would answer in the affirmative. My courage and my resolution is firm, but my hopes fluctuate, and my spirits are often depressed. I am about to proceed on a long and difficult voyage, the emergencies of which will demand all my fortitude.

00:06:42.280 --> 00:07:03.340
I am required not only to raise the spirits of others, but sometimes to sustain my own, when theirs are failing. This is the most favorable period for travelling in Russia. They fly quickly over the snow in their sledges, the motion is pleasant and, in my opinion, far more agreeable than that of an English stagecoach.

00:07:03.340 --> 00:07:18.360
The cold is not excessive, if you are wrapped in furs, a dress which I have already adopted, for there is a great difference between walking the deck and remaining seated motionless for hours, when no exercise prevents the blood from actually freezing in your veins.

00:07:19.100 --> 00:07:39.680
I have no ambition to lose my life on that post road between St. Petersburg and Archangel. I shall depart for the latter town in a fortnight or three weeks, and my intention is to hire a ship there, which can easily be done by paying the insurance for the owner, and to engage as many sailors as I think necessary among those who are accustomed to the whale fishing.

00:07:40.360 --> 00:08:01.260
I do not intend to sail until the month of June, and when shall I return? Dear sister, how can I answer this question? If I succeed, many, many months, perhaps years, will pass before you and I may meet. If I fail, you will see me again soon, or never.

00:08:02.340 --> 00:08:16.400
Farewell, my dear, excellent Margaret. Heaven shower down blessings on you and save me, that I may again and again testify my gratitude for all your love and kindness, your affectionate brother, R. Walton.

00:08:18.560 --> 00:08:27.640
Letter 2. To Mrs. Seville, England. Archangel, 28th March, sometime in the 1700s.

00:08:28.360 --> 00:08:48.400
How slowly the time passes here, encompassed as I am by frost and snow, yet a second step is taken toward my enterprise. I have hired a vessel, and am occupied in collecting my sailors. Those whom I have already engaged appear to be men on whom I can depend, and are certainly possessed of dauntless courage.

00:08:49.980 --> 00:09:07.280
But I have one want, which I have never yet been able to satisfy, and the absence of the object of which I now feel as a most severe evil, I have no friend, Margaret. When I am glowing with the enthusiasm of success, there will be none to participate my joy.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:27.500
If I am assailed by disappointment, no one will endeavor to sustain me in dejection. I shall commit my thoughts to paper, it is true, but that is a poor medium for the communication of feeling. I desire the company of a man who could sympathize with me, whose eyes would reply to mine.

00:09:27.500 --> 00:09:45.680
You may deem me romantic, my dear sister, but I bitterly feel the want of a friend. I have no one near me, gentle yet courageous, possessed of a cultivated as well as of a capacious mind, whose tastes are like my own, to approve or amend my plans.

00:09:45.680 --> 00:10:06.740
How would such a friend repair the faults of your poor brother? I am too ardent in execution, and too impatient of difficulties. But it is a still greater evil to me that I am self-educated. For the first fourteen years of my life I rammed wild on a common, and read nothing but our Uncle Thomas's books of voyages.

00:10:07.360 --> 00:10:25.620
At that age I became acquainted with the celebrated poets of our own country, but it was only when it had ceased to be in my power to derive its most important benefits from such a conviction that I perceived the necessity of becoming acquainted with more languages than that of my native country.

00:10:25.620 --> 00:10:51.820
Now I am twenty-eight, and in reality more illiterate than many schoolboys of fifteen. It is true that I have thought more, and my daydreams are more extended and magnificent, but they want, as the painters call it, keeping, and I greatly need a friend who would have sense enough not to despise me as a romantic, and affection enough for me to endeavor to regulate my mind.

00:10:52.580 --> 00:11:09.780
Well, these are useless complaints. I shall surely find no friend on the wide ocean, nor even hear an archangel among merchants and seamen. Yet some feelings, unallied to the dross of human nature, beat even in these rugged bosoms.

00:11:09.780 --> 00:11:33.800
My lieutenant, for instance, is a man of wonderful courage and enterprise. He is madly desirous of glory, or rather, to word my phrase more characteristically, of advancement in his profession. He is an Englishman, and in the midst of national and professional prejudices, unsoftened by cultivation, retains some of the noblest endowments of humanity.

00:11:35.060 --> 00:11:53.880
I first became acquainted with him on board a whale vessel. Finding that he was unemployed in this city, I easily engaged him to assist in my enterprise. The master is a person of excellent disposition, and is remarkable in the ship for his gentleness and the mildness of his discipline.

00:11:53.880 --> 00:12:16.980
This circumstance, added to his well-known integrity and dauntless courage, made me very desirous to engage him. A youth passed in solitude. My best years spent under your gentle and feminine fosterage has so refined the groundwork of my character that I cannot overcome an intense distaste to the usual brutality exercised on board ship.

00:12:16.980 --> 00:12:32.320
I have never believed it to be necessary, and when I heard of a mariner, equally noted for his kindliness of heart and the respect and obedience paid to him by his crew, I felt myself peculiarly fortunate in being able to secure his services.

00:12:32.320 --> 00:12:51.940
I heard of him first in rather a romantic manner, from a lady who owes to him the happiness of her life. This, briefly, is his story. Some years ago he loved a young Russian lady of moderate fortune, and having amassed a considerable sum in prize money, the father of the girl consented to the match.

00:12:51.940 --> 00:13:17.860
He saw his mistress once before the destined ceremony, but she was bathed in tears and throwing herself at his feet, and treated him to spare her, confessing at the same time that she loved another, but that he was poor and that her father would never consent to the union. My generous friend reassured the suppliant, and on being informed of the name of her lover, instantly abandoned his pursuit.

00:13:18.500 --> 00:13:36.540
He had already bought a farm with his money, on which he had designed to pass the remainder of his life, but he bestowed the whole on his rival, together with the remains of his prize money to purchase stock, and then himself solicited the young woman's father to consent to her marriage with her lover.

00:13:36.540 --> 00:13:51.600
But the old man decidedly refused, thinking himself bound in honour to my friend, who, when he found the father inexorable, quitted his country, nor returned until he heard that his former mistress was married according to her inclinations.

00:13:52.320 --> 00:14:11.960
What a noble fellow, you will exclaim! He is so, but then he is wholly uneducated. He is as silent as a Turk, and a kind of ignorant carelessness attends him, which, while it renders his conduct the more astonishing, detracts from the interest and sympathy which otherwise he would command.

00:14:12.840 --> 00:14:32.060
Yet do not suppose, because I complain a little, or because I can conceive a consolation for my toils, which I may never know, that I am wavering in my resolutions. Those are as fixed as fate, and my voyage is only now delayed until the weather shall permit my embarkation.

00:14:32.060 --> 00:14:53.340
The winter has been dreadfully severe, but the spring promises well, and it is considered as a remarkably early season, so that perhaps I may sail sooner than I expected. I shall do nothing rashly. You know me sufficiently to confide in my prudence and considerateness whenever the safety of others is committed to my care.

00:14:54.220 --> 00:15:08.460
I cannot describe to you my sensations on the near prospect of my undertaking. It is impossible to communicate to you a conception of the trembling sensation, half pleasurable and half fearful, with which I am preparing to depart.

00:15:09.020 --> 00:15:27.680
I am going to unexplored regions, to the land of mist and snow, but I shall kill no albatross. Therefore do not be alarmed for my safety, or if I should come back to you as worn and woeful as the ancient mariner. You will smile at my allusion, but I will disclose a secret.

00:15:28.740 --> 00:15:43.380
I have often attributed my attachment to, my passion and enthusiasm for, the dangerous mysteries of ocean, to that production of the most imaginative of modern poets. There is something at work in my soul which I do not understand.

00:15:43.380 --> 00:16:04.020
I am practically industrious, painstaking, a workman to execute with perseverance and labor, but besides this there is a love for the marvelous, a belief in the marvelous, intertwined in all my projects which hurries me out of the common pathways of men, even to the wild sea and unvisited regions I am about to explore.

00:16:04.620 --> 00:16:21.400
But to return to dearer considerations, shall I meet you again, after having traversed immense seas and returned by most southern Cape of Africa or America? I dare not expect such success, yet I cannot bear to look on the reverse of the picture.

00:16:22.500 --> 00:16:41.340
Continue for the present to write to me by every opportunity. I may receive your letters on some occasions when I need them most to support my spirits. I love you very tenderly. Remember me with affection, should you never hear from me again. Your affectionate brother, Robert Walton.

00:16:43.060 --> 00:16:51.660
Letter 3. To Mrs. Seville, England. July 7th. Sometime in the 1700s.

00:16:51.660 --> 00:17:11.300
My dear sister, I write a few lines in haste to say that I am safe and well advanced on my voyage. This letter will reach England by a merchantman now on its homeward voyage from Archangel. More fortunate than I, who may not see my native land perhaps for many years, I am however in good spirits.

00:17:11.300 --> 00:17:23.280
My men are bold and apparently firm of purpose, nor do the floating sheets of ice that continually pass us, indicating the dangers of the region toward which we are advancing, appear to dismay them.

00:17:24.020 --> 00:17:41.680
We have already reached a very high latitude, but it is the height of summer, and although not so warm as in England, the southern gales which blow us speedily towards those shores which I so ardently desire to attain, breathe a degree of renovating warmth which I had not expected.

00:17:42.760 --> 00:17:59.160
No incidents have hitherto befallen us that would make a figure in a letter. One or two stiff gales and the springing of a leak are accidents which experienced navigators scarcely remember to record, and I shall be well content if nothing worse happened to us during our voyage.

00:17:59.980 --> 00:18:15.560
Adieu, my dear Margaret. Be assured that for my own sake, as well as yours, I will not rashly encounter danger. I will be cool, persevering, and prudent. But success shall crown my endeavours. Wherefore not?

00:18:15.560 --> 00:18:44.240
Thus far I have gone, tracing a secure way over the pathless seas, the very stars themselves being witnesses and testimonies of my triumph. Why not still proceed over the untamed yet obedient element? What can stop the determined heart and resolved will of man? My swelling heart involuntarily pours itself out thus. But I must finish. Heaven bless my beloved sister. R. W.

00:18:47.420 --> 00:18:54.560
Letter four. To Mrs. Seville, England, August 5th, sometime in the 1700s.

00:18:56.680 --> 00:19:05.920
So strange an accident has happened to us that I cannot forbear recording it, although it is very probable that you will see me before these papers can come into your possession.

00:19:06.820 --> 00:19:29.280
Last Monday, July 31st, we were nearly surrounded by ice, which closed in the ship on all sides, scarcely leaving the sea room in which she floated. Our situation was somewhat dangerous, especially as we were compassed round by a very thick fog. We accordingly lay to, hoping that some change would take place in the atmosphere and weather.

00:19:30.340 --> 00:19:52.360
About two o'clock the mist cleared away and, we beheld, stretched out in every direction vast and irregular plains of ice, which seemed to have no end. Some of my comrades groaned, and my own mind began to grow watchful with anxious thoughts, when a strange sight suddenly attracted our attention and diverted our solicitude from our situation.

00:19:53.300 --> 00:20:11.820
We perceived a low carriage, fixed on a sledge and drawn by dogs, pass on towards the north, at the distance of half a mile. A being which had the shape of a man, but apparently of gigantic stature, sat in the sledge and guided the dogs.

00:20:11.820 --> 00:20:33.900
We watched the rapid progress of the traveller with our telescopes until he was lost among the distant inequalities of the ice. This appearance excited our unqualified wonder. We were, as we believed, many hundred miles from any land, but this apparition seemed to denote that it was not, in reality, so distant as we had supposed.

00:20:34.660 --> 00:20:48.940
Shut in, however, by ice, it was impossible to follow his track, which we had observed with the greatest attention. About two hours after this occurrence we heard the ground sea, and before night the ice broke and freed our ship.

00:20:49.720 --> 00:21:03.580
We, however, lay to until the morning, fearing to encounter in the dark those large, loose masses which float about after the breaking up of ice. I profited of this time to rest for a few hours.

00:21:04.680 --> 00:21:23.300
In the morning, however, as soon as it was light, I went upon deck and found all the sailors busy on one side of the vessel, apparently talking to someone in the seas. It was, in fact, a sledge, like that which we had seen before, which had drifted towards us in the night on a large fragment of ice.

00:21:23.300 --> 00:21:45.540
Only one dog remained alive, but there was a human being within it whom the sailors were persuading to enter the vessel. He was not, as the other traveller seemed to be, a savage inhabitant of some undiscovered island, but a European. When I appeared on deck, the master said, Here is our captain, and he will not allow you to perish on the open sea.

00:21:46.620 --> 00:21:58.500
On perceiving me, the stranger addressed me in English, although with a foreign accent. Before I come on board your vessel, said he, will you have the kindness to inform me whether you are bound?

00:21:59.460 --> 00:22:25.140
You may conceive my astonishment on hearing such a question addressed to me from a man on the brink of destruction, and to whom I should have supposed that my vessel would have been a resource which he would not have exchanged for the most precious wealth the earth can afford. I replied, however, that we were on a voyage of discovery toward the northern pole. Upon hearing this, he appeared satisfied and consented to come on board.

00:22:26.020 --> 00:22:49.140
Good God, Margaret, if you had seen the man who thus capitulated for his safety, your surprise would have been boundless. His limbs were nearly frozen, and his body dreadfully emaciated by fatigue and suffering. I never saw a man in so wretched a condition. We attempted to carry him into the cabin, but as soon as he had quitted the fresh air he fainted.

00:22:49.920 --> 00:23:11.620
We accordingly brought him back to the deck, and restored him to animation by rubbing him with brandy and forcing him to swallow a small quantity. As soon as he showed signs of life, we wrapped him up in blankets and placed him near the chimney of the kitchen stove. By slow degrees he recovered and ate a little soup, which restored him wonderfully.

00:23:13.100 --> 00:23:28.400
Two days passed in this manner before he was able to speak, and I often feared that his sufferings had deprived him of understanding. When he had in some measure recovered, I removed him to my own cabin and attended on him as much as my duty would permit.

00:23:29.060 --> 00:23:51.380
I never saw a more interesting creature. His eyes have generally an expression of wildness and even madness, but there are moments when, if anyone performs an act of kindness towards him, or does him any the most trifling service, his whole countenance is lighted up, as it were, with a beam of benevolence and sweetness that I never saw equalled.

00:23:51.380 --> 00:24:00.360
But he is generally melancholy and despairing, and sometimes he gnashes his teeth, as if impatient of the weight of woes that oppresses him.

00:24:01.080 --> 00:24:17.560
When my guest was a little recovered, I had great trouble to keep off the men who wished to ask him a thousand questions, but I would not allow him to be tormented by their idle curiosity in a state of body and mind whose restoration evidently depended upon entire repose.

00:24:17.560 --> 00:24:30.980
Once, however, the lieutenant asked why he had come so far upon the ice in so strange a vehicle. His countenance instantly assumed an aspect of the deepest gloom, and he replied,

00:24:31.360 --> 00:24:33.560
To seek one who fled from me.

00:24:34.600 --> 00:24:38.220
And did the man whom you pursued travel in the same fashion?

00:24:39.400 --> 00:24:40.000
Yes.

00:24:41.580 --> 00:24:49.640
Then I fancy we have seen him, for the day before we picked you up we saw some dogs drawing a sledge with a man in it across the ice.

00:24:51.180 --> 00:24:59.100
This aroused the stranger's attention, and he asked a multitude of questions concerning the route which the demon, as he called him, had pursued.

00:24:59.740 --> 00:25:02.500
Soon after, when he was alone with me, he said,

00:25:03.300 --> 00:25:11.480
I have doubtless excited your curiosity, as well as that of these good people, but you are too considerate to make inquiries.

00:25:13.180 --> 00:25:20.780
Certainly, it would indeed be very impertinent and inhuman in me to trouble you with any inquisitiveness of mine.

00:25:22.000 --> 00:25:28.180
And yet you rescued me from a strange and perilous situation, you have benevolently restored me to life.

00:25:29.320 --> 00:25:35.200
Soon after this he inquired if I thought that the breaking up of the ice had destroyed the other sledge.

00:25:36.020 --> 00:25:49.540
I replied that I could not answer with any degree of certainty, for the ice had not broken until near midnight, and the traveller might have arrived at a place of safety before that time, but of this I could not judge.

00:25:50.180 --> 00:25:54.760
From this time a new spirit of life animated the decaying frame of the stranger.

00:25:55.420 --> 00:26:01.360
He manifested the greatest eagerness to be upon deck to watch for the sledge, which had before appeared.

00:26:01.960 --> 00:26:08.040
But I have persuaded him to remain in the cabin, for he is far too weak to sustain the rawness of the atmosphere.

00:26:08.840 --> 00:26:15.800
I have promised that someone should watch for him, and give him instant notice if any new object should appear in sight.

00:26:16.700 --> 00:26:21.500
Such is my journal of what relates to this strange occurrence up to the present day.

00:26:22.180 --> 00:26:30.460
The stranger has gradually improved in health, but is very silent and appears uneasy when anyone except myself enters his cabin.

00:26:31.300 --> 00:26:41.020
Yet his manners are so conciliating and gentle that the sailors are all interested in him, although they have had very little communication with him.

00:26:41.020 --> 00:26:49.400
For my own part, I begin to love him as a brother, and his constant and deep grief fills me with sympathy and compassion.

00:26:50.320 --> 00:26:56.620
He must have been a noble creature in his better days, being even now in wreck so attractive and amiable.

00:26:57.580 --> 00:27:02.600
I said in one of my letters, my dear Margaret, that I should find no friend on the wide ocean.

00:27:02.600 --> 00:27:11.820
Yet I have found a man who, before his spirit had been broken by misery, I should have been happy to have possessed as the brother of my heart.

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:19.020
I shall continue my journal concerning the stranger at intervals, should I have any fresh incidents to record.

00:27:25.320 --> 00:27:28.100
My affection for my guest increases every day.

00:27:28.100 --> 00:27:33.080
He excites at once my admiration and my pity to an astonishing degree.

00:27:33.900 --> 00:27:39.140
How can I see so noble a creature destroyed by misery without feeling the most poignant grief?

00:27:39.840 --> 00:27:51.900
He is so gentle, yet so wise, his mind is so cultivated, and when he speaks, although his words are culled with the choicest art, yet they flow with rapidity and unparalleled eloquence.

00:27:51.900 --> 00:28:00.000
He is now much recovered from his illness, and is continually on the deck, apparently watching for the sledge that preceded his own.

00:28:01.080 --> 00:28:10.080
Yet, although unhappy, he is not so utterly occupied by his own misery, but that he interests himself deeply in the projects of others.

00:28:10.660 --> 00:28:15.760
He has frequently conversed with me on mine, which I have communicated to him without disguise.

00:28:15.760 --> 00:28:25.520
He entered attentively into all my arguments in favour of my eventual success, and into every minute detail of the measures I had taken to secure it.

00:28:26.380 --> 00:28:34.680
I was easily led by the sympathy which he evinced to use the language of my heart, to give utterance to the burning ardour of my soul,

00:28:34.700 --> 00:28:44.720
and to say, with all the fervour that warmed me, how gladly I would sacrifice my fortune, my existence, my every hope, to the furtherance of my enterprise.

00:28:45.500 --> 00:28:58.200
One man's life or death were but a small price to pay for the acquirement of the knowledge which I sought, for the dominion I should acquire and transmit over the elemental foes of our race.

00:28:59.300 --> 00:29:07.320
As I spoke, a dark gloom spread over my listener's countenance. At first, I perceived that he tried to suppress his emotion.

00:29:07.320 --> 00:29:16.560
He placed his hands before his eyes, and my voice quivered and failed me as I beheld tears trickle fast from beneath his fingers.

00:29:17.440 --> 00:29:24.080
A groan burst from his heaving breast. I paused, at length he spoke in broken accents.

00:29:25.200 --> 00:29:32.260
Unhappy man, do you share my madness? Have you drunk also of the intoxicating draught?

00:29:32.260 --> 00:29:37.960
Hear me, let me reveal my tale, and you will dash the cup from your lips.

00:29:39.940 --> 00:29:43.700
Such words, you may imagine, strongly excited my curiosity.

00:29:44.940 --> 00:29:56.060
But the paroxysm of grief that had seized the stranger overcame his weakened powers, and many hours of repose and tranquil conversation were necessary to restore his composure.

00:29:56.840 --> 00:30:09.700
Having conquered the violence of his feelings, he appeared to despise himself for being the slave of passion, and quelling the dark tyranny of despair, he led me again to converse concerning myself personally.

00:30:10.280 --> 00:30:18.000
He asked me the history of my earlier years. The tale was quickly told, but it awakened various trains of reflection.

00:30:18.760 --> 00:30:33.120
I spoke of my desire of finding a friend, of my thirst for a more intimate sympathy with a fellow mind than had ever fallen to my lot, and expressed my conviction that a man could boast of little happiness who did not enjoy this blessing.

00:30:34.260 --> 00:30:46.440
I agree with you, replied the stranger. We are unfashioned creatures, but half made up, if one wiser, better, dearer than ourselves, such a friend ought to be.

00:30:47.260 --> 00:30:51.460
Do not lend his aid to perfectionate our weak and faulty natures.

00:30:52.440 --> 00:30:59.340
I once had a friend, the most noble of human creatures, and am entitled therefore to judge respecting friendship.

00:30:59.340 --> 00:31:10.520
You have hope and the world before you, and have no cause for despair, but I have lost everything and cannot begin life anew.

00:31:11.620 --> 00:31:19.440
As he said this, his countenance became expressive of a calm, settled grief that touched me to the heart.

00:31:20.660 --> 00:31:23.740
But he was silent and presently retired to his cabin.

00:31:25.040 --> 00:31:32.300
Even broken in spirit as he is, no one can feel more deeply than he does the beauties of nature.

00:31:33.200 --> 00:31:42.520
The starry sky, the sea, and every sight afforded by these wonderful regions seems still to have the power of elevating his soul from earth.

00:31:43.340 --> 00:31:49.840
Such a man has a double existence. He may suffer misery and be overwhelmed by disappointments.

00:31:49.840 --> 00:32:00.580
Yet, when he has retired into himself, he will be like a celestial spirit that has a halo around him, within whose circle no grief or folly ventures.

00:32:02.080 --> 00:32:09.100
Will you smile at the enthusiasm I express concerning this divine wanderer? You would not if you saw him.

00:32:09.720 --> 00:32:16.160
You have been tutored and refined by books and retirement from the world, and you are therefore somewhat fastidious.

00:32:16.160 --> 00:32:22.940
But this only renders you the more fit to appreciate the extraordinary merits of this wonderful man.

00:32:24.040 --> 00:32:34.120
Sometimes I have endeavoured to discover what quality it is which he possesses that elevates him so immeasurably above any other person I ever knew.

00:32:34.120 --> 00:32:46.780
I believe it to be an intuitive discernment, a quick but never failing power of judgment, a penetration into the causes of things, unequalled for clearness and precision,

00:32:47.620 --> 00:32:54.920
and to this a facility of expression and a voice whose varied intonations are soul-subduing music.

00:32:56.640 --> 00:33:00.120
August 19th, sometime in the 1700s.

00:33:01.260 --> 00:33:03.180
Yesterday the stranger said to me,

00:33:04.020 --> 00:33:09.840
You may easily perceive, Captain Walton, that I have suffered great and unparalleled misfortunes.

00:33:10.420 --> 00:33:18.140
I had determined at one time that the memory of these evils should die with me, but you have won me to alter my determination.

00:33:19.180 --> 00:33:28.880
You seek for knowledge and wisdom, as I once did, and I ardently hope that the gratification of your wishes may not be a serpent to sting you, as mine has been.

00:33:29.800 --> 00:33:42.380
I do not know that the relation of my disasters will be useful to you, yet when I reflect that you are pursuing the same course, exposing yourself to the same dangers which have rendered me what I am,

00:33:42.780 --> 00:33:52.360
I imagine that you may deduce an apt moral from my tale, one that may direct you if you succeed in your undertaking and console you in case of failure.

00:33:53.760 --> 00:33:57.660
Prepare to hear of occurrences which are usually deemed marvellous.

00:33:57.660 --> 00:34:05.040
Were we among the tamer scenes of nature, I might fear to encounter your unbelief, perhaps your ridicule.

00:34:05.740 --> 00:34:14.760
But many things will appear possible in these wild and mysterious regions which would provoke the laughter of those unacquainted with the ever varied powers of nature.

00:34:15.660 --> 00:34:24.500
Nor can I doubt but that my tale conveys in its series internal evidence of the truth of the events of which it is composed.

00:34:25.980 --> 00:34:36.720
You may easily imagine that I was much gratified by the offered communication, yet I could not endure that he should renew his grief by a recital of his misfortunes.

00:34:37.200 --> 00:34:47.200
I felt the greatest eagerness to hear the promised narrative, partly from curiosity and partly from a strong desire to ameliorate his fate, if it were in my power.

00:34:47.640 --> 00:34:50.080
I expressed these feelings in my answer.

00:34:51.500 --> 00:35:03.440
I thank you, he replied, for your sympathy, but it is useless. My fate is nearly fulfilled. I wait but for one event, and then I shall repose in peace.

00:35:04.360 --> 00:35:13.180
I understand your feeling, continued he, perceiving that I wished to interrupt him. But you are mistaken, my friend, if thus you will allow me to name you.

00:35:13.180 --> 00:35:20.800
Nothing can alter my destiny. Listen to my history, and you will perceive how irrevocably it is determined.

00:35:22.460 --> 00:35:27.540
He then told me that he would commence his narrative the next day when I should be at leisure.

00:35:27.540 --> 00:35:42.840
This promise drew for me the warmest thanks. I have resolved every night, when I am not imperatively occupied by my duties, to record, as nearly as possible in his own words, what he has related during the day.

00:35:42.840 --> 00:35:59.320
If I should be engaged, I will at least make notes. This manuscript will doubtless afford you the greatest pleasure, but to me, who know him, and who hear it from his own lips, with what interest and sympathy shall I read it in some future day?

00:35:59.320 --> 00:36:18.840
Even now, as I commence my task, his full-toned voice swells in my ears. His lustrous eyes dwell on me with all their melancholy sweetness. I see his thin hand raised in animation, while the lineaments of his face are irradiated by the soul within.

00:36:20.280 --> 00:36:28.460
Strange and harrowing must be his story. Frightful the storm which embraced the gallant vessel on its course and wrecked it thus.

00:36:49.430 --> 00:36:54.960
I am by birth a Genovese, and my family is one of the most distinguished of that Republic.

00:36:55.760 --> 00:37:01.500
My ancestors had been for many years counselors and syndics, and my father had filled several

00:37:01.500 --> 00:37:06.980
public situations with honor and reputation. He was respected by all who knew him for his

00:37:06.980 --> 00:37:12.960
integrity and indefatigable attention to public business. He passed his younger days perpetually

00:37:12.960 --> 00:37:17.780
occupied by the affairs of his country. A variety of circumstances had prevented his

00:37:17.780 --> 00:37:22.620
marrying early, nor was it until the decline of life that he had become a husband and the

00:37:22.620 --> 00:37:28.840
father of a family. As the circumstances of his marriage illustrate his character, I cannot

00:37:28.840 --> 00:37:34.120
refrain from relating them. One of his most intimate friends was a merchant who, from

00:37:34.120 --> 00:37:39.860
a flourishing state, fell through numerous mischances into poverty. This man, whose name

00:37:39.860 --> 00:37:44.720
was Beaufort, was of a proud and unbending disposition, and could not bear to live in

00:37:44.720 --> 00:37:48.780
poverty and oblivion in the same country where he had formerly been distinguished for his

00:37:48.780 --> 00:37:54.480
rank and magnificence. Having paid his debts, therefore, in the most honorable manner, he

00:37:54.480 --> 00:37:59.660
retreated with his daughter to the town of Lucerne, where he lived unknown and in wretchedness.

00:38:00.560 --> 00:38:05.860
My father loved Beaufort with the truest friendship, and was deeply grieved by his retreat in these

00:38:05.860 --> 00:38:11.600
unfortunate circumstances. He bitterly deplored the false pride which led his friend to a

00:38:11.600 --> 00:38:16.920
conduct so little worthy of the affection that united them. He lost no time in endeavoring

00:38:16.920 --> 00:38:21.780
to seek him out, with the hope of persuading him to begin the world again through his credit

00:38:21.780 --> 00:38:27.460
and assistance. Beaufort had taken effectual measures to conceal himself, and it was ten

00:38:27.460 --> 00:38:33.120
months before my father discovered his abode. Overjoyed at this discovery, he hastened to

00:38:33.120 --> 00:38:38.660
the house which was situated in a mean street near the Reuss. But when he entered, misery

00:38:38.660 --> 00:38:44.420
and despair alone welcomed him. Beaufort had saved but a very small sum of money from the

00:38:44.420 --> 00:38:48.780
lack of his fortunes, but it was sufficient to provide him with sustenance for some months,

00:38:49.080 --> 00:38:53.500
and in the meantime he hoped to procure some respectable employment in a merchant's house.

00:38:54.260 --> 00:38:59.820
The interval was, consequently, spent in inaction. His grief only became more deep and rankling

00:38:59.820 --> 00:39:05.420
when he had leisure for reflection, and at length it took so fast hold of his mind that

00:39:05.420 --> 00:39:09.860
at the end of three months he lay on a bed of sickness incapable of any exertion.

00:39:10.880 --> 00:39:15.520
His daughter attended him with the greatest tenderness, but she saw with despair that

00:39:15.520 --> 00:39:20.260
their little fund was rapidly decreasing, and that there was no other prospect of support.

00:39:20.900 --> 00:39:25.980
But Carolyn Beaufort possessed a mind of an uncommon mold, and her courage rose to support

00:39:25.980 --> 00:39:32.100
her in her adversity. She procured plain work, she plated straw, and by various means contrived

00:39:32.100 --> 00:39:34.880
to earn a pittance scarcely sufficient to support life.

00:39:35.800 --> 00:39:40.840
Several months passed in this manner. Her father grew worse, her time was more entirely

00:39:40.840 --> 00:39:46.480
occupied in attending him, her means of subsistence decreased, and in the tenth month her father

00:39:46.480 --> 00:39:52.080
died in her arms, leaving her an orphan and a beggar. This last blow overcame her, and

00:39:52.080 --> 00:39:57.700
she knelt by Beaufort's coffin, weeping bitterly, when my father entered the chamber. He came

00:39:57.700 --> 00:40:03.060
like a protecting spirit to the poor girl who committed herself to his care, and after

00:40:03.060 --> 00:40:07.860
the interment of his friend he conducted her to Geneva and placed her under the protection

00:40:07.860 --> 00:40:12.260
of a relation. Two years after this event Carolyn became his wife.

00:40:13.800 --> 00:40:18.640
There was a considerable difference between the ages of my parents, but this circumstance

00:40:18.640 --> 00:40:23.740
seemed to unite them only closer in bonds of devoted affection. There was a sense of

00:40:23.740 --> 00:40:27.860
justice in my father's upright mind which rendered it unnecessary that he should approve

00:40:27.860 --> 00:40:33.420
highly to love strongly. Perhaps during former years he had suffered from the late discovered

00:40:33.420 --> 00:40:38.720
unworthiness of one beloved and so was disposed to set a greater value on tried worth.

00:40:39.700 --> 00:40:43.960
There was a show of gratitude and worship in his attachment to my mother, differing

00:40:43.960 --> 00:40:48.720
wholly from the doting fondness of age, for it was inspired by reverence for her virtues

00:40:48.720 --> 00:40:54.620
and a desire to be the means of, in some degree, recompensing her for the sorrows she had endured,

00:40:54.620 --> 00:41:00.580
but which gave inexpressible grace to his behavior to her. Everything was made to yield

00:41:00.580 --> 00:41:06.660
to her wishes and her convenience. He strove to shelter her, as a fair exotic as sheltered

00:41:06.660 --> 00:41:11.620
by the gardener, from every rougher wind and to surround her with all that could tend to

00:41:11.620 --> 00:41:17.060
excite pleasurable emotion in her soft and benevolent mind. Her health, and even the

00:41:17.060 --> 00:41:21.560
tranquility of her hitherto constant spirit, had been shaken by what she had gone through.

00:41:22.580 --> 00:41:27.540
During the two years that it elapsed, previous to their marriage, my father had gradually

00:41:27.540 --> 00:41:32.000
relinquished all his public functions, and immediately after their union they sought

00:41:32.000 --> 00:41:36.480
the pleasant climate of Italy and the change of scene and interest attendant on a tour

00:41:36.480 --> 00:41:40.380
through that land of wonders as a restorative for her weakened frame.

00:41:43.060 --> 00:41:48.920
From Italy they visited Germany and France. I, their eldest child, was born at Naples

00:41:48.920 --> 00:41:53.800
and as an infant accompanied them in their rambles. I remained for several years their

00:41:53.800 --> 00:41:58.600
only child. Much as they were attached to each other, they seemed to draw inexhaustible

00:41:58.600 --> 00:42:04.100
stores of affection from a very mine of love to bestow them upon me. My mother's tender

00:42:04.100 --> 00:42:09.160
caresses and my father's smile of benevolent pleasure while regarding me are my first recollections.

00:42:10.180 --> 00:42:15.180
I was their plaything and their idol, and something better, their child, the innocent

00:42:15.180 --> 00:42:20.000
and helpless creature bestowed upon them by Heaven, whom to bring up to good and whose

00:42:20.000 --> 00:42:25.140
future lot it was in their hands to direct to happiness or misery according as they fulfilled

00:42:25.140 --> 00:42:29.940
their duties toward me. With this deep consciousness of what they owed towards the being to which

00:42:29.940 --> 00:42:34.940
they had given life, added to the active spirit of tenderness that animated both, it may be

00:42:34.940 --> 00:42:39.660
imagined that while during every hour of my infant life I received a lesson of patience,

00:42:39.660 --> 00:42:45.220
of charity and of self-control, and was so guided by a silken cord that all seemed but

00:42:45.220 --> 00:42:46.980
one train of enjoyment to me.

00:42:48.080 --> 00:42:52.800
For a long time I was their only care. My mother had much desired to have a daughter,

00:42:53.100 --> 00:42:58.840
but I continued their single offspring. When I was about five years old, while making an

00:42:58.840 --> 00:43:03.320
excursion beyond the frontiers of Italy, they had passed a week on the shores of the Lake

00:43:03.320 --> 00:43:08.040
of Como. Their benevolent disposition often made them enter the cottages of the poor.

00:43:08.040 --> 00:43:13.360
This, to my mother, was more than a duty, it was a necessity, a passion, remembering

00:43:13.360 --> 00:43:18.660
what she had suffered and how she had been relieved. For her to act in her turn the guardian

00:43:18.660 --> 00:43:20.040
angel to the afflicted.

00:43:21.720 --> 00:43:26.080
During one of their walks a poor cot in the foldings of a veil attracted their notice

00:43:26.080 --> 00:43:31.040
as being singularly disconsolate, while the number of half-clothed children gathered about

00:43:31.040 --> 00:43:36.140
it spoke of penury of its worst shape. One day, when my father had gone by himself to

00:43:36.140 --> 00:43:39.820
Milan, my mother accompanied by me visited this abode.

00:43:40.800 --> 00:43:45.980
She found a peasant and his wife hard working, bent down by care and labor, distributing

00:43:45.980 --> 00:43:51.420
a scanty meal to five hungry babes. Among these there was one which attracted my mother

00:43:51.420 --> 00:43:56.880
far above all the rest. She appeared of a different stock. The four others were dark-eyed,

00:43:57.060 --> 00:44:02.460
hardy little vagrants. This child was thin and very fair. Her hair was the brightest

00:44:02.460 --> 00:44:07.040
living gold, and despite the poverty of her clothing, seemed to set a crown of distinction

00:44:07.040 --> 00:44:12.400
on her head. Her brow was clear and ample, her blue eyes cloudless, and her lips and

00:44:12.400 --> 00:44:18.060
the molding of her face so expressive of sensibility and sweetness that none could behold her without

00:44:18.060 --> 00:44:23.580
looking on her as of a distinct species, a being heaven-sent, and bearing a celestial

00:44:23.580 --> 00:44:25.060
stamp in all her features.

00:44:26.140 --> 00:44:30.880
The peasant woman, perceiving that my mother fixed eyes of wonder and admiration on this

00:44:30.880 --> 00:44:36.520
lovely girl, eagerly communicated her history. She was not her child, but the daughter of

00:44:36.520 --> 00:44:42.700
a Milanese noblewoman. Her mother was a German and had died on giving her birth. The infant

00:44:42.700 --> 00:44:47.940
had been placed with these good people to nurse. They were better off then. They had

00:44:47.940 --> 00:44:53.040
not been long married, and their eldest child was but just born. The father of their charge

00:44:53.040 --> 00:44:58.060
was one of those Italians nursed in the memory of the antique glory of Italy, one among

00:44:58.060 --> 00:45:04.060
the sciavi Agnor Frumenti, who exerted himself to obtain the liberty of his country. He became

00:45:04.060 --> 00:45:08.500
the victim of its weakness. Whether he had died or still lingered in the dungeons of

00:45:08.500 --> 00:45:13.680
Austria was not known. His property was confiscated. His child became an orphan and a beggar.

00:45:14.700 --> 00:45:19.260
She continued with her foster parents, and bloomed in their rude abode, fairer than a

00:45:19.260 --> 00:45:25.300
garden rose among dark-leaved brambles. When my father returned from Milan, he found, playing

00:45:25.300 --> 00:45:29.940
with me in the hall of our villa, a child fairer than the pictured cherub, a creature

00:45:29.940 --> 00:45:34.640
who seemed to shed radiance from all her looks, and whose form and motions were lighter than

00:45:34.640 --> 00:45:38.420
the chamois of the hills. The apparition was soon explained.

00:45:39.140 --> 00:45:43.520
With his permission, my mother prevailed on her rustic guardians to yield their charge

00:45:43.520 --> 00:45:48.360
to her. They were fond of the sweet orphan. Her presence had seemed a blessing to them,

00:45:48.440 --> 00:45:52.600
but it would be unfair to her to keep her in poverty and want when Providence offered

00:45:52.600 --> 00:45:57.980
her such powerful protection. They consulted their village priest, and the result was that

00:45:57.980 --> 00:46:03.820
Elizabeth Levenza became the inmate of my parents' house, my more than sister, the beautiful

00:46:03.820 --> 00:46:06.860
and adored companion of all my occupations and my pleasures.

00:46:07.660 --> 00:46:12.140
Everyone loved Elizabeth. The passionate and almost reverential attachment with which all

00:46:12.140 --> 00:46:17.860
regarded her became, while I shared it, my pride and my delight. On the evening previous

00:46:17.860 --> 00:46:22.860
to her being brought to my home, my mother said playfully, I have a present for my victor.

00:46:23.040 --> 00:46:28.020
Tomorrow he shall have it. And when, on the morrow, she presented Elizabeth to me as her

00:46:28.020 --> 00:46:33.340
promised gift, I, with childish seriousness, interpreted her words literally, and looked

00:46:33.340 --> 00:46:39.300
upon Elizabeth as mine, mine to protect, love, and cherish. All praises I bestowed on her

00:46:39.300 --> 00:46:44.880
I received as made to a possession of my own. We called each other familiarly by the name

00:46:44.880 --> 00:46:50.620
of cousin. No word, no expression could body forth the kind of relation in which she stood

00:46:50.620 --> 00:46:54.980
to me, my more than sister, since till death she was to be mine only.

00:47:28.240 --> 00:47:47.840
We were brought up together. There was not quite a year of difference in our ages. I need not say that we were strangers to any species of disunion or dispute. Harmony was the soul of our companionship, and the diversity and contrast that subsisted in our characters drew us nearer together.

00:47:49.420 --> 00:48:01.480
Elizabeth was of a calmer and more concentrated disposition. But, with all my ardour, I was capable of a more intense application, and was more deeply smitten with the thirst for knowledge.

00:48:02.680 --> 00:48:27.420
She busied herself with following the aerial creations of the poets, and in the majestic and wondrous scenes which surrounded our Swiss home, the sublime shapes of the mountains, the changes of the seasons, tempest and calm, the silence of winter, and the life and turbulence of our alpine summers, she found ample scope for admiration and delight.

00:48:28.880 --> 00:48:55.660
While my companion contemplated with a serious and satisfied spirit the magnificent appearances of things, I delighted in investigating their causes. The world was to me a secret which I desired to divine. Curiosity, earnest research to learn the hidden laws of nature, gladness akin to rapture as they were unfolded to me, are among the earliest sensations I can remember.

00:48:57.740 --> 00:49:09.340
On the birth of a second son, my junior by seven years, my parents gave up entirely their wandering life, and fixed themselves in their native country.

00:49:10.800 --> 00:49:28.820
We possessed a house in Geneva, and a campaign on Belle-Rive, the eastern shore of the lake, at the distance of rather more than a league from the city. We resided principally in the latter, and the lives of my parents were passed in considerable seclusion.

00:49:30.020 --> 00:49:44.820
It was my temper to avoid a crowd, and to attach myself fervently to a few. I was indifferent therefore to my school fellows in general, but I united myself in the bonds of the closest friendship to one among them.

00:49:45.620 --> 00:50:02.560
Henry Clerval was the son of a merchant of Geneva. He was a boy of singular talent and fancy. He loved enterprise, hardship, and even danger for its own sake. He was deeply read in books of chivalry and romance.

00:50:02.560 --> 00:50:27.700
He composed heroic songs, and began to write many a tale of enchantment and nightly adventure. He tried to make us act plays, and to enter into masquerades, in which the characters were drawn from the heroes of Ronceval, of the round table of King Arthur, and the chivalrous train who shed their blood to redeem the holy sepulcher from the hands of the infidels.

00:50:29.720 --> 00:50:49.920
No human being could have passed a happier childhood than myself. My parents were possessed by the very spirit of kindness and indulgence. We felt that they were not the tyrants to rule our lot according to their caprice, but the agents and creators of all the many delights which we enjoyed.

00:50:49.920 --> 00:51:00.960
When I mingled with other families, I distinctly discerned how peculiarly fortunate my lot was, and gratitude assisted the development of filial love.

00:51:02.800 --> 00:51:18.280
My temper was sometimes violent, and my passions vehement, but by some law in my temperature they were turned not towards childish pursuits, but to an eager desire to learn, and not to learn all things indiscriminately.

00:51:19.420 --> 00:51:43.200
I confess that neither the structure of languages, nor the code of governments, nor the politics of various states possessed attractions for me. It was the secrets of heaven and earth that I desired to learn, and whether it was the outward substance of things, or the inner spirit of nature, and the mysterious soul of man that occupied me,

00:51:43.200 --> 00:51:51.540
still my inquiries were directed to the metaphysical, or in its highest sense, the physical secrets of the world.

00:51:53.660 --> 00:52:16.720
Meanwhile, Clerval occupied himself, so to speak, with the moral relations of things. The busy stage of life, the virtues of heroes, and the actions of men were his theme, and his hope and his dream was to become one among those whose names are recorded in story as the gallant and adventurous benefactors of our species.

00:52:18.380 --> 00:52:35.580
The saintly soul of Elizabeth shone like a shrine-dedicated lamp in our peaceful home. Her sympathy was ours. Her smile, her soft voice, the sweet glance of her celestial eyes were ever there to bless and animate us.

00:52:36.940 --> 00:52:51.420
She was the living spirit of love to soften and attract. I might have become sullen in my study, rough through the ardour of my nature, but that she was there to subdue me to a semblance of her own gentleness.

00:52:51.420 --> 00:53:18.540
And Clerval, could aught ill entrench on the noble spirit of Clerval? Yet he might not have been so perfectly humane, so thoughtful in his generosity, so full of kindness and tenderness amidst his passion for adventurous exploit, had she not unfolded to him the real loveliness of beneficence, and made the doing good the end and aim of his soaring ambition.

00:53:20.380 --> 00:53:36.360
I feel exquisite pleasure in dwelling on the recollections of childhood before misfortune had tainted my mind and changed its bright visions of extensive usefulness into gloomy and narrow reflections upon self.

00:53:37.360 --> 00:54:01.880
Besides, in drawing the picture of my early days, I also record those events which led, by insensible steps, to my after-tale of misery. For when I would account to myself for the birth of that passion which ever afterwards ruled my destiny, I find it arise, like a mountain river, from ignoble and almost forgotten sources.

00:54:01.880 --> 00:54:10.980
But swelling as it proceeded, it became the torrent which, in its course, has swept away all my hopes and joys.

00:54:12.020 --> 00:54:24.540
Natural philosophy is the genius that has regulated my fate. I desire, therefore, in this narration, to state those facts which led to my predilection for that science.

00:54:26.020 --> 00:54:44.160
When I was thirteen years of age, we all went on a party of pleasure to the baths near Thonon. The inclementcy of the weather obliged us to remain a day confined to the inn. In this house I chanced to find a volume of the works of Cornelius Agrippa.

00:54:45.100 --> 00:54:56.000
I opened it with apathy. The theory which he attempts to demonstrate, and the wonderful facts which he relates, soon changed this feeling into enthusiasm.

00:54:56.000 --> 00:55:09.820
A new light seemed to dawn upon my mind, and bounding with joy I communicated my discovery to my father. My father looked carelessly at the title page of my book and said,

00:55:09.820 --> 00:55:17.800
Ah! Cornelius Agrippa! My dear Victor, do not waste your time upon this. It is sad trash.

00:55:19.300 --> 00:55:35.280
If, instead of this remark, my father had taken the pains to explain to me that the principles of Agrippa had been entirely exploded, and that a modern system of science had been introduced which possessed much greater powers than the ancient,

00:55:35.280 --> 00:55:54.660
because the powers of the latter were chimerical, while those of the former were real and practical. Under such circumstances I should certainly have thrown Agrippa aside and have contented my imagination, warmed as it was, by returning with greater ardour to my former studies.

00:55:55.780 --> 00:56:15.860
It is even possible that the train of my ideas would never have received the fatal impulse that led to my ruin. But the cursory glance my father had taken of my volume by no means assured me that he was acquainted with its contents, and I continued to read with the greatest avidity.

00:56:17.460 --> 00:56:37.030
When I returned home, my first care was to procure the whole works of this author, and afterwards of Paracelsus and Albertus Magnus. I read and studied the wild fancies of these writers with delight. They appeared to me treasures known to few besides myself.

00:56:38.270 --> 00:56:57.430
I have described myself as always having been imbued with a fervent longing to penetrate the secrets of nature. In spite of the intense labour and wonderful discoveries of modern philosophers, I always came from my studies discontented and unsatisfied.

00:56:58.970 --> 00:57:21.590
Sir Isaac Newton is said to have avowed that he felt like a child picking up shells beside the great and unexplored ocean of truth. Those of his successors in each branch of natural philosophy with whom I was acquainted appeared even to my boy's apprehensions as tyros engaged in the same pursuit.

00:57:23.590 --> 00:57:41.230
The untaught peasant beheld the elements around him, and was acquainted with their practical uses. The most learned philosopher knew little more. He had partially unveiled the face of nature, but her immortal lineaments were still a wonder and a mystery.

00:57:41.230 --> 00:58:06.410
He might dissect, anatomize, and give names, but, not to speak of a final cause, causes in their secondary and tertiary grades were utterly unknown to him. I had gazed upon the fortifications and impediments that seemed to keep human beings from entering the citadel of nature, and rashly and ignorantly I had repined.

00:58:07.590 --> 00:58:34.370
But here were books, and here were men who had penetrated deeper and knew more. I took their word for all that they averred, and I became their disciple. It may appear strange that such should arise in the eighteenth century, but while I followed the routine of education in the schools of Geneva I was, to a great degree, self-taught with regard to my favourite studies.

00:58:35.950 --> 00:58:58.850
My father was not scientific, and I was left to struggle with a child's blindness, added to a student's thirst for knowledge. Under the guidance of my new preceptors I entered with the greatest diligence into the search of the philosopher's stone and the elixir of life, but the latter soon obtained my undivided attention.

00:59:00.190 --> 00:59:12.170
Wealth was an inferior object, but what glory would attend the discovery if I could banish disease from the human frame, and render man invulnerable to any but a violent death?

00:59:13.410 --> 00:59:15.190
Nor were these my only visions.

00:59:15.190 --> 00:59:37.190
The raising of ghosts or devils was a promise liberally accorded by my favourite authors, the fulfilment of which I most eagerly sought, and if my incantations were always unsuccessful I attributed the failure rather to my own inexperience and mistake, than to a want of skill or fidelity in my instructors.

00:59:38.570 --> 01:00:01.630
And thus for a time I was occupied by exploded systems, mingling, like an unadept, a thousand contradictory theories, and floundering desperately in a very slough of multifarious knowledge, guided by an ardent imagination and childish reasoning, till an accident again changed the current of my ideas.

01:00:02.830 --> 01:00:12.550
When I was about fifteen years old we had retired to our house near Belle-Rive, when we witnessed a most violent and terrible thunderstorm.

01:00:13.930 --> 01:00:22.210
It advanced from behind the mountains of Jura, and the thunder burst at once with frightful loudness from various quarters of the heavens.

01:00:23.350 --> 01:00:30.330
I remained, while the storm lasted, watching its progress with curiosity and delight.

01:00:31.550 --> 01:00:49.910
As I stood at the door, on a sudden I beheld a stream of fire issue from an old and beautiful oak, which stood about twenty yards from our house, and so soon as the dazzling light vanished, the oak had disappeared, and nothing remained but a blasted stump.

01:00:50.750 --> 01:00:56.550
When we visited it the next morning we found the tree shattered in a singular manner.

01:00:58.290 --> 01:01:07.890
It was not splintered by the shock, but entirely reduced to thin ribbons of wood. I had never beheld anything so utterly destroyed.

01:01:10.590 --> 01:01:15.290
Before this I was not unacquainted with the more obvious laws of electricity.

01:01:16.590 --> 01:01:34.770
On this occasion a man of great research in natural philosophy was with us, and excited by this catastrophe he entered on the explanation of a theory which he had formed on the subject of electricity and galvanism, which was at once new and astonishing to me.

01:01:35.850 --> 01:01:52.170
All that he said threw greatly into the shade Cornelius Agrippa, Albertus Magnus, and Paracelsus, the lords of my imagination, but by some fatality the overthrow of these men disinclined me to pursue my accustomed studies.

01:01:53.370 --> 01:02:03.130
It seemed to me as if nothing would or could ever be known. All that had so long engaged my attention suddenly grew despicable.

01:02:03.990 --> 01:02:27.850
By one of those caprices of the mind which we are perhaps most subject to in early youth, I at once gave up my former occupations, set down natural history and all its progeny as a deformed and abortive creation, and entertained the greatest disdain for a would-be science which could never even step within the threshold of real knowledge.

01:02:29.850 --> 01:02:41.850
In this mood of mind I betook myself to the mathematics and the branches of study appertaining to that science as being built upon secure foundations, and so worthy of my consideration.

01:02:44.170 --> 01:02:53.570
Thus, strangely, are our souls constructed, and by such slight ligaments are we bound to prosperity or ruin.

01:02:54.490 --> 01:03:15.970
When I look back, it seems to me as if this almost miraculous change of inclination and will was the immediate suggestion of the guardian angel of my life, the last effort made by the spirit of preservation to avert the storm that was even then hanging in the stars and ready to envelop me.

01:03:17.350 --> 01:03:36.730
Her victory was announced by an unusual tranquillity and gladness of soul which followed the relinquishing of my ancient and latterly tormenting studies. It was thus that I was to be taught to associate evil with their prosecution, happiness with their disregard.

01:03:36.730 --> 01:03:53.910
It was a strong effort of the spirit of good, but it was ineffectual. Destiny was too potent, and her immutable laws had decreed my utter and terrible destruction.

01:04:16.650 --> 01:04:21.070
When I had attained the age of seventeen, my parents resolved that I should become a

01:04:21.070 --> 01:04:23.310
student at the University of Ingolstadt.

01:04:23.870 --> 01:04:29.070
I had hitherto attended the schools of Geneva, but my father thought it necessary for the

01:04:29.070 --> 01:04:34.330
completion of my education that I should be made acquainted with other customs than those

01:04:34.330 --> 01:04:35.530
of my native country.

01:04:36.590 --> 01:04:41.590
My departure was therefore fixed at an early date, but before the day resolved upon could

01:04:41.590 --> 01:04:48.530
arrive, the first misfortune of my life occurred—an omen, as it were, of my future misery.

01:04:49.570 --> 01:04:54.910
Elizabeth had caught the scarlet fever, her illness was severe, and she was in the greatest

01:04:54.910 --> 01:05:00.830
danger. During her illness, many arguments had been urged to persuade my mother to refrain

01:05:00.830 --> 01:05:07.050
from attending upon her. She had at first yielded to her entreaties, but when she heard

01:05:07.050 --> 01:05:11.770
that the life of her favorites was menaced, she could no longer control her anxiety.

01:05:13.170 --> 01:05:18.290
She attended her sickbed, her watchful attentions triumphed over the malignity of the

01:05:18.290 --> 01:05:24.450
temper. Elizabeth was saved, but the consequences of this imprudence were fatal to her

01:05:24.450 --> 01:05:30.650
preserver. On the third day, my mother sickened. Her fever was accompanied by the most alarming

01:05:30.650 --> 01:05:37.610
symptoms, and the looks of her medical attendants prognosticated the worst event. On her

01:05:37.610 --> 01:05:43.810
deathbed, the fortitude and benignity of this best of women did not desert her. She joined

01:05:43.810 --> 01:05:45.530
the hands of Elizabeth and myself.

01:05:46.370 --> 01:05:52.330
My children, she said, my firmest hopes of future happiness were placed in the prospect

01:05:52.330 --> 01:05:58.130
of your union. This expectation will now be the consolation of your father. Elizabeth,

01:05:58.190 --> 01:06:05.490
my love, you must supply my place to my younger children. Alas, I regret that I am taken from

01:06:05.490 --> 01:06:12.910
you. And, happy and beloved as I have been, is it not hard to quit you all? But these

01:06:12.910 --> 01:06:18.470
are not thoughts befitting me. I will endeavour to resign myself cheerfully to death, and

01:06:18.470 --> 01:06:24.930
will indulge a hope of meeting you in another world. She died calmly, and her countenance

01:06:24.930 --> 01:06:30.590
expressed affection even in death. I need not describe the feelings of those whose dearest

01:06:30.590 --> 01:06:35.770
ties are rent by that most irreparable evil, the void that presents itself to the soul

01:06:35.770 --> 01:06:41.530
and the despair that is exhibited on the countenance. It is so long before the mind can persuade

01:06:41.530 --> 01:06:47.470
itself that she whom we saw every day, and whose very existence appeared part of our own,

01:06:47.750 --> 01:06:52.810
can have departed forever, that the brightness of a beloved eye can have been extinguished,

01:06:53.010 --> 01:06:58.790
and the sound of a voice so familiar and dear to the ear can be hushed, never more to be heard.

01:06:59.650 --> 01:07:05.090
These are the reflections of the first days. But when the lapse of time proves the reality

01:07:05.090 --> 01:07:11.730
of the evil, then the actual bitterness of grief commences. Yet from whom has not the

01:07:11.730 --> 01:07:17.270
rude hand rent away some dear connection? And why should I describe a sorrow which all have

01:07:17.270 --> 01:07:23.110
felt and must feel? The time at length arrives when grief is rather an indulgence than a

01:07:23.110 --> 01:07:28.250
necessity, and the smile that plays upon the lips, although it may be deemed a sacrilege,

01:07:28.530 --> 01:07:34.070
is not banished. My mother was dead, but we had still duties we ought to perform. We must

01:07:34.070 --> 01:07:39.550
continue our course with the rest, and learn to think ourselves fortunate whilst one remains

01:07:39.550 --> 01:07:46.110
whom the spoiler has not seized. My departure for Ingolstadt, which had been deferred by these

01:07:46.110 --> 01:07:52.810
events, was now again determined upon. I obtained from my father a respite of some weeks. It

01:07:52.810 --> 01:07:57.930
appeared to me sacrilege so soon to leave the repose akin to death of the house of mourning

01:07:57.930 --> 01:08:03.630
and to rush into the thick of life. I was new to sorrow, but it did not the less alarm me.

01:08:04.070 --> 01:08:09.710
I was unwilling to quit the sight of those that remained to me, and above all I desired to see my

01:08:09.710 --> 01:08:15.570
sweet Elizabeth in some degree consoled. She indeed veiled her grief, and strove to act the

01:08:15.570 --> 01:08:20.990
comforter to us all. She looked steadily on life, and assumed its duties with courage and zeal.

01:08:21.470 --> 01:08:25.770
She devoted herself to those whom she had been taught to call her uncle and cousins.

01:08:26.790 --> 01:08:32.050
Never was she so enchanting as at this time, when she recalled the sunshine of her smiles

01:08:32.050 --> 01:08:38.050
and spent them upon us. She forgot even her own regret in her endeavours to make us forget.

01:08:39.810 --> 01:08:44.930
The day of my departure at length arrived. Clairvaux spent the last evening with us.

01:08:45.370 --> 01:08:50.150
He had endeavoured to persuade his father to permit him to accompany me and to become my

01:08:50.150 --> 01:08:55.610
fellow student, but in vain. His father was a narrow-minded trader, and saw idleness and ruin

01:08:55.610 --> 01:09:00.710
in the aspirations and ambition of his son. Henry deeply felt the misfortune of being

01:09:00.710 --> 01:09:07.470
from a liberal education. He said little, but when he spoke, I read in his kindling eye and in his

01:09:07.470 --> 01:09:13.650
animated glance a restrained but firm resolve not to be chained to the miserable details of commerce.

01:09:14.430 --> 01:09:19.850
We sat late. We could not tear ourselves away from each other, nor persuade ourselves to say

01:09:19.850 --> 01:09:26.990
the word farewell. It was said, and we retired under the pretense of seeking repose, each fancying

01:09:26.990 --> 01:09:32.210
the other was deceived. But when, at morning's dawn, I descended to the carriage which was to

01:09:32.210 --> 01:09:38.330
convey me away, they were all there. My father, again to bless me, Clairvaux, to press my hand

01:09:38.330 --> 01:09:44.090
once more, my Elizabeth to renew her entreaties that I would write often and to bestow the last

01:09:44.090 --> 01:09:51.010
feminine attentions on her playmate and friend. I threw myself into the chaise that was to convey

01:09:51.010 --> 01:09:57.430
me away and indulge in the most melancholy reflections. I, who had ever been surrounded

01:09:57.430 --> 01:10:02.350
by amiable companions, continually engaged in endeavouring to bestow mutual pleasure.

01:10:03.070 --> 01:10:09.710
I was now alone. In the university whither I was going, I must form my own friends and be my own

01:10:09.710 --> 01:10:15.730
protector. My life had hitherto been remarkably secluded and domestic, and this had given me

01:10:15.730 --> 01:10:21.410
invincible repugnance to new countenances. I loved my brothers, Elizabeth and Clairvaux.

01:10:21.950 --> 01:10:26.850
These were old familiar faces, but I believed myself totally unfitted for the company of

01:10:26.850 --> 01:10:32.410
strangers. Such were my reflections as I commenced my journey. But as I proceeded,

01:10:32.850 --> 01:10:37.110
my spirits and hopes rose. I ardently desired the acquisition of knowledge.

01:10:37.790 --> 01:10:43.070
I had often, when at home, thought it hard to remain during my youth, cooped up in one place,

01:10:43.070 --> 01:10:48.450
and had longed to enter the world and take my station among other human beings. Now my desires

01:10:48.450 --> 01:10:54.950
were complied with, and it would indeed have been folly to repent. I had sufficient leisure for these

01:10:54.950 --> 01:10:59.910
and many other reflections during my journey to Ingolstadt, which was long and fatiguing.

01:11:00.110 --> 01:11:06.370
At length the high white steeple of the town met my eyes. I alighted and was conducted to my

01:11:06.370 --> 01:11:11.410
solitary apartment to spend the evening as I pleased. The next morning I delivered my

01:11:11.410 --> 01:11:17.770
introduction, and paid a visit to some of the principal professors. Chant, or rather the evil

01:11:17.770 --> 01:11:22.690
influence, the angel of destruction, which asserted omnipotent sway over me from the

01:11:22.690 --> 01:11:27.970
moment I turned my reluctant steps from my father's door, led me first to Monsieur Cramp,

01:11:28.490 --> 01:11:34.070
professor of natural philosophy. He was an uncouth man, but deeply imbued in the secrets

01:11:34.070 --> 01:11:39.090
of his science. He asked me several questions concerning my progress in the different branches

01:11:39.090 --> 01:11:44.890
of science appertaining to natural philosophy. I replied carelessly, and partly in contempt,

01:11:45.510 --> 01:11:49.050
mentioned the names of my alchemists as the principal authors I had studied.

01:11:49.810 --> 01:11:50.890
The professor stared.

01:11:51.830 --> 01:11:55.670
Have you, he said, really spent your time in studying such nonsense?

01:11:56.170 --> 01:11:57.470
I replied in the affirmative.

01:11:58.330 --> 01:12:03.590
Every minute, continued Monsieur Cramp with warmth, every instance that you have wasted

01:12:03.590 --> 01:12:09.570
on those books is utterly and entirely lost. You have burdened your memory with exploded

01:12:09.570 --> 01:12:16.230
systems and useless names. Good God! In what desert land have you lived where no one was

01:12:16.230 --> 01:12:21.430
kind enough to inform you that these fancies which you have so greedily imbibed are a thousand

01:12:21.430 --> 01:12:26.830
years old and as musty as they are ancient? I little expected, in this enlightened and

01:12:26.830 --> 01:12:32.750
scientific age, to find a disciple of Albertus Magnus and Paracelsus. My dear sir, you must

01:12:32.750 --> 01:12:38.130
begin your studies entirely anew. So saying, he stepped aside and wrote down a list of

01:12:38.130 --> 01:12:43.310
several books treating of natural philosophy which he desired me to procure, and dismissed

01:12:43.310 --> 01:12:47.570
me after mentioning that in the beginning of the following week he intended to commence

01:12:47.570 --> 01:12:52.050
a course of lectures upon natural philosophy in its general relations, and that Monsieur

01:12:52.050 --> 01:12:57.090
Voltmann, a fellow professor, would lecture upon chemistry the alternate days he omitted.

01:12:57.680 --> 01:13:02.770
I returned home not disappointed, for I have said that I had long considered those authors

01:13:02.770 --> 01:13:08.030
useless whom the professor reprobated, but I returned not at all the more inclined to

01:13:08.030 --> 01:13:13.550
recur to these studies in any shape. Monsieur Cramp was a little squat man with a gruff

01:13:13.550 --> 01:13:18.710
voice and a repulsive countenance. The teacher, therefore, did not prepossess me in favour of

01:13:18.710 --> 01:13:24.790
his pursuits. In rather a too philosophical and connected strain, perhaps, I have given

01:13:24.790 --> 01:13:30.290
an account of the conclusions I had come to concerning them in my early years. As a child,

01:13:30.550 --> 01:13:34.630
I had not been content with the results promised by the modern professors of natural science.

01:13:35.410 --> 01:13:40.630
With a confusion of ideas only to be accounted for by my extreme youth and my want of a guide

01:13:40.630 --> 01:13:46.390
on such matters, I had retrod the steps of knowledge along the paths of time and exchanged

01:13:46.390 --> 01:13:52.430
the discoveries of recent inquirers for the dreams of forgotten alchemists. Besides,

01:13:52.430 --> 01:13:57.850
I had a contempt for the uses of modern natural philosophy. It was very different when the masters

01:13:57.850 --> 01:14:04.930
of the science sought immortality and power. Such views, although futile, were grand. But now the

01:14:04.930 --> 01:14:11.010
scene was changed. The ambition of the inquirer seemed to limit itself to the annihilation of

01:14:11.010 --> 01:14:16.470
those visions on which my interest in the science was chiefly founded. I was required to exchange

01:14:16.470 --> 01:14:21.910
shimmers of boundless grandeur for realities of little worth. Such were my reflections during

01:14:21.910 --> 01:14:26.910
the first two or three days of my residence at Ingolstadt, which were chiefly spent in becoming

01:14:26.910 --> 01:14:31.930
acquainted with the localities and the principal residence in my new abode. But as the ensuing

01:14:31.930 --> 01:14:37.130
week commenced, I thought of the information which Mr. Cramp had given me concerning the lectures.

01:14:37.870 --> 01:14:43.130
And although I could not consent to go and hear that little conceited fellow deliver sentences

01:14:43.130 --> 01:14:48.850
out of the pulpit, I recollected what he had said of Mr. Waldman, whom I had never seen,

01:14:48.850 --> 01:14:53.790
as he had hitherto been out of town. Partly from curiosity and partly from idleness,

01:14:54.250 --> 01:14:58.110
I went into the lecturing room which Mr. Waldman entered shortly after.

01:14:58.810 --> 01:15:03.390
This professor was very unlike his colleague. He appeared about fifty years of age,

01:15:03.650 --> 01:15:08.610
but with an aspect expressive of the greatest benevolence. A few grey hairs covered his temples,

01:15:09.090 --> 01:15:15.390
but those at the back of his head were nearly black. His person was short but remarkably erect,

01:15:15.390 --> 01:15:21.150
and his voice the sweetest I had ever heard. He began his lecture by a recapitulation of the

01:15:21.150 --> 01:15:25.950
history of chemistry and the various improvements made by different men of learning, pronouncing

01:15:25.950 --> 01:15:31.610
with fervour the names of the most distinguished discoverers. He then took a cursory view of the

01:15:31.610 --> 01:15:37.370
present state of the science, and explained many of its elementary terms. After having made a few

01:15:37.370 --> 01:15:42.890
preparatory experiments, he concluded with a panegyric upon modern chemistry, the terms of

01:15:42.890 --> 01:15:44.170
which I shall never forget.

01:15:44.710 --> 01:15:50.890
The ancient teachers of this science, he said, promised impossibilities and performed nothing.

01:15:51.670 --> 01:15:57.390
The modern masters promise very little. They know that metals cannot be transmuted,

01:15:57.530 --> 01:16:03.790
and that the excelsior of life is a shimmerer. But these philosophers, whose hands seem only

01:16:03.790 --> 01:16:08.250
made to dabble in dirt, and their eyes to pour over the microscope or crucible,

01:16:08.810 --> 01:16:14.010
have indeed performed miracles. They penetrate into the recesses of nature,

01:16:14.510 --> 01:16:20.630
and show how she walks in our hiding places. They ascend into the heavens. They have discovered how

01:16:20.630 --> 01:16:26.570
the blood circulates, and the nature of the air we breathe. They have acquired new and almost

01:16:26.570 --> 01:16:33.010
unlimited powers. They can command the thunders of heaven, mimic the earthquake, and even mock

01:16:33.010 --> 01:16:35.170
the invisible world with its own shadows.

01:16:36.170 --> 01:16:42.090
Such were the professor's words. Rather let me say, such the words of the fate announced to

01:16:42.090 --> 01:16:47.890
destroy me. As he went on, I felt as if my soul were grappling with a palpable enemy.

01:16:48.410 --> 01:16:52.890
One by one the various keys were touched which formed the mechanism of my being.

01:16:53.710 --> 01:16:57.930
Chord after chord were sounded, and soon my mind was filled with one thought,

01:16:57.930 --> 01:17:00.050
one conception, one purpose.

01:17:00.770 --> 01:17:06.750
So much has been done, exclaimed the soul of Frankenstein. More, far more will I achieve.

01:17:07.510 --> 01:17:10.770
Treading in the steps already marked, I will pioneer a new way,

01:17:11.110 --> 01:17:15.510
explore unknown powers, and unfold to the world the deepest mysteries of creation.

01:17:16.850 --> 01:17:22.610
I closed my eyes that night. My internal being was in a state of insurrection and turmoil.

01:17:23.070 --> 01:17:27.290
I felt that order would thence arise, but I had no power to produce it.

01:17:27.930 --> 01:17:33.950
By degrees, after the morning's dawn, sleep came. I awoke, and my yesternight's thoughts

01:17:33.950 --> 01:17:38.790
were as a dream. There only remained a resolution to return to my ancient studies,

01:17:39.190 --> 01:17:44.030
and to devote myself to a science for which I believe myself to possess a natural talent.

01:17:44.770 --> 01:17:50.230
On the same day I paid Monsieur Waldemann a visit. His manners in private were even more

01:17:50.230 --> 01:17:55.390
mild and attractive than in public, for there was a certain dignity in his mane during his lectures,

01:17:55.390 --> 01:17:59.190
which in his own house was replaced by the greatest affability and kindness.

01:17:59.650 --> 01:18:04.550
I gave him pretty nearly the same account of my former pursuits as I had given his fellow

01:18:04.550 --> 01:18:10.090
professor. He heard with attention the little narration concerning my studies, and smiled at

01:18:10.090 --> 01:18:15.570
the names of Cornelius Agrippa and Paracelsus, but without the contempt that Monsieur Cramp had

01:18:15.570 --> 01:18:22.110
exhibited. He said that these were men to whose indefatigable zeal modern philosophers were

01:18:22.110 --> 01:18:28.610
indebted for most of the foundations of their knowledge. They had left to us, as an easier task,

01:18:28.910 --> 01:18:34.370
to give new names and arrange in connected classifications the facts which they, in a

01:18:34.370 --> 01:18:39.970
great degree, had been the instruments of bringing to light. The labours of men of genius,

01:18:40.490 --> 01:18:46.990
however erroneously directed, scarcely ever fail in ultimately turning to the solid advantage of

01:18:46.990 --> 01:18:52.830
I listened to a statement which was delivered without any presumption or affectation,

01:18:53.110 --> 01:18:57.450
and then added that his lecture had removed my prejudice against modern chemists.

01:18:57.970 --> 01:19:02.010
I expressed myself in measured terms, with the modesty and deference

01:19:02.010 --> 01:19:06.910
due from a youth to his instructor, without letting escape. An experience in life would

01:19:06.910 --> 01:19:11.750
have made me ashamed. Any of the enthusiasm which stimulated my intended labours.

01:19:12.390 --> 01:19:15.610
I requested his advice concerning books I ought to procure.

01:19:16.310 --> 01:19:21.910
I am happy, said Monsieur Voltman, to have gained a disciple, and if your application

01:19:21.910 --> 01:19:28.030
equals your ability, I have no doubt of your success. Chemistry is that branch of natural

01:19:28.030 --> 01:19:33.770
philosophy in which the greatest improvements have been and may be made. It is on that account

01:19:33.770 --> 01:19:40.170
that I have made it my peculiar study. But at the same time I have not neglected the other branches

01:19:40.170 --> 01:19:46.770
of science. A man would make a very sorry chemist if he attended to that department

01:19:46.770 --> 01:19:53.130
of human knowledge alone. If your wish is to become really a man of science, and not merely

01:19:53.130 --> 01:19:58.370
a petty experimentalist, I would advise you to apply to every branch of natural philosophy,

01:19:58.710 --> 01:20:04.170
including mathematics. He then took me into his laboratory and explained to me the uses

01:20:04.170 --> 01:20:09.490
of his various machines, instructing me as to what I ought to procure, and promising me

01:20:09.490 --> 01:20:14.510
use of his own when I should have advanced far enough in the science not to derange the mechanism.

01:20:15.190 --> 01:20:18.970
He also gave me a list of books which I had requested, and I took my leave.

01:20:19.790 --> 01:20:24.050
Thus ended a day memorable to me. It decided my future destiny.

01:20:27.010 --> 01:20:32.050
From this day natural philosophy, and particularly chemistry, in the most comprehensive sense of the

01:20:32.050 --> 01:20:37.410
term, became nearly my sole occupation. I read with ardour those works so full of genius and

01:20:37.410 --> 01:20:42.250
discrimination which modern inquirers have written on these subjects. I attended the

01:20:42.250 --> 01:20:47.190
lectures and cultivated the acquaintance of the men of science of the University, and found even

01:20:47.190 --> 01:20:53.050
in Mr. Cramp a great deal of sound sense and real information, combined as is true with a repulsive

01:20:53.050 --> 01:20:59.490
physiognomy and manners, but not, on that account, the less valuable. In Mr. Waltman I found a true

01:20:59.490 --> 01:21:04.410
friend. His gentleness was never tinged by dogmatism, and his instructions were given

01:21:04.410 --> 01:21:10.430
an air of frankness and good nature that banished every idea of pedantry. In a thousand ways he

01:21:10.430 --> 01:21:15.890
smoothed for me the path of knowledge and made the most abstruse inquiries clear and facile to my

01:21:15.890 --> 01:21:21.190
apprehension. My application was at first fluctuating and uncertain. It gained strength

01:21:21.190 --> 01:21:26.230
as I proceeded, and soon became so ardent and eager that the stars often disappeared

01:21:26.230 --> 01:21:32.990
in the light of morning, whilst I was yet engaged in my laboratory. As I applied so closely,

01:21:32.990 --> 01:21:38.430
may be easily conceived that my progress was rapid. My ardour was indeed the astonishment

01:21:38.430 --> 01:21:44.430
of the students, and my proficiency that of the masters. Professor Cramp often asked me,

01:21:44.430 --> 01:21:49.910
with a sly smile, how Cornelius Agrippa went on, whilst Monsieur Waltman expressed the most

01:21:49.910 --> 01:21:55.610
heartfelt exaltation in my progress. Two years passed in this manner, during which I paid no

01:21:55.610 --> 01:22:01.170
visit to Geneva, but was engaged, heart and soul, in the pursuit of some discoveries which I hoped

01:22:01.170 --> 01:22:07.150
to make. None but those who have experienced them can conceive of the enticements of science.

01:22:08.070 --> 01:22:13.190
In other studies you go as far as others have gone before you, and there is nothing more to know,

01:22:13.610 --> 01:22:19.350
but in scientific pursuit there is continual food for discovery and wonder. A mind of moderate

01:22:19.350 --> 01:22:25.210
capacity which closely pursues one study must infallibly arrive at great proficiency in that

01:22:25.210 --> 01:22:31.530
I, who continually sought the attainment of one object of pursuit and was solely wrapped up in

01:22:31.530 --> 01:22:37.830
this, improved so rapidly that at the end of two years I made some discoveries in the improvement

01:22:37.830 --> 01:22:43.790
of some chemical instrument which procured me great esteem and admiration at the university.

01:22:44.550 --> 01:22:49.110
When I had arrived at this point and had become as well acquainted with the theory and practice of

01:22:49.110 --> 01:22:54.750
natural philosophy as depended on the lessons of any of the professors at Ingolstadt, my residence

01:22:54.750 --> 01:23:00.330
there being no longer conducive to my improvement, I thought of returning to my friends and my native

01:23:00.330 --> 01:23:06.970
town when an incident happened that protracted my stay. One of the phenomena which had peculiarly

01:23:06.970 --> 01:23:13.930
attracted my attention was the structure of the human frame, and indeed any animal endued with life.

01:23:14.990 --> 01:23:21.130
Whence, I often ask myself, did the principle of life proceed? It was a bold question and one which

01:23:21.130 --> 01:23:26.930
has ever been considered as a mystery. Yet with how many things are we upon the brink of becoming

01:23:26.930 --> 01:23:33.330
acquainted if cowardice or carelessness did not restrain our inquiries? I resolved these

01:23:33.330 --> 01:23:39.410
circumstances in my mind and determined henceforth to apply myself more particularly to those branches

01:23:39.410 --> 01:23:45.830
of natural philosophy which related to physiology. Unless I had been animated by an almost supernatural

01:23:45.830 --> 01:23:50.930
enthusiasm, my application to this study would have been irksome and almost intolerable.

01:23:51.130 --> 01:23:57.590
To examine the causes of life we must first have recourse to death. I became acquainted with the

01:23:57.590 --> 01:24:03.630
science of anatomy, but this was not sufficient. I must also observe the natural decay and corruption

01:24:03.630 --> 01:24:10.090
of the human body. In my education my father had taken the greatest precautions that my mind should

01:24:10.090 --> 01:24:20.430
be impressed with no supernatural horrors. I do not even remember to have trembled at a tale of

01:24:20.430 --> 01:24:26.250
The darkness had no effect upon my fancy, and a churchyard was to me merely the receptacle of bodies

01:24:26.250 --> 01:24:33.150
deprived of life, which, from being the seat of beauty and strength, had become food for the worm.

01:24:34.110 --> 01:24:39.070
Now I was led to examine the cause and the progress of this decay and forced to spend

01:24:39.070 --> 01:24:44.830
days and nights in vaults and charnel houses. My attention was fixed upon every object the

01:24:44.830 --> 01:24:51.030
most insupportable to the delicacy of human feelings. I saw how the fine form of man was

01:24:51.030 --> 01:24:56.430
degraded and wasted. I beheld the corruption of death succeed to the blooming cheek of life.

01:24:56.710 --> 01:25:02.910
I saw how the worm inherited the wonders of the eye and the brain. I paused, examining and analyzing

01:25:02.910 --> 01:25:09.610
all the minutiae of causation as exemplified in the change from life to death and death to life,

01:25:09.610 --> 01:25:15.870
until, from the midst of this darkness, a sudden light broke in upon me—a light so brilliant

01:25:15.870 --> 01:25:21.510
and wondrous, yet so simple, that while I became dizzy with the immensity of the prospect which it

01:25:21.510 --> 01:25:27.450
illuminated, I was surprised that among so many men of genius who had directed their inquiries

01:25:27.450 --> 01:25:32.870
towards the same science, that I alone should be reserved to discover so astonishing a secret.

01:25:33.590 --> 01:25:39.710
Remember, I am not recording the vision of a madman. The sun does not more certainly

01:25:39.710 --> 01:25:45.250
shine in the heavens than that which I now affirm is true. Some miracle might have produced it,

01:25:45.370 --> 01:25:50.410
yet the stages of the discovery were distinct and probable. After days and nights of incredible

01:25:50.410 --> 01:25:56.350
labour and fatigue, I succeeded in discovering the cause of generation and life. Nay, more,

01:25:56.570 --> 01:26:00.410
I became myself capable of bestowing animation upon lifeless matter.

01:26:01.210 --> 01:26:06.850
The astonishment which I had at first experienced on this discovery soon gave place to delight in

01:26:06.850 --> 01:26:12.470
rapture. After so much time spent in painful labour, to arrive at once at the summit of my

01:26:12.470 --> 01:26:17.770
desires was the most gratifying consummation of my toils. But this discovery was so great

01:26:17.770 --> 01:26:22.950
and overwhelming that all the steps by which I had been progressively led to it were obliterated,

01:26:23.110 --> 01:26:28.610
and I beheld only the result. What had been the study and desire of the wisest men since

01:26:28.610 --> 01:26:35.830
creation of the world was now within my grasp. Not that, like a magic scene, it all opened upon

01:26:35.830 --> 01:26:41.570
me at once. The information I had obtained was of a nature rather to direct my endeavours so soon as

01:26:41.570 --> 01:26:45.950
I should point them towards the object of my search than to exhibit that object already

01:26:45.950 --> 01:26:51.710
accomplished. I was like the Arabian who had been buried with the dead and found a passage to life

01:26:51.710 --> 01:26:57.330
aided only by one glimmering and seemingly ineffectual light. I see by your eagerness

01:26:57.330 --> 01:27:02.910
and the wonder and hope which your eyes express, my friend, that you expect to be informed of the

01:27:02.910 --> 01:27:09.150
secret with which I am acquainted. That cannot be. Listen patiently until the end of my story,

01:27:09.310 --> 01:27:15.230
and you will easily perceive why I am so reserved on that subject. I will not lead you on,

01:27:15.450 --> 01:27:21.530
unguarded and ardent, as I then was, to your destruction and infallible misery. Learn from

01:27:21.530 --> 01:27:28.510
me, if not by my precepts, at least by my example, how dangerous is the acquirement of knowledge and

01:27:28.510 --> 01:27:33.990
how much happier that man is who believes his native town to be the world than he who aspires

01:27:33.990 --> 01:27:39.510
to become greater than his nature will allow. When I found so astonishing a power placed within my

01:27:39.510 --> 01:27:44.270
hands, I hesitated a long time concerning the manner in which I should employ it.

01:27:44.690 --> 01:27:50.130
Although I possessed the capacity of bestowing life, yet to prepare a frame for the reception

01:27:50.130 --> 01:27:55.750
of it, with all its intricacies of fibres, muscles and veins, still remained a work of

01:27:55.750 --> 01:28:01.150
inconceivable difficulty and labour. I doubted at first whether I should attempt the creation

01:28:01.150 --> 01:28:07.050
of a being like myself, or one of simpler organisation, but my imagination was too much

01:28:07.050 --> 01:28:12.050
exalted by my first success to permit me to doubt of my ability to give life to an animal

01:28:12.050 --> 01:28:17.650
as complex and wonderful as man. The materials at present within my command hardly appeared

01:28:17.650 --> 01:28:22.770
adequate to so arduous an undertaking, but I doubted not that I should ultimately succeed.

01:28:23.230 --> 01:28:28.750
I prepared myself for a multitude of reverses. My operations might be incessantly baffled,

01:28:28.970 --> 01:28:33.990
and at last my work be imperfect, yet when I considered the improvement which every day

01:28:33.990 --> 01:28:39.130
takes place in science and mechanics, I was encouraged to hope my present attempts would

01:28:39.130 --> 01:28:44.770
at least lay the foundations of future success. Nor could I consider the magnitude and complexity

01:28:44.770 --> 01:28:51.410
of my plan as any argument of its impracticability. It was with these feelings that I began the

01:28:51.410 --> 01:28:57.230
creation of a human being. As the minuteness of the parts formed a great hindrance to my speed,

01:28:57.750 --> 01:29:03.890
I resolved, contrary to my first intention, to make a being of gigantic stature, that is to say,

01:29:04.090 --> 01:29:09.730
about eight feet in height and proportionally large. After having formed this determination

01:29:09.730 --> 01:29:13.990
and having spent some months in successfully collecting and arranging my materials,

01:29:13.990 --> 01:29:19.310
I began. No one can conceive the variety of feelings which bore me onwards,

01:29:20.390 --> 01:29:25.970
like a hurricane in the first enthusiasm of success. Life and death appeared to me ideal

01:29:25.970 --> 01:29:31.470
bounds which I should break through and pour a torrent of light into our dark world. A new

01:29:31.470 --> 01:29:37.090
species would bless me as its creator and source. Many happy and excellent natures would owe their

01:29:37.090 --> 01:29:42.790
being to me. No father could claim the gratitude of his child so completely as I should deserve

01:29:43.450 --> 01:29:48.810
pursuing these reflections. I thought that if I could bestow animation upon lifeless matter,

01:29:49.310 --> 01:29:54.650
I might in process of time, although I now found it impossible, to renew life where death had

01:29:54.650 --> 01:30:00.990
apparently devoted the body to corruption. These thoughts supported my spirits while I pursued my

01:30:00.990 --> 01:30:06.950
undertaking with unremitting ardour. My cheek had grown pale with study and my person had become

01:30:06.950 --> 01:30:14.130
emaciated with confinement. Sometimes, on the very brink of certainty, I failed. Yet still I

01:30:14.130 --> 01:30:20.850
clung to the hope which the next day or the next hour might realise. One secret which I alone

01:30:20.850 --> 01:30:27.330
possessed was the hope to which I had dedicated myself, and the moon gazed on my midnight labours

01:30:27.330 --> 01:30:32.690
while, with unrelaxed and breathless eagerness, I pursued nature to her hiding places.

01:30:33.350 --> 01:30:39.250
Who shall conceive the horrors of my secret toil as I dabbled among the unhallowed damps of the

01:30:39.250 --> 01:30:46.010
grave or tortured the living animal to animate the lifeless clay? My limbs now tremble and my

01:30:46.010 --> 01:30:51.310
eyes swim with the remembrance, but then a resistless and almost frantic impulse urged

01:30:51.310 --> 01:30:57.270
me forward. I seem to have lost all soul or sensation but for this one pursuit.

01:30:57.870 --> 01:31:04.710
It was indeed but a passing trance that only made me feel with renewed acuteness so soon as

01:31:04.710 --> 01:31:09.250
the unnatural stimulus ceasing to operate. I had returned to my old habits.

01:31:10.530 --> 01:31:16.690
I collected bones from the charnel houses and disturbed with profane fingers the tremendous

01:31:16.690 --> 01:31:22.950
secrets of the human frame, in a solitary chamber or other cell at the top of the house,

01:31:22.950 --> 01:31:27.330
and separated from all the other apartments by a gallery and staircase,

01:31:27.830 --> 01:31:33.430
I kept my workshop of filthy creation. My eyeballs were starting from their sockets

01:31:33.430 --> 01:31:38.850
and attending to the details of my employment. The dissecting room and the slaughterhouse

01:31:38.850 --> 01:31:45.310
furnished many of my materials, and often did my human nature turn with loathing from my occupation.

01:31:45.790 --> 01:31:51.810
While still urged on by an eagerness which perpetually increased, I brought my work near

01:31:51.810 --> 01:31:56.130
to a conclusion. The summer months passed while I was thus engaged, half and soul,

01:31:56.170 --> 01:32:01.350
in one pursuit. It was a most beautiful season, never did the fields bestow a more plentiful

01:32:01.350 --> 01:32:06.230
harvest or the vines yield a more luxuriant vintage. I brought my work near to a conclusion.

01:32:06.810 --> 01:32:11.150
The summer months passed while I was thus engaged, half and soul, in one pursuit. It

01:32:11.150 --> 01:32:15.810
was a most beautiful season, never did the fields bestow a more plentiful harvest nor

01:32:15.810 --> 01:32:21.130
the vines yield a luxurious vintage, but my eyes were insensible to the charms of nature.

01:32:21.810 --> 01:32:26.170
And the same feelings which made me neglect the scenes around me caused me also to forget

01:32:26.170 --> 01:32:31.470
those friends who were so many miles absent, and whom I had not seen for so long a time.

01:32:32.270 --> 01:32:36.790
I knew my silence disquieted them, and I well remembered the words of my father.

01:32:37.550 --> 01:32:43.110
I know that while you are pleased with yourself you will think of us with affection, and we

01:32:43.110 --> 01:32:44.610
shall hear regularly from you.

01:32:45.070 --> 01:32:50.710
You must pardon me if I regard any interruption in your correspondence as a proof that your

01:32:50.710 --> 01:32:52.290
other duties are equally neglected.

01:32:53.490 --> 01:32:58.270
I knew well, therefore, what would be my father's feelings, but I could not tear my thoughts

01:32:58.270 --> 01:33:03.490
from my employment, loathsome in itself, but which had taken an irresistible hold of my

01:33:03.490 --> 01:33:04.030
imagination.

01:33:04.950 --> 01:33:09.830
I wished, as it were, to procrastinate all that related to my feelings of affection until

01:33:09.830 --> 01:33:14.490
the great object, which swallowed up every habit of my nature, should be completed.

01:33:15.270 --> 01:33:21.350
I then thought my father would be unjust if he ascribed my neglect to vice or faultiness

01:33:21.350 --> 01:33:26.070
on my part, but I am now convinced that he was justified in conceiving that I should

01:33:26.070 --> 01:33:27.850
not be altogether free from blame.

01:33:28.830 --> 01:33:34.210
A human being in perfection ought always to preserve a calm and peaceful mind, and never

01:33:34.210 --> 01:33:38.410
allow passion or a transitory desire to disturb his tranquillity.

01:33:39.330 --> 01:33:42.730
I do not think that the pursuit of knowledge is an exception to this rule.

01:33:43.370 --> 01:33:48.050
If the study to which you apply yourself has a tendency to weaken your affections and to

01:33:48.050 --> 01:33:53.810
destroy your taste for those simple pleasures in which no alloy can possibly mix, then that

01:33:53.810 --> 01:33:58.930
study is certainly unlawful, that is to say, not befitting the human mind.

01:34:00.030 --> 01:34:05.410
If this rule were always observed, if no man allowed any pursuit whatsoever to interfere

01:34:05.410 --> 01:34:11.550
with the tranquillity of his domestic affections, Greece had not been enslaved, Caesar would

01:34:11.550 --> 01:34:16.670
have spared his country, America would have been discovered more gradually, and the empires

01:34:16.670 --> 01:34:19.310
of Mexico and Peru had not been destroyed.

01:34:21.330 --> 01:34:25.710
But I forget that I am moralizing in the most interesting part of my tale, and your looks

01:34:25.710 --> 01:34:26.730
remind me to proceed.

01:34:27.990 --> 01:34:33.110
My father made no reproach in his letters, and only took notice of my silence by inquiring

01:34:33.110 --> 01:34:35.770
into my occupations more particularly than before.

01:34:36.470 --> 01:34:41.610
Winter, spring, and summer passed away during my labours, but I did not watch the blossom

01:34:41.610 --> 01:34:48.310
on the expanding leaves, sights which before always yielded me supreme delight, so deeply

01:34:48.310 --> 01:34:49.910
was I engrossed in my occupation.

01:34:51.270 --> 01:34:56.930
The leaves of that year had withered before my work drew near a close, and now every day

01:34:56.930 --> 01:34:59.290
showed me more plainly how well I had succeeded.

01:35:00.290 --> 01:35:05.470
But my enthusiasm was checked by my anxiety, and I appeared rather like one doomed by

01:35:05.470 --> 01:35:11.470
slavery to toil in the mines, or any other unwholesome trade, than an artist occupied

01:35:11.470 --> 01:35:12.690
by his favourite employment.

01:35:13.450 --> 01:35:18.530
Every night I was oppressed by a slow fever, and I became nervous to a most painful degree.

01:35:19.210 --> 01:35:23.710
The fall of a leaf startled me, and I shunned my fellow creatures as if I had been guilty

01:35:23.710 --> 01:35:24.370
of a crime.

01:35:24.370 --> 01:35:31.430
Sometimes I grew alarmed at the wreck I perceived that I had become, and the energy of my purpose

01:35:31.430 --> 01:35:32.710
alone sustained me.

01:35:33.390 --> 01:35:37.550
My labours would soon end, and I believed that exercise and amusement would then drive

01:35:37.550 --> 01:35:42.790
away incipient disease, and I promised myself both of these when my creation should be complete.

01:36:07.330 --> 01:36:17.430
This is Frankenstein or the Modern Prometheus by Mary Wollstonecraft Godwin Shelley.

01:36:38.550 --> 01:36:40.870
It was already one in the morning.

01:36:41.710 --> 01:36:46.330
The rain pattered dismally against the panes and my candle was nearly burnt out.

01:36:47.370 --> 01:36:53.230
When by the glimmer of the half extinguished light I saw the dull yellow eye of the creature open.

01:36:54.370 --> 01:36:58.870
It breathed hard and a convulsive motion agitated its limbs.

01:37:00.730 --> 01:37:03.910
How can I describe my emotions at this catastrophe?

01:37:03.910 --> 01:37:09.830
Or how delineate the wretch whom with such infinite pains and care I had endeavored to form.

01:37:10.970 --> 01:37:16.370
His limbs were in proportion and I had selected his features as beautiful.

01:37:17.750 --> 01:37:24.690
Beautiful, great God! His yellow skin scarcely covered the work of muscles and arteries beneath.

01:37:25.910 --> 01:37:31.210
His hair was of a lustrous black and flowing, his teeth of a pearly whiteness.

01:37:31.210 --> 01:37:42.250
But these luxuriances only formed a more horrid contrast with his watery eyes that seemed almost of the same color as the done white sockets in which they were set.

01:37:42.890 --> 01:37:46.310
His shriveled complexion and straight black lips.

01:37:48.010 --> 01:37:52.310
The different accidents of life are not so changeable as the feelings of human nature.

01:37:53.250 --> 01:38:01.010
I had worked hard for nearly two years for the sole purpose of infusing life into an inanimate body.

01:38:02.270 --> 01:38:05.910
For this I had deprived myself of rest and health.

01:38:07.250 --> 01:38:10.730
I had desired it with an ardor that far exceeded moderation.

01:38:11.670 --> 01:38:20.330
But now that I had finished, the beauty of the dream vanished and breathless horror and disgust filled my heart.

01:38:21.330 --> 01:38:32.990
Unable to endure the aspect of the being I had created, I rushed out of the room and continued a long time traversing my bedchamber, unable to compose my mind to sleep.

01:38:35.170 --> 01:38:46.350
At length, lassitude succeeded to the tumult I had before endured, and I threw myself on the bed in my clothes, endeavoring to seek a few moments of forgetfulness.

01:38:47.370 --> 01:38:54.970
But it was in vain. I slept, indeed. But I was disturbed by the wildest dreams.

01:38:55.990 --> 01:39:01.070
I thought I saw Elizabeth in the bloom of health, walking in the streets of Ingolstadt.

01:39:02.890 --> 01:39:11.030
Delighted and surprised, I embraced her. But as I imprinted the first kiss on her lips, they became livid with the hue of death.

01:39:11.790 --> 01:39:17.290
Her features appeared to change, and I thought that I held the corpse of my dead mother in my arms.

01:39:18.870 --> 01:39:24.170
A shroud enveloped her form, and I saw the grave worms crawling in the folds of the flannel.

01:39:25.570 --> 01:39:35.270
I started from my sleep with horror. A cold dew covered my forehead, my teeth chattered, and every limb became convulsed.

01:39:35.270 --> 01:39:47.670
When by the dim and yellow light of the moon, as it forced its way through the window shutters, I beheld the wretch, the miserable monster whom I had created.

01:39:49.070 --> 01:39:56.910
He held up the curtain of the bed, and his eyes, if eyes they may be called, were fixed on me.

01:39:57.730 --> 01:40:05.270
His jaws opened, and he muttered some inarticulate sounds, while a grin wrinkled his cheeks.

01:40:06.790 --> 01:40:09.290
He might have spoken, but I did not hear.

01:40:10.810 --> 01:40:17.250
One hand was stretched out, seemingly to detain me, but I escaped and rushed downstairs.

01:40:19.210 --> 01:40:26.070
I took refuge in the courtyard belonging to the house which I inhabited, where I remained during the rest of the night.

01:40:26.070 --> 01:40:39.950
Walking up and down in the greatest agitation, listening attentively, catching and fearing each sound, as if it were to announce the approach of the demoniacal corpse to which I had so miserably given life.

01:40:41.390 --> 01:40:50.250
Oh, no mortal could support the horror of that countenance. A mummy again endued with animation could not be so hideous as that wretch.

01:40:51.210 --> 01:41:04.610
I had gazed on him while unfinished. He was ugly then, but when those muscles and joints were rendered capable of motion, it became a thing such as even Dante could not have conceived.

01:41:06.990 --> 01:41:15.610
I passed the night wretchedly. Sometimes my pulse beat so quickly and hardly that I felt the palpitation of every artery.

01:41:16.930 --> 01:41:22.490
At others, I nearly sank to the ground through languor and extreme weakness.

01:41:24.290 --> 01:41:35.210
Mingled with this horror, I felt the bitterness of disappointment. Dreams that had been my food and pleasant rest for so long a space were now become a hell to me.

01:41:35.210 --> 01:41:40.530
And the change was so rapid, the overthrow so complete.

01:41:41.590 --> 01:41:52.790
Mourning, dismal and wet, at length dawned, and discovered to my sleepless and aching eyes the church of Ingolstadt, its white steeple and clock which indicated the sixth hour.

01:41:53.950 --> 01:42:08.630
The porter opened the gates of the court, which had that night been my asylum, and I issued into the streets, pacing them with quick steps, as if I sought to avoid the wretch whom I feared every turning of the street would present to my view.

01:42:09.990 --> 01:42:21.070
I did not dare return to the apartment which I inhabited, but felt impelled to hurry on, although drenched by the rain which poured from a black and comfortless sky.

01:42:22.790 --> 01:42:30.670
I continued walking in this manner for some time, endeavouring by bodily exercise to ease the load that weighed upon my mind.

01:42:31.870 --> 01:42:36.530
I traversed the streets without any clear conception of where I was or what I was doing.

01:42:38.030 --> 01:42:45.870
My heart palpitated in the sickness of fear, and I hurried on with irregular steps, not daring to look about me.

01:42:47.630 --> 01:43:00.810
Like one who on a lonely road doth walk in fear and dread, and having once turned round walks on and turns no more his head, because he knows a frightful fiend doth close behind him tread.

01:43:01.730 --> 01:43:03.750
Coleridge's Ancient Mariner

01:43:05.310 --> 01:43:12.510
Continuing thus, I came at length opposite to the inn at which the various diligences and carriages usually stopped.

01:43:13.250 --> 01:43:22.650
Here I paused, I knew not why, but I remained some minutes with my eyes fixed on a coach that was coming towards me from the other end of the street.

01:43:24.070 --> 01:43:28.110
As it drew nearer, I observed that it was the Swiss diligence.

01:43:29.370 --> 01:43:37.750
It stopped just where I was standing, and on the door being opened, I perceived Henry Clairvaux, who on seeing me instantly sprung out.

01:43:37.750 --> 01:43:42.830
My dear Frankenstein, exclaimed he, how glad I am to see you.

01:43:43.170 --> 01:43:47.810
How fortunate that you should be here at the very moment of my alighting.

01:43:48.370 --> 01:43:50.790
Nothing could equal my delight on seeing Clairvaux.

01:43:51.430 --> 01:43:58.790
His presence brought back to my thoughts my father, Elizabeth, and all those scenes of home so dear to my recollection.

01:43:59.590 --> 01:44:04.430
I grasped his hand, and in a moment forgot my horror and misfortune.

01:44:05.150 --> 01:44:11.130
I felt suddenly, and for the first time during many months, calm and serene joy.

01:44:12.650 --> 01:44:17.810
I welcomed my friend therefore in the most cordial manner, and we walked towards my college.

01:44:19.390 --> 01:44:27.110
Clairvaux continued talking for some time about our mutual friends, and his own good fortune in being permitted to come to Ingolstadt.

01:44:28.010 --> 01:44:38.050
You may easily believe, said he, how great was the difficulty to persuade my father that all necessary knowledge was not comprised in the noble art of bookkeeping.

01:44:38.890 --> 01:44:50.290
And indeed, I believe I left him incredulous to the last, for his constant answer to my unwearied entreaties was the same as that of the Dutch schoolmaster in the vicar of Wakefield.

01:44:51.270 --> 01:44:56.450
I have ten thousand florins a year without Greek. I eat heartily without Greek.

01:44:57.730 --> 01:45:05.910
But his affection for me at length overcame his dislike of learning, and he has permitted me to undertake a voyage of discovery to the land of knowledge.

01:45:08.030 --> 01:45:14.090
It gives me the greatest delight to see you, but tell me how you left my father, brothers, and Elizabeth.

01:45:15.350 --> 01:45:21.150
Very well and very happy. Only a little uneasy that they hear from you so seldom.

01:45:22.970 --> 01:45:26.950
By the by, I mean to lecture you a little upon their account myself.

01:45:27.850 --> 01:45:37.190
But, my dear Frankenstein, continued he, stopping short and gazing full in my face, I did not before remark how very ill you appear.

01:45:37.890 --> 01:45:43.190
So thin and pale. You look as if you had been watching for several nights.

01:45:45.030 --> 01:45:55.410
You have guessed right. I have lately been so deeply engaged in one occupation that I have not allowed myself sufficient rest, as you see.

01:45:56.610 --> 01:46:04.530
But I hope, I sincerely hope, that all these employments are now at an end, and that I am at length free.

01:46:05.290 --> 01:46:14.450
I trembled excessively. I could not endure to think of, and far less to allude to, the occurrences of the preceding night.

01:46:15.790 --> 01:46:19.970
I walked with a quick pace, and we soon arrived at my college.

01:46:21.330 --> 01:46:30.870
I then reflected, and the thought made me shiver, that the creature whom I had left in my apartment might still be there, alive and walking about.

01:46:31.750 --> 01:46:38.150
I dreaded to behold this monster, but I feared still more that Henry should see him.

01:46:39.330 --> 01:46:45.790
Entreating him, therefore, to remain a few minutes at the bottom of the stairs, I darted up towards my own room.

01:46:46.830 --> 01:46:50.890
My hand was already on the lock of the door before I recollected myself.

01:46:52.590 --> 01:46:56.250
I then paused, and a cold shivering came over me.

01:46:56.910 --> 01:47:05.470
I threw the door forcibly open, as children are accustomed to do when they expect a specter to stand in waiting for them on the other side.

01:47:05.950 --> 01:47:10.350
But nothing appeared. I stepped fearfully in.

01:47:11.130 --> 01:47:15.090
The apartment was empty, and my bedroom was also freed from its hideous guest.

01:47:15.970 --> 01:47:20.510
I could hardly believe that so great a good fortune could have befallen me.

01:47:20.510 --> 01:47:28.270
But when I became assured that my enemy had indeed fled, I clapped my hands for joy and ran down to Clairvaux.

01:47:30.470 --> 01:47:34.910
We ascended into my room, and the servant presently brought breakfast.

01:47:35.570 --> 01:47:37.750
But I was unable to contain myself.

01:47:39.030 --> 01:47:41.730
It was not joy only that possessed me.

01:47:42.170 --> 01:47:47.770
I felt my flesh tingle with excess of sensitiveness, and my pulse beat rapidly.

01:47:48.790 --> 01:47:52.870
I was unable to remain for a single instant in the same place.

01:47:53.390 --> 01:47:56.470
I jumped over the chairs, clapped my hands, and laughed aloud.

01:47:57.570 --> 01:48:02.030
Clairvaux at first attributed my unusual spirits to joy on his arrival.

01:48:02.890 --> 01:48:10.010
But when he observed me more attentively, he saw a wildness in my eyes for which he could not account.

01:48:10.590 --> 01:48:16.150
And my loud, unrestrained, heartless laughter frightened and astonished him.

01:48:17.250 --> 01:48:22.090
My dear Victor, cried he, what for God's sake is the matter?

01:48:23.010 --> 01:48:27.950
Do not laugh in that manner. How ill you are! What is the cause of all this?

01:48:28.870 --> 01:48:36.270
Do not ask me, cried I, putting my hands before my eyes, for I thought I saw the dreaded specter glide into the room.

01:48:37.250 --> 01:48:41.810
He can tell. Oh, save me! Save me!

01:48:41.810 --> 01:48:48.290
I imagined that the monster seized me. I struggled furiously and fell down in a fit.

01:48:49.490 --> 01:48:53.490
Poor Clairvaux, what must have been his feelings?

01:48:54.410 --> 01:48:59.790
A meeting which he anticipated with such joy so strangely turned to bitterness.

01:49:00.730 --> 01:49:09.070
But I was not the witness of his grief, for I was lifeless and did not recover my senses for a long, long time.

01:49:11.730 --> 01:49:16.510
This was the commencement of a nervous fever which confined me for several months.

01:49:17.730 --> 01:49:20.330
During all that time Henry was my only nurse.

01:49:21.610 --> 01:49:26.910
I afterwards learned that knowing my father's advanced age and unfitness for so long a journey,

01:49:27.530 --> 01:49:34.450
and how wretched my sickness would make Elizabeth, he spared them this grief by concealing the extent of my disorder.

01:49:35.650 --> 01:49:40.130
He knew that I could not have a more kind and attentive nurse than himself.

01:49:41.510 --> 01:49:51.870
And, firm in the hope he felt of my recovery, he did not doubt that, instead of doing harm, he performed the kindest action that he could towards them.

01:49:53.630 --> 01:50:02.410
But I was in reality very ill, and surely nothing but the unbounded and unremitting attentions of my friend could have restored me to life.

01:50:03.330 --> 01:50:12.050
The form of the monster on whom I had bestowed existence was forever before my eyes, and I raved incessantly concerning him.

01:50:13.210 --> 01:50:15.310
Doubtless my words surprised Henry.

01:50:16.990 --> 01:50:21.230
He at first believed them to be the wanderings of my disturbed imagination,

01:50:21.990 --> 01:50:32.670
but the pertinacity with which I continually recurred to the same subject persuaded him that my disorder indeed owed its origin to some uncommon and terrible event.

01:50:34.710 --> 01:50:41.650
By very slow degrees, and with frequent relapses that alarmed and grieved my friend, I recovered.

01:50:42.750 --> 01:50:48.130
I remember the first time I became capable of observing outward objects with any kind of pleasure.

01:50:49.350 --> 01:50:55.490
I perceived that the fallen leaves had disappeared and that the young buds were shooting forth from the trees that shaded my window.

01:50:56.970 --> 01:51:01.470
It was a divine spring, and the season contributed greatly to my convalescence.

01:51:04.210 --> 01:51:07.870
I felt also sentiments of joy and affection revive in my bosom.

01:51:08.550 --> 01:51:14.970
My gloom disappeared, and in a short time I became as cheerful as before I was attacked by the fatal passion.

01:51:16.590 --> 01:51:22.770
Dearest Clairvaux, exclaimed I, how kind, how very good you are to me.

01:51:23.770 --> 01:51:31.310
This whole winter, instead of being spent in study as you promised yourself, has been consumed in my sick room.

01:51:32.130 --> 01:51:34.190
How shall I ever repay you?

01:51:34.190 --> 01:51:42.090
I feel the greatest remorse for the disappointment of which I have been the occasion, but you will forgive me.

01:51:44.030 --> 01:51:49.930
You will repay me entirely if you do not discompose yourself, but get well as fast as you can.

01:51:50.330 --> 01:51:55.890
And since you appear in such good spirits, I may speak to you on one subject, may I not?

01:51:56.790 --> 01:52:01.670
I trembled. One subject? What could it be?

01:52:02.350 --> 01:52:05.870
Could he allude to an object on whom I dared not even think?

01:52:07.530 --> 01:52:10.910
Compose yourself, said Clairvaux, who observed my change of colour.

01:52:11.730 --> 01:52:14.490
I will not mention it if it agitates you.

01:52:14.930 --> 01:52:19.750
But your father and cousin would be very happy if they received a letter from you in your own handwriting.

01:52:21.170 --> 01:52:24.910
They hardly know how ill you have been, and are uneasy at your long silence.

01:52:26.450 --> 01:52:28.470
Is that all, my dear Henry?

01:52:28.870 --> 01:52:36.270
How could you suppose that my first thought would not fly towards those dear, dear friends whom I love, and who are so deserving of my love?

01:52:37.410 --> 01:52:45.110
If this is your present temper, my friend, you will perhaps be glad to see a letter that has been lying here some days for you.

01:52:45.230 --> 01:52:47.270
It is from your cousin, I believe.

01:53:15.970 --> 01:53:22.590
This is Frankenstein or The Modern Prometheus by Mary Wollstonecraft Godwin Shelley.

01:53:26.350 --> 01:53:30.770
Clairvaux then put the following letter into my hands. It was from my own Elizabeth.

01:53:31.650 --> 01:53:38.670
My dearest cousin, you have been ill, very ill, and even the constant letters of dear kind Henry

01:53:38.670 --> 01:53:45.070
are not sufficient to reassure me on your account. You are forbidden to write, to hold a pen.

01:53:45.850 --> 01:53:50.170
Yet one word from you, dear Victor, is necessary to calm our apprehensions.

01:53:50.910 --> 01:53:54.650
For a long time I have thought that each post would bring this line,

01:53:54.890 --> 01:53:58.970
and my persuasions have restrained my uncle from undertaking a journey to Ingolstadt.

01:53:59.990 --> 01:54:05.370
I have prevented his encountering the inconveniences and perhaps dangers of so long a journey.

01:54:06.110 --> 01:54:09.810
Yet how often have I regretted not being able to perform it myself?

01:54:10.550 --> 01:54:16.330
I figure to myself that the task of attending on your sickbed has devolved on some mercenary

01:54:16.890 --> 01:54:22.290
who could never guess your wishes nor minister to them with the care and affection of your poor

01:54:22.290 --> 01:54:28.130
cousin. Yet that is over now. Clairvaux writes that indeed you are getting better.

01:54:29.230 --> 01:54:33.650
I eagerly hope that you will confirm this intelligence soon in your own handwriting.

01:54:35.050 --> 01:54:42.130
Get well and return to us. You will find a happy, cheerful home and friends who love you dearly.

01:54:42.130 --> 01:54:46.290
Your father's health is vigorous, and he asks but to see you,

01:54:46.750 --> 01:54:52.350
but to be assured that you are well. And not a care will ever cloud his benevolent countenance.

01:54:53.790 --> 01:54:56.890
How pleased you would be to remark the improvement of our earnest.

01:54:57.650 --> 01:55:04.370
He is now 16 and full of activity and spirit. He is desirous to be a true Swiss and to enter

01:55:04.370 --> 01:55:10.810
into foreign service, but we cannot part with him, at least until his elder brother returns to us.

01:55:11.770 --> 01:55:16.470
My uncle is not pleased with the idea of a military career in a distant country,

01:55:16.790 --> 01:55:22.550
but Ernest never had your powers of application. He looks upon study as an odious fetter.

01:55:23.210 --> 01:55:29.230
His time is spent in the open air climbing the hills or rowing on the lake. I fear that he will

01:55:29.230 --> 01:55:33.670
become an idler unless we yield the point and permit him to enter on the profession which he

01:55:33.670 --> 01:55:39.830
has selected. Little alteration except the growth of our dear children has taken place since you

01:55:39.830 --> 01:55:47.790
left us. The blue lake and snow-clad mountains, they never change, and I think our placid home

01:55:47.790 --> 01:55:54.810
and our contented hearts are regulated by the same immutable laws. My trifling occupations take up

01:55:54.810 --> 01:56:01.250
my time and amuse me, and I am rewarded for any exertions by seeing none but happy kind faces

01:56:01.250 --> 01:56:08.070
around me. Since you left us, but one change has taken place in our little household.

01:56:09.250 --> 01:56:16.030
Do you remember on what occasion Justine Moritz entered our family? Probably you do not.

01:56:16.870 --> 01:56:22.850
I will relate her history, therefore, in a few words. Madame Moritz, her mother,

01:56:23.310 --> 01:56:26.710
was a widow with four children, of whom Justine was the third.

01:56:28.870 --> 01:56:33.670
This girl had always been the favourite of her father, but through a strange perversity,

01:56:33.670 --> 01:56:40.530
her mother could not endure her, and after the death of Monsieur Moritz, treated her very ill.

01:56:41.730 --> 01:56:46.450
My aunt observed this, and when Justine was twelve years of age,

01:56:46.870 --> 01:56:49.870
prevailed on her mother to allow her to live at our house.

01:56:51.150 --> 01:56:55.870
The republican institutions of our country have produced simpler and happier manners

01:56:55.870 --> 01:56:59.390
than those which prevail in the great monarchies that surround it.

01:57:00.110 --> 01:57:04.430
Hence there is less distinction between the several classes of its inhabitants,

01:57:05.250 --> 01:57:12.630
and the lower orders, being neither so poor nor so despised. Their manners are more refined and

01:57:12.630 --> 01:57:19.670
moral. A servant in Geneva does not mean the same thing as a servant in France and England.

01:57:21.190 --> 01:57:25.130
Justine, thus received in our family, learned the duties of a servant,

01:57:25.130 --> 01:57:31.550
a condition which, in our fortunate country, does not include the idea of ignorance and

01:57:31.550 --> 01:57:37.910
a sacrifice of the dignity of a human being. Justine, you may remember, was a great favourite

01:57:37.910 --> 01:57:45.390
of yours, and I recollect you once remarked that if you were in an ill humour, one glance from

01:57:45.390 --> 01:57:50.510
Justine could dissipate it, for the same reason that Ariosto gives concerning the beauty of

01:57:50.510 --> 01:57:58.670
Angelica. She looked so frank-hearted and happy. My aunt conceived a great attachment for her,

01:57:59.010 --> 01:58:04.050
by which she was induced to give her an education superior to that which she had first intended.

01:58:05.630 --> 01:58:11.610
This benefit was fully repaid. Justine was the most grateful little creature in the world.

01:58:12.750 --> 01:58:17.850
I do not mean that she made any professions. I never heard one pass her lips,

01:58:17.850 --> 01:58:21.530
but you could see by her eyes that she almost adored her protectress.

01:58:23.390 --> 01:58:27.470
Although her disposition was gay and in many respects inconsiderate,

01:58:27.850 --> 01:58:33.590
yet she paid the greatest attention to every gesture of my aunt. She thought her the model

01:58:33.590 --> 01:58:39.250
of all excellence and endeavoured to imitate her phraseology and manners, so that even now

01:58:39.250 --> 01:58:47.830
she often reminds me of her. When my dearest aunt died, everyone was too much occupied in their own

01:58:47.830 --> 01:58:53.050
grief to notice poor Justine, who had attended her during her illness with the most anxious

01:58:53.050 --> 01:59:00.150
affection. Poor Justine was very ill, but other trials were reserved for her.

01:59:01.470 --> 01:59:07.670
One by one her brothers and sister died, and her mother, with the exception of her neglected

01:59:07.670 --> 01:59:15.390
daughter, was left childless. The conscience of the woman was troubled. She began to think that

01:59:15.390 --> 01:59:20.730
deaths of her favourites was a judgment from heaven to chastise her partiality.

01:59:21.590 --> 01:59:26.790
She was a Roman Catholic, and I believe her confessor confirmed the idea which she had

01:59:26.790 --> 01:59:33.250
conceived. Accordingly, a few months after your departure for Ingolstadt,

01:59:33.810 --> 01:59:40.570
Justine was called home by her repentant mother. Poor girl! She wept when she quitted our house.

01:59:41.210 --> 01:59:47.130
She was much altered since the death of my aunt. Grief had given softness and a winning

01:59:47.130 --> 01:59:51.510
mildness to her manners, which had before been remarkable for vivacity.

01:59:53.010 --> 01:59:56.690
Nor was her residence at her mother's house of a nature to restore her gaiety.

01:59:57.690 --> 02:00:03.790
The poor woman was very vacillating in her repentance. She sometimes begged Justine to

02:00:03.790 --> 02:00:09.330
forgive her unkindness, but much oftener accused her of having caused the deaths of her brothers

02:00:09.330 --> 02:00:15.570
and sister. Perpetual fretting at length threw Madame Moritz into a decline,

02:00:16.130 --> 02:00:21.110
which at first increased her irritability. But she is now at peace forever.

02:00:23.210 --> 02:00:27.530
She died on the first approach of cold weather at the beginning of this last winter.

02:00:28.990 --> 02:00:32.950
Justine has just returned to us, and I assure you I love her tenderly.

02:00:33.730 --> 02:00:39.750
She is very clever and gentle, and extremely pretty. As I mentioned before,

02:00:40.470 --> 02:00:44.550
her mind and her expression continually remind me of my dear aunt.

02:00:47.670 --> 02:00:52.030
I must say also a few words to you, my dear cousin of little darling William.

02:00:52.630 --> 02:00:58.850
I wish you could see him. He is very tall of his age, with sweet laughing blue eyes,

02:00:58.850 --> 02:01:05.190
dark eyelashes, and curling hair. When he smiles, two little dimples appear on each

02:01:05.190 --> 02:01:11.150
cheek, which are rosy with health. He has already had one or two little wives,

02:01:12.030 --> 02:01:16.930
but Louisa Byron is his favorite, a pretty little girl of five years of age.

02:01:18.790 --> 02:01:23.270
Now, dear Victor, I dare say you wish to be indulged in a little gossip concerning the

02:01:23.270 --> 02:01:29.330
people of Geneva. The pretty Miss Mansfield has already received the congratulatory

02:01:29.330 --> 02:01:34.410
visits on her approaching marriage with a young Englishman, John Melbourne Esquire.

02:01:35.250 --> 02:01:42.010
Her ugly sister Manon married Monsieur Duvalard, the rich banker, last autumn.

02:01:43.570 --> 02:01:53.250
Your favorite school fellow, Louis Manoir, has suffered several misfortunes since the

02:01:53.250 --> 02:01:57.270
He has already recovered his spirits and is reported to be on the point of marrying

02:01:57.270 --> 02:02:04.950
a lively pretty French woman, Madame Tavernier. She is a widow and much older than Manoir,

02:02:05.050 --> 02:02:08.250
but she is very much admired and a favorite with everybody.

02:02:10.510 --> 02:02:16.130
I have written myself into better spirits, dear cousin, but my anxiety returns upon me

02:02:16.130 --> 02:02:22.450
as I conclude. Right, dearest Victor, one line, one word will be a blessing to us.

02:02:23.170 --> 02:02:29.430
Ten thousand thanks to Henry for his kindness, his affection, and his many letters. We are

02:02:29.430 --> 02:02:37.490
sincerely grateful. Adieu, my cousin, take care of yourself, and I entreat you. Right.

02:02:40.090 --> 02:02:45.330
Elizabeth Lavenza, Geneva, March 18th, 17.

02:02:48.710 --> 02:02:54.310
Dear, dear Elizabeth, I exclaimed when I had read her letter. I will write instantly and relieve

02:02:54.310 --> 02:03:03.090
them from the anxiety they must feel. I wrote, and this exertion greatly fatigued me, but my

02:03:03.090 --> 02:03:09.290
convalescence had commenced and proceeded regularly. In another fortnight, I was able to leave my

02:03:09.290 --> 02:03:15.310
chamber. One of my first duties on my recovery was to write a letter to my mother.

02:03:15.310 --> 02:03:19.030
My next duty was to introduce Clairvaux to the several professors of the university.

02:03:20.750 --> 02:03:26.510
In doing this, I underwent a kind of rough usage, ill befitting the wounds that my mind had

02:03:26.510 --> 02:03:33.930
sustained. Ever since the fatal night, the end of my labors and the beginning of my misfortunes,

02:03:34.370 --> 02:03:38.470
I had conceived a violent antipathy even to the name of natural philosophy.

02:03:40.350 --> 02:03:45.190
When I was otherwise quite restored to health, the sight of a chemical instrument would renew

02:03:45.190 --> 02:03:52.710
all the agony of my nervous symptoms. Henry saw this, and had removed all my apparatus from my

02:03:52.710 --> 02:04:00.630
view. He had also changed my apartment, for he perceived that I had acquired a dislike for the

02:04:00.630 --> 02:04:07.330
room which had previously been my laboratory. But these cares of Clairvaux were made of no avail

02:04:07.330 --> 02:04:13.350
when I visited the professors. Mr. Waldman inflicted torture when he praised, with kindness

02:04:13.350 --> 02:04:20.670
and warmth, the astonishing progress I had made in the sciences. He soon perceived that I disliked

02:04:20.670 --> 02:04:27.350
the subject, but not guessing the real cause, he attributed my feelings to modesty and changed

02:04:27.350 --> 02:04:33.970
the subject from my improvement to the science itself, with a desire, as I evidently saw,

02:04:33.990 --> 02:04:41.270
of drawing me out. What could I do? He meant to please, and he tormented me.

02:04:42.070 --> 02:04:48.010
I felt as if he had placed carefully, one by one, in my view, those instruments which were to be

02:04:48.010 --> 02:04:56.050
afterwards used in putting me to a slow and cruel death. I writhed under his words, yet dared not

02:04:56.050 --> 02:05:03.390
exhibit the pain I felt. Clairvaux, whose eyes and feelings were always quick in discerning the

02:05:03.390 --> 02:05:11.030
sensations of others, declined the subject, alleging in excuse his total ignorance, and the

02:05:11.030 --> 02:05:17.950
conversation took a more general turn. I thanked my friend from my heart, but I did not speak.

02:05:19.130 --> 02:05:24.730
I saw plainly that he was surprised, but he never attempted to draw my secret from me.

02:05:25.470 --> 02:05:29.690
And although I loved him with a mixture of affection and reverence that knew no bounds,

02:05:30.310 --> 02:05:35.310
yet I could never persuade myself to confide in him that event which was so often present

02:05:35.310 --> 02:05:42.370
to my recollection, but which I feared the detail to another would only impress more deeply.

02:05:46.210 --> 02:05:51.630
M. Crimp was not equally docile, and in my condition at that time of almost

02:05:51.630 --> 02:05:57.490
insupportable sensitiveness, his harsh blunt encomiums gave me even more pain than the

02:05:57.490 --> 02:06:04.410
benevolent approbation of M. Waldman. Damn the fellow, cried he! Why, M. Clairvaux, I assure

02:06:04.410 --> 02:06:10.810
you he has outstripped us all. Ay, stare if you please, but it is nevertheless true.

02:06:11.910 --> 02:06:17.290
A youngster who but a few years ago believed in Cornelius Agrippa as firmly as in the Gospel

02:06:17.290 --> 02:06:23.890
has now set himself at the head of the university. And if he is not soon pulled down,

02:06:24.090 --> 02:06:30.410
we shall all be out of countenance. Ay, ay, continued he, observing my face expressive of

02:06:30.410 --> 02:06:36.090
suffering, M. Frankenstein is modest, an excellent quality in a young man.

02:06:37.230 --> 02:06:43.210
Young men should be diffident of themselves, you know, M. Clairvaux. I was myself when young,

02:06:43.430 --> 02:06:50.470
but that wears out in a very short time. M. Crimp had now commenced a eulogy on himself,

02:06:50.930 --> 02:06:54.630
which happily turned the conversation from a subject that was so annoying to me.

02:06:56.710 --> 02:07:02.390
Clairvaux had never sympathized in my tastes for natural science, and his literary pursuits

02:07:02.390 --> 02:07:08.670
differed wholly from those which had occupied me. He came to the university with the design of

02:07:08.670 --> 02:07:14.650
making himself complete master of the Oriental languages, and thus he should open a field for

02:07:14.650 --> 02:07:21.990
the plan of life he had marked out for himself. Resolved to pursue no inglorious career,

02:07:21.990 --> 02:07:27.270
he turned his eyes toward the east, as affording scope for his spirit of enterprise.

02:07:28.370 --> 02:07:32.790
The Persian, Arabic, and Sanskrit languages engaged his attention,

02:07:33.230 --> 02:07:36.310
and I was easily induced to enter on the same studies.

02:07:38.030 --> 02:07:43.470
Idleness had ever been irksome to me, and now that I wished to fly from reflection and hated my

02:07:43.470 --> 02:07:50.370
former studies, I felt great relief in being the fellow pupil with my friend, and found not only

02:07:50.370 --> 02:07:58.010
instruction, but consolation in the works of the Orientalists. I did not, like him, attempt a

02:07:58.010 --> 02:08:02.770
critical knowledge of their dialects, for I did not contemplate making any other use of them than

02:08:02.770 --> 02:08:10.290
temporary amusement. I read merely to understand their meaning, and they well repaid my labors.

02:08:12.430 --> 02:08:18.070
Their melancholy is soothing and their joy elevating, to a degree I never experienced

02:08:18.070 --> 02:08:25.190
studying the authors of any other country. When you read their writings, life appears to consist

02:08:25.190 --> 02:08:32.570
in a warm sun and a garden of roses, in the smiles and frowns of a fair enemy, and the fire that

02:08:32.570 --> 02:08:39.110
consumes your own heart. How different from the manly and heroic poetry of Greece and Rome!

02:08:41.410 --> 02:08:47.350
Summer passed away in these occupations, and my return to Geneva was fixed for the latter end of

02:08:47.350 --> 02:08:54.510
autumn. But being delayed by several accidents, winter and snow arrived. The roads were deemed

02:08:54.510 --> 02:09:02.230
impassable, and my journey was retarded until the ensuing spring. I felt this delay very bitterly,

02:09:02.870 --> 02:09:09.790
for I longed to see my native town and my beloved friends. My return had only been delayed so long,

02:09:09.870 --> 02:09:14.810
from an unwillingness to leave Clairvaux in a strange place, before he had become acquainted

02:09:14.810 --> 02:09:22.190
with any of its inhabitants. The winter, however, was spent cheerfully, and although the spring was

02:09:22.190 --> 02:09:27.250
uncommonly late, when it came, its beauty compensated for its dilatoriness.

02:09:30.130 --> 02:09:34.890
The month of May had already commenced, and I expected the letter daily, which was to fix the

02:09:34.890 --> 02:09:40.390
date of my departure, when Henry proposed a pedestrian tour in the environs of Ingolstadt,

02:09:40.390 --> 02:09:44.670
that I might bid a personal farewell to the country I had so long inhabited.

02:09:45.990 --> 02:09:51.890
I acceded with pleasure to this proposition. I was fond of exercise, and Clairvaux had always

02:09:51.890 --> 02:09:56.750
been my favorite companion in the ramble of this nature that I had taken among the scenes of my

02:09:56.750 --> 02:10:06.230
native country. We passed a fortnight in these perambulations. My health and spirits had long

02:10:06.230 --> 02:10:11.730
been restored, and they gained additional strength from the salubrious air I breathed,

02:10:11.790 --> 02:10:16.330
the natural incidence of our progress, and the conversation of my friend.

02:10:17.830 --> 02:10:21.670
Study had before secluded me from the intercourse of my fellow creatures,

02:10:22.110 --> 02:10:27.650
and rendered me unsocial, but Clairvaux called forth the better feelings of my heart.

02:10:28.330 --> 02:10:33.550
He again taught me to love the aspect of nature and the cheerful faces of children.

02:10:34.450 --> 02:10:38.670
Excellent friend, how sincerely you did love me,

02:10:38.930 --> 02:10:42.670
and endeavored to elevate my mind until it was on a level with your own.

02:10:44.070 --> 02:10:49.910
A selfish pursuit had cramped and narrowed me, until your gentleness and affection warmed and

02:10:49.910 --> 02:10:57.970
opened my senses. I became the same happy creature who, a few years ago, loved and beloved by all,

02:10:57.970 --> 02:11:04.730
had no sorrow or care. When happy inanimate nature had the power of bestowing on me the

02:11:04.730 --> 02:11:11.450
most delightful sensations, a serene sky and verdant fields filled me with ecstasy.

02:11:13.150 --> 02:11:18.810
The present season was indeed divine. The flowers of spring bloomed in the hedges,

02:11:18.950 --> 02:11:24.850
while those of summer were already in bud. I was undisturbed by thoughts which during

02:11:24.850 --> 02:11:29.850
the preceding year had pressed upon me, notwithstanding my endeavors to throw them off,

02:11:30.170 --> 02:11:36.890
with an invincible burden. Henry rejoiced in my gaiety and searly sympathized in my feelings.

02:11:37.730 --> 02:11:42.610
He exerted himself to amuse me while he expressed the sensations that filled his soul.

02:11:44.010 --> 02:11:50.670
The resources of his mind on this occasion were truly astonishing. His conversation was full of

02:11:50.670 --> 02:11:57.230
imagination, and very often, in imitation of the Persian and Arabic writers, he invented tales of

02:11:57.230 --> 02:12:04.170
wonderful fancy and passion. At other times, he repeated my favorite poems or drew me out

02:12:04.170 --> 02:12:10.830
into arguments which he supported with great ingenuity. We returned to our college on a Sunday

02:12:10.830 --> 02:12:15.930
afternoon. The peasants were dancing, and everyone we met appeared gay and happy.

02:12:16.590 --> 02:12:23.250
My own spirits were high, and I bounded along with feelings of unbridled joy and hilarity.

02:12:49.230 --> 02:12:55.530
On my return, I found the following letter

02:12:55.530 --> 02:13:02.790
from my father. My dear Victor, you have probably waited impatiently for a letter to fix the date

02:13:02.790 --> 02:13:08.250
of your return to us, and I was at first tempted to write only a few lines, merely mentioning the

02:13:08.250 --> 02:13:14.670
day on which I should expect you. But that would be a cruel kindness, and I dare not do it. What

02:13:14.670 --> 02:13:20.790
would be your surprise, my son, when you expected a happy and glad welcome, to behold on the contrary

02:13:20.790 --> 02:13:28.010
tears and wretchedness? And how, Victor, can I relate our misfortune? Absence cannot have rendered

02:13:28.010 --> 02:13:34.330
you callous to our joys and griefs, and how shall I inflect pain on my long-absent son? I wish to

02:13:34.330 --> 02:13:40.710
prepare you for the woeful news, but I know it is impossible. Even now your eye skims over the page

02:13:40.710 --> 02:13:48.510
to seek the words which are to convey to you the horrible tidings. William is dead. That sweet child

02:13:48.510 --> 02:13:54.930
whose smiles delighted and warmed my heart, who was so gentle yet so gay. Victor, he is murdered.

02:13:56.090 --> 02:14:02.670
I will not attempt to console you, but will simply relate the circumstances of the transaction. Last

02:14:02.670 --> 02:14:09.710
Thursday, May the 7th, I, my niece, and your two brothers went to walk in Blancpale. The evening

02:14:09.710 --> 02:14:15.670
was warm and serene, and we prolonged our walk farther than usual. It was already dusk before

02:14:15.670 --> 02:14:20.090
we thought of returning, and then we discovered that William and Ernest, who had gone on before,

02:14:20.430 --> 02:14:26.910
were not to be found. We accordingly rested on a seat until they should return. Presently Ernest

02:14:26.910 --> 02:14:32.170
came and inquired if we had seen his brother. He said that he had been playing with him,

02:14:32.530 --> 02:14:37.290
that William had run away to hide himself, and that he vainly sought for him, and afterwards

02:14:37.290 --> 02:14:44.050
he waited a long time, but that he did not return. This account rather alarmed us, and we continued

02:14:44.050 --> 02:14:48.550
to search for him until night fell, when Elizabeth conjectured that he might have returned to the

02:14:48.550 --> 02:14:55.090
house. He was not there. We returned again with torches, for I could not rest when I thought

02:14:55.090 --> 02:14:59.790
that my sweet boy had lost himself and was exposed to all the damps and dews of night.

02:15:00.890 --> 02:15:07.250
Elizabeth also suffered extreme anguish. About five in the morning I discovered my lovely boy,

02:15:07.390 --> 02:15:12.150
whom the night before I had seen blooming and active in health, stretched on the grass,

02:15:12.150 --> 02:15:19.130
livid and motionless. The print of the murderer's finger was on his neck. He was conveyed home,

02:15:19.250 --> 02:15:24.790
and the anguish that was visible in my countenance betrayed the secret to Elizabeth. She was very

02:15:24.790 --> 02:15:30.930
earnest to see the corpse. At first I attempted to prevent her, but she persisted, and entering

02:15:30.930 --> 02:15:35.950
the room where it lay, hastily examined the neck of the victim, and clasping her hands,

02:15:35.950 --> 02:15:42.910
exclaimed, Oh, God, I have murdered my darling child. She fainted and was restored with extreme

02:15:42.910 --> 02:15:50.150
difficulty. When she again lived, it was only to weep and sigh. She told me that that same evening

02:15:50.150 --> 02:15:54.670
William had teased her to let him wear a very valuable miniature that she possessed of your

02:15:54.670 --> 02:16:00.010
mother. This picture is gone, and was doubtless the temptation which urged the murderer to the

02:16:00.010 --> 02:16:04.790
deed. We have no trace of him at present, although our exertions to discover him are

02:16:04.790 --> 02:16:12.030
remitted, but they will not restore my beloved William. Come, dearest Victor, you alone can

02:16:12.030 --> 02:16:17.390
console Elizabeth. She weeps continually and accuses herself unjustly as the cause of his

02:16:17.390 --> 02:16:23.690
death. Her words pierce my heart. We are all unhappy, but will not that be an additional

02:16:23.690 --> 02:16:29.890
motive for you, my son, to return and be our comforter? Your dear mother, alas, Victor,

02:16:29.890 --> 02:16:35.630
I now say thank God she did not live to witness the cruel, miserable death of her youngest darling.

02:16:36.770 --> 02:16:41.710
Come, Victor, not brooding thoughts of vengeance against the assassin, but with feelings of peace

02:16:41.710 --> 02:16:47.310
and gentleness that will heal instead of festering the wounds of our minds. Enter the house of

02:16:47.310 --> 02:16:52.190
mourning, my friend, but with kindness and affection for those who love you, and not with

02:16:52.190 --> 02:16:58.290
hatred for your enemies. Your affectionate and afflicted father, Alphonse Frankenstein,

02:16:58.290 --> 02:17:09.250
Geneva, May 12th, 17 blank blank. Clairvaux, who had watched my countenance as I read this

02:17:09.250 --> 02:17:13.950
letter, was surprised to observe the despair that succeeded the joy I had first expressed

02:17:13.950 --> 02:17:19.070
on receiving news from my friends. I threw the letter on the table and covered my face with my

02:17:19.070 --> 02:17:23.950
hands. My dear Frankenstein, exclaimed Henry when he perceived me weep with bitterness,

02:17:23.950 --> 02:17:30.370
Are you always to be unhappy? My dear friend, what has happened? I motioned him to take up the

02:17:30.370 --> 02:17:36.130
letter while I walked up and down the room in the extremist agitation. Tears also gushed from the

02:17:36.130 --> 02:17:41.190
eyes of Clairvaux as he read the account of my misfortune. I can offer you no consolation,

02:17:41.350 --> 02:17:48.490
my friend, said he. Your disaster is irreparable. What do you intend to do? To go instantly to

02:17:48.490 --> 02:17:54.590
Geneva. Come with me, Henry, to order the horses. During our walk, Clairvaux endeavoured to say a

02:17:54.590 --> 02:18:00.450
few words of consolation. He could only express his heartfelt sympathy. Poor William, said he.

02:18:00.770 --> 02:18:06.690
Dear lovely child, he now sleeps with his angel mother, who that had seen him bright and joyous

02:18:06.690 --> 02:18:13.030
in his young beauty, but must weep over his untimely loss. To die so miserably, to feel the

02:18:13.030 --> 02:18:18.930
how much more a murder that could destroy radiant innocence. Poor little fellow,

02:18:19.410 --> 02:18:26.290
one only consolation have we. His friends mourn and weep, but he is at rest. The pang is over,

02:18:26.730 --> 02:18:32.170
his sufferings are at an end forever. A sod covers his gentle form and he knows no pain.

02:18:32.730 --> 02:18:37.610
He can no longer be a subject for pity. We must reserve that for his miserable survivors.

02:18:38.890 --> 02:18:43.690
Clairvaux spoke thus as we hurried through the streets. The words impressed themselves on my

02:18:43.690 --> 02:18:49.070
mind and I remembered them afterwards in solitude. But now, as soon as the horses arrived,

02:18:49.450 --> 02:18:56.910
I hurried into a cabriolet and bade farewell to my friend. My journey was very melancholy. At first,

02:18:56.910 --> 02:19:02.190
I wished to hurry on, for I longed to console and sympathise with my loved and sorrowing friends,

02:19:02.190 --> 02:19:08.830
but when I drew near my native town, I slackened my progress. I could hardly sustain the multitude

02:19:08.830 --> 02:19:14.270
of feelings that crowded into my mind. I passed through scenes familiar to my youth, but which

02:19:14.270 --> 02:19:21.070
I had not seen for nearly six years. How altered everything might be during that time. One sudden

02:19:21.070 --> 02:19:25.730
and desolating change had taken place, but a thousand little circumstances might have done

02:19:25.730 --> 02:19:30.950
by degrees worked other alterations, which, although they were done more tranquilly,

02:19:30.950 --> 02:19:38.510
might not be the less decisive. Fear overcame me. I dared no advance, dreading a thousand nameless

02:19:38.510 --> 02:19:45.050
evils that made me tremble, although I was unable to define them. I remained two days at Lausanne,

02:19:45.430 --> 02:19:52.070
in this painful state of mind. I contemplated the lake. The waters were placid, all around was calm,

02:19:52.390 --> 02:19:58.590
and the snowy mountains, the palaces of nature, were not changed. By degrees the calm and heavenly

02:19:58.590 --> 02:20:05.890
scene restored me, and I continued my journey towards Geneva. The road ran by the side of the

02:20:05.890 --> 02:20:11.350
lake, which became narrower as I approached my native town. I discovered more distinctly the black

02:20:11.350 --> 02:20:18.290
sides of Jura and the bright summit of Mont Blanc. I wept like a child. Dear mountains,

02:20:18.570 --> 02:20:24.110
my own beautiful lake, how do you welcome your wanderer? Your summits are clear, the sky and

02:20:24.110 --> 02:20:31.250
the lake are blue and placid. Is this to prognosticate peace, or to mock at my unhappiness? I fear,

02:20:31.290 --> 02:20:35.670
my friend, that I shall render myself tedious by dwelling on these preliminary circumstances,

02:20:36.310 --> 02:20:41.150
but they were days of comparative happiness, and I think of them with pleasure. My country,

02:20:41.190 --> 02:20:46.250
my beloved country, who but a native can tell the delight I took in again beholding thy

02:20:46.250 --> 02:20:53.750
streams, thy mountains, and more than all, thy lovely lake? Yet, as I drew nearer home,

02:20:53.750 --> 02:21:00.290
grief and fear again overcame me. Night also closed around, and when I could hardly see the

02:21:00.290 --> 02:21:05.970
dark mountains I felt still more gloomily. The picture appeared a vast and dim scene of evil,

02:21:06.330 --> 02:21:10.870
and I foresaw obscurely that I was destined to become the most wretched of human beings.

02:21:11.850 --> 02:21:18.050
Alas, I prophesied truly, and failed only in one single circumstance, that in all the misery I

02:21:18.050 --> 02:21:22.550
imagined and dreaded I did not conceive the hundredth part of the anguish I was destined

02:21:22.550 --> 02:21:28.410
to endure. It was completely dark when I arrived in the environs of Geneva. The gates

02:21:28.410 --> 02:21:33.410
of the town were already shut, and I was obliged to pass the night at Zecharon, a village at the

02:21:33.410 --> 02:21:39.350
distance of Haffer League from the city. The sky was serene, and as I was unable to rest,

02:21:39.690 --> 02:21:44.170
I resolved to visit the spot where my poor William had been murdered. As I could not

02:21:44.170 --> 02:21:48.650
pass through the town, I was obliged to cross the lake in a boat to arrive at Plain Ballet.

02:21:49.350 --> 02:21:54.190
During this short voyage, I saw the lightning playing on the summit of Mont Blanc in the most

02:21:54.190 --> 02:22:00.430
beautiful figures. The storm appeared to approach rapidly, and on landing, I ascended a low hill

02:22:00.430 --> 02:22:06.350
that I might observe its progress. It advanced, the heavens were clouded, and I soon felt the

02:22:06.350 --> 02:22:12.910
rain coming slowly in large drops, but its violence quickly increased. I quitted my seat

02:22:12.910 --> 02:22:17.670
and walked on, although the darkness and storm increased every minute and the thunder burst

02:22:17.670 --> 02:22:23.790
with a terrific crash over my head. It was echoed from Salève, the Jures, and the Alps of Savoy.

02:22:24.550 --> 02:22:29.770
Vivid flashes of lightning dazzled my eyes, illuminating the lake, making it appear like

02:22:29.770 --> 02:22:35.210
a vast sheet of fire. Then, for an instant, everything seemed of a pitchy darkness until

02:22:35.210 --> 02:22:40.690
the eye recovered itself in the preceding flash. The storm, as is often the case in Switzerland,

02:22:41.210 --> 02:22:46.490
appeared at once in various parts of the heavens. The most violent storm hung exactly north of the

02:22:46.490 --> 02:22:51.710
town, over the part of the lake which lies between the promontory of Belle Rive and the village of

02:22:51.710 --> 02:22:57.750
Coppet. Another storm enlightened Jure with faint flashes, and another darkened and sometimes

02:22:57.750 --> 02:23:04.490
disclosed the mole, a peak mountain to the east of the lake. While I watched the tempests, so

02:23:04.490 --> 02:23:10.990
beautiful that terrific, I wandered on with a hasty step. This noble war in the sky elevated

02:23:10.990 --> 02:23:17.530
my spirits. I clasped my hands and exclaimed aloud, William, dear angel, this is thy funeral,

02:23:17.650 --> 02:23:23.630
this is thy dirge. As I said these words, I perceived in the gloom a figure which stole from

02:23:23.630 --> 02:23:30.750
behind a clump of trees near me. I stood fixed, gazing intently. I could not be mistaken. A flash

02:23:30.750 --> 02:23:36.310
of lightning illuminated the object and discovered its shape plainly to me, its gigantic stature,

02:23:36.310 --> 02:23:41.430
and the deformity of its aspect more hideous than belongs to humanity. Instantly informed

02:23:41.430 --> 02:23:47.230
me that it was the wretch, the filthy demon to whom I had given life. What did he there? Could

02:23:47.230 --> 02:23:53.650
he be, I shuddered the conception, the murderer of my brother? No sooner did that idea cross my

02:23:53.650 --> 02:23:59.430
imagination than I became convinced of its truth. My teeth chattered, and I was forced to lean

02:23:59.430 --> 02:24:07.030
against a tree for support. The figure passed me quickly, and I lost it in the gloom. Nothing

02:24:07.030 --> 02:24:13.190
in human shape could have destroyed the fair child. He was the murderer, I could not doubt it. The

02:24:13.190 --> 02:24:18.870
mere presence of the idea was an irresistible proof of the fact. I thought of pursuing the devil,

02:24:19.190 --> 02:24:23.730
but it would have been in vain, for another flash discovered him to me, hanging among the rocks of

02:24:23.730 --> 02:24:30.290
the nearly perpendicular ascent of Mount Salève, a hill that bounds Plain-Palais on the south. He

02:24:30.290 --> 02:24:37.870
soon reached the summit and disappeared. I remained motionless. The thunder ceased,

02:24:38.310 --> 02:24:43.450
but the rain still continued, and the scene was enveloped in an impenetrable darkness. I

02:24:43.450 --> 02:24:49.150
revolved in my mind the events which I had until now sought to forget. The whole train of my

02:24:49.150 --> 02:24:53.870
progress towards the creation, the appearance of the works of my own hands at my bedside,

02:24:54.270 --> 02:25:00.430
its departure. Two years had now nearly elapsed since the night on which he first received life,

02:25:00.930 --> 02:25:07.330
and was this his first crime? Alas, I had turned loose into the world a depraved wretch,

02:25:07.690 --> 02:25:12.230
whose delight was in carnage and misery. Had he not murdered my brother?

02:25:13.930 --> 02:25:17.890
No one can conceive the anguish I suffered during the remainder of the night,

02:25:17.890 --> 02:25:24.410
which I spent, cold and wet, in the open air. But I did not feel the inconvenience of the weather.

02:25:25.090 --> 02:25:30.870
My imagination was busy in scenes of evil and despair. I considered the being whom I had cast

02:25:30.870 --> 02:25:35.990
among mankind, and endowed with the will and power to effect purposes of horror such as the

02:25:35.990 --> 02:25:41.610
deity which he had now done, nearly in the light of my own vampire, my own spirit let loose from

02:25:41.610 --> 02:25:49.490
my grave, and forced to destroy all that was dear to me. Day dawned, and I directed my steps

02:25:49.490 --> 02:25:55.410
towards the town. The gates were open, and I hastened to my father's house. My first thought

02:25:55.410 --> 02:26:00.990
was to discover what I knew of the murderer, and cause instant pursuit to be made. But I paused

02:26:00.990 --> 02:26:07.230
when I reflected on the story that I had to tell. A being whom I myself had formed and endued with

02:26:07.230 --> 02:26:13.590
life had met me at midnight among the precipices of an inaccessible mountain. I remembered also the

02:26:13.590 --> 02:26:18.930
nervous fever with which I had been seized just at that time that I had dated my creation, and which

02:26:18.930 --> 02:26:24.910
would give an air of delirium to a tale otherwise so utterly improbable. I well knew that if any

02:26:24.910 --> 02:26:29.910
other had communicated such a revelation to me, I would have looked upon it as the ravings of an

02:26:29.910 --> 02:26:35.550
insanity. Besides, the strange nature of the animal would elude all pursuit, even if I were

02:26:35.550 --> 02:26:41.510
so far credited as to persuade my relatives to commence it, and then of what use would be pursuit,

02:26:41.890 --> 02:26:47.710
who could arrest a creature capable of scaling the overhanging sides of Mont-Saleve. These

02:26:47.710 --> 02:26:54.170
reflections determined me, and I resolved to remain silent. It was about five in the morning

02:26:54.170 --> 02:26:59.550
when I entered my father's house. I told the servants not to disturb the family, and went into

02:26:59.550 --> 02:27:06.550
the library to attend their usual hour of rising. Six years had elapsed, passed in a dream but for

02:27:06.550 --> 02:27:12.110
one indelible trace, and I stood in the same place where I had last embraced my father before my

02:27:12.110 --> 02:27:19.630
departure for Ingolstadt. Beloved and venerable parent, he still remained to me. I gazed on the

02:27:19.630 --> 02:27:25.010
picture of my mother, which stood over the mantelpiece. It was an historical subject,

02:27:25.010 --> 02:27:32.310
painted at my father's desire, and represented Caroline Beaufort in an agony of despair, kneeling

02:27:32.310 --> 02:27:38.630
by the coffin of her dead father. Her garb was rustic, and her cheek pale, but there was an air

02:27:38.630 --> 02:27:43.910
of dignity and beauty that hardly permitted the sentiment of pity. Below this picture was a

02:27:43.910 --> 02:27:49.790
miniature of William, and my tears flowed when I looked upon it. While I was thus engaged,

02:27:49.790 --> 02:27:53.630
Ernest entered. He had heard me arrive, and hastened to welcome me.

02:27:54.250 --> 02:27:59.290
Welcome, my dearest Victor, said he. Ah, I wish you had come three months ago, and then you would

02:27:59.290 --> 02:28:04.370
have found us all joyous and delighted. You come to us now to share a misery which nothing can

02:28:04.370 --> 02:28:10.370
alleviate, yet your presence will, I hope, revive our father, who seems sinking under his misfortune,

02:28:10.970 --> 02:28:16.150
and your persuasions will induce poor Elizabeth to cease her vain and tormenting self-accusations.

02:28:17.250 --> 02:28:19.970
Poor William, he was our darling and our pride.

02:28:22.990 --> 02:28:28.870
Tears, unrestrained, fell from my brother's eyes. A sense of mortal agony crept over my frame.

02:28:29.730 --> 02:28:35.470
Before, I had only imagined the wretchedness of my desolated home. The reality came on me as a new

02:28:35.470 --> 02:28:42.650
and not less terrible disaster. I tried to calm Ernest. I inquired more minutely concerning my

02:28:42.650 --> 02:28:50.670
father, and her I named my cousin. She, most of all, said Ernest, requires consolation. She accused

02:28:50.670 --> 02:28:55.870
herself of having caused the death of my brother, and that made her very wretched. But since the

02:28:55.870 --> 02:29:00.830
murderer has been discovered... The murderer discovered? Good God, how can that be? Who could

02:29:00.830 --> 02:29:06.170
attempt to pursue him? It is impossible. One might as well try to overtake the winds or combine a

02:29:06.770 --> 02:29:10.170
I saw him too. He was free last night.

02:29:11.670 --> 02:29:17.290
I do not know what you mean, replied my brother, in accents of wonder. But to us, the discovery we

02:29:17.290 --> 02:29:23.350
have made completes our misery. No one would believe it at first, and even now Elizabeth will

02:29:23.350 --> 02:29:29.450
not be convinced, notwithstanding all the evidence. Indeed, who would credit that Justine Moritz,

02:29:29.570 --> 02:29:35.390
who was so amiable and fond of all the family, could suddenly become so capable of so frightful,

02:29:35.390 --> 02:29:43.110
and so appalling a crime? Justine Moritz? Poor, poor girl, is she the accused? But it is wrongfully.

02:29:43.250 --> 02:29:49.510
Everyone knows that. No one believes it, surely, Ernest? No one did at first, but several

02:29:49.510 --> 02:29:54.390
circumstances came out that have almost forced conviction upon us, and her own behaviour has

02:29:54.390 --> 02:29:59.870
been so confused as to add to the evidence of facts a weight that, I fear, leaves no hope for

02:29:59.870 --> 02:30:03.770
doubt. But she will be tried today, and you will then hear all.

02:30:05.430 --> 02:30:10.130
He then related that, the morning on which the murderer of poor William had been discovered,

02:30:10.650 --> 02:30:16.230
Justine had been taken ill, and confined to her bed for several days. During this interval,

02:30:16.450 --> 02:30:20.470
one of the servants, happening to examine the apparel she had worn on the night of the murder,

02:30:20.990 --> 02:30:24.870
had discovered in her pocket the picture of my mother, which had been judged to be the

02:30:24.870 --> 02:30:28.970
temptation of the murderer. The servant instantly showed it to one of the others,

02:30:28.970 --> 02:30:34.410
who, without saying a word to any of the family, went to a magistrate, and upon their deposition,

02:30:34.690 --> 02:30:39.390
Justine was apprehended, on being charged with the fact the poor girl confirmed the suspicion,

02:30:39.630 --> 02:30:46.870
in a great measure, by her extreme confusion of manner. This was a strange tale, but it did not

02:30:46.870 --> 02:30:54.470
shake my faith, and I replied earnestly, You are all mistaken. I know the murderer. Justine, poor,

02:30:54.470 --> 02:31:03.050
Justine, is innocent. At that instant, my father entered. I saw unhappiness deeply impressed on

02:31:03.050 --> 02:31:08.190
his countenance, but he endeavoured to welcome me cheerfully, and, after we had exchanged our

02:31:08.190 --> 02:31:13.490
mournful greeting, would have introduced some other topic than that of our disaster, had not

02:31:13.490 --> 02:31:18.730
earnest exclaimed, Good God, Papa! Victor says that he knows who was the murderer of our poor

02:31:18.730 --> 02:31:25.930
William. We do also, unfortunately, replied my father, for indeed I had rather have been

02:31:25.930 --> 02:31:30.290
forever ignorant than have discovered so much depravity and ungratitude in one I valued so

02:31:30.290 --> 02:31:37.810
highly. My dear father, you are mistaken. Justine is innocent. If she is, God forbid that she should

02:31:37.810 --> 02:31:44.130
suffer as guilty. She is to be tried today, and I hope, I sincerely hope, that she will be acquitted.

02:31:45.990 --> 02:31:51.970
This speech calmed me. I was firmly convinced in my own mind that Justine, and indeed every human

02:31:51.970 --> 02:31:56.830
being, was guiltless of this murder. I had no fear, therefore, that any circumstantial evidence

02:31:56.830 --> 02:32:01.750
could be brought forward strong enough to convict her. My tale was not one to announce publicly.

02:32:02.350 --> 02:32:07.370
A astounding horror would be looked upon as madness by the vulgar. Did anyone indeed exist,

02:32:07.410 --> 02:32:12.730
except I, the creator, who would believe, unless his senses convinced him, in the existence of the

02:32:12.730 --> 02:32:19.490
living monument of presumption and rash ignorance which I had left loose upon the world? We were

02:32:19.490 --> 02:32:25.690
soon joined by Elizabeth. Time had altered her since I last beheld her. It had endowed her with

02:32:25.690 --> 02:32:31.370
loveliness, surpassing the beauty of her childish years. There was the same candour, the same vivacity,

02:32:31.870 --> 02:32:37.230
but it was a lie to an expression more full of sensibility and intellect. She welcomed me with

02:32:38.850 --> 02:32:44.790
Your arrival, my dear cousin, said she, fills me with hope. You perhaps will find some means to

02:32:44.790 --> 02:32:52.970
justify my poor guiltless Justine. Alas, who is safe if she can be convicted of crime? I rely on

02:32:52.970 --> 02:32:59.090
her innocence as certainly as I do upon my own. Our misfortune is doubly hard to us. We have not

02:32:59.090 --> 02:33:05.330
only lost that lovely darling boy, but this poor girl whom I sincerely love is to be torn away by

02:33:05.330 --> 02:33:13.170
even a worth fate. If she is condemned, I never shall know joy more. But she will not, I am sure

02:33:13.170 --> 02:33:18.630
she will not, and then I shall be happy again, even after the sad death of my little William.

02:33:20.170 --> 02:33:26.910
She is innocent, my Elizabeth, said I, and that shall be proved. Fear nothing, but let your spirits

02:33:26.910 --> 02:33:33.450
be cheered by the assurance of her acquittal. How kind and generous you are! Everyone else believes

02:33:33.450 --> 02:33:39.250
in her guilt, and that made me wretched, for I knew it was impossible, and to see everyone else

02:33:39.250 --> 02:33:46.290
prejudiced in so deadly a manner rendered me hopeless and despairing. She wept. Dearest niece,

02:33:46.630 --> 02:33:53.290
said my father, dry your tears. If she is, as you believe, innocent, rely on the justice of our laws

02:33:53.290 --> 02:34:00.170
and the activity with which I shall prevent the slightest shadow of partiality.

02:34:00.170 --> 02:34:10.450
recorded by Alex Foster, 15th of September, 2005, www.alexfoster.me.uk

02:34:36.630 --> 02:34:40.970
We passed a few sad hours until eleven o'clock, when the trial was to commence.

02:34:40.970 --> 02:34:46.990
My father and the rest of the family being obliged to attend as witnesses, I accompanied them to the court.

02:34:47.930 --> 02:34:52.030
During the whole of this wretched mockery of justice, I suffered living torture.

02:34:52.850 --> 02:35:00.150
It was to be decided whether the result of my curiosity and lawless devices would cause the death of two of my fellow beings,

02:35:00.610 --> 02:35:06.250
one a smiling babe full of innocence and joy, the other far more dreadfully murdered,

02:35:06.250 --> 02:35:11.670
with every aggravation of infamy that could make the murder memorable in horror.

02:35:13.250 --> 02:35:17.970
Justine also was a girl of merit and possessed qualities which promised to render her life happy.

02:35:18.570 --> 02:35:24.590
Now all was to be obliterated in an ignominious grave, and I the cause.

02:35:25.490 --> 02:35:30.590
A thousand times rather would I have confessed myself guilty of the crime ascribed to Justine,

02:35:30.590 --> 02:35:36.990
but I was absent when it was committed, and such a declaration would have been considered as the ravings of a madman,

02:35:37.110 --> 02:35:40.090
and would not have exculpated her who suffered through me.

02:35:42.490 --> 02:35:48.870
The appearance of Justine was calm. She was dressed in mourning, and her countenance, always engaging,

02:35:49.450 --> 02:35:53.130
was rendered by the solemnity of her feelings exquisitely beautiful.

02:35:53.130 --> 02:36:00.130
Yet she appeared confident in innocence and did not tremble, although gazed on and execrated by thousands,

02:36:00.550 --> 02:36:05.830
for all the kindness which her beauty might otherwise have excited was obliterated in the minds of the spectators

02:36:05.830 --> 02:36:09.510
by the imagination of the enormity she was supposed to have committed.

02:36:10.790 --> 02:36:14.510
She was tranquil, yet her tranquillity was evidently constrained,

02:36:15.070 --> 02:36:19.310
and as her confusion had before her been adduced as proof of her guilt,

02:36:20.190 --> 02:36:22.730
she worked up in her mind to an appearance of courage.

02:36:23.810 --> 02:36:28.770
When she entered the court, she threw her eyes round it, and quickly discovered where we were seated.

02:36:29.890 --> 02:36:34.290
A tear seemed to dim her eye when she saw us, but she quickly recovered herself,

02:36:34.730 --> 02:36:38.450
and a look of sorrowful affection seemed to attest her utter guiltlessness.

02:36:39.730 --> 02:36:46.090
The trial began, and after the advocate against her had stated the charge, several witnesses were called.

02:36:47.030 --> 02:36:53.810
Several strange facts combined against her, which might have staggered anyone who had not such proof of her innocence as I had.

02:36:54.710 --> 02:36:58.170
She had been out the whole of the night on which the murder had been committed,

02:36:58.570 --> 02:37:02.610
and towards morning had been perceived by a market woman not far from the spot

02:37:02.610 --> 02:37:05.430
where the body of the murdered child had been afterwards found.

02:37:05.950 --> 02:37:09.930
The woman asked her what she did there, but she looked very strangely,

02:37:10.410 --> 02:37:13.450
and only returned a confused and unintelligible answer.

02:37:14.310 --> 02:37:19.410
She returned to the house about eight o'clock, and when one inquired where she had passed the night,

02:37:19.910 --> 02:37:25.630
she replied that she had been looking for the child and demanded earnestly if anything had been heard concerning him.

02:37:26.570 --> 02:37:31.370
When shown the body, she fell into violent hysterics and kept her bed for several days.

02:37:31.890 --> 02:37:36.110
The picture was then produced, which the servant had found in her pocket,

02:37:36.750 --> 02:37:43.690
and when Elizabeth, in a faltering voice, proved that it was the same which an hour before the child had been missed

02:37:43.690 --> 02:37:49.390
she had placed around his neck, a murmur of horror and indignation filled the court.

02:37:51.470 --> 02:37:53.270
Justine was called on for her defence.

02:37:54.310 --> 02:37:57.510
As the trial had proceeded, her countenance had halted.

02:37:58.610 --> 02:38:02.490
Surprise, horror and misery were strongly expressed.

02:38:03.590 --> 02:38:07.690
Sometimes she struggled with her tears, but when she was desired to plead,

02:38:08.270 --> 02:38:12.610
she collected her powers and spoke in an audible, though variable voice.

02:38:42.210 --> 02:38:45.730
She then related that by the permission of Elizabeth,

02:38:46.170 --> 02:38:49.530
she had passed the evening of the night on which the murder had been committed

02:38:49.530 --> 02:38:54.230
at the house of an aunt at Shen, a village situated about a league from Geneva.

02:38:55.230 --> 02:38:57.490
On her return at about nine o'clock, she said that she had been looking for the child,

02:38:57.490 --> 02:39:01.650
She met a man who asked her if she had seen anything of the child who was lost.

02:39:02.630 --> 02:39:06.110
She was alarmed by this account and passed several hours in looking for him

02:39:06.110 --> 02:39:11.030
when the gates of Geneva were shut and she was forced to remain several hours of the night in her barn

02:39:11.030 --> 02:39:15.970
belonging to a cottage, being unwilling to call up the inhabitants to whom she was well known.

02:39:17.130 --> 02:39:18.970
Most of the night she spent here watching.

02:39:19.630 --> 02:39:22.290
Towards morning she believed that she slept for a few minutes.

02:39:22.810 --> 02:39:25.170
Some steps disturbed her and she awoke.

02:39:25.170 --> 02:39:30.710
It was dawn and she quitted her asylum that she might again endeavour to find my brother.

02:39:31.870 --> 02:39:36.110
If she had gone near the spot where his body lay, it was without her knowledge.

02:39:37.170 --> 02:39:40.790
That she had been bewildered when questioned by the market woman was not surprising

02:39:40.790 --> 02:39:45.570
since she had passed a sleepless night and the fate of poor William was yet uncertain.

02:39:46.850 --> 02:39:49.470
Concerning the picture, she could give no account.

02:39:50.770 --> 02:39:54.130
I know, continued the unhappy victim,

02:39:54.770 --> 02:39:58.690
how heavily and fatally this one circumstance weighs against me.

02:39:59.150 --> 02:40:03.610
But I have no power of explaining it, and when I have expressed my utter ignorance

02:40:03.610 --> 02:40:09.090
I am only left to conjecture concerning the probabilities by which it might have been placed in my pocket.

02:40:10.030 --> 02:40:14.210
But here also I am checked. I believe that I have no enemy on earth

02:40:14.210 --> 02:40:18.090
and none surely would have been so wicked as to destroy me wantonly.

02:40:18.090 --> 02:40:24.470
Did the murderer place it there? I know of no opportunity afforded him for so doing.

02:40:25.090 --> 02:40:30.190
Or, if I had, why should he have stolen the jewel to part with it again so soon?

02:40:31.890 --> 02:40:37.390
I commit my cause to the justice of my judges, yet I see no room for hope.

02:40:38.170 --> 02:40:42.270
I beg permission to have a few witnesses examined concerning my character

02:40:42.270 --> 02:40:47.770
and if their testimony shall not overweigh my supposed guilt, I must be condemned.

02:40:47.770 --> 02:40:51.190
Although I would pledge my salvation on my innocence.

02:40:54.310 --> 02:40:59.110
Several witnesses were called who had known her for many years, and they spoke well of her.

02:40:59.450 --> 02:41:02.630
But fear and hatred of the crime of which they supposed her guilty

02:41:02.630 --> 02:41:05.170
rendered them timorous and unwilling to come forward.

02:41:07.450 --> 02:41:12.410
Elizabeth saw even this last resource, her excellent dispositions and irreproachable conduct

02:41:12.410 --> 02:41:16.770
about to fail the accused, when, although violently agitated,

02:41:16.770 --> 02:41:19.330
she desired permission to address the court.

02:41:20.690 --> 02:41:27.230
I am, said she, the cousin of the unhappy child who was murdered, or rather his sister,

02:41:27.590 --> 02:41:33.270
for I was educated by and have lived with his parents ever since and even long before his birth.

02:41:34.210 --> 02:41:38.190
It may therefore be judged indecent in me to come forward on this occasion,

02:41:38.610 --> 02:41:43.810
but when I see a fellow creature about to perish to the cowardice of her pretended friends,

02:41:43.810 --> 02:41:48.630
I wish to be allowed to speak that I may say what I know of her character.

02:41:49.750 --> 02:41:51.590
I am well acquainted with the accused.

02:41:52.390 --> 02:41:58.270
I have lived in the same house with her at one time for five and at another for nearly two years.

02:41:59.070 --> 02:42:04.790
During all that period she appeared to me the most amiable and benevolent of human creatures.

02:42:05.490 --> 02:42:11.130
She nursed Madame Frankenstein, my aunt, in her last illness with the greatest affection and care,

02:42:11.130 --> 02:42:19.050
and afterwards attended her own mother during a tedious illness in a manner that excited the admiration of all who knew her,

02:42:19.310 --> 02:42:24.050
after which she again lived in my uncle's house where she was beloved by all the family.

02:42:24.690 --> 02:42:30.490
She was warmly attached to the child who is now dead and acted towards him like a most affectionate mother.

02:42:31.290 --> 02:42:37.470
For my own part I do not hesitate to say that notwithstanding all the evidence produced against her,

02:42:37.670 --> 02:42:40.470
I believe and rely on her perfect innocence.

02:42:41.130 --> 02:42:43.710
She had no temptation for such an action.

02:42:44.470 --> 02:42:49.630
As to the bauble on which the chief proof rests, if she had so earnestly desired it,

02:42:49.810 --> 02:42:53.930
I should have willingly given it to her. So much do I esteem and value her.

02:42:55.910 --> 02:42:59.930
A murmur of approbation followed Elizabeth's simple and powerful appeal,

02:43:00.490 --> 02:43:05.250
but it was excited by her generous interference and not in favour of poor Justine,

02:43:05.250 --> 02:43:11.270
on whom the public indignation was turned with renewed violence, charging her with the blackest ingratitude.

02:43:12.550 --> 02:43:16.190
She herself wept as Elizabeth spoke, but she did not answer.

02:43:17.470 --> 02:43:21.210
My own agitation and anguish was extreme during the whole trial.

02:43:21.950 --> 02:43:24.530
I believed in her innocence. I knew it.

02:43:25.070 --> 02:43:28.070
Could the demon who had, I did not a minute doubt,

02:43:28.490 --> 02:43:33.310
murdered my brother also in his hellish sport have betrayed the innocent to death in ignominy?

02:43:33.310 --> 02:43:36.750
I could not sustain the horror of my situation,

02:43:37.190 --> 02:43:43.710
and when I perceived that the popular voice and the countenances of the judge had already condemned my unhappy victim,

02:43:44.310 --> 02:43:46.190
I rushed out of the court in agony.

02:43:47.070 --> 02:43:49.770
The tortures of the accused did not equal mine.

02:43:50.570 --> 02:43:56.690
She was sustained by innocence, but the fangs of remorse tore my bosom and would not forgo their hold.

02:43:59.030 --> 02:44:01.550
I passed a night of unmingled wretchedness.

02:44:01.550 --> 02:44:07.190
In the morning I went to the court. My lips and throat were parched.

02:44:08.070 --> 02:44:13.730
I dared not ask the fatal question, but I was known, and the officer guessed the cause of my visit.

02:44:14.410 --> 02:44:19.490
The ballots had been thrown. They were all black, and Justine was condemned.

02:44:21.170 --> 02:44:24.210
I cannot pretend to describe what I then felt.

02:44:25.410 --> 02:44:28.170
I had before experienced sensations of horror,

02:44:28.170 --> 02:44:31.710
and when I have endeavoured to bestow upon them adequate expressions,

02:44:32.930 --> 02:44:37.470
but words cannot convey an idea of the heart-sickening despair that I then endured.

02:44:38.510 --> 02:44:43.410
The person to whom I addressed myself added that Justine had already confessed her guilt.

02:44:44.530 --> 02:44:48.970
That evidence, he observed, was hardly required in so glaring a case,

02:44:49.130 --> 02:44:54.910
but I am glad of it, and indeed none of our judges like to condemn a criminal upon circumstantial evidence,

02:44:55.330 --> 02:44:56.330
be it ever so decisive.

02:44:56.330 --> 02:45:02.350
This was strange and unexpected intelligence. What could it mean?

02:45:03.210 --> 02:45:07.990
Had my eyes deceived me, and was I really as mad as the whole world would believe me to be

02:45:07.990 --> 02:45:10.390
if I disclosed the object of my suspicions?

02:45:11.110 --> 02:45:15.570
I hastened to return home, and Elizabeth eagerly demanded the result.

02:45:16.830 --> 02:45:21.790
My cousin, replied I, it is decided as you may have expected.

02:45:22.430 --> 02:45:27.870
All judges had rather that ten innocent should suffer than that one guilty should escape.

02:45:28.930 --> 02:45:30.250
But she has confessed.

02:45:37.730 --> 02:45:43.370
This was a dire blow to poor Elizabeth, who had relied with firmness upon Justine's innocence.

02:45:44.730 --> 02:45:48.470
Alas, said she, how shall I ever again believe in human goodness?

02:45:49.110 --> 02:45:55.150
Justine, whom I loved and esteemed as my sister, how could she put on those smiles of innocence only to betray?

02:45:55.970 --> 02:46:01.550
Her mild eyes seemed incapable of any severity or guile, and yet she has committed a murder.

02:46:03.510 --> 02:46:08.030
Soon after, we heard that the poor victim had expressed a desire to see my cousin.

02:46:09.010 --> 02:46:14.170
My father wished her not to go, but said that he left it to her own judgment and feelings to decide.

02:46:14.830 --> 02:46:21.410
Yes, said Elizabeth, I will go, although she is guilty, and you, Victor, shall accompany me.

02:46:21.930 --> 02:46:23.270
I cannot go alone.

02:46:24.970 --> 02:46:28.870
The idea of this visit was torture to me, yet I could not refuse.

02:46:30.050 --> 02:46:35.150
We entered the gloomy prison chamber and beheld Justine sitting on some straw at the farther end.

02:46:35.770 --> 02:46:39.150
Her hands were manacled, and her head rested on her knees.

02:46:39.730 --> 02:46:47.330
She rose on seeing us enter, and when we were left alone with her, she threw herself at the feet of Elizabeth, weeping bitterly.

02:46:48.090 --> 02:46:49.470
My cousin wept also.

02:46:50.690 --> 02:46:55.890
Oh, Justine, said she, why did you rob me of my last consolation?

02:46:56.210 --> 02:47:02.470
I relied on your innocence, and although I was then very wretched, I was not so miserable as I am now.

02:47:04.410 --> 02:47:07.630
And do you also believe that I am so very, very wicked?

02:47:07.630 --> 02:47:11.890
Do you also join with my enemies to crush me, to condemn me as a murderer?

02:47:12.890 --> 02:47:15.490
Her voice was suffocated with sobs.

02:47:16.630 --> 02:47:18.490
Rise, my poor girl, said Elizabeth.

02:47:19.190 --> 02:47:21.030
Why do you kneel if you are innocent?

02:47:21.710 --> 02:47:23.210
I am not one of your enemies.

02:47:23.630 --> 02:47:29.950
I believed you guiltless, notwithstanding every evidence, until I heard that you had yourself declared your guilt.

02:47:30.790 --> 02:47:32.590
That report, you say, is false.

02:47:32.590 --> 02:47:39.410
And be assured, dear Justine, that nothing can shake my confidence in you for a moment, but your own confession.

02:47:40.610 --> 02:47:43.730
I did confess, but I confessed a lie.

02:47:44.670 --> 02:47:52.030
I confessed that I might obtain absolution, but now that falsehood lies heavier at my heart than all my other sins.

02:47:52.770 --> 02:47:54.430
The God of heaven forgive me.

02:47:55.130 --> 02:47:58.490
Ever since I was condemned, my confessor has besieged me.

02:47:58.490 --> 02:48:03.570
He threatened and menaced until I almost began to think that I was the monster that he said I was.

02:48:04.390 --> 02:48:09.470
He threatened excommunication and hellfire in my last moments if I continued obdurate.

02:48:10.350 --> 02:48:12.690
Dear lady, I had none to support me.

02:48:13.170 --> 02:48:16.910
All looked on me as a wretch doomed to ignominy and perdition.

02:48:17.550 --> 02:48:18.610
What could I do?

02:48:19.190 --> 02:48:24.430
In an evil hour I subscribed to a lie, and now only am I truly miserable.

02:48:25.530 --> 02:48:27.330
She paused, weeping.

02:48:27.330 --> 02:48:29.090
And then continued.

02:48:30.330 --> 02:48:37.990
I thought with horror, my sweet lady, that you should believe your Justine, whom your blessed aunt had so highly honored and whom you loved,

02:48:38.490 --> 02:48:43.190
was a creature capable of a crime which none but the devil himself could have perpetrated.

02:48:43.930 --> 02:48:51.430
Dear William, dearest blessed child, I soon shall see you again in heaven, where we shall all be happy.

02:48:51.970 --> 02:48:56.490
And that consoles me, going as I am to suffer ignominy and death.

02:48:58.690 --> 02:49:03.310
Oh, Justine, forgive me for having for one moment distrusted you.

02:49:03.710 --> 02:49:04.990
Why did you confess?

02:49:06.030 --> 02:49:08.270
But do not mourn, dear girl, do not fear.

02:49:09.090 --> 02:49:16.150
I will proclaim, I will prove your innocence, I will melt the stony hearts of your enemies by the tears and prayers.

02:49:16.870 --> 02:49:17.950
You shall not die.

02:49:18.450 --> 02:49:23.290
You, my playfellow, my companion, my sister, perish on the scaffold?

02:49:23.290 --> 02:49:27.290
No, I could never survive so horrible a misfortune.

02:49:31.250 --> 02:49:32.750
Justine shook her head mournfully.

02:49:33.630 --> 02:49:35.830
I do not fear to die, she said.

02:49:36.610 --> 02:49:37.730
That pang is past.

02:49:38.630 --> 02:49:41.950
God raises my weakness and gives me courage to endure the worst.

02:49:42.730 --> 02:49:51.590
I leave a sad and bitter world, and if you remember me and think of me as of one unjustly condemned, I am resigned to the fate awaiting me.

02:49:51.590 --> 02:49:55.730
Learn from me, dear lady, to submit impatience to the will of heaven.

02:49:58.890 --> 02:50:06.310
During this conversation, I had retired to a corner of the prison room, where I could conceal the horrid anguish that possessed me.

02:50:06.950 --> 02:50:09.150
Despair? Who dared talk of that?

02:50:09.950 --> 02:50:18.070
The poor victim, who on the morrow was to pass the awful boundary between life and death, felt not, as I did, such deep and bitter agony.

02:50:19.050 --> 02:50:25.030
I gnashed my teeth and ground them together, uttering a groan that came from my inmost soul.

02:50:26.530 --> 02:50:27.290
Justine started.

02:50:28.530 --> 02:50:30.930
When she saw who it was, she approached me and said,

02:50:31.330 --> 02:50:33.950
Dear sir, you are very kind to visit you.

02:50:35.010 --> 02:50:37.670
I do hope you do not believe that I am guilty.

02:50:39.610 --> 02:50:41.010
I could not answer.

02:50:41.830 --> 02:50:43.350
No, Justine, said Elizabeth.

02:50:43.350 --> 02:50:49.950
He is more convinced of your innocence than I was, for even when he heard that you had confessed, he did not credit it.

02:50:51.210 --> 02:50:52.530
I truly thank him.

02:50:52.990 --> 02:50:58.550
In these last moments, I feel the sincerest gratitude towards those who think of me with kindness.

02:50:59.570 --> 02:51:02.930
How sweet is the affection of others to such a wretch as I am.

02:51:03.430 --> 02:51:12.950
It removes more than half my misfortune, and I feel as if I could die in peace now that my innocence is acknowledged by you, dear lady, and your cousin.

02:51:15.870 --> 02:51:19.810
Thus the poor sufferer tried to comfort others and herself.

02:51:20.890 --> 02:51:23.710
She indeed gained the resignation she desired.

02:51:24.730 --> 02:51:32.500
But I, the true murderer, felt the never-dying worm alive in my bosom, which allowed of no hope or consolation.

02:51:34.010 --> 02:51:38.830
Elizabeth also wept and was unhappy, but hers also was the misery of innocence,

02:51:38.830 --> 02:51:45.370
which, like a cloud that passes over the fair moon, for a while hides but cannot tarnish its brightness.

02:51:46.850 --> 02:51:50.070
Anguish and despair had penetrated into the core of my heart.

02:51:50.730 --> 02:51:54.170
I bore a hell within me which nothing could extinguish.

02:51:55.030 --> 02:52:00.870
We stayed several hours with Justine, and it was with great difficulty that Elizabeth could tear herself away.

02:52:01.230 --> 02:52:04.850
I wish, cried she, that I were to die with you.

02:52:05.170 --> 02:52:07.230
I cannot live in this world of misery.

02:52:09.590 --> 02:52:15.110
Justine assumed an air of cheerfulness, while she with difficulty repressed her bitter tears.

02:52:15.990 --> 02:52:19.710
She embraced Elizabeth and said in a voice of half-suppressed emotion,

02:52:20.510 --> 02:52:25.070
Farewell, sweet lady, dearest Elizabeth, my beloved and only friend.

02:52:26.050 --> 02:52:29.990
May heaven, in its bounty, bless and preserve you.

02:52:30.310 --> 02:52:33.170
May this be the last misfortune that you will ever suffer.

02:52:33.870 --> 02:52:36.950
Live and be happy, and make others so.

02:52:39.810 --> 02:52:42.910
And on the morrow, Justine died.

02:52:44.610 --> 02:52:51.190
Elizabeth's heart-rending eloquence failed to move the judges from their settled conviction in the criminality of the saintly sufferer.

02:52:52.330 --> 02:52:55.750
My passionate and indignant appeals were lost upon them,

02:52:56.130 --> 02:53:01.550
and when I received their cold answers and heard the harsh, unfeeling reasoning of these men,

02:53:02.070 --> 02:53:04.370
my purposed avowal died away on my lips.

02:53:04.370 --> 02:53:11.010
Thus I might proclaim myself a madman, but not revoke the sentence passed upon my wretched victim.

02:53:12.250 --> 02:53:14.910
She perished on the scaffold as a murderess.

02:53:17.110 --> 02:53:22.810
From the tortures of my own heart, I turned to contemplate the deep and voiceless grief of my Elizabeth.

02:53:23.770 --> 02:53:29.970
This also was my doing, and my father's woe and the desolation of that late so smiling home

02:53:29.970 --> 02:53:33.150
all was the work of my thrice accursed hands.

02:53:33.150 --> 02:53:37.730
Ye weep, unhappy ones, but these are not your last tears.

02:53:38.570 --> 02:53:44.810
Again shall you rise the funeral wail, and the sound of your lamentations shall again and again be heard.

02:53:45.750 --> 02:53:49.890
Frankenstein, your son, your kinsman, your early much-loved friend,

02:53:50.630 --> 02:53:53.970
he who would spend each vital drop of blood for your sakes,

02:53:54.250 --> 02:53:59.290
who has no thought nor sense of joy, except as it is mirrored also in your dear countenances,

02:53:59.290 --> 02:54:03.950
who would fill the air with blessings and spend his life in serving you,

02:54:04.570 --> 02:54:07.370
he bids you weep, to shed countless tears,

02:54:08.710 --> 02:54:12.490
happy beyond his hopes if thus inexorable fate be satisfied,

02:54:13.070 --> 02:54:18.690
and if the destruction pours before the peace of the grave have succeeded to your sad torments.

02:54:20.070 --> 02:54:25.810
Thus spoke my prophetic soul, as, torn by remorse, horror and despair,

02:54:25.810 --> 02:54:31.470
I beheld those I loved spend vain sorrow upon the graves of William and Justine,

02:54:31.930 --> 02:54:34.950
the first hapless victims to my unhallowed arts.

02:54:49.190 --> 02:54:49.770
9.

02:54:55.150 --> 02:55:00.030
Nothing is more painful to the human mind than, after the feelings have been worked

02:55:00.030 --> 02:55:05.650
up by a quick succession of events, the dead calmness of inaction and certainty which follows

02:55:05.650 --> 02:55:12.550
and deprives the soul both of hope and fear. Justine died, she rested, and I was alive.

02:55:13.530 --> 02:55:18.550
The blood flowed freely in my veins, but a weight of despair and remorse pressed on my heart which

02:55:18.550 --> 02:55:25.570
nothing could remove. Sleep fled from my eyes. I wandered like an evil spirit, for I had committed

02:55:25.570 --> 02:55:32.030
deeds of mischief beyond description horrible, and more, much more, I persuaded myself, was yet

02:55:33.530 --> 02:55:39.570
yet my heart overflowed with kindness and the love of virtue. I had begun life with benevolent

02:55:39.570 --> 02:55:43.550
intentions and thirsted for the moment when I should put them in practice and make myself

02:55:43.550 --> 02:55:50.850
useful to my fellow beings. Now all was blasted. Instead of that serenity of conscience which

02:55:50.850 --> 02:55:55.910
allowed me to look back upon the past with self-satisfaction and from thence to gather

02:55:55.910 --> 02:56:02.010
promise of new hopes, I was seized by remorse and the sense of guilt which hurried me away to a

02:56:02.010 --> 02:56:10.310
hell of intense tortures such as no language can describe. This state of mind preyed upon my health

02:56:10.310 --> 02:56:16.590
which had perhaps never entirely recovered from the first shock it had sustained. I shunned the

02:56:16.590 --> 02:56:23.710
face of man. All sound of joy or complacency was tortured to me. Solitude was my only consolation,

02:56:24.110 --> 02:56:31.770
deep, dark, death-like solitude. My father observed with pain the alteration perceptible

02:56:31.770 --> 02:56:36.950
in my disposition and habits, and endeavored by arguments deduced from the feelings of his

02:56:36.950 --> 02:56:42.510
serene conscience and guiltless life to inspire me with fortitude and awaken in me the courage

02:56:42.510 --> 02:56:49.610
to dispel the dark cloud which brooded over me. Do you think, Victor, said he, that I do not suffer

02:56:49.610 --> 02:56:56.330
also? No one could love a child more than I loved your brother. Tears came into his eyes as he spoke.

02:56:57.090 --> 02:57:01.750
But is it not a duty to the survivors that we should refrain from augmenting their unhappiness?

02:57:01.750 --> 02:57:07.890
By an appearance of immoderate grief? It is also a duty owed to yourself, for excessive sorrow

02:57:07.890 --> 02:57:13.690
prevents improvement or enjoyment, or even the discharge of daily usefulness without which no

02:57:13.690 --> 02:57:22.190
man is fit for society. This advice, although good, was totally inapplicable to my case. I

02:57:22.190 --> 02:57:26.670
should have been the first to hide my grief and console my friends if remorse had not mingled its

02:57:26.670 --> 02:57:32.930
bitterness and terror its alarm with my other sensations. Now I could only answer my father

02:57:32.930 --> 02:57:40.410
with a look of despair and endeavor to hide myself from his view. About this time we retired to our

02:57:40.410 --> 02:57:46.030
house at Belle Reve. This change was particularly agreeable to me. The shutting of the gates

02:57:46.030 --> 02:57:51.310
regularly at ten o'clock and the impossibility of remaining on the lake after that hour had rendered

02:57:51.310 --> 02:57:58.390
our residence within the walls of Geneva very irksome to me. I was now free. Often after the

02:57:58.390 --> 02:58:03.570
rest of the family had retired for the night I took the boat and passed many hours upon the water.

02:58:04.790 --> 02:58:10.430
Sometimes with my sail set I was carried by the wind and sometimes after rowing it into the middle

02:58:10.430 --> 02:58:16.490
of the lake I left the boat to pursue its own course and gave way to my own miserable reflections.

02:58:17.550 --> 02:58:23.230
I was often tempted when all was at peace around me and I the only unquiet thing that

02:58:23.230 --> 02:58:28.530
wandered restless in a scene so beautiful and heavenly. If I accept some bat or the

02:58:28.530 --> 02:58:34.070
frogs whose harsh and interrupted croaking was heard only when I approached the shore. Often

02:58:34.070 --> 02:58:39.350
I say I was tempted to plunge into the silent lake that the waters might close over me and

02:58:39.350 --> 02:58:44.650
my calamities forever. But I was restrained when I thought of the heroic and suffering

02:58:44.650 --> 02:58:50.750
Elizabeth whom I tenderly loved and whose existence was bound up in mine. I thought

02:58:50.750 --> 02:58:56.410
also of my father and surviving brother should I by my base desertion leave them exposed and

02:58:56.410 --> 02:59:03.430
unprotected to the malice of the fiend whom I had let loose among them. At these moments I

02:59:03.430 --> 02:59:08.690
wept bitterly and wished that peace would revisit my mind only that I might afford them consolation

02:59:08.690 --> 02:59:16.010
and happiness but that could not be. Remorse extinguished every hope. I had been the author

02:59:16.010 --> 02:59:21.410
of unalterable evils and I lived in daily fear lest the monster whom I had created should

02:59:21.410 --> 02:59:27.170
perpetrate some new wickedness. I had an obscure feeling that all was not over and that he would

02:59:27.170 --> 02:59:32.470
still commit some signal crime which by its enormity should almost efface the recollection

02:59:32.470 --> 02:59:38.530
of the past. There was always scope for fear so long as anything I loved remained behind.

02:59:39.750 --> 02:59:46.350
My abhorrence of this fiend cannot be conceived. When I thought of him I gnashed my teeth, my eyes

02:59:46.350 --> 02:59:52.110
became inflamed and I ardently wished to extinguish that life which I had so thoughtlessly bestowed.

02:59:53.150 --> 02:59:58.270
When I reflected on his crimes and malice my hatred and revenge burst all bounds of

02:59:59.430 --> 03:00:04.730
I would have made a pilgrimage to the highest peak of the Andes could I when there have

03:00:04.730 --> 03:00:10.950
precipitated him to their base. I wished to see him again that I might wreak the utmost extent

03:00:10.950 --> 03:00:17.870
of abhorrence on his head and avenge the deaths of William and Justine. Our house was the house

03:00:17.870 --> 03:00:24.950
of mourning. My father's health was deeply shaken by the horror of the recent events. Elizabeth was

03:00:24.950 --> 03:00:31.290
sad and desponding. She no longer took delight in her ordinary occupations. All pleasure seemed to

03:00:31.290 --> 03:00:36.750
her sacrilege toward the dead. Eternal woe and tears she then thought was the just tribute she

03:00:36.750 --> 03:00:43.210
should pay to innocents so blasted and destroyed. She was no longer that happy creature who in

03:00:43.210 --> 03:00:48.130
earlier youth wandered with me on the banks of the lake and talked with ecstasy of our future

03:00:48.130 --> 03:00:54.470
prospects. The first of those sorrows which are sent to wean us from the earth had visited her and

03:00:54.470 --> 03:01:03.090
its dimming influence quenched her dearest smiles. When I reflect my dear cousin said she, on the

03:01:03.090 --> 03:01:07.770
miserable death of Justine Moritz I no longer see the world and its works as they before appeared

03:01:07.770 --> 03:01:13.450
to me. Before I looked upon the accounts of vice and injustice that I read in books or heard from

03:01:13.450 --> 03:01:19.330
others as tales of ancient days or imaginary evils. At least they were remote and more familiar to

03:01:19.330 --> 03:01:25.530
the imagination. But now misery has come home and men appear to me as monsters thirsting for

03:01:25.530 --> 03:01:31.850
each other's blood. Yet I am certainly unjust. Everybody believed that poor girl to be guilty

03:01:31.850 --> 03:01:36.090
and if she could have committed the crime for which she suffered assuredly she would have been

03:01:36.090 --> 03:01:40.910
the most apraved of human creatures. For the sake of a few jewels to have murdered the son of her

03:01:40.910 --> 03:01:45.570
benefactor and friend, a child whom she had nursed from its birth and appeared to love as it had been

03:01:45.570 --> 03:01:50.590
her own? I could not consent to the death of any human being but certainly I should have thought

03:01:50.590 --> 03:01:56.450
such a creature unfit to remain in the society of men. But she was innocent. I know, I feel,

03:01:56.470 --> 03:02:02.770
she was innocent. You are of the same opinion and that confirms me. Alas! Victor, when falsehood can

03:02:02.770 --> 03:02:08.190
look so like the truth, who can assure themselves of certain happiness? I feel as if I were walking

03:02:08.190 --> 03:02:12.870
on the edge of a precipice towards which thousands are crowding and endeavoring to plunge me into the

03:02:13.910 --> 03:02:19.530
William and Justine were assassinated and the murderer escapes. He walks about the world free

03:02:19.530 --> 03:02:24.450
and perhaps respected. But even if I were condemned to suffer on the scaffold for the same crimes,

03:02:24.770 --> 03:02:31.610
I would not change places with such a wretch. I listened to this discourse with the extremist

03:02:31.610 --> 03:02:39.830
agony. I, not indeed, but in effect, was the true murderer. Elizabeth read my anguish in my

03:02:39.830 --> 03:02:46.530
countenance and, kindly taking my hand, said, My dearest friend, you must calm yourself. These

03:02:46.530 --> 03:02:52.210
events have affected me, God knows how deeply, but I am not so wretched as you are. There is an

03:02:52.210 --> 03:02:57.450
expression of despair and sometimes of revenge in your countenance that makes me tremble. Dear

03:02:57.450 --> 03:03:02.590
Victor, banish these dark passions. Remember the friends around you who center all their hopes in

03:03:02.590 --> 03:03:09.050
you. Have we lost the power of rendering you happy? Ah, while we love, while we are true to

03:03:09.050 --> 03:03:14.070
each other, here in this land of peace and beauty, your native country, we may reap every

03:03:14.070 --> 03:03:21.350
tranquil blessing. What can disturb our peace? And could not such words from her whom I fondly

03:03:21.350 --> 03:03:26.090
prized before every other gift of fortune suffice to chase away the fiend that lurked in my heart?

03:03:26.870 --> 03:03:31.950
Even as she spoke I drew near to her as if in terror lest at that very moment the destroyer

03:03:31.950 --> 03:03:37.910
had been near to rob me of her. Thus not the tenderness of friendship, nor the beauty of earth,

03:03:37.910 --> 03:03:44.870
nor of heaven could redeem my soul from woe. The very accents of love were ineffectual. I

03:03:44.870 --> 03:03:50.530
was encompassed by a cloud which no beneficial influence could penetrate. The wounded deer

03:03:50.530 --> 03:03:55.350
dragging its fainting limbs to some untrodden break there to gaze upon the arrow which had

03:03:55.350 --> 03:04:02.610
pierced it and to die was but a type of me. Sometimes I could cope with the sullen despair

03:04:02.610 --> 03:04:08.890
that overwhelmed me, but sometimes the whirlwind passions of my soul drove me to seek, by bodily

03:04:08.890 --> 03:04:15.690
exercise and by change of place, some relief for my intolerable sensations. It was during an access

03:04:15.690 --> 03:04:21.230
of this kind that I suddenly left my home, and bending my steps towards the near alpine valleys,

03:04:21.670 --> 03:04:27.170
sought in the magnificence, the eternity of such scenes, to forget myself and my ephemeral because

03:04:27.170 --> 03:04:33.990
human sorrows. My wanderings were directed towards the valley of Chamonix. I had visited

03:04:33.990 --> 03:04:40.750
it frequently during my boyhood. Six years had passed since then. I was a wreck, but not had

03:04:40.750 --> 03:04:47.430
changed in those savage and enduring scenes. I performed the first part of my journey on horseback.

03:04:48.210 --> 03:04:53.450
I afterwards hired a mule as the more sure-footed and least liable to receive injury on these rugged

03:04:53.450 --> 03:04:59.510
roads. The weather was fine. It was about the middle of the month of August, nearly two months

03:04:59.510 --> 03:05:05.970
after the death of Justine, that miserable epoch from which I dated all my woe. The weight upon my

03:05:05.970 --> 03:05:11.750
spirit was sensibly lightened as I plunged yet deeper in the ravine of Arves. The immense mountains

03:05:11.750 --> 03:05:16.790
and precipices that overhung me on every side, the sound of the river raging among the rocks,

03:05:17.230 --> 03:05:23.090
and the dashing of the waterfalls around, spoke of a power mighty as omnipotence. And I ceased to

03:05:23.090 --> 03:05:28.750
hear or to bend before any being less almighty than that which had created and ruled the elements,

03:05:29.270 --> 03:05:36.090
here displayed in their most terrific guise. Still, as I ascended higher, the valley assumed

03:05:36.090 --> 03:05:41.610
a more magnificent and astonishing character. Ruined castles hanging on the precipices of

03:05:41.610 --> 03:05:47.470
piney mountains, the impetuous arve, and cottages every here and there peeping forth from among the

03:05:47.470 --> 03:05:54.250
trees formed a scene of singular beauty. But it was augmented and rendered sublime by the mighty

03:05:54.250 --> 03:06:00.890
Alps, whose white and shining pyramids and domes towered above all as belonging to another earth,

03:06:01.210 --> 03:06:08.850
the habitations of another race of beings. I passed the bridge of Polissier, where the ravine,

03:06:08.910 --> 03:06:14.890
which the river forms, opened before me, and I began to ascend the mountain that overhangs it.

03:06:14.890 --> 03:06:21.730
Soon after, I entered the valley of Chamonix. This valley is more wonderful and sublime,

03:06:21.850 --> 03:06:26.370
but not so beautiful and picturesque as that of Servox, through which I had just passed.

03:06:27.870 --> 03:06:32.910
The high and snowy mountains were its immediate boundaries, but I saw no more ruined castles

03:06:32.910 --> 03:06:39.470
and fertile fields. Immense glaciers approached the road. I heard the rumbling thunder of the

03:06:39.470 --> 03:06:46.770
marked the smoke of its passage. Mont Blanc, the supreme and magnificent Mont Blanc, raised

03:06:46.770 --> 03:06:51.150
itself from the surrounding aghiles, and its tremendous dome overlooked the valley.

03:06:53.010 --> 03:06:58.930
A tingling, long-lost sense of pleasure often came across me during this journey. Some turn in the

03:06:58.930 --> 03:07:04.690
road, some new object suddenly perceived and recognized reminded me of days gone by and were

03:07:04.690 --> 03:07:09.750
associated with the light-hearted gaiety of boyhood. The very winds whispered in soothing

03:07:09.750 --> 03:07:16.810
accents, and maternal nature bade me weep no more. Then again the kindly influence ceased

03:07:16.810 --> 03:07:23.350
to act. I found myself fettered again to grief and indulging in all the misery of reflection.

03:07:24.610 --> 03:07:30.970
Then I spurred on my animal, striving so to forget the world, my fears, and more than all

03:07:30.970 --> 03:07:37.310
myself. Or, in a more desperate fashion, I alighted and threw myself on the grass,

03:07:37.570 --> 03:07:46.570
weighed down by horror and despair. At length I arrived to the village of Chamonix. Exhaustion

03:07:46.570 --> 03:07:53.250
succeeded to the extreme fatigue both of body and of mind which I had endured. For a short space of

03:07:53.250 --> 03:07:57.890
time I remained at the window, watching the pallid lightnings that played above Mont Blanc,

03:07:57.890 --> 03:08:04.330
and listening to the rushing of the arve which pursued its noisy way beneath. The same lulling

03:08:04.330 --> 03:08:10.190
sounds acted as a lullaby to my two keen sensations. When I placed my head upon my pillow,

03:08:10.690 --> 03:08:16.270
sleep crept over me. I felt it as it came and blessed the giver of oblivion.

03:08:33.690 --> 03:08:34.330
X.

03:08:40.270 --> 03:08:42.630
I spent the following day roaming through the valley.

03:08:43.270 --> 03:08:47.970
I stood beside the sources of the Arviron, which take their rise in a glacier that,

03:08:47.970 --> 03:08:52.730
with slow pace, is advancing down from the summit of the hills to barricade the valley.

03:08:53.910 --> 03:08:59.550
The abrupt sides of vast mountains were before me. The icy wall of the glacier overhung me.

03:09:00.210 --> 03:09:05.650
A few shattered pines were scattered around, and the solemn silence of this glorious presence

03:09:05.650 --> 03:09:12.130
chamber of imperial nature was broken only by the brawling waves or the fall of some vast fragment.

03:09:12.630 --> 03:09:17.890
The thunder sound of the avalanche or the cracking reverberated along the mountains

03:09:17.890 --> 03:09:23.070
of the accumulated ice, which, through the silent working of immutable laws,

03:09:23.410 --> 03:09:28.870
was ever and anon rent and torn, as if it had been but a plaything in their hands.

03:09:30.110 --> 03:09:35.310
These sublime and magnificent scenes afforded me the greatest consolation that I was capable

03:09:35.310 --> 03:09:41.870
of receiving. They elevated me from all littleness of feeling, and although they did not remove my

03:09:41.870 --> 03:09:49.750
grief, they subdued and tranquilized it. In some degree, also, they diverted my mind from the

03:09:49.750 --> 03:09:56.270
thoughts over which it had brooded for the last month. I retired to rest at night, my slumbers,

03:09:56.270 --> 03:10:02.450
as it were, waited on and ministered to by the assemblance of grand shapes which I had contemplated

03:10:02.450 --> 03:10:09.750
during the day. They congregated round me. The unstained snowy mountaintop, the glittering

03:10:09.750 --> 03:10:16.330
pinnacle, the pine woods, and ragged bare ravine, the eagle soaring amidst the clouds,

03:10:16.870 --> 03:10:19.890
they all gathered round me and bade me be at peace.

03:10:22.390 --> 03:10:28.050
Where had they fled when the next morning I awoke? All of soul and spiriting fled with sleep,

03:10:28.730 --> 03:10:35.590
and dark melancholy clouded every thought. The rain was pouring in torrents, and thick mists

03:10:35.590 --> 03:10:40.990
hid the summits of the mountains, so that I even saw not the faces of those mighty friends.

03:10:42.430 --> 03:10:46.310
Still I would penetrate their misty vale and seek them in their cloudy retreats.

03:10:47.270 --> 03:10:52.850
What were rain and storm to me? My mule was brought to the door, and I resolved to ascend

03:10:52.850 --> 03:10:58.470
to the summit of Mont-en-Vert. I remembered the effect that the view of the tremendous and ever

03:10:58.470 --> 03:11:04.770
moving glacier had produced upon my mind when I first saw it. It had then filled me with a

03:11:04.770 --> 03:11:11.170
sublime ecstasy that gave wings to the soul and allowed it to soar from the obscure world to light

03:11:11.170 --> 03:11:18.150
and joy. The sight of the awful and majestic in nature had indeed always the effect of

03:11:18.150 --> 03:11:25.570
solemnizing my mind and causing me to forget the passing cares of life. I determined to go without

03:11:25.570 --> 03:11:30.850
a guide, for I was well acquainted with the path, and the presence of another would destroy the

03:11:30.850 --> 03:11:39.110
grandeur of the scene. The ascent is precipitous, but the path is cut into continual and short

03:11:39.110 --> 03:11:44.830
windings which enable you to surmount the perpendicularity of the mountain. It is a

03:11:44.830 --> 03:11:50.970
scene terrifically desolate. In a thousand spots the traces of the winter avalanche may be perceived,

03:11:51.530 --> 03:11:57.450
where trees lie broken and strewed on the ground, some entirely destroyed, others bent,

03:11:57.450 --> 03:12:02.250
leaning upon the jutting rocks of the mountain or transversely upon other trees.

03:12:03.490 --> 03:12:10.770
The path, as you ascend higher, is intersected by ravines of snow down which stones continually

03:12:10.770 --> 03:12:16.910
roll from above. One of them is particularly dangerous, as the slightest sound, such as even

03:12:16.910 --> 03:12:22.230
speaking in a loud voice, produces a concussion of air sufficient to draw destruction upon the

03:12:22.230 --> 03:12:29.770
speaker. The pines are not tall or luxuriant, but they are somber and add an air of severity to the

03:12:29.770 --> 03:12:36.250
scene. I looked on the valley beneath. Vast mists were rising from the rivers which ran through it

03:12:36.250 --> 03:12:41.610
and curling in thick wreaths around the opposite mountains, whose summits were hid in the uniform

03:12:41.610 --> 03:12:47.670
clouds, while rain poured from the dark sky and added to the melancholy impression I received

03:12:47.670 --> 03:12:54.850
from the objects around me. Alas, why does man boast of sensibility superior to those apparent

03:12:54.850 --> 03:13:01.550
in the brute? It only renders them more necessary beings. If our impulses were confined to hunger,

03:13:01.790 --> 03:13:07.230
thirst, and desire, we might be nearly free. But now we are moved by every wind that blows

03:13:07.230 --> 03:13:14.750
and a chance word or scene that that word may convey to us. We rest. A dream has power to

03:13:14.750 --> 03:13:21.470
sleep. We rise. One wandering thought pollutes the day. We feel, conceive, or reason, laugh,

03:13:21.470 --> 03:13:28.190
or weep, embrace fond woe, or cast our cares away. It is the same, for be it joy or sorrow,

03:13:28.370 --> 03:13:33.430
the path of its departure still is free. Man's yesterday may ne'er be like his morrow,

03:13:33.810 --> 03:13:41.870
not may endure but mutability. It was nearly noon when I arrived at the top of the ascent.

03:13:42.670 --> 03:13:46.350
For some time I sat upon the rock that overlooks the sea of ice.

03:13:47.470 --> 03:13:52.950
A mist covered both that and the surrounding mountains. Presently a breeze dissipated the

03:13:52.950 --> 03:13:59.150
cloud and I descended upon the glacier. The surface is very uneven, rising like the waves

03:13:59.150 --> 03:14:06.550
of a troubled sea, descending low and interspersed by rifts that sink deep. The field of ice is

03:14:06.550 --> 03:14:12.270
almost a league in width, but I spent nearly two hours in crossing it. The opposite mountain

03:14:12.270 --> 03:14:19.150
is a bare perpendicular rock. From the side where I now stood Mont-en-Bert was exactly opposite

03:14:19.150 --> 03:14:26.430
at the distance of a league, and above it rose Mont Blanc in awful majesty. I remained in a

03:14:26.430 --> 03:14:32.690
recess of the rock, gazing on this wonderful and stupendous scene. The sea, or rather the vast

03:14:32.690 --> 03:14:38.370
river of ice, wound among its dependent mountains, whose aerial summits hung over its recesses.

03:14:39.430 --> 03:14:44.790
Their icy and glittering peaks shone in the sunlight over the clouds. My heart,

03:14:44.910 --> 03:14:50.190
which was before sorrowful, now swelled with something like joy. I exclaimed,

03:14:50.770 --> 03:14:54.670
wandering spirits, if indeed ye wander and do not rest in your narrow beds,

03:14:55.190 --> 03:15:00.030
allow me this faint happiness, or take me, as your companion, away from the joys of life.

03:15:02.690 --> 03:15:06.850
As I said this, I suddenly beheld the figure of a man, at some distance,

03:15:07.270 --> 03:15:12.210
advancing towards me with superhuman speed. He bounded over the crevices in the ice,

03:15:12.350 --> 03:15:16.630
among which I had walked with caution. His stature, also, as he approached,

03:15:16.990 --> 03:15:23.830
seemed to exceed that of man. I was troubled. A mist came over my eyes, and I felt a faintness

03:15:23.830 --> 03:15:30.010
seize me, but I was quickly restored by the cold gale of the mountains. I perceived,

03:15:30.010 --> 03:15:35.990
as the shape came nearer, sight tremendous and abhorred, that it was the wretch whom I had created.

03:15:37.410 --> 03:15:42.290
I trembled with rage and horror, resolving to wait his approach and then close with him

03:15:42.290 --> 03:15:49.230
in mortal combat. He approached. His countenance bespoke bitter anguish, combined with disdain and

03:15:49.230 --> 03:15:59.990
malignity, while its unearthly ugliness rendered it almost too horrible for human eyes. But I

03:15:59.990 --> 03:16:04.870
only recovered to overwhelm him with words expressive of furious detestation and contempt.

03:16:06.050 --> 03:16:12.250
Devil, I exclaimed, do you dare approach me? And do not you fear the fierce vengeance of my arm

03:16:12.250 --> 03:16:18.270
wreaked on your miserable head? Be gone, vile insect, or rather stay that I may trample you

03:16:18.270 --> 03:16:22.570
to dust, and owe that I could, with the extinction of your miserable existence,

03:16:22.930 --> 03:16:25.630
restore those victims whom you have so diabolically murdered.

03:16:26.630 --> 03:16:30.750
I expected this reception, said the demon.

03:16:31.850 --> 03:16:37.010
All men hate the wretched. How then must I be hated,

03:16:37.590 --> 03:16:45.450
who am miserable beyond all living things? Yet you, my creator, detest and spurn me,

03:16:45.510 --> 03:16:53.310
thy creature, to whom thou art bound by ties only dissolvable by the annihilation of one of us.

03:16:54.190 --> 03:16:59.090
You purpose to kill me? How dare you sport thus with life?

03:17:00.210 --> 03:17:05.390
Do your duty towards me, and I will do mine towards you and the rest of mankind.

03:17:06.210 --> 03:17:13.070
If you will comply with my conditions, I will leave them and you at peace. But if you refuse,

03:17:13.170 --> 03:17:19.430
I will glut the maw of death until it be satiated with the blood of your remaining friends.

03:17:21.450 --> 03:17:27.050
Abhorred monster, fiend that thou art, the tortures of hell are too mild a vengeance for thy crimes.

03:17:27.770 --> 03:17:32.810
Wretched devil, you reproach me with your creation. Come on, then, that I may extinguish

03:17:32.810 --> 03:17:39.350
the spark which I so negligently bestowed. My rage was without bounds. I sprang on him,

03:17:39.570 --> 03:17:43.890
impelled by all the feelings which can arm one being against the existence of another.

03:17:44.610 --> 03:17:47.030
He easily eluded me and said,

03:17:47.690 --> 03:17:54.710
Be calm. I entreat you to hear me before you give vent to your hatred on my devoted head.

03:17:55.530 --> 03:17:59.210
Have I not suffered enough that you seek to increase my misery?

03:18:00.570 --> 03:18:07.570
Life, although it may only be an accumulation of anguish, is dear to me, and I will defend it.

03:18:08.570 --> 03:18:15.430
Remember, thou hast made me more powerful than thyself. My height is superior to thine,

03:18:15.970 --> 03:18:22.390
my joints more supple. But I will not be tempted to set myself in opposition to thee.

03:18:23.610 --> 03:18:29.630
I am thy creature, and I will be even mild and docile to my natural lord and king,

03:18:30.210 --> 03:18:34.690
if thou wilt also perform thy part, the which thou owest me.

03:18:35.570 --> 03:18:43.330
O Frankenstein, be not equitable to every other and trample upon me alone,

03:18:44.130 --> 03:18:49.310
to whom thy justice and even thy clemency and affection is most due.

03:18:50.850 --> 03:18:58.210
Remember that I am thy creature. I ought to be thy Adam, but I am rather the fallen angel,

03:18:58.870 --> 03:19:07.050
whom thou drivest from joy for no misdeed. Everywhere I see bliss from which I alone

03:19:07.050 --> 03:19:16.890
am irrevocably excluded. I was benevolent and good. Misery made me a fiend. Make me happy,

03:19:17.150 --> 03:19:24.710
and I shall again be virtuous. Be gone. I will not hear you. There can be no community

03:19:24.710 --> 03:19:30.370
between you and me. We are enemies. Be gone, or let us try our strength in a fight in which one

03:19:30.370 --> 03:19:40.350
must fall. How can I move thee? Will no entreaties cause thee to turn a favorable eye upon thy

03:19:40.350 --> 03:19:52.990
creature, who implores thy goodness and compassion? Believe me, Frankenstein, I was benevolent. My

03:19:52.990 --> 03:20:02.250
not alone, miserably alone. You, my creator, abhor me. What hope can I gather from your fellow

03:20:02.250 --> 03:20:11.210
creatures who owe me nothing? They spurn and hate me. The desert mountains and dreary glaciers are

03:20:11.210 --> 03:20:19.950
my refuge. I have wandered here many days. The caves of ice, which I only do not fear,

03:20:19.950 --> 03:20:25.050
are a dwelling to me, and the only one which man does not grudge.

03:20:26.230 --> 03:20:31.970
These bleak skies I hail, for they are kinder to me than your fellow beings.

03:20:33.690 --> 03:20:40.650
If the multitude of mankind knew of my existence, they would do as you do and arm themselves for

03:20:40.650 --> 03:20:49.330
my destruction. Shall I not then hate them who abhor me? I will keep no terms with my enemies.

03:20:49.950 --> 03:20:57.590
I am miserable, and they shall share my wretchedness. Yet it is in your power to

03:20:57.590 --> 03:21:04.690
recompense me and deliver them from an evil which it only remains for you to make so great

03:21:04.690 --> 03:21:11.670
that not only you and your family, but thousands of others shall be swallowed up in the whirlwinds

03:21:11.670 --> 03:21:21.530
rage. Let your compassion be moved, and do not disdain me. Listen to my tale. When you have

03:21:21.530 --> 03:21:30.270
heard that, abandon or commiserate me, as you shall judge that I deserve. But hear me. The guilty are

03:21:30.270 --> 03:21:36.730
allowed by human laws, bloody as they are, to speak in their own defense before they are condemned.

03:21:38.030 --> 03:21:45.230
Listen to me, Frankenstein. You accuse me of murder, and yet you would, with a satisfied

03:21:45.230 --> 03:21:54.130
conscience, destroy your own creature. Oh, praise the eternal justice of man. Yet I ask you not to

03:21:54.130 --> 03:22:02.130
spare me. Listen to me, and then, if you can, and if you will, destroy the work of your hands.

03:22:05.010 --> 03:22:10.850
Why do you call to my remembrance, I rejoined, circumstances of which I shudder to reflect,

03:22:11.510 --> 03:22:16.850
that I have been the miserable origin and author. Cursed be the day, abhorred devil,

03:22:17.290 --> 03:22:23.830
in which few first saw light. Cursed, although I curse myself, be the hands that formed you.

03:22:24.590 --> 03:22:28.990
You have made me wretched beyond expression. You have left me no power to consider whether

03:22:28.990 --> 03:22:32.110
I am just to you or not. Be gone! Relieve me from the death of my own son.

03:22:32.110 --> 03:22:33.650
The sight of your detested form.

03:22:36.190 --> 03:22:41.650
Thus I relieve thee, my creator, he said, and placed his hated hands before my eyes,

03:22:41.730 --> 03:22:46.790
which I flung from me with violence. Thus I take from thee a sight which you abhor.

03:22:47.770 --> 03:22:54.330
Still thou canst listen to me, and grant me thy compassion. By the virtues that I once possessed,

03:22:54.610 --> 03:23:01.350
I demand this from you. Hear my tale. It is long and strange, and the temperature of this place is

03:23:01.350 --> 03:23:08.470
not fitting to your fine sensations. Come to the hut upon the mountain. The sun is yet high in the

03:23:08.470 --> 03:23:15.050
heavens. Before it descends to hide itself behind your snowy precipices and illuminate another world,

03:23:15.530 --> 03:23:21.530
you will have heard my story and can decide. On you it rests whether I quit forever the

03:23:21.530 --> 03:23:27.970
neighborhood of man and lead a harmless life, or become the scourge of your fellow creatures

03:23:27.970 --> 03:23:35.730
and the author of your own speedy ruin. As he said this, he led the way across the ice.

03:23:36.450 --> 03:23:43.570
I followed. My heart was full, and I did not answer him. But as I proceeded, I weighed the

03:23:43.570 --> 03:23:48.110
various arguments that he had used, and determined at least to listen to his tale.

03:23:49.470 --> 03:23:54.230
I was partly urged by curiosity, and compassion confirmed my resolution.

03:23:55.190 --> 03:24:00.590
I had hitherto supposed him to be the murderer of my brother, and I eagerly sought a confirmation

03:24:00.590 --> 03:24:08.510
or denial of this opinion. For the first time, also, I felt what the duties of a creator towards

03:24:08.510 --> 03:24:13.250
his creature were, and that I ought to render him happy before I complained of his wickedness.

03:24:14.050 --> 03:24:20.430
These motives urged me to comply with his demand. We crossed the ice, therefore, and ascended the

03:24:20.430 --> 03:24:28.390
rock. The air was cold, and the rain again began to descend. We entered the hut, the fiend with an

03:24:28.390 --> 03:24:34.570
air of exultation, I with a heavy heart and depressed spirits. But I consented to listen,

03:24:34.990 --> 03:24:40.330
and seating myself by the fire which my odious companion had lighted, he thus began his tale.

03:25:07.050 --> 03:25:13.490
It is with considerable difficulty that I remember the original error of my being. All the events

03:25:13.490 --> 03:25:20.190
of that period appear confused and indistinct. A strange multiplicity of sensations sees me,

03:25:20.630 --> 03:25:26.890
and I saw, felt, heard, and smelled at the same time. And it was, indeed, a long time before I

03:25:26.890 --> 03:25:36.330
learned to distinguish between the operations of my various senses. By degrees I remember a

03:25:36.330 --> 03:25:42.910
shut my eyes. Darkness then came over me, and troubled me. But hardly had I felt this when,

03:25:42.930 --> 03:25:49.130
by opening my eyes, as I now suppose, the light poured in upon me again. I walked,

03:25:49.270 --> 03:25:53.730
and I believed, descended, but I presently found a great alteration in my sensations.

03:25:54.530 --> 03:26:01.730
Before, dark and opaque bodies had surrounded me, impervious to my touch or sight. But I now

03:26:01.730 --> 03:26:07.490
found that I could wander on at liberty with no obstacles, which I could not surmount or avoid.

03:26:08.450 --> 03:26:13.250
The light became more and more oppressive to me, and the heat wearing me as I walked,

03:26:13.790 --> 03:26:19.650
I sought a place where I could receive shade. This was the forest near Ingolstadt. And here

03:26:19.650 --> 03:26:24.830
I lay by the side of a brook, resting from my fatigue until I felt tormented by hunger and

03:26:24.830 --> 03:26:30.630
thirst. This roused me from my nearly dormant state, and I ate some berries which I had found

03:26:30.630 --> 03:26:36.730
hanging on the trees or lying on the ground. I slacked my thirst at the brook, and then lying

03:26:36.730 --> 03:26:46.430
down was overcome by sleep. It was dark when I awoke. I felt cold also, and half frightened,

03:26:46.850 --> 03:26:52.570
as it were instinctively, finding myself so desolate. Before I had quitted your apartment

03:26:52.570 --> 03:26:58.210
on a sensation of cold, I had covered myself with some clothes. But these were insufficient

03:26:58.210 --> 03:27:04.230
to secure me from the dews of night. I was poor, helpless, miserable wench. I knew and

03:27:04.230 --> 03:27:10.370
could distinguish nothing. But feeling pain invade me on all sides, I sat down and wept.

03:27:11.690 --> 03:27:17.570
Soon a gentle light stole over the heavens and gave me a sensation of pleasure. I stared up

03:27:17.570 --> 03:27:24.410
and beheld a radiant form rise from among the trees. The moon. I gazed with a kind of wonder.

03:27:24.410 --> 03:27:29.750
It moved slowly, but it enlightened my path, and I again went out in search of berries.

03:27:30.570 --> 03:27:36.330
I was still cold when under one of the trees I found a huge cloak, with which I covered myself

03:27:36.330 --> 03:27:44.530
and sat down upon the ground. No distinct ideas occupied my mind. I was confused. I felt light

03:27:44.530 --> 03:27:51.030
and hunger and thirst and darkness, innumerable sounds rang in my ears, and on all sides various

03:27:51.030 --> 03:27:57.030
scents saluted me. The only object that I could distinguish was the bright moon, and I fixed my

03:27:57.030 --> 03:28:03.290
eyes on that with pleasure. Several changes of the day and night passed, and the orb of night

03:28:03.290 --> 03:28:09.610
had greatly lessened when I began to distinguish my sensations from each other. I gradually saw

03:28:09.610 --> 03:28:14.510
plainly the clear stream that supplied me with drink and the trees that shaded me with their

03:28:14.510 --> 03:28:21.450
foliage. I was delighted when I first discovered that a pleasant sound, which often saluted my

03:28:21.450 --> 03:28:26.510
ears, proceeded from the throats of the little winged animals, who had often interpreted the

03:28:26.510 --> 03:28:33.170
light, intercepted the light from my eyes. I also began to observe with greater accuracy the forms

03:28:33.170 --> 03:28:38.990
that surrounded me, and to perceive the boundaries of the radiant roof of light which canopied me.

03:28:39.690 --> 03:28:45.990
Sometimes I tried to imitate the pleasant songs of the birds, but was unable. Sometimes I wished

03:28:45.990 --> 03:28:51.570
to express my sensations in my own mode, but the uncouth and inarticulate sounds which broke from

03:28:51.570 --> 03:28:57.750
me frightened me into silence again. The moon had disappeared from the night and again with a

03:28:57.750 --> 03:29:04.670
lessened form showed itself while I still remained in the forest. My sensations had by this time

03:29:04.670 --> 03:29:11.090
become distinct, and my mind received every day additional ideas. My eyes became accustomed to

03:29:11.090 --> 03:29:16.670
the light and to perceive objects in their right forms. I distinguished the insect from the herb,

03:29:16.990 --> 03:29:22.150
and by degrees one herb from another. I found that the sparrow uttered none but the harshest

03:29:22.150 --> 03:29:30.590
tones whilst those of the blackbird and thrush were sweet and enticing. One day when I was

03:29:30.590 --> 03:29:36.550
cold I found a fire which had been left by some wandering beggars, and was overcome with the light

03:29:36.550 --> 03:29:41.890
at the warmth I experienced from it. In my joy I thrust my hand into the live embers,

03:29:42.090 --> 03:29:47.710
but quickly drew it out again with a cry of pain. How strange, I thought, that the same

03:29:47.710 --> 03:29:54.030
cause should produce such opposite effects. I examined the materials of the fire, and to my joy

03:29:54.030 --> 03:29:58.950
found it to be composed of wood. I quickly collected some branches, but they were wet

03:29:58.950 --> 03:30:05.270
and would not burn. I was pained at this, and sat still watching the operation of the fire.

03:30:06.250 --> 03:30:12.490
The wet wood which I had placed near the heat dried in itself become inflamed. I reflected on

03:30:12.490 --> 03:30:17.450
this, and by touching the various branches I discovered the cause and busied myself in

03:30:17.450 --> 03:30:23.670
collecting a great quantity of wood that I might dry it and have a plentiful supply of fire. When

03:30:23.670 --> 03:30:28.930
I came on and brought sleep with it I was in the greatest fear lest my fire should be extinguished.

03:30:28.930 --> 03:30:35.510
I covered it carefully with dry wood and leaves and placed wet branches upon it, and then,

03:30:35.530 --> 03:30:41.350
spreading my cloak, I lay on the ground and sank into sleep. It was morning when I awoke,

03:30:41.410 --> 03:30:46.450
and my first care was to visit the fire. I uncovered it, and a gentle breeze quickly

03:30:46.450 --> 03:30:53.370
fanned it into flame. I observed this also, and contrived the fan of branches which roused the

03:30:53.370 --> 03:30:58.490
embers when they were nearly extinguished. When night came again I found with pleasure

03:30:58.490 --> 03:31:03.090
that the fire gave light as well as heat, and that the discovery of this element was useful

03:31:03.090 --> 03:31:07.930
to me and my food, for I found that some of the ovals that the travelers had left had been

03:31:07.930 --> 03:31:13.470
roasted and tasted much more savory than the berries I gathered from the trees. I tried

03:31:13.470 --> 03:31:18.830
therefore to dress my food in the same manner, placing it on the live embers. I found the

03:31:18.830 --> 03:31:23.270
berries were spoiled by this operation, and the nuts and roots much improved.

03:31:24.790 --> 03:31:30.210
Food, however, became scarce, and I often spent the whole day searching in vain for a few acorns

03:31:30.210 --> 03:31:36.730
to assuage the pangs of hunger. When I found this, I resolved to quit the place that I had hitherto

03:31:36.730 --> 03:31:43.210
inhabited, to seek for one where the few wants I experienced would be more easily satisfied.

03:31:43.990 --> 03:31:49.250
In this emigration I exceedingly lamented the loss of fire which I had obtained through accident,

03:31:49.250 --> 03:31:54.890
and knew not how to reproduce it. I gave several hours to the serious consideration of this

03:31:54.890 --> 03:32:01.610
difficulty, but I was obliged to relinquish all supply, all attempt to supply it, and wrapping

03:32:01.610 --> 03:32:07.650
myself in my cloak, I had struck across the wood towards the setting sun. I passed three days in

03:32:07.650 --> 03:32:14.970
these rambles, and at length discovered the open country. A great fall of snow had taken place the

03:32:14.970 --> 03:32:22.450
night before, and the fields were of one uniform white. The appearance was discolored, and I found

03:32:22.450 --> 03:32:28.450
my feet chilled by the cold damp substance that covered the ground. It was about seven in the

03:32:28.450 --> 03:32:34.350
morning, and I longed to obtain food and shelter. At length I perceived a small hut on a rising

03:32:34.350 --> 03:32:39.810
ground which had doubtlessly been built for the convenience of some shepherd. This was a new sight

03:32:39.810 --> 03:32:45.130
to me, and I examined the structure with great curiosity. Finding the door open, I entered.

03:32:45.790 --> 03:32:49.650
An old man sat in it near a fire over which he was preparing his breakfast.

03:32:50.410 --> 03:32:54.870
He turned on hearing a noise, and perceiving me, shrieked loudly, and quitting the hut,

03:32:55.010 --> 03:33:02.190
ran across the field with the speed of which his debilitated form hardly seemed capable.

03:33:02.950 --> 03:33:08.950
His appearance differed from any I had ever before seen, and his flight somewhat surprised me,

03:33:08.950 --> 03:33:13.750
but I was enchanted by the appearance of the hut. Here the snow and rain could not penetrate.

03:33:14.210 --> 03:33:20.490
The ground was dry, and it presented to me then as exquisite and divine a retreat as pandemonium

03:33:20.490 --> 03:33:27.190
appeared to the demons of hell after their sufferings in the lake of fire. I greedily

03:33:27.190 --> 03:33:33.130
devoured the remnants of the shepherd's breakfast, which consisted of bread, cheese, milk, and wine.

03:33:33.130 --> 03:33:41.090
The latter, however, I did not like. Then, overcome by fatigue, I lay down among some straw

03:33:41.090 --> 03:33:47.330
and fell asleep. It was noon when I awoke, and allured by the warmth of the sun, which shone

03:33:47.330 --> 03:33:53.210
brightly on the white ground, I determined to recommence my travels, and thus depositing the

03:33:53.210 --> 03:33:58.410
remains of the peasant breakfast and wallet I found. I proceeded across the fields for several

03:33:58.410 --> 03:34:05.330
hours until, at sunset, I arrived at a village. How miraculous did this appear! The huts, the

03:34:05.330 --> 03:34:11.590
neater cottages, the stately houses engaged my admiration by turns. The vegetables in the garden,

03:34:11.890 --> 03:34:16.630
the milk and cheese that I saw placed at the windows of some of the cottages allured my

03:34:16.630 --> 03:34:22.250
appetite. One of the best of these I entered, but I had hardly placed my foot within the door before

03:34:22.250 --> 03:34:28.690
children shrieked, and one of the women fainted. The whole village was roused, some fled, some

03:34:28.690 --> 03:34:35.010
attacked me, until, grievously bruised by stones and other kinds of missile weapons, I escaped to

03:34:35.010 --> 03:34:41.870
the open country and fearfully took refuge in a low hovel, quite bare, and making a wretched

03:34:41.870 --> 03:34:47.670
appearance after the palaces I had beheld in the village. This hovel, however, joined a cottage

03:34:47.670 --> 03:34:54.310
of neat and pleasant appearance, but after my late dearly bought experience I dared not enter it.

03:34:54.750 --> 03:35:01.530
My place of refuge was constructed of wood, but so low that I could enter it I could with difficulty

03:35:01.530 --> 03:35:07.550
sit upright in it. No wood, however, was placed on the earth which formed the floor, but it was dry,

03:35:08.050 --> 03:35:13.390
and although the wind entered it by innumerable chinks, I found it an agreeable asylum from the

03:35:13.390 --> 03:35:21.010
snow and rain. Here, then, I retreated and laid down to have, happy to have found a shelter,

03:35:21.610 --> 03:35:26.950
however miserable from the inclementcy of the season and still more from the barbarity of man.

03:35:27.770 --> 03:35:33.790
As soon as morning dawned I crept from my kennel that I might view the adjacent cottage and

03:35:33.790 --> 03:35:40.250
discover if it could remain in the habitation I had found. It was situated against the back of

03:35:40.250 --> 03:35:46.270
cottage and surrounded on both sides, on the sides which were exposed by a pigsty and a clear

03:35:46.270 --> 03:35:53.170
pool of water. One part was open, and by that I had crept in, but now I covered every crevice by

03:35:53.170 --> 03:35:58.630
which I might be perceived with stone and wood, yet in such a manner that I might move on the

03:35:58.630 --> 03:36:04.870
occasion to pass out, all the light I enjoyed came through the sty and that was sufficient for me.

03:36:05.610 --> 03:36:10.190
Having thus arranged my dwelling and carpeting it with clean straw, I retired,

03:36:10.270 --> 03:36:16.070
for I saw the figure of a man in the distance, and I remembered too well my treatment the night before

03:36:16.070 --> 03:36:23.970
to trust myself in his power. I had first, however, provided for my sustenance for the day

03:36:23.970 --> 03:36:31.510
by a loaf of coarse bread which I purloined and a cup from which I drank more conveniently than

03:36:31.510 --> 03:36:37.970
my hand of the pure water which flowed by my retreat. The floor was a little raised so that

03:36:37.970 --> 03:36:44.210
it was kept perfectly dry, and by its vicinity to the chimney of the cottage it was tolerably warm.

03:36:45.430 --> 03:36:50.230
Thus being provided, I resolved to reside in this hovel until something should occur

03:36:50.230 --> 03:36:56.190
which might alter my determination. It was indeed a paradise compared to the bleak forest,

03:36:56.190 --> 03:37:01.910
my former residence, and the rain-dropping branches and dank earth. I ate my breakfast

03:37:01.910 --> 03:37:07.490
with pleasure and was about to remove a plank to procure myself a little water when I heard a step,

03:37:08.210 --> 03:37:13.150
and looking through a small chink I beheld a young creature with a pail on her head passing

03:37:13.150 --> 03:37:19.890
before my hovel. The girl was young and of gentle demeanor, unlike what I have since found cottagers

03:37:19.890 --> 03:37:26.590
and farm house servants to be. Yet she was meanly dressed, a coarse blue petticoat, and a linen

03:37:26.590 --> 03:37:33.450
jacket being her only garb. Her fair hair was plaited but not adorned. She looked patient yet

03:37:33.450 --> 03:37:39.350
sad. I had lost sight of her, and in about a quarter of an hour she returned bearing the pail

03:37:39.350 --> 03:37:45.890
which was now partially filled with milk. As she walked along, seemingly uncommon by the burden,

03:37:45.890 --> 03:37:52.230
a young man met her, whose countenance expressed a deeper despondence. Uttering a few sounds with

03:37:52.230 --> 03:37:56.850
an air of melancholy, he took the pail from her head and bore it to the cottage himself.

03:37:57.590 --> 03:38:03.450
She followed and they disappeared. Presently I saw the young man again with some tools in his hand

03:38:03.450 --> 03:38:08.450
across the field behind the cottage, and the girl was also busied, sometimes in the house,

03:38:08.650 --> 03:38:14.310
sometimes in the yard. On examining my dwelling, I found that one of the windows of the cottage

03:38:14.310 --> 03:38:18.610
had formerly occupied a part of it, but the panes had been filled up with wood,

03:38:19.430 --> 03:38:24.490
and one of these was a small and almost imperceptible chink through which the eye

03:38:24.490 --> 03:38:30.630
could just penetrate. Through this crevice a small room was visible, whitewashed and clean,

03:38:30.770 --> 03:38:38.870
but very bare of furniture. In one corner, near a small fire, sat an old man, leaning his head on

03:38:38.870 --> 03:38:45.150
his hands in a disconsolid attitude. The young girl was occupied in arranging the cottage,

03:38:45.410 --> 03:38:51.390
but presently she took something out of a drawer which employed her hands, and she sat beside the

03:38:51.390 --> 03:38:56.870
old man, who, taking up an instrument, began to play and to produce sounds sweeter than the voice

03:38:56.870 --> 03:39:02.890
of the thrush or the nightingale. It was a lovely sight, even to me, poor wretch, who had never

03:39:03.710 --> 03:39:10.250
beheld aught beautiful before. The silver hair and benevolent countenance of the aged cottager

03:39:10.250 --> 03:39:16.650
won my reverence, while the gentle manners of the girl enticed my love. He played a sweet,

03:39:16.890 --> 03:39:21.230
mournful air which I perceived drew tears from the eyes of his amiable companion,

03:39:21.810 --> 03:39:27.790
of which the old man took no notice until she sobbed audibly. Then he pronounced a few sounds,

03:39:27.790 --> 03:39:33.550
and the fair creature, leaving her work, knelt at his feet. He raised her and smiled with such

03:39:33.550 --> 03:39:38.650
kindness and affection that I felt sensations of a particular and overpowering nature.

03:39:39.330 --> 03:39:44.790
They were a mixture of pain and pleasure, such as I had never before expressed, experienced,

03:39:45.290 --> 03:39:51.050
from either hunger or cold, warmth nor food, and I withdrew from the window, unable to bear these

03:39:51.050 --> 03:39:56.770
emotions. Soon after, the young man returned, bearing on his shoulders a load of wood.

03:39:57.590 --> 03:40:02.370
The girl met him at the door, helped to relieve him of his burden, and, taking some of the fuel

03:40:02.370 --> 03:40:07.770
into the cottage, placed it on the fire. Then she and the youth went apart into a nook of the

03:40:07.770 --> 03:40:13.390
cottage, and he showed her a large loaf and a piece of cheese. She seemed pleased and went

03:40:13.390 --> 03:40:18.170
into the garden for some roots and plants, which she placed in water and then upon the fire.

03:40:20.750 --> 03:40:26.550
Afterward, she continued her work, whilst the young man went into the garden and appeared busily

03:40:26.550 --> 03:40:32.710
employed in digging and pulling up roots. After he had been employed thus about an hour,

03:40:33.050 --> 03:40:35.790
the young woman joined him, and they entered the cottage together.

03:40:37.570 --> 03:40:41.970
The old man had in the meantime been pensive, but on the appearance of his companions,

03:40:42.570 --> 03:40:47.770
he assumed a more cheerful air, and they sat down to eat. The meal was quickly dispatched.

03:40:48.170 --> 03:40:53.390
The young woman was again occupied in arranging the cottage, and the old man walked before the

03:40:53.390 --> 03:40:59.070
cottage in the sun for a few minutes, leaning on the arm of the youth. Nothing could exceed in

03:40:59.070 --> 03:41:04.710
beauty the contrast between these two excellent creatures. One was old with silver hairs and

03:41:04.710 --> 03:41:10.030
accountants beaming with benevolence and love. The younger was slight and graceful in his figure,

03:41:10.410 --> 03:41:14.990
and his features were molded with the finest symmetry, yet his eyes and attitude expressed

03:41:14.990 --> 03:41:20.430
utmost sadness and despondency. The old man returned to the cottage, and the youth,

03:41:20.470 --> 03:41:25.390
with tools different from those he had used in the morning, directed his steps across the fields.

03:41:26.790 --> 03:41:33.130
Night quickly shut in, but to my extreme wonder, I found the cottagers had a means of prolonging

03:41:33.130 --> 03:41:38.830
light by the use of tapirs, and was delighted to find that in the setting of the sun did not

03:41:38.830 --> 03:41:44.450
put an end to the pleasure I experienced in watching my human neighbors. In the evening,

03:41:44.450 --> 03:41:49.950
the young girl and her companion were employed in various occupations, which I did not understand,

03:41:50.430 --> 03:41:55.270
and the old man again took up the instrument, which produced the divine sounds that enchanted

03:41:55.270 --> 03:42:01.870
me in the morning. As soon as he had finished, the youth began not to play, but to utter sounds that

03:42:01.870 --> 03:42:06.830
were monotonous, and neither resembling the harmony of the old man's instrument, nor the

03:42:06.830 --> 03:42:12.610
songs of the birds, I since found out that he read aloud, but at that time I knew nothing of the

03:42:12.610 --> 03:42:19.310
words or letters. The family, after having been thus occupied for a short time,

03:42:19.930 --> 03:42:25.670
extinguished their lights and retired, as I conjectured, to rest.

03:42:50.530 --> 03:42:54.890
I lay on my straw, but I could not sleep.

03:42:55.450 --> 03:43:01.230
I thought of the occurrences of the day. What chiefly struck me was the gentle manners of these

03:43:01.230 --> 03:43:07.430
people, and I longed to join them, but dared not. I remembered too well the treatment I had suffered

03:43:07.430 --> 03:43:13.370
the night before from the barbarous villagers, and resolved, whatever course of conduct I might

03:43:13.370 --> 03:43:19.070
hereafter think it right to pursue, that for the present I would remain quietly in my hobble,

03:43:19.070 --> 03:43:24.970
watching and endeavoring to discover the motives which influenced their actions.

03:43:27.010 --> 03:43:33.770
The cottagers arose the next morning before the sun. The young woman arranged the cottage and

03:43:33.770 --> 03:43:39.830
prepared the food, and the youth departed after the first meal. This day was passed in the same

03:43:39.830 --> 03:43:45.130
routine as that which preceded it. The young man was constantly employed out of doors,

03:43:45.130 --> 03:43:50.950
and the girl in various laborious occupations within. The old man, whom I soon perceived to

03:43:50.950 --> 03:43:57.490
be blind, enjoyed his leisure hours on his instrument or in contemplation. Nothing could

03:43:57.490 --> 03:44:03.550
exceed the love and respect which the younger cottagers exhibited towards their venerable

03:44:03.550 --> 03:44:10.550
companion. They performed towards him every little office of attention and duty with gentleness,

03:44:10.550 --> 03:44:17.990
and he rewarded them with his benevolent smiles. They were not entirely happy. The young man and

03:44:17.990 --> 03:44:23.310
his companion often went apart and appeared to weep. I saw no cause for their unhappiness,

03:44:23.490 --> 03:44:30.010
but I was deeply affected by it. If such lovely creatures were miserable, it was less strange

03:44:30.010 --> 03:44:36.230
that I, an imperfect and solitary being, should be wretched. Yet why were these gentle beings

03:44:36.230 --> 03:44:42.970
unhappy? They possessed a delightful house, for which it was in my eyes, and every luxury.

03:44:43.530 --> 03:44:47.250
They had a fire to warm them when chill and delicious viands when hungry.

03:44:48.370 --> 03:44:53.190
They were dressed in excellent clothes, and still more, they enjoyed one another's company and

03:44:53.190 --> 03:44:59.950
speech, interchanging each day looks of affection and kindness. What did their tears imply? Did they

03:44:59.950 --> 03:45:07.050
really express pain? I was at first unable to solve these questions, but perpetual attention

03:45:07.050 --> 03:45:16.030
and time explained to me many appearances which were first enigmatic. A considerable period

03:45:16.030 --> 03:45:21.290
elapsed before I discovered one of the causes of the uneasiness of this amenable family.

03:45:21.810 --> 03:45:26.190
It was poverty, and they suffered that evil in a very distressing degree.

03:45:26.830 --> 03:45:31.570
Their nourishment consisted entirely of the vegetables of their garden and the milk of one

03:45:31.570 --> 03:45:37.130
cow, which gave very little during the winter when its masters could scarcely procure food to

03:45:37.130 --> 03:45:43.030
support it. They often, I believe, suffered the pangs of hunger very poignantly, especially the

03:45:43.030 --> 03:45:48.390
two younger cottagers, for several times they placed food before the old man when they reserved

03:45:48.390 --> 03:45:54.970
none for themselves. This trait of kindness moved me sensibly. I had been accustomed during the night

03:45:54.970 --> 03:46:01.030
to steal a part of their store for my own consumption, but when I found that in doing

03:46:01.030 --> 03:46:07.350
this I inflicted pain on the cottagers, I abstained and satisfied myself with berries, nuts, and roots,

03:46:07.690 --> 03:46:13.370
which I gathered from a neighboring wood. I also discovered another means through which I was

03:46:13.370 --> 03:46:19.190
enabled to insist their labors. I found that the youth spent a great part of each day in collecting

03:46:19.190 --> 03:46:24.890
wood for the family fire, and during the night I often took his tools, the use of which I quickly

03:46:24.890 --> 03:46:31.050
discovered, and brought home firing sufficient for the consumption of several days. I remember

03:46:31.050 --> 03:46:36.150
the first time I did this. The young woman, when she opened the door in the morning, appeared greatly

03:46:36.150 --> 03:46:41.830
astonished on seeing such a great pile of wood on the outside. She uttered some words in a loud

03:46:41.830 --> 03:46:48.650
voice, and the youth joined her, who also expressed surprise. I observed with pleasure that he did not

03:46:48.650 --> 03:46:53.250
go into the forest that day, but spent it in repairing the cottage and cultivating the garden.

03:46:55.350 --> 03:47:01.170
By degrees I made a discovery of still greater moment. I found that these people possessed the

03:47:01.170 --> 03:47:05.730
method of communicating their experience and feelings to one another by articulate sounds.

03:47:06.830 --> 03:47:10.670
I perceived that the words they spoke sometimes produced pleasure or pain,

03:47:11.070 --> 03:47:17.490
smiles or sadness in the minds and countenances of the hearers. This was indeed a god-like science,

03:47:17.490 --> 03:47:23.470
and I ardently desired to become acquainted with it, but I was baffled in every attempt I made for

03:47:23.470 --> 03:47:30.070
its purpose. Their pronunciation was quick, and the words they uttered, not having any apparent

03:47:30.070 --> 03:47:35.970
connection with visible objects, I was unable to discover any clue by which I could unravel the

03:47:35.970 --> 03:47:41.630
mystery of their reference. By great application, however, and after having remained during the

03:47:41.630 --> 03:47:46.590
space of several revolutions of the moon in my hobble, I discovered the names that were given

03:47:46.590 --> 03:47:53.150
to some of the most familiar objects of discourse. I learned and applied the words fire, milk, bread,

03:47:53.150 --> 03:47:59.630
and wood. I learned the names of the cottagers themselves. The youth and his companion had each

03:47:59.630 --> 03:48:07.010
of them several names, but the old man had only one, which was father. The girl was called sister,

03:48:07.090 --> 03:48:14.830
or Agatha, and the youth Felix, brother, or son. I cannot describe the delight I felt when I learned

03:48:14.830 --> 03:48:20.450
the ideas appropriated to each of these sounds and was able to pronounce them. I distinguished

03:48:20.450 --> 03:48:28.290
several other words without being able as yet to understand or apply them, such as good, dearest,

03:48:28.750 --> 03:48:36.990
unhappy. I spent the winter in this manner. The gentle manners and beauty of the cottagers

03:48:36.990 --> 03:48:42.470
greatly endeared them to me. When they were unhappy, I felt depressed. When they rejoiced,

03:48:42.550 --> 03:48:48.770
I sympathized in their joys. I saw few human beings besides them, and if any other happened

03:48:48.770 --> 03:48:53.490
under the cottage, their harsh manners and rude gait only enhanced me to the superior

03:48:53.490 --> 03:48:59.870
accomplishments of my friends. The old man, I could perceive, often endeavored to encourage

03:48:59.870 --> 03:49:04.930
his children, as sometimes I found that he called to them to cast off their melancholy.

03:49:05.370 --> 03:49:10.150
He would talk in a cheerful accent, and the expression of goodness that bestowed pleasure

03:49:10.150 --> 03:49:17.430
upon me. Agatha listened with respect. Her eyes sometimes filled with tears, which she endeavored

03:49:17.430 --> 03:49:23.770
to wipe away unperceived, but I found, generally found, that her countenance and tone were more

03:49:23.770 --> 03:49:30.870
cheerful after having listened to the exhortations of her father. It was not thus with Felix. He was

03:49:30.870 --> 03:49:36.350
always the saddest of the group, and even to my unpracticed senses he appears to have suffered

03:49:36.350 --> 03:49:43.570
more deeply than his friends. But if his countenance was more sorrowful, his voice was more cheerful

03:49:43.570 --> 03:49:48.910
of that of his sister, especially when he addressed the old man.

03:49:51.550 --> 03:49:54.990
I could mention innumerable instances which, although slight,

03:49:55.630 --> 03:50:02.030
marked the dispositions of these amiable cottagers. In the midst of poverty and want, Felix carried

03:50:02.670 --> 03:50:08.290
with pleasure to his sister the first little white flower that peeped out from beneath the snowy

03:50:08.290 --> 03:50:14.650
ground. Early in the morning, before she had risen, he had cleared away the snow that obstructed her

03:50:14.650 --> 03:50:20.310
path to the milk house, drew water from the well, and brought the wood from the outhouse,

03:50:20.830 --> 03:50:26.210
where, to his perpetual astonishment, he found his store always replenished by an invisible hand.

03:50:27.190 --> 03:50:32.590
In the day, I believed, he worked sometimes for a neighboring farmer, because he often went forth

03:50:32.590 --> 03:50:38.270
and did not return until dinner, yet brought no wood with him. At other times, he worked in the

03:50:38.270 --> 03:50:44.570
garden, but as there was little to do in the frosty season, he read to the old man and Agatha.

03:50:46.690 --> 03:50:52.410
This reading had puzzled me extremely at first, but by degrees I discovered that he uttered many

03:50:52.410 --> 03:50:58.630
of the same sounds when he read as when he talked. I conjectured, therefore, that he found on the

03:50:58.630 --> 03:51:04.210
paper signs for speech which he understood, and I ardently longed to comprehend these also.

03:51:04.690 --> 03:51:09.290
But how was that possible when I did not even understand the sounds for which they stood as

03:51:09.290 --> 03:51:16.530
signs? I improved, however, sensibly in this science, but not sufficiently to follow any kind

03:51:16.530 --> 03:51:22.810
of conversation, although I applied my whole mind to the endeavor, for I easily perceived,

03:51:23.030 --> 03:51:30.430
although I eagerly longed to discover myself to the cottagers, I ought not make to the attempt

03:51:30.430 --> 03:51:36.310
until I at first become master of their language, which knowledge might enable me to make them

03:51:36.310 --> 03:51:42.870
overlook the deformity of my figure, for with this also the contrast perpetually presented to

03:51:42.870 --> 03:51:50.230
my eyes had made me acquainted. I admired the perfect forms of my cottagers, their grace,

03:51:50.410 --> 03:51:57.290
beauty, and delicate complexions, but how I was terrified when I viewed myself in the transparent

03:51:57.290 --> 03:52:03.810
pool. At first I stared back, unable to believe that it was indeed I who reflected in the mirror,

03:52:04.350 --> 03:52:10.070
and when I became fully convinced that I was in reality the monster that I am,

03:52:10.430 --> 03:52:14.990
I was filled with the bitterest sensations of despondence and mortification.

03:52:15.990 --> 03:52:21.650
Alas, I did not yet entirely know the fatal effects of this miserable deformity.

03:52:22.570 --> 03:52:28.050
As the sun became warmer and the light of the day longer, the snows vanished, and I beheld

03:52:28.730 --> 03:52:34.890
the bare trees and black earth. From this time Felix was more employed, and the heart-moving

03:52:34.890 --> 03:52:42.090
indications of impending famine disappeared. Their food, after which I found, was coarse,

03:52:42.730 --> 03:52:48.290
but it was wholesome, and they procured a sufficiency of it. Several new kinds of plants

03:52:48.290 --> 03:52:53.330
sprang up in the garden, which they dressed, and these signs of comfort increased daily

03:52:53.330 --> 03:53:01.310
as the season advanced. The old man, leaning on his son, walked each day at noon when it did not

03:53:01.310 --> 03:53:07.810
rain, and I found it was called when the heavens poured forth its waters. This frequently took

03:53:07.810 --> 03:53:13.130
place, but a high wind quickly dried the earth, and the season became far more pleasant than it

03:53:13.130 --> 03:53:18.950
had been. My mode of life and my hobble was uniform. During the morning I attended the

03:53:18.950 --> 03:53:23.830
motions of the cottagers, and when they were dispersed in various occupations I slept.

03:53:24.370 --> 03:53:29.710
The remainder of the day was spent in observing my friends. When they had retired to rest,

03:53:29.770 --> 03:53:35.350
if there was any moon or the night was starlight, I went to the woods and collected my own food

03:53:35.350 --> 03:53:41.410
and fuel for the cottage. When I returned as often as it was necessary, I cleared their path

03:53:41.410 --> 03:53:48.230
the snow and performed those offices that I had seen done by Felix. I afterwards found that these

03:53:48.230 --> 03:53:54.230
labors, performed by an invisible hand, greatly astonished them, and once or twice I heard them

03:53:54.230 --> 03:54:00.370
on these occasions utter the words, good spirit, wonderful, but I did not then understand the

03:54:01.230 --> 03:54:08.290
signification of these terms. My thoughts now become more active, and I long to discover the

03:54:08.290 --> 03:54:13.870
motives and feelings of these lovely creatures. I was inquisitive to know why Felix appeared so

03:54:13.870 --> 03:54:20.570
miserable and Agatha so sad. I thought, foolish wrench, that it might be in my power to restore

03:54:20.570 --> 03:54:26.770
happiness to these deserving people. When I slept or was absent, the forms of the venerable blind

03:54:26.770 --> 03:54:34.010
father, the gentle Agatha, and the excellent Felix flitted before me. I looked upon them as superior

03:54:34.010 --> 03:54:39.650
beings who would be the arbiters of my future destiny. I formed in my imagination a thousand

03:54:39.650 --> 03:54:45.990
pictures of presenting myself to them and their gentle reception of me. I imagined that they would

03:54:45.990 --> 03:54:52.190
be disgusted until, by my gentle demeanor and conciliating words, I should first win their favor

03:54:52.190 --> 03:54:59.190
and afterwards their love. These thoughts exhilarated me and led me to apply with fresh

03:54:59.190 --> 03:55:06.170
to the acquiring the art of language. My organs were indeed harsh but supple, and although my

03:55:06.170 --> 03:55:12.150
voice was very unlike the soft music of their tones, yet I pronounced such words as I understood

03:55:12.150 --> 03:55:20.170
with tolerable ease. It was as the ass and the lap dog, yet surely the gentle ass whose intentions

03:55:20.170 --> 03:55:29.070
were affectionate, although his manners were rude, deserved better treatment than blows and excretion.

03:55:29.750 --> 03:55:36.490
The pleasant showers and gentle warmth of spring greatly altered the aspect of the earth. Men who

03:55:36.490 --> 03:55:42.250
before this change seemed to have been hid in caves dispersed themselves and were employed in

03:55:42.250 --> 03:55:48.030
various arts of cultivation. The birds sang in more cheerful tones and the leaves began to bud

03:55:48.030 --> 03:55:55.030
forth on the trees. Happy, happy earth. Fit habitation for gods, which so short a time before

03:55:55.030 --> 03:56:02.070
was bleak, damp, and unwholesome. My spirits were elevated by the enhancing appearance of nature.

03:56:02.830 --> 03:56:06.190
The past was blotted from my memory, the present was tranquil,

03:56:06.770 --> 03:56:13.270
and the future guided by bright rays of hope and anticipations of joy.

03:56:38.070 --> 03:56:41.590
I now hasten to the more moving part of my story.

03:56:41.590 --> 03:56:48.410
I shall relate events that impressed me with feelings which, from what I had been, had made

03:56:48.410 --> 03:56:55.290
me what I am. Spring advanced rapidly and the weather became fine and the skies cloudless.

03:56:56.090 --> 03:56:59.870
It surprised me that what before was desert and gloomy should now bloom

03:56:59.870 --> 03:57:07.210
with the most beautiful flowers and verdure. My senses were gratified and refreshed by a thousand

03:57:07.210 --> 03:57:13.170
scents of delight and a thousand sights of beauty. It was on one of these days when my

03:57:13.170 --> 03:57:19.070
cottagers periodically rested from labor, the old man played on his guitar and the children listened

03:57:19.070 --> 03:57:25.030
to him, that I observed the countenance of Felix was melancholy beyond expression. He sighed

03:57:25.030 --> 03:57:31.950
frequently and once his father paused in his music and I conjectured by his manner that he

03:57:31.950 --> 03:57:39.310
the cause of the son's sorrow. Felix replied in a cheerful accent and the old man was recommencing

03:57:39.310 --> 03:57:45.590
his music when someone tapped at the door. It was a lady on horseback accompanied by a countryman

03:57:45.590 --> 03:57:51.950
as a guide. The lady was dressed in a dark suit and covered with a thick black veil. Agatha asked

03:57:51.950 --> 03:57:57.830
a question to which the stranger only replied by pronouncing in a sweet accent the name of Felix.

03:57:58.470 --> 03:58:01.910
Her voice was musical but unlike that of either of my friends.

03:58:02.750 --> 03:58:10.230
On hearing this word Felix came up hastily to the lady who when she saw him threw up her veil

03:58:10.230 --> 03:58:17.410
and I beheld a countenance of angelic beauty and expression. Her hair of shining raven black and

03:58:17.410 --> 03:58:23.950
curiously braided. Her eyes were dark but gentle though animated. Her features of a regular

03:58:23.950 --> 03:58:29.750
proportion and her complexion wondrously fair each cheek tingled with a lovely pink.

03:58:30.890 --> 03:58:36.510
Felix sometimes ravaged with delight when he saw her. Every trait of sorrow vanished from his face

03:58:36.510 --> 03:58:42.790
and it instantly expressed a degree of ecstatic joy of which I could hardly have believed capable.

03:58:43.410 --> 03:58:48.190
His eyes sparkled as his cheeks flushed with pleasure and at that moment I thought of him

03:58:48.190 --> 03:58:53.870
as beautiful as the stranger. She appeared affected by different feelings wiping a few

03:58:53.870 --> 03:58:59.010
tears from her lovely eyes. She held her hand out to Felix who kissed it rapturously

03:58:59.010 --> 03:59:05.770
and called her as well as I could distinguish his sweet Abraham. She did not appear to understand

03:59:05.770 --> 03:59:11.850
him but smiled. He assisted her to dismount and dismissing her guide conducted her into the

03:59:11.850 --> 03:59:17.410
cottage. Some conversation took place between him and his father and the young stranger now

03:59:17.410 --> 03:59:22.950
at the old man's feet and would have kissed his hand but he raised her and embraced her affectionately.

03:59:24.990 --> 03:59:30.210
I soon perceived that although the stranger uttered the articulate sounds and soon appeared

03:59:30.210 --> 03:59:36.350
to have a language of her own she was neither understood by nor herself understood the cottagers.

03:59:37.450 --> 03:59:42.890
They made many signs which I did not comprehend and I saw that her presence diffused gladness

03:59:42.890 --> 03:59:48.790
through the cottage dispelling their sorrow as the sun dissipates the morning mist. Felix

03:59:48.790 --> 03:59:55.210
seemed particularly happy and with smiles of delight welcomed his Abraham. Agatha the ever

03:59:55.210 --> 04:00:00.990
gentle Agatha kissed the hands of the lovely stranger and pointing to her brother made signs

04:00:00.990 --> 04:00:06.810
which appeared to me to mean that he had been sorrowful until she came. Some hours passed thus

04:00:06.810 --> 04:00:11.850
while they by their countenances expressed joy the cause of which I did not comprehend.

04:00:12.930 --> 04:00:18.330
Presently I found by the frequent recurrence of some sound which the stranger repeated after them

04:00:18.330 --> 04:00:23.790
that she was endeavoring to learn their language and the idea instantly occurred to me that I

04:00:23.790 --> 04:00:29.290
should make use of the same instructions to the same end. The stranger learned about 20 words at

04:00:29.290 --> 04:00:35.590
the first lesson most of them indeed were those which I had before understood but I profited by

04:00:35.590 --> 04:00:42.950
others. As night came on Agatha and the and the Arabian retired early when they separated Felix

04:00:42.950 --> 04:00:49.350
kissed the hand of the stranger and said good night sweet Safi. He sat up much longer conversing with

04:00:49.350 --> 04:00:55.290
his father and by the frequent repetition of her name I conjectured that their lovely guest was the

04:00:55.290 --> 04:01:01.790
subject of their conversation. I ardently desired to understand them and bent every faculty towards

04:01:01.790 --> 04:01:09.350
that purpose but found it utterly impossible. The next morning Felix went out to his work

04:01:09.350 --> 04:01:14.630
and after the usual occupations of Agatha were finished the Arabian sat at the feet of the old

04:01:14.630 --> 04:01:20.810
man and taking his guitar played some airs so entrancingly beautiful that they at once

04:01:20.810 --> 04:01:26.370
drew tears of sorrow and delight from my eyes. She sang and her voice flowed with a rich cadence

04:01:26.370 --> 04:01:32.430
swelling or dying like a night night like a nightingale of the woods. When she had finished

04:01:32.430 --> 04:01:37.830
she gave the guitar to Agatha who at first declined it. She played a simple air and her

04:01:37.830 --> 04:01:42.610
voice accompanied it in sweet accents but unlike the wondrous strain of the stranger

04:01:43.330 --> 04:01:49.130
the old man appeared enraptured and said some words with Agatha endeavored to explain to Safi

04:01:49.130 --> 04:01:54.250
and by which he appeared to wish to express that she bestowed on him the greatest delight by her

04:01:54.250 --> 04:02:01.270
music. The days now passed as peacefully as before with the sole alteration that joy had

04:02:01.270 --> 04:02:07.190
taken place of sadness and accountances of my friends. Safi was always gay and happy.

04:02:07.690 --> 04:02:12.990
She and I improved rapidly in the knowledge of language so that in two months I began to

04:02:12.990 --> 04:02:18.750
comprehend most of the words uttered by my protectors. In the meanwhile also the black

04:02:18.750 --> 04:02:23.630
ground was covered with herbage and the green banks interspersed with innumerable flowers

04:02:23.630 --> 04:02:30.130
sweet to the scent and the eyes stars of pale radiance among the moonlit woods. The sun became

04:02:30.130 --> 04:02:37.050
warmer the nights clear and balmy and my nocturnal ramblers rambles were an extreme pleasure to me

04:02:37.050 --> 04:02:41.470
although they were considerably shortened by the late setting and early rising of the sun

04:02:41.470 --> 04:02:46.490
for I never ventured abroad during daylight fearful of meeting with the same treatment

04:02:46.490 --> 04:02:49.470
I had formerly endured at the first village which I entered.

04:02:51.550 --> 04:02:56.970
My days were spent in close attention that I might more speedily master the language

04:02:56.970 --> 04:03:02.230
and that I may boast and I may boast that I improved more rapidly than the Arabian

04:03:02.230 --> 04:03:07.930
who understood very little and conversed in broken accents whilst I comprehended and can

04:03:07.930 --> 04:03:14.470
imitate almost every word that was spoken. While I improved in speech I also learned the science of

04:03:14.470 --> 04:03:19.450
letters as it was taught to the stranger and this opened before me a wide range of words

04:03:19.450 --> 04:03:26.190
a wide field for wonder and delight. The book from which Felix instructed Safi was Volney's

04:03:26.190 --> 04:03:32.630
Ruins of Empires. I should not have understood the purport of this book had not Felix in reading it

04:03:32.630 --> 04:03:37.930
gave very minute explanations. He had chosen this work he said because the

04:03:37.930 --> 04:03:44.290
the clamatory style was framed in imitation of the eastern authors though this work I obtained

04:03:44.290 --> 04:03:50.510
through this work I obtained a curious knowledge of history and a view of the several empires at

04:03:50.510 --> 04:03:55.850
present existing in the world. It gave me an insight into the manners governments and religions

04:03:55.850 --> 04:04:02.050
of the different nations of the earth. I heard of the slothful Asiatics of the

04:04:02.050 --> 04:04:14.270
stupendous genius and mental activity of the Grecians of the war and wondrous virtue of the

04:04:14.270 --> 04:04:19.550
chivalry Christianity and kings. I heard of the discovery of the American hemisphere

04:04:19.550 --> 04:04:25.110
and wept with Safi over the hapless fate of its of its original inhabitants.

04:04:26.790 --> 04:04:33.210
These wonderful narrations inspired me with strange feelings was man indeed at once so powerful so

04:04:33.210 --> 04:04:39.930
virtuous and magnificent yet so vicious and base. He appeared at one time the mere scion of evil

04:04:39.930 --> 04:04:45.710
of the evil principle and at another as all that can be conceived of noble and godlike.

04:04:46.390 --> 04:04:51.030
To be a great and virtuous man appeared the highest honor that can befall a sensitive being.

04:04:51.750 --> 04:04:58.670
To be based and vicious as many on record have been appeared the lowest

04:04:59.850 --> 04:05:05.690
degration a condition more object that than that of the blind mole or harmless worm.

04:05:06.450 --> 04:05:11.110
For a long time I could not conceive how one man could go forth to murder his fellow

04:05:11.110 --> 04:05:17.030
or even why there were laws and governments but when I heard details of the vice and bloodshed

04:05:17.030 --> 04:05:23.670
my wonder ceased and I turned away with disgust and loathing. Every conversation of the cottagers

04:05:23.670 --> 04:05:30.550
now opened new wonders to me. While I listened to the instructors instructions with Felix bestowed

04:05:30.550 --> 04:05:37.450
upon the Arabian the strange system of human society was explained to me. I heard of the division

04:05:37.450 --> 04:05:43.670
of property of immense wealth and squalid poverty of rank descent and noble blood.

04:05:44.350 --> 04:05:50.250
The words introduced me to turn towards myself. I learned that the possessions most esteemed by

04:05:50.250 --> 04:05:57.550
your fellow creatures were high and unsullied descent united with riches. A man might be

04:05:57.550 --> 04:06:03.030
respected with only one of these advantages but without either he was considered except in very

04:06:03.030 --> 04:06:09.310
rare instances as a vagabond and a slave doomed to waste his powers for the profits of the chosen

04:06:09.310 --> 04:06:16.810
few. And what was I of my creation and creator I was absolutely ignorant but I knew that I possess

04:06:16.810 --> 04:06:24.530
no money no friends no kind of property. I was beside endured with a hideously figured a figure

04:06:24.530 --> 04:06:31.930
hideously deformed and lonesome. I was not even the same nature as man. I was more agile than they

04:06:31.930 --> 04:06:37.750
and could subsist on upon a coarser diet. I bore the extremities of heat and coal with less injury

04:06:37.750 --> 04:06:45.050
to my frame and my stature far exceeded theirs. When I looked around I saw and heard of none like

04:06:45.050 --> 04:06:52.570
me. Was I then a monster a blot upon the earth from which all men fled and whom all men disowned?

04:06:53.330 --> 04:06:57.850
I cannot describe to you the agony that these reflections inflicted upon me.

04:06:58.230 --> 04:07:04.570
I tried to dispel them but sorrow only increased with knowledge. Oh that I had forever remained

04:07:04.570 --> 04:07:11.390
in my native wood nor known nor felt beyond the sensations of hunger thirst and heat.

04:07:12.530 --> 04:07:17.810
Of what a strange nature is knowledge it clings to the mind when it is once seized on it like a light

04:07:17.810 --> 04:07:24.130
on a rock. I had sometimes wished to shake off all thought and feeling but I learned that it

04:07:24.130 --> 04:07:30.050
was only one means to overcome the sensation of pain and that was death a state of which I feared

04:07:30.050 --> 04:07:36.850
yet did not understand. I admired virtue and good feelings and loved the gentle manners and admirable

04:07:36.850 --> 04:07:42.530
qualities of my cottagers but I was shut off from the intercourse with them except through means

04:07:42.530 --> 04:07:48.870
which I obtained by stealth when I was unseen and unknown which rather increased than satisfied

04:07:48.870 --> 04:07:56.750
the desire I had of becoming one of my fellows. The gentle words of Agatha and the animated smiles

04:07:56.750 --> 04:08:02.950
of the charming Arabian were not for me. The mild exhortations of the old man and the lively

04:08:02.950 --> 04:08:08.670
conversation of the loved Felix were not for me. Miserable unhappy wrench.

04:08:10.910 --> 04:08:16.870
Other lessons were impressed upon me even more deeply. I heard of the differences between the

04:08:16.870 --> 04:08:21.950
sexes and the birth and growth of children. How the father doted on the smiles of the infant

04:08:21.950 --> 04:08:28.570
and the lively sallies of the older child. How all life and cares of the mother were wrapped up in

04:08:28.570 --> 04:08:34.870
precious charge. How the mind of youth expanded and gained knowledge of brother sister and all

04:08:34.870 --> 04:08:41.270
various relationships which bind one human being to another in mutual bonds. But where were my

04:08:41.270 --> 04:08:47.050
friends in relations? No father had watched my infant days. No mother had blessed me with smiles

04:08:47.050 --> 04:08:54.270
or caresses. Nor if they had all my past life was now a blot a blind vacancy in which I distinguished

04:08:54.270 --> 04:09:02.430
nothing. From my earliest remembrance I had been as I then was in height and proportion.

04:09:02.970 --> 04:09:09.870
I had never yet seen a being resembling me or who claimed any intercourse with me. What was I?

04:09:10.190 --> 04:09:16.570
The question returned only to be answered with groans. I will soon explain to what those feelings

04:09:16.570 --> 04:09:22.690
tended but allow me to return to the cottagers whose story excited me in such various feeling

04:09:22.690 --> 04:09:28.670
of indignation delight and wonder but which all terminated in innocent love and reverence for my

04:09:28.670 --> 04:09:37.270
protectors. For so I loved in an innocent half painful self-deceit to call them.

04:10:00.410 --> 04:10:03.530
Some time elapsed before I learned the history of my friends.

04:10:03.950 --> 04:10:08.590
It was one which could not fail to impress itself deeply on my mind, unfolding as it

04:10:08.590 --> 04:10:14.230
did in a number of circumstances, each interesting and wonderful to one so utterly inexperienced

04:10:14.230 --> 04:10:15.070
as I was.

04:10:15.990 --> 04:10:18.110
The name of the old man was De Lacey.

04:10:18.570 --> 04:10:23.430
He was descended from a good family in France, where he had lived for many years in affluence,

04:10:23.870 --> 04:10:26.550
respected by his superiors and beloved by his equals.

04:10:27.290 --> 04:10:32.210
His son was bred in the service of his country, and Agatha had ranked with ladies of the highest

04:10:32.210 --> 04:10:32.750
distinction.

04:10:33.390 --> 04:10:38.730
A few months before my arrival, they had lived in a large and luxurious city called Paris,

04:10:39.290 --> 04:10:43.990
surrounded by friends and possessed of every enjoyment which virtue, refinement of intellect

04:10:43.990 --> 04:10:47.410
or taste, accompanied by a moderate fortune, could afford.

04:10:48.110 --> 04:10:50.570
The father of Safie had been the cause of their ruin.

04:10:51.150 --> 04:10:55.970
He was a Turkish merchant, and had inhabited Paris for many years, when for some reason

04:10:55.970 --> 04:10:59.030
which I could not learn, he became obnoxious to the government.

04:10:59.030 --> 04:11:04.230
He was seized and cast into prison the very day that Safie arrived from Constantinople

04:11:04.230 --> 04:11:04.970
to join him.

04:11:05.370 --> 04:11:07.510
He was tried and condemned to death.

04:11:08.310 --> 04:11:10.710
The injustice of his sentence was very flagrant.

04:11:10.890 --> 04:11:15.290
All Paris was indignant, and it was judged that his religion and wealth, rather than

04:11:15.290 --> 04:11:18.330
the crime alleged against him, had been the cause of his condemnation.

04:11:19.470 --> 04:11:21.570
Felix had accidentally been present at the trial.

04:11:21.870 --> 04:11:25.890
His horror and indignation were uncontrollable when he heard the decision of the court.

04:11:25.890 --> 04:11:30.890
He made at that moment a solemn vow to deliver him, and then looked around for the means.

04:11:31.590 --> 04:11:36.270
After many fruitless attempts to gain admittance to the prison, he found a strongly graded

04:11:36.270 --> 04:11:40.770
window in an unguarded part of the building, which lighted the dungeon of the unfortunate

04:11:40.770 --> 04:11:46.130
Mohammedan, who, loaded with chains, waited in despair the execution of the barbarous

04:11:46.130 --> 04:11:46.630
sentence.

04:11:47.530 --> 04:11:51.850
Felix visited the great at night, and made known to the prisoner his intentions in his

04:11:51.850 --> 04:11:52.130
favor.

04:11:52.670 --> 04:11:58.210
The Turk, amazed and delighted, endeavored to rekindle the zeal of his deliverer by promises

04:11:58.210 --> 04:11:59.570
of reward and wealth.

04:12:00.450 --> 04:12:02.350
Felix rejected his offers with contempt.

04:12:03.110 --> 04:12:07.510
Yet when he saw the lovely Safie, who was allowed to visit her father, and who by her

04:12:07.510 --> 04:12:12.610
gestures expressed her lively gratitude, the youth could not help owning to his own mind

04:12:12.610 --> 04:12:17.210
that the captive possessed a treasure which would fully reward his toil and hazard.

04:12:17.790 --> 04:12:21.330
The Turk quickly perceived the impression that his daughter had made on the heart of

04:12:21.330 --> 04:12:26.330
Felix, and endeavored to secure him more entirely in his interests by the promise of her hand

04:12:26.330 --> 04:12:29.510
in marriage so soon as he should be conveyed to a place of safety.

04:12:30.610 --> 04:12:35.030
Felix was too delicate to accept this offer, yet he looked forward to the probability of

04:12:35.030 --> 04:12:37.390
the event as to the consummation of his happiness.

04:12:38.310 --> 04:12:43.090
During the ensuing days, while the preparations were going forward for the escape of the merchant,

04:12:43.490 --> 04:12:47.930
the zeal of Felix was warmed by several letters that he received from this lovely girl, who

04:12:48.470 --> 04:12:53.270
her thoughts in the language of her lover by the aid of an old man, a servant of her

04:12:53.270 --> 04:12:54.610
father who understood French.

04:12:55.370 --> 04:12:59.910
She thanked him in the most ardent terms for his intended services toward her parent, and

04:12:59.910 --> 04:13:02.610
at the same time she gently deplored her own fate.

04:13:03.570 --> 04:13:08.270
I have copies of these letters, for I found means during my residence in the hovel to

04:13:08.270 --> 04:13:12.130
procure implements of writing, and the letters were often in the hands of Felix or Agatha.

04:13:12.730 --> 04:13:14.950
Before I depart, I will give them to you.

04:13:15.050 --> 04:13:16.790
They will prove the truth of my tale.

04:13:16.790 --> 04:13:21.590
But at present, as the sun is already far declined, I shall only have time to repeat

04:13:21.590 --> 04:13:23.050
the substance of them to you.

04:13:24.350 --> 04:13:28.610
Safi related that her mother was a Christian Arab, seized and made a slave by the Turks.

04:13:29.150 --> 04:13:33.570
Recommended by her beauty, she had won the heart of the father of Safi, who married her.

04:13:34.210 --> 04:13:38.650
The young girl spoke in high and enthusiastic terms of her mother, who, born in freedom,

04:13:39.210 --> 04:13:41.370
spurned the bondage to which she was now reduced.

04:13:41.790 --> 04:13:45.810
She instructed her daughter in the tenets of her religion, and taught her to aspire

04:13:45.810 --> 04:13:50.610
to higher powers of intellect and an independence of spirit forbidden to the female followers

04:13:50.610 --> 04:13:51.210
of Muhammad.

04:13:51.950 --> 04:13:56.890
This lady died, but her lessons were indelibly impressed on the mind of Safi, who sickened

04:13:56.890 --> 04:14:01.150
at the prospect of again returning to Asia and being immured within the walls of a harem,

04:14:01.650 --> 04:14:05.850
allowed only to occupy herself with infantile amusements ill-suited to the temper of her

04:14:05.850 --> 04:14:09.650
soul, now accustomed to grand ideas and a noble emulation for virtue.

04:14:10.350 --> 04:14:14.590
The prospect of marrying a Christian and remaining in a country where women were allowed to take

04:14:14.590 --> 04:14:16.950
rank in society was enchanting to her.

04:14:18.550 --> 04:14:22.930
The day for the execution of the Turk was fixed, but on the night previous to it, he

04:14:22.930 --> 04:14:26.450
quitted his prison and before morning was distant many leagues from Paris.

04:14:27.370 --> 04:14:31.010
Felix had procured passports in the name of his father, sister and himself.

04:14:31.530 --> 04:14:36.030
He had previously communicated his plan to the former, who aided the deceit by quitting

04:14:36.030 --> 04:14:40.250
his house under the pretense of a journey, and concealed himself with his daughter in

04:14:40.250 --> 04:14:41.730
an obscure part of Paris.

04:14:42.590 --> 04:14:47.690
Felix conducted the fugitives through France to Lyon and across Mount Sinis to Leghorn,

04:14:48.050 --> 04:14:52.550
where the merchant had decided to wait a favorable opportunity of passing into some part of the

04:14:52.550 --> 04:14:53.970
Turkish dominions.

04:14:54.410 --> 04:14:58.610
Safi resolved to remain with her father until the moment of his departure, before which

04:14:58.610 --> 04:15:03.330
time the Turk renewed his promise that she should be united to his deliverer, and Felix

04:15:03.330 --> 04:15:05.450
remained with them in expectation of that event.

04:15:05.950 --> 04:15:10.630
And in the meantime, he enjoyed the society of the Arabian, who exhibited toward him the

04:15:10.630 --> 04:15:12.230
simplest and tenderest affection.

04:15:12.970 --> 04:15:17.210
They conversed with one another through the means of an interpreter, and sometimes with

04:15:17.210 --> 04:15:21.890
the interpretation of looks, and Safi sang to him the divine aires of her native country.

04:15:22.810 --> 04:15:27.350
The Turk allowed this intimacy to take place and encouraged the hopes of the youthful lovers,

04:15:27.790 --> 04:15:30.210
while in his heart he had formed far other plans.

04:15:30.650 --> 04:15:34.870
He loathed the idea that his daughter should be united to a Christian, but he feared the

04:15:34.870 --> 04:15:39.270
resentment of Felix if he should appear lukewarm, for he knew that he was still in the power

04:15:39.270 --> 04:15:43.690
of his deliverer if he should choose to betray him to the Italian state which they inhabited.

04:15:44.370 --> 04:15:48.470
He revolved a thousand plans by which he should be enabled to prolong the deceit until it

04:15:48.470 --> 04:15:52.810
might be no longer necessary, and secretly to take his daughter with him when he departed.

04:15:53.690 --> 04:15:56.790
His plans were facilitated by the news which arrived from Paris.

04:15:57.330 --> 04:16:01.750
The government of France were greatly enraged at the escape of their victim, and spared

04:16:01.750 --> 04:16:04.350
no pains to detect and punish his deliverer.

04:16:04.350 --> 04:16:09.370
The plot of Felix was quickly discovered, and De Lacy and Agatha were thrown into prison.

04:16:10.070 --> 04:16:12.950
The news reached Felix and roused him from his dream of pleasure.

04:16:13.670 --> 04:16:18.670
His blind and aged father and his gentle sister lay in a noisome dungeon while he enjoyed

04:16:18.670 --> 04:16:21.710
the free air and the society of her whom he loved.

04:16:22.390 --> 04:16:23.870
This idea was torture to him.

04:16:24.210 --> 04:16:28.390
He quickly arranged with the Turk that if the latter should find a favorable opportunity

04:16:28.390 --> 04:16:33.710
for escape before Felix could return to Italy, Safi should remain as a border at a convent

04:16:33.710 --> 04:16:38.730
in Leghorn, and then, quitting the lovely Arabian, he hastened to Paris and delivered

04:16:38.730 --> 04:16:43.870
himself up to the vengeance of the law, hoping to free De Lacy and Agatha by this proceeding.

04:16:44.650 --> 04:16:45.990
He did not succeed.

04:16:46.650 --> 04:16:51.230
They remained confined for five months before the trial took place, the result of which

04:16:51.230 --> 04:16:55.370
deprived them of their fortune and condemned them to a perpetual exile from their native

04:16:55.370 --> 04:16:55.950
country.

04:16:56.870 --> 04:17:01.170
They found a miserable asylum in the cottage in Germany, where I discovered them.

04:17:01.730 --> 04:17:06.450
Felix soon learned that the treacherous Turk for whom he and his family endured such unheard

04:17:06.450 --> 04:17:11.630
of oppression on discovering that his deliverer was thus reduced to poverty and ruin, became

04:17:11.630 --> 04:17:16.130
a traitor to good feeling and honor, and had quitted Italy with his daughter, insultingly

04:17:16.130 --> 04:17:21.170
sending Felix a pittance of money to aid him, as he said, in some plan of future maintenance.

04:17:22.450 --> 04:17:26.370
Such were the events that preyed on the heart of Felix and rendered him, when I first saw

04:17:26.370 --> 04:17:28.570
him, the most miserable of his family.

04:17:29.150 --> 04:17:33.150
He could have endured poverty, and while this distress had been the mead of his virtue,

04:17:33.570 --> 04:17:34.470
he gloried in it.

04:17:34.810 --> 04:17:39.030
But the ingratitude of the Turk and the loss of his beloved safety were misfortunes more

04:17:39.030 --> 04:17:40.210
bitter and irreparable.

04:17:40.870 --> 04:17:44.590
The arrival of the Arabian now infused new life into his soul.

04:17:46.030 --> 04:17:50.290
When the news reached Leghorn that Felix was deprived of his wealth and rank, the merchant

04:17:50.290 --> 04:17:54.070
commanded his daughter to think no more of her lover but to prepare to return to her

04:17:54.070 --> 04:17:54.770
native country.

04:17:55.370 --> 04:18:00.030
The generous nature of safety was outraged by this command, she attempted to expostulate

04:18:00.030 --> 04:18:04.370
with her father, but he left her angrily, reiterating his tyrannical mandate.

04:18:05.370 --> 04:18:09.890
A few days after, the Turk entered his daughter's apartment and told her hastily that he had

04:18:09.890 --> 04:18:13.970
reason to believe that his residence at Leghorn had been divulged, and he should speedily

04:18:13.970 --> 04:18:15.490
be delivered up to the French government.

04:18:16.170 --> 04:18:20.850
He had consequently hired a vessel to convey him to Constantinople, for which city he should

04:18:20.850 --> 04:18:21.890
sail in a few hours.

04:18:21.890 --> 04:18:26.410
He intended to leave his daughter under the care of a confidential servant, to follow

04:18:26.410 --> 04:18:30.110
at her leisure with the greater part of his property, which had not yet arrived at Leghorn.

04:18:30.670 --> 04:18:35.490
When alone, safety resolved in her own mind, the plan of conduct that it would become her

04:18:35.490 --> 04:18:36.790
to pursue in this emergency.

04:18:37.470 --> 04:18:39.450
A residence in Turkey was abhorrent to her.

04:18:39.790 --> 04:18:42.730
Her religion and her feelings were alike averse to it.

04:18:43.370 --> 04:18:48.110
By some papers of her father which fell into her hands, she heard of the exile of her lover,

04:18:48.410 --> 04:18:50.630
and learnt the name of the spot where he then resided.

04:18:51.200 --> 04:18:54.890
She hesitated some time, but at length she formed her determination.

04:18:55.630 --> 04:18:59.790
Taking with her some jewels that belonged to her, and a sum of money, she quitted Italy

04:18:59.790 --> 04:19:04.310
with an attendant, a native of Leghorn, but who understood the common language of Turkey,

04:19:04.630 --> 04:19:05.830
and departed for Germany.

04:19:06.470 --> 04:19:11.190
She arrived in safety at a town about twenty leagues from the cottage of De Lacey, when

04:19:11.190 --> 04:19:13.190
her attendant felt dangerously ill.

04:19:14.110 --> 04:19:18.710
Safety nursed her with the most devoted affection, but the poor girl died, and the Arabian was

04:19:18.710 --> 04:19:22.930
left alone, unacquainted with the language of the country, and utterly ignorant of the

04:19:22.930 --> 04:19:23.710
customs of the world.

04:19:24.570 --> 04:19:26.410
She fell, however, into good hands.

04:19:26.990 --> 04:19:30.650
The Italian had mentioned the name of the spot for which they were bound, and after

04:19:30.650 --> 04:19:34.830
her death the woman of the house in which they lived took care that safety should arrive

04:19:34.830 --> 04:19:36.750
in safety at the cottage of her lover.

04:19:38.310 --> 04:19:42.270
Such was the history of my beloved cottagers.

04:19:42.930 --> 04:19:44.270
It impressed me deeply.

04:19:44.870 --> 04:19:50.050
I learned from the views of social life which it developed to admire their virtues and to

04:19:50.050 --> 04:19:51.630
deprecate the vices of mankind.

04:19:52.770 --> 04:19:57.870
As yet I looked upon crime as a distant evil, benevolence and generosity were ever present

04:19:57.870 --> 04:20:02.910
before me, inciting within me a desire to become an actor in the busy scene where so

04:20:02.910 --> 04:20:05.730
many admirable qualities were called forth and displayed.

04:20:06.730 --> 04:20:11.370
But in giving an account of the progress of my intellect I must not omit a circumstance

04:20:11.370 --> 04:20:14.530
which occurred in the beginning of the month of August of the same year.

04:20:15.310 --> 04:20:19.610
One night during my accustomed visit to the neighboring woods where I collected my own

04:20:19.610 --> 04:20:25.190
food and brought home firing for my protectors, I found on the ground a leathern portmanteau

04:20:25.190 --> 04:20:27.930
containing several articles of dress and some books.

04:20:29.330 --> 04:20:32.790
I eagerly seized the prize and returned with it to my hovel.

04:20:33.330 --> 04:20:37.090
Fortunately the books were written in the language, the elements of which I had acquired

04:20:37.090 --> 04:20:37.830
at the cottage.

04:20:38.310 --> 04:20:44.270
They consisted of Paradise Lost, a volume of Plutarch's Lives and the Sorrows of Werther.

04:20:45.130 --> 04:20:47.730
The possession of these treasures gave me extreme delight.

04:20:48.290 --> 04:20:52.830
I now continually studied and exercised my mind upon these histories whilst my friends

04:20:52.830 --> 04:20:55.110
were employed in their ordinary occupations.

04:20:55.850 --> 04:20:58.290
I can hardly describe to you the effect of these books.

04:20:58.850 --> 04:21:04.590
They produced in me an infinity of new images and feelings that sometimes raised me to ecstasy

04:21:04.590 --> 04:21:07.430
but more frequently sunk me into the lowest ejection.

04:21:08.230 --> 04:21:13.850
In the Sorrows of Werther, besides the interest of its simple and affecting story, so many

04:21:13.850 --> 04:21:18.450
opinions are canvassed and so many lights thrown upon what had hitherto been to me obscure

04:21:18.450 --> 04:21:23.430
subjects that I found in it a never-ending source of speculation and astonishment.

04:21:24.210 --> 04:21:29.170
The gentle and domestic manner as it described, combined with lofty sentiments and feelings

04:21:29.170 --> 04:21:34.330
which had for their object something out of self, accorded well with my experience among

04:21:34.330 --> 04:21:38.530
my protectors and with the wants which were forever alive in my own bosom.

04:21:39.290 --> 04:21:44.490
But I thought Werther himself was a more divine being than I had ever beheld or imagined.

04:21:44.930 --> 04:21:48.410
His character contained no pretension, but it sank deep.

04:21:49.110 --> 04:21:53.330
The disquisitions upon death and suicide were calculated to fill me with wonder.

04:21:53.950 --> 04:21:58.890
I did not pretend to enter into the merits of the case, yet I inclined towards the opinions

04:21:58.890 --> 04:22:03.630
of the hero whose extinction I wept without precisely understanding it.

04:22:04.530 --> 04:22:09.250
As I read, however, I applied much personally to my own feelings and condition.

04:22:09.870 --> 04:22:14.810
I found myself similar, yet at the same time strangely unlike to the beings concerning

04:22:14.810 --> 04:22:17.630
whom I read and to whose conversation I was a listener.

04:22:18.210 --> 04:22:23.030
I sympathized with and partly understood them, but I was unformed in mind.

04:22:23.350 --> 04:22:25.870
I was dependent on none and related to none.

04:22:26.470 --> 04:22:31.490
The path of my departure was free, and there was none to lament my annihilation.

04:22:32.230 --> 04:22:35.390
My person was hideous, and my stature gigantic.

04:22:36.090 --> 04:22:37.170
What did this mean?

04:22:37.690 --> 04:22:38.530
Who was I?

04:22:38.670 --> 04:22:39.470
What was I?

04:22:39.890 --> 04:22:40.970
Whence did I come?

04:22:41.550 --> 04:22:42.870
What was my destination?

04:22:43.770 --> 04:22:47.710
These questions continually recurred, but I was unable to solve them.

04:22:48.610 --> 04:22:53.050
The volume of Plutarch's Lives, which I possessed, contained the histories of the first founders

04:22:53.050 --> 04:22:54.570
of the ancient republics.

04:22:54.570 --> 04:22:57.870
This book had a far different effect on me from the sorrows of Werther.

04:22:58.310 --> 04:23:03.390
I learned from Werther's imaginations, despondency, and gloom, but Plutarch taught me high thoughts.

04:23:03.730 --> 04:23:08.470
He elevated me above the wretched sphere of my own reflections to admire and love the

04:23:08.470 --> 04:23:09.630
heroes of past ages.

04:23:10.390 --> 04:23:13.390
Many things I read surpassed my understanding and experience.

04:23:13.950 --> 04:23:18.490
I had a very confused knowledge of kingdoms, wide extensive country, mighty rivers and

04:23:18.490 --> 04:23:23.930
boundless seas, but I was perfectly unacquainted with towns and large assemblages of men.

04:23:23.930 --> 04:23:28.350
The cottage of my protectors had been the only school in which I had studied human nature,

04:23:28.750 --> 04:23:31.710
but this book developed new and mightier scenes of action.

04:23:32.670 --> 04:23:37.150
I read of men concerned in public affairs, governing or massacring their species.

04:23:37.670 --> 04:23:43.050
I felt the greatest ardor for virtue rise within me, and aberrance for vice, as far

04:23:43.050 --> 04:23:47.410
as I understood the signification of those terms, relative as they were, as I applied

04:23:47.410 --> 04:23:49.030
them, to pleasure and pain alone.

04:23:49.790 --> 04:23:55.790
Induced by these feelings, I was of course led to admire peaceable lawgivers, Numa, Salin,

04:23:55.910 --> 04:23:59.030
and Lycurgus, in preference to Romulus and Thesis.

04:23:59.590 --> 04:24:04.210
The patriarchal lives of my protectors caused these impressions to take a firm hold on my

04:24:04.210 --> 04:24:04.490
mind.

04:24:04.870 --> 04:24:09.690
Perhaps, if my first introduction to humanity had been made by a young soldier burning for

04:24:09.690 --> 04:24:13.110
glory and slaughter, I should have been imbued with different sensations.

04:24:13.670 --> 04:24:17.730
But Paradise Lost excited different and far deeper emotions.

04:24:18.130 --> 04:24:22.310
I read it, as I'd read the other volumes which had fallen into my hands, as a true

04:24:22.310 --> 04:24:22.810
history.

04:24:23.530 --> 04:24:27.970
It moved every feeling of wonder and awe that the picture of an omnipotent god warring with

04:24:27.970 --> 04:24:29.710
his creatures was capable of exciting.

04:24:30.450 --> 04:24:35.050
I often referred the several situations, as their similarities struck me, to my own.

04:24:35.690 --> 04:24:40.810
Like Adam, I was apparently united by no link to any other being in existence.

04:24:41.490 --> 04:24:44.590
But his state was far different from mine in every other respect.

04:24:44.590 --> 04:24:50.130
He had come forth from the hands of a god, a perfect creature, happy and prosperous,

04:24:50.550 --> 04:24:52.650
guarded by the especial care of his creator.

04:24:52.970 --> 04:24:56.770
He was allowed to converse with and acquire knowledge from beings of a superior nature,

04:24:56.790 --> 04:24:59.350
but I was wretched, helpless, and alone.

04:25:00.090 --> 04:25:05.430
Many times I considered Satan as the fitter emblem of my condition, for often, like him,

04:25:05.650 --> 04:25:10.290
when I viewed the bliss of my protectors, the bitter gall of envy rose within me.

04:25:11.590 --> 04:25:14.330
Another circumstance strengthened and confirmed these feelings.

04:25:14.730 --> 04:25:19.370
Soon after my arrival in the hovel, I discovered some papers in the pocket of the dress which

04:25:19.370 --> 04:25:20.710
I had taken from your laboratory.

04:25:21.310 --> 04:25:25.430
At first I had neglected them, but now that I was able to decipher the characters in

04:25:25.430 --> 04:25:28.330
which they were written, I began to study them with diligence.

04:25:29.250 --> 04:25:32.190
It was your journal of the four months that preceded my creation.

04:25:32.850 --> 04:25:37.390
You minutely described in these papers every step you took in the progress of your work.

04:25:37.730 --> 04:25:40.990
This history was mingled with accounts of domestic occurrences.

04:25:41.450 --> 04:25:43.050
You doubtless recollect these papers.

04:25:43.510 --> 04:25:44.210
Here they are.

04:25:44.670 --> 04:25:48.070
Everything is related in them which bears reference to my accursed origin.

04:25:48.550 --> 04:25:53.370
The whole detail of that series of disgusting circumstances which produced it is set in

04:25:53.370 --> 04:25:53.590
view.

04:25:54.090 --> 04:25:58.770
The minutest description of my odious and loathsome person is given, in language which

04:25:58.770 --> 04:26:01.530
painted your own horrors and rendered mine indelible.

04:26:02.210 --> 04:26:03.450
I sickened as I read.

04:26:03.450 --> 04:26:07.190
Hateful day when I received life, I exclaimed in agony.

04:26:08.010 --> 04:26:12.710
A cursed creator, why did you form a monster so hideous that even you turned from me in

04:26:12.710 --> 04:26:13.070
disgust?

04:26:13.770 --> 04:26:19.050
God, in pity, made man beautiful and alluring after his own image, but my form is a filthy

04:26:19.050 --> 04:26:22.030
type of yours, more horrid even from the very resemblance.

04:26:22.670 --> 04:26:27.170
Satan had his companions, fellow devils, to admire and encourage him, but I am solitary

04:26:27.170 --> 04:26:27.990
and abhorred.

04:26:28.630 --> 04:26:32.110
These were the reflections of my hours of despondency and solitude.

04:26:32.110 --> 04:26:37.810
But when I contemplated the virtues of the cottagers, their amiable and benevolent dispositions,

04:26:38.090 --> 04:26:42.830
I persuaded myself that when they should become acquainted with my admiration of their virtues,

04:26:43.210 --> 04:26:46.690
they would compassionate me and overlook my personal deformity.

04:26:47.290 --> 04:26:51.810
Could they turn from their door one, however monstrous, who solicited their compassion

04:26:51.810 --> 04:26:52.410
and friendship?

04:26:52.910 --> 04:26:58.090
I resolved at least not to despair, but in every way to fit myself for an interview with

04:26:58.090 --> 04:26:59.650
them which would decide my fate.

04:27:00.410 --> 04:27:05.110
I postponed this attempt for some months longer, for the importance attached to its success

04:27:05.110 --> 04:27:07.950
inspired me with a dread lest I should fail.

04:27:08.990 --> 04:27:13.810
Besides, I found that my understanding improved so much with every day's experience that I

04:27:13.810 --> 04:27:17.990
was unwilling to commence this undertaking until a few more months could have added to

04:27:17.990 --> 04:27:18.710
my sagacity.

04:27:19.630 --> 04:27:22.130
Several changes in the meantime took place in the cottage.

04:27:22.810 --> 04:27:27.990
The presence of Saffi diffused happiness among its inhabitants, and I also found that a greater

04:27:27.990 --> 04:27:29.570
degree of plenty reigned there.

04:27:30.090 --> 04:27:34.630
Felix and Agatha spent more time in amusement and conversation, and were assisted in their

04:27:34.630 --> 04:27:35.550
labors by servants.

04:27:36.170 --> 04:27:39.450
They did not appear rich, but they were contented and happy.

04:27:39.790 --> 04:27:44.770
Their feelings were serene and peaceful, while mine became every day more tumultuous.

04:27:45.990 --> 04:27:50.810
Increase of knowledge only discovered to me more clearly what a wretched outcast I was.

04:27:51.430 --> 04:27:56.890
A cherished hope, it's true, but it vanished when I beheld my person reflected in water

04:27:56.890 --> 04:28:02.490
or my shadow in the moonshine, even as that frail image and that inconstant shade.

04:28:03.470 --> 04:28:08.170
I endeavored to crush these fears and to fortify myself for the trial which in a few months

04:28:08.170 --> 04:28:13.910
I resolved to undergo, and sometimes I allowed my thoughts, unchecked by reason, to ramble

04:28:13.910 --> 04:28:19.210
in the fields of paradise, and dared to fancy amiable and lovely creatures sympathizing

04:28:19.210 --> 04:28:21.370
with my feelings and cheering my gloom.

04:28:21.670 --> 04:28:25.010
Their angelic countenances breathed smiles of consolation.

04:28:25.010 --> 04:28:27.070
But it was all a dream.

04:28:27.730 --> 04:28:30.370
No Eve soothed my sorrows nor shared my thoughts.

04:28:30.770 --> 04:28:31.530
I was alone.

04:28:32.590 --> 04:28:36.590
I remembered Adam's supplication to his Creator, but where was mine?

04:28:37.030 --> 04:28:41.250
He had abandoned me, and in the bitterness of my heart I cursed him.

04:28:42.130 --> 04:28:43.070
Autumn passed thus.

04:28:43.650 --> 04:28:48.970
I saw with surprise and grief the leaves decay and fall, and nature again assumed the barren

04:28:48.970 --> 04:28:52.670
and bleak appearance it had worn when I first beheld the woods and the lovely moon.

04:28:52.670 --> 04:28:55.250
Yet I did not heed the bleakness of the weather.

04:28:55.550 --> 04:28:59.390
I was better fitted by my confirmation for the endurance of cold than heat.

04:29:00.190 --> 04:29:03.770
But my chief delights were the sight of the flowers, the birds, and all the gay apparel

04:29:03.770 --> 04:29:04.230
of summer.

04:29:04.710 --> 04:29:08.510
When those deserted me, I turned with more attention towards the cottagers.

04:29:09.170 --> 04:29:11.870
Their happiness was not decreased by the absence of summer.

04:29:12.270 --> 04:29:16.690
They loved and sympathized with one another, and their joys, depending on each other, were

04:29:16.690 --> 04:29:19.390
not interrupted by the casualties that took place around them.

04:29:19.390 --> 04:29:23.970
The more I saw of them, the greater became my desire to claim their protection and kindness.

04:29:24.290 --> 04:29:28.690
My heart yearned to be known and loved by these amiable creatures, to see their sweet

04:29:28.690 --> 04:29:33.390
looks directed towards me with affection was the utmost limit of my ambition.

04:29:34.330 --> 04:29:37.650
I dared not think that they would turn them from me with disdain and horror.

04:29:38.190 --> 04:29:40.610
The poor that stopped at their door were never driven away.

04:29:41.150 --> 04:29:45.210
I asked, it is true, for greater treasures than a little food or rest.

04:29:45.210 --> 04:29:50.850
I required kindness and sympathy, but I did not believe myself utterly unworthy of it.

04:29:51.790 --> 04:29:56.150
The winter advanced, and an entire revolution of the seasons had taken place since I awoke

04:29:56.150 --> 04:29:56.790
into life.

04:29:57.250 --> 04:30:01.310
My attention at this time was solely directed towards my plan of introducing myself into

04:30:01.310 --> 04:30:02.690
the cottage of my protectors.

04:30:03.510 --> 04:30:07.830
I revolved many projects, but that on which I finally fixed was to enter the dwelling

04:30:07.830 --> 04:30:09.590
when the blind old man should be alone.

04:30:10.170 --> 04:30:14.670
I had sagacity enough to discover that the unnatural hideousness of my person was the

04:30:14.670 --> 04:30:17.690
object of horror with those who had formerly beheld me.

04:30:18.250 --> 04:30:21.570
My voice, although harsh, had nothing terrible in it.

04:30:22.030 --> 04:30:25.830
I thought, therefore, that if in the absence of his children I could gain the goodwill

04:30:25.830 --> 04:30:31.110
and mediation of the old De Lacy, I might by his means be tolerated by my younger protectors.

04:30:32.130 --> 04:30:36.770
One day, when the sun shone on the red leaves that strewed the ground in diffused cheerfulness,

04:30:37.310 --> 04:30:42.350
although it denied warmth, Safie, Agatha, and Felix departed on a long country walk,

04:30:42.350 --> 04:30:45.790
and the old man, at his own desire, was left alone in the cottage.

04:30:46.610 --> 04:30:50.970
When his children had departed, he took up his guitar and played several mournful but

04:30:50.970 --> 04:30:54.690
sweet airs, more sweet and mournful than I had ever heard him play before.

04:30:55.530 --> 04:31:00.270
At first his countenance was illuminated with pleasure, but as he continued, thoughtfulness

04:31:00.270 --> 04:31:01.350
and sadness succeeded.

04:31:01.850 --> 04:31:05.390
At length, laying aside the instrument, he sat absorbed in reflection.

04:31:06.490 --> 04:31:07.610
My heart beat quick.

04:31:07.990 --> 04:31:12.930
This was the hour and moment of trial which would decide my hopes and realize my fears.

04:31:13.490 --> 04:31:15.410
The servants were gone to a neighboring fair.

04:31:15.810 --> 04:31:17.730
All was silent in and around the cottage.

04:31:17.790 --> 04:31:23.010
It was an excellent opportunity, yet when I proceeded to execute my plan, my limbs failed

04:31:23.010 --> 04:31:24.250
me and I sank to the ground.

04:31:24.950 --> 04:31:29.410
Again I rose, and exerting all the firmness of which I was master, removed the planks

04:31:29.410 --> 04:31:31.870
which I had placed before my hovel to conceal my retreat.

04:31:32.670 --> 04:31:37.490
The fresh air revived me, and with renewed determination, I approached the door of their cottage.

04:31:38.450 --> 04:31:38.990
I knocked.

04:31:40.430 --> 04:31:41.590
Who is there?

04:31:42.070 --> 04:31:42.930
said the old man.

04:31:43.290 --> 04:31:44.070
Come in.

04:31:45.250 --> 04:31:45.770
I entered.

04:31:46.830 --> 04:31:48.310
Pardon this intrusion, I said.

04:31:48.810 --> 04:31:50.730
I am a traveler in want of a little rest.

04:31:51.410 --> 04:31:55.150
You would greatly oblige me if you would allow me to remain a few minutes before the fire.

04:31:56.570 --> 04:32:01.590
Enter, said Delacy, and I will try in what manner I can to relieve your wants, but unfortunately

04:32:01.590 --> 04:32:05.650
my children are from home, and as I am blind, I am afraid I should find it difficult to

04:32:05.650 --> 04:32:06.810
procure food for you.

04:32:07.490 --> 04:32:09.650
Oh, do not trouble yourself, my kind host.

04:32:09.770 --> 04:32:10.570
I have food.

04:32:10.930 --> 04:32:12.890
It is warmth and rest only that I need.

04:32:13.950 --> 04:32:16.750
I sat down, and a silence ensued.

04:32:17.530 --> 04:32:21.630
I knew that every minute was precious to me, yet I remained irresolute in what manner to

04:32:21.630 --> 04:32:22.550
commence the interview.

04:32:23.270 --> 04:32:27.910
When the old man addressed me, By your language, stranger, I suppose you are my countryman.

04:32:27.990 --> 04:32:28.630
You are French?

04:32:29.990 --> 04:32:34.190
No, but I was educated by a French family, and understand that language only.

04:32:34.830 --> 04:32:39.410
I am now going to claim the protection of some friends whom I sincerely love, and of

04:32:39.410 --> 04:32:40.730
whose favor I have some hopes.

04:32:41.490 --> 04:32:42.370
Are they Germans?

04:32:43.430 --> 04:32:46.430
No, they are French, but let us change the subject.

04:32:46.830 --> 04:32:48.810
I am an unfortunate and deserted creature.

04:32:49.270 --> 04:32:51.950
I look around, and I have no relation or friend upon earth.

04:32:52.330 --> 04:32:56.450
These amiable people to whom I go have never seen me, and know little of me.

04:32:56.450 --> 04:33:01.390
I am full of fears, for if I fail there, I am an outcast in the world forever.

04:33:02.930 --> 04:33:03.870
Oh, do not despair.

04:33:04.310 --> 04:33:08.530
To be friendless is indeed unfortunate, but the hearts of men, when unprejudiced by any

04:33:08.530 --> 04:33:11.730
obvious self-interest, are full of brotherly love and charity.

04:33:12.550 --> 04:33:17.450
Rely therefore on your hopes, and if these friends are good and amiable, do not despair.

04:33:19.150 --> 04:33:20.070
They are kind.

04:33:20.170 --> 04:33:23.750
They are the most excellent creatures in the world, but unfortunately they are prejudiced

04:33:23.750 --> 04:33:24.370
against me.

04:33:24.750 --> 04:33:26.090
I have good dispositions.

04:33:26.090 --> 04:33:30.850
My life has been hitherto harmless, and in some degree beneficial, but if fatal prejudice

04:33:30.850 --> 04:33:35.430
clouds their eyes, and when they ought to see a feeling and kind friend, they behold

04:33:35.430 --> 04:33:36.990
only a detestable monster.

04:33:38.490 --> 04:33:43.770
That is indeed unfortunate, but if you are really blameless, cannot you undeceive them?

04:33:44.890 --> 04:33:49.890
I am about to undertake that task, and it is on that account that I feel so many overwhelming

04:33:49.890 --> 04:33:50.610
terrors.

04:33:51.070 --> 04:33:52.670
I tenderly love these friends.

04:33:52.670 --> 04:33:57.130
I have, unknown to them, been for many months in the habits of daily kindness toward them,

04:33:57.490 --> 04:34:01.750
but they believe that I wish to injure them, and that is the prejudice which I wish to

04:34:01.750 --> 04:34:02.190
overcome.

04:34:03.870 --> 04:34:05.090
Where do these friends reside?

04:34:06.350 --> 04:34:07.310
Near this spot.

04:34:08.610 --> 04:34:10.390
The old man paused, and then continued,

04:34:11.410 --> 04:34:16.090
If you will unreservedly confide to me the particulars of your tale, I perhaps may be

04:34:16.090 --> 04:34:17.330
of use in undeceiving them.

04:34:17.610 --> 04:34:21.710
I am blind, and cannot judge of your countenance, but there is something in your words which

04:34:21.710 --> 04:34:23.310
persuades me that you are sincere.

04:34:23.990 --> 04:34:29.270
I am poor and in exile, but it will afford me true pleasure to be in any way serviceable

04:34:29.270 --> 04:34:30.270
to a human creature.

04:34:31.830 --> 04:34:35.110
Excellent man, I thank you and accept your generous offer.

04:34:35.630 --> 04:34:40.110
You raise me from the dust by this kindness, and I trust that by your aid I shall not be

04:34:40.110 --> 04:34:42.930
driven from the society and sympathy of your fellow creatures.

04:34:43.850 --> 04:34:48.910
Heaven forbid, even if you were really criminal, for that can only drive you to desperation

04:34:48.910 --> 04:34:50.470
and not instigate you to virtue.

04:34:51.030 --> 04:34:52.870
I also am unfortunate.

04:34:53.230 --> 04:34:56.110
I and my family have been condemned, although innocent.

04:34:56.770 --> 04:34:59.950
Judge therefore if I do not feel for your misfortunes.

04:35:01.010 --> 04:35:04.010
How can I thank you, my best and only benefactor?

04:35:04.630 --> 04:35:08.230
From your lips first have I heard the voice of kindness directed toward me.

04:35:08.450 --> 04:35:12.690
I shall be forever grateful, and your present humanity assures me of success with those

04:35:12.690 --> 04:35:14.330
friends whom I am on the point of meeting.

04:35:15.530 --> 04:35:18.050
May I know their names and residence of those friends?

04:35:19.050 --> 04:35:20.010
I paused.

04:35:20.950 --> 04:35:25.590
This, I thought, was the moment of decision, which was to rob me of or bestow happiness

04:35:25.590 --> 04:35:26.370
on me forever.

04:35:27.370 --> 04:35:32.350
I struggled vainly for firmness sufficient to answer him, but the effort destroyed all

04:35:32.350 --> 04:35:33.310
my remaining strength.

04:35:33.750 --> 04:35:35.710
I sank on the chair and sobbed aloud.

04:35:36.930 --> 04:35:39.490
At that moment I heard the steps of my younger protectors.

04:35:39.530 --> 04:35:45.050
I had not a moment to lose, but seizing the hand of the old man, I cried, Now is the time.

04:35:45.450 --> 04:35:46.670
Save and protect me.

04:35:46.830 --> 04:35:49.510
You and your family are the friends whom I seek.

04:35:50.370 --> 04:35:52.470
Do not you desert me in the hour of trial?

04:35:53.410 --> 04:35:54.430
Great, God!

04:35:54.870 --> 04:35:55.710
exclaimed the old man.

04:35:55.790 --> 04:35:56.830
Who are you?

04:35:57.690 --> 04:36:02.570
At that instant the cottage door was opened, and Felix, Safie, and Agatha entered.

04:36:03.550 --> 04:36:06.890
Who can describe their horror and consternation on beholding me?

04:36:07.850 --> 04:36:12.110
Agatha fainted, and Safie, unable to attend to her friend, rushed out of the cottage.

04:36:12.670 --> 04:36:17.870
Felix darted forward, and with supernatural force tore me from his father, to whose knees

04:36:17.870 --> 04:36:18.530
I clung.

04:36:18.990 --> 04:36:23.210
In a transport of fury he dashed me to the ground and struck me violently with a stick.

04:36:24.110 --> 04:36:28.810
I could have torn him limb from limb as the lion rinsed the antelope, but my heart sank

04:36:28.810 --> 04:36:31.650
within me as with bitter sickness, and I refrained.

04:36:32.790 --> 04:36:37.950
I saw him on the point of repeating his blow, when, overcome by pain and anguish, I quitted

04:36:37.950 --> 04:36:42.390
the cottage, and in the general tumult escaped unperceived to my hovel.

04:36:59.910 --> 04:37:12.370
XVI CURSED, CURSED CREATOR! Why did I live? Why in that instant did I not extinguish the

04:37:12.370 --> 04:37:20.190
spark of existence which you had so wantonly bestowed? I know not. Despair had not yet

04:37:20.190 --> 04:37:27.310
taken possession of me. My feelings were those of rage and revenge. I could with pleasure

04:37:27.310 --> 04:37:32.690
have destroyed the cottage and its inhabitants, and have glutted myself with their shrieks

04:37:32.690 --> 04:37:40.350
and misery. When night came I quitted my retreat and wandered in the wood, and now no longer

04:37:41.070 --> 04:37:49.070
of discovery. I gave vent to my anguish and fearful howlings. I was like a wild beast

04:37:49.070 --> 04:37:54.110
that had broken the toils, destroying the objects that obstructed me and ranging through

04:37:54.110 --> 04:38:03.130
the wood with a stag-like swiftness. Oh, what a miserable night I passed! The cold stars

04:38:03.130 --> 04:38:09.870
shone in mockery, and the bare trees waved their branches above me. Now and then the

04:38:09.870 --> 04:38:18.390
sweet voice of a bird burst forth amidst the universal stillness. All save I were at rest

04:38:18.390 --> 04:38:27.570
or in enjoyment. I, like the arch-fiend, bore a hell within me, and finding myself unsympathized

04:38:27.570 --> 04:38:34.090
with, wished to tear up the trees, spread havoc and destruction around me, and then

04:38:34.090 --> 04:38:41.410
to have sat down and enjoyed the ruin. But this was a luxury of sensation that could

04:38:41.410 --> 04:38:47.190
not endure. I became fatigued with excessive bodily exertion and sank on the damp grass

04:38:47.190 --> 04:38:54.350
in the sick impotence of despair. There was none among the myriads of men that existed

04:38:54.350 --> 04:39:01.830
who would pity or assist me. And should I feel kindness towards my enemies? No, from

04:39:01.830 --> 04:39:08.350
that moment I declared everlasting war against the species, and more than all against him

04:39:08.350 --> 04:39:18.170
who had formed me and sent me forth to this insupportable misery. The sun rose. I heard

04:39:18.170 --> 04:39:23.790
the voices of men and knew that it was impossible to return to my retreat during that day. Accordingly

04:39:23.790 --> 04:39:29.470
I hid myself in some thick underwood, determining to devote the ensuing hours to reflection

04:39:29.470 --> 04:39:37.250
on my situation. The pleasant sunshine and the pure air of day restored me to some degree

04:39:37.250 --> 04:39:42.630
of tranquility, and when I considered what had passed at the cottage, I could not help

04:39:42.630 --> 04:39:49.330
believing that I had been too hasty in my conclusions. I had certainly acted imprudently.

04:39:49.330 --> 04:39:54.730
It was apparent that my conversation had interested the father on my behalf, and I was a fool

04:39:54.730 --> 04:40:00.770
in having exposed my person to the horror of his children. I ought to have familiarized

04:40:00.770 --> 04:40:06.450
the old DeLacy to me, and by degrees to have discovered myself to the rest of his family,

04:40:07.010 --> 04:40:12.030
when they should have been prepared for my approach. But I did not believe my errors

04:40:12.030 --> 04:40:17.030
to be irretrievable, and after much consideration I resolved to return to the cottage, seek

04:40:17.030 --> 04:40:23.710
the old man, and by my representations win him to my party. These thoughts calmed me,

04:40:23.850 --> 04:40:29.950
and in the afternoon I sank into a profound sleep. But the fever of my blood did not allow

04:40:29.950 --> 04:40:37.390
me to be visited by peaceful dreams. The horrible scene of the preceding day was forever acting

04:40:37.390 --> 04:40:44.310
before my eyes. The females were flying and the enraged Felix tearing me from his father's

04:40:44.310 --> 04:40:51.990
feet. I awoke exhausted, and finding that it was already night, I crept forth from my

04:40:51.990 --> 04:40:58.450
hiding place and went in search of food. When my hunger was appeased, I directed my steps

04:40:58.450 --> 04:41:05.690
towards the well-known path that conducted to the cottage. All there was at peace. I

04:41:05.690 --> 04:41:10.550
crept into my hovel and remained in silent expectation of the accustomed hour when the

04:41:10.550 --> 04:41:19.070
family arose. That hour passed. The sun mounted high in the heavens, but the cottagers did

04:41:19.070 --> 04:41:27.230
not appear. I trembled violently, apprehending some dreadful misfortune. The inside of the

04:41:27.230 --> 04:41:33.270
cottage was dark, and I heard no motion. I cannot describe the agony of this suspense.

04:41:35.050 --> 04:41:40.530
Presently two countrymen passed by, but pausing near the cottage they entered into conversation

04:41:40.530 --> 04:41:46.110
using violent gesticulations. But I did not understand what they said as they spoke the

04:41:46.110 --> 04:41:52.490
language of the country, which differed from that of my protectors. Soon after, however,

04:41:53.270 --> 04:41:58.050
Felix approached with another man. I was surprised as I knew that he had not quitted the cottage

04:41:58.050 --> 04:42:03.330
that morning, and waited anxiously to discover from his discourse the meaning of these unusual

04:42:03.330 --> 04:42:03.790
appearances.

04:42:05.290 --> 04:42:10.110
"'Do you consider,' said his companion to him, "'that you will be obliged to pay three

04:42:10.110 --> 04:42:15.050
months' rent and to lose the produce of your garden? I do not wish to take any unfair advantage,

04:42:15.050 --> 04:42:18.630
and I beg, therefore, that you will take some days to consider of your determination.'

04:42:19.810 --> 04:42:25.810
"'It is utterly useless,' replied Felix. We can never again inhabit your cottage. The

04:42:25.810 --> 04:42:30.110
life of my father is in the greatest danger, going to the dreadful circumstances that I

04:42:30.110 --> 04:42:35.690
have related. My wife and my sister will never recover from their horror. I entreat

04:42:35.690 --> 04:42:41.850
you not to reason with me any more. Take possession of your tenement and let me fly from this

04:42:42.810 --> 04:42:47.950
place.' Felix trembled violently as he said this. He and his companion entered the cottage

04:42:47.950 --> 04:42:54.450
in which they remained for a few minutes, and then departed. I never saw any of the family

04:42:54.450 --> 04:42:55.570
of De Lacy more.

04:42:58.530 --> 04:43:04.290
I continued for the remainder of the day in my hovel in a state of utter and stupid despair.

04:43:05.650 --> 04:43:10.990
My protectors had departed and had broken the only link that held me to the world. For

04:43:10.990 --> 04:43:16.110
the first time the feelings of revenge and hatred filled my bosom, and I did not strive

04:43:16.110 --> 04:43:21.910
to control them. But allowing myself to be borne away by the stream, I bent my mind towards

04:43:21.910 --> 04:43:30.770
injury and death. When I thought of my friends, of the mild voice of De Lacy, the gentle eyes

04:43:30.770 --> 04:43:38.270
of Agatha, and the exquisite beauty of the Arabian, these thoughts vanished, and a gush

04:43:38.270 --> 04:43:47.050
of tears somewhat soothed me. But again, when I reflected that they had spurned and deserted

04:43:47.050 --> 04:43:56.190
me, anger returned, a rage of anger, and unable to injure anything human, I turned

04:43:56.190 --> 04:44:03.630
my fury towards inanimate objects. As night advanced I placed a variety of combustibles

04:44:03.630 --> 04:44:08.930
around the cottage, and after having destroyed every vestige of cultivation in the garden,

04:44:10.110 --> 04:44:14.950
I waited with forced impatience until the moon had sunk to commence my operations.

04:44:16.410 --> 04:44:22.070
As the night advanced a fierce wind arose from the woods and quickly dispersed the cloud

04:44:22.070 --> 04:44:28.610
that had loitered in the heavens. The blast tore along like a mighty avalanche and produced

04:44:28.610 --> 04:44:36.570
a kind of insanity in my spirits that burst all bounds of reason and reflection. I lighted

04:44:36.570 --> 04:44:43.230
the dry branch of a tree and danced with fury around the devoted cottage. My eyes still

04:44:43.230 --> 04:44:51.410
fixed on the western horizon, my brand. It sank, and with a loud scream I fired the straw

04:44:51.410 --> 04:44:58.550
and heath and bushes which I had collected. The wind fanned the fire, and the cottage

04:44:58.550 --> 04:45:05.330
was quickly enveloped by the flames, which clung to it and licked it with their forked

04:45:05.330 --> 04:45:12.250
and destroying tongues. As soon as I was convinced that no assistance could save any part of

04:45:12.250 --> 04:45:19.550
the habitation, I quitted the scene and sought for refuge in the woods. And now, with the

04:45:19.550 --> 04:45:26.830
world before me, whither should I bend my steps? I resolved to fly far from the scene

04:45:26.830 --> 04:45:40.110
of my misfortunes. But to me, hated and despised, every country must be equally horrible. At

04:45:40.110 --> 04:45:46.870
least my mind. I learned from your papers that you were my father, my creator, and to

04:45:46.870 --> 04:45:54.270
whom could I apply with more fitness than to him who had given me life. Among the lessons

04:45:54.270 --> 04:46:01.290
that Felix had bestowed upon Safi, geography had not been omitted. I had learned from these

04:46:01.290 --> 04:46:07.190
the relative situations of the different countries of the earth. You had mentioned Geneva as

04:46:07.190 --> 04:46:15.430
the name of your native town, and towards this place I resolved to proceed. But how

04:46:15.430 --> 04:46:20.290
was I to direct myself? I knew that I must travel in a southwesterly direction to reach

04:46:20.290 --> 04:46:25.650
my destination, but the sun was my only guide. I did not know the names of the towns that

04:46:25.650 --> 04:46:33.030
I was to pass through, nor could I ask information from a single human being. But I did not despair.

04:46:33.610 --> 04:46:40.150
From you only could I hope for Sukkur, although towards you I felt no sentiment, but that

04:46:40.150 --> 04:46:48.550
of hatred. Unfeeling, heartless creator! You had endowed me with perceptions and passions

04:46:48.550 --> 04:46:55.510
and then cast me abroad an object for the scorn and horror of mankind. But on you only

04:46:55.510 --> 04:47:02.450
had I any claim for pity and redress. And from you I determined to seek that justice

04:47:02.730 --> 04:47:10.250
which I vainly attempted to gain from any other being that wore the human form. My travels

04:47:10.250 --> 04:47:17.710
were long, and the sufferings I endured intense. It was late in autumn when I quitted the district

04:47:17.710 --> 04:47:24.190
where I had so long resided. I traveled only at night, fearful of encountering the visage

04:47:24.190 --> 04:47:32.430
of a human being. Nature decayed around me, and the sun became heatless. Rain and snow

04:47:32.430 --> 04:47:38.730
poured around me, mighty rivers were frozen, the surface of the earth was hard and chill

04:47:38.730 --> 04:47:48.810
and bare, and I found no shelter. Oh earth, how often did I implicate curses on the cause

04:47:48.810 --> 04:47:56.430
of my being! The mildness of my nature had fled, and all within me was turned to gall

04:47:56.430 --> 04:48:04.130
and bitterness. The nearer I approached your habitation, the more deeply did I feel the

04:48:04.130 --> 04:48:12.590
spirit of revenge enkindled in my heart. Snow fell, and the waters were hardened, but I

04:48:12.590 --> 04:48:18.430
rested not. A few incidents now and then directed me, and I possessed a map of the country.

04:48:19.270 --> 04:48:25.590
But I often wandered wide from my path. The agony of my feelings allowed me no respite,

04:48:25.590 --> 04:48:33.110
no incident occurred from which my rage and misery could not extract its food. But a circumstance

04:48:33.110 --> 04:48:37.990
that happened when I arrived on the confines of Switzerland, when the sun had recovered

04:48:37.990 --> 04:48:43.750
its warmth and the earth again began to look green, confirmed in a special manner the bitterness

04:48:44.290 --> 04:48:50.870
and horror of my feelings. I generally rested during the day and traveled only when I was

04:48:50.870 --> 04:48:56.650
secured by night from the view of man. One morning, however, finding that my path lay

04:48:56.650 --> 04:49:02.590
through a deep wood, I ventured to continue my journey after the sun had risen. The day,

04:49:02.590 --> 04:49:08.030
which was one of the first of spring, cheered even me by the loveliness of its sunshine

04:49:08.030 --> 04:49:14.990
and the bombiness of the air. I felt emotions of gentleness and pleasure that had long appeared

04:49:14.990 --> 04:49:22.890
dead revive within me. Half surprised by the novelty of these sensations, I allowed myself

04:49:22.890 --> 04:49:29.630
to be borne away by them, and forgetting my solitude and deformity, dared to be happy.

04:49:30.950 --> 04:49:38.680
Soft tears again bedewed my cheeks, and I even raised my humid eyes with thankfulness

04:49:39.440 --> 04:49:47.860
towards the blessed sun which bestowed such joy upon me. I continued to wind among the

04:49:47.860 --> 04:49:53.840
paths of the wood until I came to its boundary, which was skirted by a deep and rapid river

04:49:53.840 --> 04:50:00.480
into which many of the trees bent their branches, now budding with the fresh spring. Here I

04:50:00.480 --> 04:50:07.900
paused, not exactly knowing what path to pursue, when I heard the sound of voices that induced

04:50:07.900 --> 04:50:14.060
me to conceal myself under the shade of a cypress. I was scarcely hid when a young girl

04:50:14.060 --> 04:50:20.580
came running towards the spot where I was concealed laughing, as if she ran from someone

04:50:20.580 --> 04:50:26.000
in sport. She continued her course along the precipitous sides of the river when suddenly

04:50:26.000 --> 04:50:31.180
her foot slipped, and she fell into the rapid stream. I rushed from my hiding place and

04:50:31.180 --> 04:50:35.080
with extreme labor, from the force of the current, saved her and dragged her to shore.

04:50:35.880 --> 04:50:41.460
She was senseless, and I endeavored by every means in my power to restore animation the

04:50:41.460 --> 04:50:48.720
deeper parts of the woods. I followed speedily, I hardly knew why, but when the man saw me

04:50:48.720 --> 04:50:55.040
drew near, he aimed a gun, which he carried at my body and fired. I sank to the ground,

04:50:55.880 --> 04:51:05.060
and my injurer, with increased swiftness, escaped into the wood. This was then the reward

04:51:05.060 --> 04:51:12.020
of my benevolence. I had saved a human being from destruction, the feelings of kindness

04:51:12.020 --> 04:51:17.300
and gentleness which I had entertained, but a few moments before gave place to hellish

04:51:17.300 --> 04:51:26.360
rage and gnashing of teeth. Inflamed by pain, I vowed eternal hatred and vengeance to all

04:51:26.360 --> 04:51:35.040
mankind. But the agony of my wound overcame me. My pulses paused, and I fainted. I was

04:51:35.860 --> 04:51:41.340
for some weeks I led a miserable life in the woods, endeavoring to cure the wound which

04:51:41.340 --> 04:51:47.420
I had received. The ball had entered my shoulder, and I knew not whether it had remained there

04:51:47.420 --> 04:51:53.920
or passed through. At any rate, I had no means of extracting it. My sufferings were augmented

04:51:53.920 --> 04:52:04.500
also by the oppressive sense of the injustice and ingratitude of their infliction. My daily

04:52:04.500 --> 04:52:10.060
revenge, such as would alone compensate for the outrages and anguish I had endured.

04:52:11.680 --> 04:52:19.300
After some weeks my wound healed, and I continued my journey. The labors I endured were no longer

04:52:19.300 --> 04:52:25.640
to be alleviated by the bright sun or gentle breezes of spring. All joy was but a mockery

04:52:25.640 --> 04:52:31.300
which insulted my desolate state and made me feel more painfully that I was not made

04:52:31.300 --> 04:52:39.240
for the enjoyment of pleasure. But my toils now drew near a close, and in two months from

04:52:39.240 --> 04:52:46.240
this time I reached the environs of Geneva. It was evening when I arrived, and I retired

04:52:46.240 --> 04:52:51.380
to a hiding place among the fields that surround it to meditate in what manner I should apply

04:52:51.380 --> 04:52:57.840
to you. I was oppressed by fatigue and hunger and far too unhappy to enjoy the gentle breezes

04:52:57.840 --> 04:53:04.660
of evening or the prospect of the sun setting behind the stupendous mountains of Jura. At

04:53:04.660 --> 04:53:10.660
this time a slight sleep relieved me from the pain of reflection which was disturbed

04:53:10.660 --> 04:53:15.620
by the approach of a beautiful child, who came running into the recess I had chosen

04:53:15.620 --> 04:53:23.780
with all the sportiveness of infancy. Suddenly, as I gazed on him, an idea seized me that

04:53:23.780 --> 04:53:30.540
this little creature was unprejudiced and had lived too short a time to have imbibed

04:53:30.540 --> 04:53:38.080
a horror of deformity. If therefore I could seize him and educate him as my companion

04:53:38.080 --> 04:53:44.300
and friend, I should not be so desolate in this peopled earth. Urged by this impulse

04:53:44.300 --> 04:53:50.320
I seized on the boy as he passed and drew him towards me. As soon as he beheld my form

04:53:50.320 --> 04:53:54.680
he placed his hands before his eyes and uttered a shriek. I drew his hand forcibly from his

04:53:54.680 --> 04:53:58.920
face and said, Child, what is the meaning of this? I do not intend to hurt you. Listen

04:53:58.920 --> 04:54:06.740
to me. He struggled violently. Let me go, he cried. Monster! Ugly wretch! You wish to

04:54:06.740 --> 04:54:12.820
eat me and tear me to pieces. You are an ogre. Let me go or I will tell my papa. Boy, you

04:54:12.820 --> 04:54:18.280
will never see your father again. You must come with me. Hideous monster! Let me go.

04:54:18.630 --> 04:54:24.520
My papa is a syndic. He is Monsieur Frankenstein. He will punish you. You dare not keep me.

04:54:25.920 --> 04:54:33.200
Frankenstein! You belong then to my enemy. To him towards whom I have sworn eternal revenge

04:54:33.200 --> 04:54:39.380
you shall be my first victim. The child still struggled and loaded me with epithets which

04:54:39.380 --> 04:54:46.820
carried despair to my heart. I grasped his throat to silence him and in a moment he lay

04:54:46.820 --> 04:54:54.920
dead at my feet. I gazed on my victim and my heart swelled with exultation and hellish

04:54:54.920 --> 04:55:02.680
triumph. Clapping my hands, I exclaimed, I too can create desolation. My enemy is not

04:55:02.680 --> 04:55:09.220
invulnerable. This death will carry despair to him and a thousand other miseries shall

04:55:09.220 --> 04:55:11.040
torment and destroy him.

04:55:12.520 --> 04:55:20.740
As I fixed my eyes on the child, I saw something glittering on his breast. I took it. It was

04:55:20.740 --> 04:55:28.380
a portrait of a most lovely woman. In spite of my malignity, it softened and attracted

04:55:28.380 --> 04:55:35.360
me. For a few moments I gazed with delight on her dark eyes, fringed by dark lashes and

04:55:35.360 --> 04:55:42.960
her lovely lips. But presently my rage returned. I remembered that I was forever deprived of

04:55:42.960 --> 04:55:47.140
the delights that such beautiful creatures could bestow and that she whose resemblance

04:55:47.140 --> 04:55:54.080
I contemplated would, in regarding me, have changed that air of divine benignity to one

04:55:54.080 --> 04:55:56.200
expressive of disgust and of fright.

04:55:58.220 --> 04:56:04.480
Can you wonder that such thoughts transported me with rage? I only wonder that at that moment,

04:56:04.960 --> 04:56:10.040
instead of venting my sensations and exclamations and agony, I did not rush among mankind and

04:56:10.040 --> 04:56:15.500
perish in the attempt to destroy them. While I was overcome by these feelings, I left the

04:56:15.500 --> 04:56:20.600
spot where I had committed the murder, and seeking a more secluded hiding-place, I entered

04:56:20.600 --> 04:56:28.020
a barn which had appeared to me to be empty. A woman was sleeping on some straw. She was

04:56:28.020 --> 04:56:34.360
young, not indeed so beautiful as her whose portrait I held, but of an agreeable aspect

04:56:34.360 --> 04:56:40.520
and blooming in the loveliness of youth and health. Here, I thought, is one of those whose

04:56:40.520 --> 04:56:47.520
joy-emparting smiles are bestowed on all but me. And then I bent over her and whispered,

04:56:49.240 --> 04:56:57.700
Awake, fairest, thy lover is near. He would give his life but to obtain one look of affection

04:56:57.700 --> 04:57:02.040
from thine eyes. My beloved, awake!

04:57:03.360 --> 04:57:10.480
The sleeper stirred. A thrill of terror ran through me. Should she indeed awake and see

04:57:10.480 --> 04:57:16.920
me and curse me and denounce the murderer? Thus would she assuredly act if her darkened

04:57:16.920 --> 04:57:24.260
eyes opened and she beheld me. The thought was madness. It stirred from the fiend within

04:57:24.260 --> 04:57:32.020
me. Not I, but she shall suffer. The murder I have committed because I am forever robbed

04:57:32.020 --> 04:57:41.000
of all that she could give me, she shall atone. The crime had its source in her. Be hers

04:57:41.000 --> 04:57:41.880
the punishment.

04:57:43.930 --> 04:57:50.420
Thanks to the lessons of Felix and the sanguinary laws of man, I had learned now to work mischief.

04:57:51.240 --> 04:57:58.960
I bent over her and placed the portrait securely in one of the folds of her dress. She moved

04:57:58.960 --> 04:58:01.420
again and I fled.

04:58:04.020 --> 04:58:09.240
For some days I haunted the spot where these scenes had taken place, sometimes wishing

04:58:09.240 --> 04:58:15.680
to see you, sometimes resolved to quit the world and its miseries forever. At length

04:58:15.680 --> 04:58:22.380
I wandered towards these mountains and have ranged through their immense recesses consumed

04:58:22.380 --> 04:58:30.000
by a burning passion which you alone can gratify. We may not part until you have promised to

04:58:30.000 --> 04:58:38.680
comply with my requisition. I am alone and miserable. Man will not associate with me,

04:58:39.100 --> 04:58:47.340
but one as deformed and horrible as myself would not deny herself to me. My companion

04:58:47.340 --> 04:58:53.820
must be of the same species and have the same defects. This being you must create.

04:59:16.420 --> 04:59:20.600
The being finished speaking and fixed his looks upon me in the expectation of a reply.

04:59:21.420 --> 04:59:28.580
But I was bewildered, perplexed, and unable to arrange my ideas sufficiently to understand the full extent of his proposition.

04:59:31.180 --> 04:59:39.020
You must create a female for me, with whom I can live in the interchange of those sympathies necessary for my being.

04:59:40.020 --> 04:59:47.700
This you alone can do, and I demanded of you as a right which you must not refuse to concede.

04:59:48.420 --> 04:59:56.000
The latter part of his tale had kindled anew in me the anger that had died away while he narrated his peaceful life among the cottagers.

04:59:57.080 --> 05:00:01.900
And as he said this, I could no longer suppress the rage that burned within me.

05:00:02.360 --> 05:00:07.820
I do refuse it, I replied, and no torture shall ever extort a consent from me.

05:00:08.340 --> 05:00:14.380
You may render me the most miserable of men, but you shall never make me base in my own eyes.

05:00:14.380 --> 05:00:21.040
Shall I create another like yourself whose joint wickedness might desolate the world? Be gone.

05:00:21.760 --> 05:00:26.360
I have answered you. You may torture me, but I will never consent.

05:00:27.500 --> 05:00:30.160
You are in the wrong, replied the fiend.

05:00:31.260 --> 05:00:35.300
And instead of threatening, I am content to reason with you.

05:00:35.940 --> 05:00:43.440
I am malicious because I am miserable. Am I not shunned and hated by all mankind?

05:00:44.380 --> 05:00:47.820
You, my creator, would tear me to pieces and triumph.

05:00:49.020 --> 05:00:54.340
Remember that, and tell me why I should pity man more than he pities me.

05:00:55.260 --> 05:01:02.840
You would not call it murder if you could precipitate me into one of those ice rifts and destroy my frame, the work of your own hands.

05:01:03.720 --> 05:01:06.780
Shall I respect man when he condemns me?

05:01:06.780 --> 05:01:17.480
Let him live with me in the interchange of kindness, and instead of injury I would bestow every benefit upon him with tears of gratitude at his acceptance.

05:01:18.800 --> 05:01:25.620
But that cannot be. The human senses are insurmountable barriers to our union.

05:01:26.880 --> 05:01:30.600
Yet mine shall not be the submission of abject slavery.

05:01:30.600 --> 05:01:40.900
I will revenge my injuries. If I cannot inspire love, I will cause fear, and chiefly towards you, my archenemy.

05:01:41.400 --> 05:01:46.520
Because, my creator, do I swear inextinguishable hatred.

05:01:47.420 --> 05:01:57.860
Have a care. I will work at your destruction, nor finish until I desolate your heart, so that you shall curse the hour of your birth.

05:01:57.860 --> 05:02:05.940
A fiendish rage animated him as he said this. His face was wrinkled into contortions too horrible for human eyes to behold.

05:02:06.980 --> 05:02:08.980
Presently he calmed himself and proceeded.

05:02:10.280 --> 05:02:18.520
I intend to reason. This passion is detrimental to me, for you do not reflect that you are the cause of its success.

05:02:19.740 --> 05:02:26.360
If any being felt emotions of benevolence towards me, I should return them a hundred and a hundredfold.

05:02:27.220 --> 05:02:32.860
But for that one creature's sake, I would make peace with the whole kind.

05:02:34.140 --> 05:02:37.960
But I now indulge in dreams of bliss that cannot be realized.

05:02:38.920 --> 05:02:42.440
What I ask of you is reasonable and moderate.

05:02:43.180 --> 05:02:48.580
I demand a creature of another sex, but as hideous as myself.

05:02:48.580 --> 05:02:56.300
The gratification is small, but it is all that I can receive, and it shall content me.

05:02:56.900 --> 05:03:02.780
It is true. We shall be monsters, cut off from all the world.

05:03:03.480 --> 05:03:07.060
But on that account, we shall be more attached to one another.

05:03:07.840 --> 05:03:15.120
Our lives will not be happy, but they will be harmless, and free from the misery I now feel.

05:03:15.920 --> 05:03:24.320
Oh, my creator, make me happy. Let me feel gratitude towards you for one benefit.

05:03:25.120 --> 05:03:29.380
Let me see that I excite the sympathy of some existing thing.

05:03:30.580 --> 05:03:33.140
Do not deny me my requests.

05:03:34.360 --> 05:03:39.680
I was moved. I shuddered when I thought of the possible consequences of my consent.

05:03:40.900 --> 05:03:43.840
But I felt that there was some justice in his argument.

05:03:44.720 --> 05:03:49.960
His tale and the feelings he now expressed proved him to be a creature of fine sensations.

05:03:51.780 --> 05:03:57.580
And did I not, as his maker, owe him all the portion of happiness that it was in my power to bestow?

05:03:58.300 --> 05:04:01.620
He saw my change of feelings and continued.

05:04:02.900 --> 05:04:09.400
If you consent, neither you nor any other human being shall ever see us again.

05:04:09.940 --> 05:04:13.300
I will go to the vast wilds of South America.

05:04:13.840 --> 05:04:20.340
My food is not that of man. I do not destroy the lamb and the kid to glut my appetite.

05:04:21.180 --> 05:04:23.940
Acorns and berries afford me sufficient nourishment.

05:04:24.800 --> 05:04:29.180
My companion will be of the same nature as myself, and will be content with the same fare.

05:04:30.220 --> 05:04:32.660
We shall make a bed of dried leaves.

05:04:33.400 --> 05:04:38.120
The sun will shine on us as on man, and will ripen our food.

05:04:38.880 --> 05:04:43.300
The picture I present to you is peaceful and human,

05:04:44.280 --> 05:04:48.940
and you must feel that you could deny it only in the wantonness of power and cruelty.

05:04:50.000 --> 05:04:55.160
Pityless as you have been towards me, I now see compassion in your eyes.

05:04:55.800 --> 05:05:01.600
Let me seize the favorable moment and persuade you to promise what I so ardently desire.

05:05:02.680 --> 05:05:07.680
You propose, replied I, to fly from the habitations of man,

05:05:08.560 --> 05:05:12.420
to dwell in those wilds where the beasts of the field will be your only companions.

05:05:13.620 --> 05:05:20.000
How can you, who long for the love and sympathy of man, persevere in this exile?

05:05:20.600 --> 05:05:26.000
You will return and again seek their kindness, and you will meet with their detestation.

05:05:26.000 --> 05:05:32.140
Your evil passions will be renewed, and you will then have a companion to aid you in the task of destruction.

05:05:33.080 --> 05:05:36.820
This may not be. Cease to argue the point, for I cannot consent.

05:05:38.960 --> 05:05:41.380
How inconstant are your feelings!

05:05:42.540 --> 05:05:46.040
But a moment ago you were moved by my representations.

05:05:47.920 --> 05:05:50.840
And why do you again harden yourself to my complaints?

05:05:50.840 --> 05:05:56.260
I swear to you, by the earth which I inhabit and by you that made me,

05:05:56.660 --> 05:06:01.500
that with the companion you bestow I will quit the neighborhood of man and dwell,

05:06:01.740 --> 05:06:05.180
as it may chance, in the most savage of places.

05:06:06.160 --> 05:06:10.360
My evil passions will have fled, for I shall meet with sympathy.

05:06:11.380 --> 05:06:17.860
My life will flow quietly away, and in my dying moments I shall not curse my Maker.

05:06:18.860 --> 05:06:21.180
His words had a strange effect upon me.

05:06:22.380 --> 05:06:26.520
I compassionated him, and sometimes felt a wish to console him.

05:06:27.700 --> 05:06:33.820
But when I looked upon him, when I saw the filthy mass that moved and talked,

05:06:35.040 --> 05:06:40.560
my heart sickened, and my feelings were altered to those of horror and hatred,

05:06:41.780 --> 05:06:43.940
I tried to stifle these sensations.

05:06:43.940 --> 05:06:47.320
I thought that as I could not sympathize with him,

05:06:47.600 --> 05:06:51.340
I had no right to withhold from him the small portion of happiness

05:06:51.340 --> 05:06:53.860
which was yet in my power to bestow.

05:06:55.060 --> 05:06:59.060
You swear, I said, to be harmless,

05:06:59.980 --> 05:07:06.100
but have you not already shown a degree of malice that should reasonably make me distrust you?

05:07:06.100 --> 05:07:11.340
May not even this be a feint that will increase your triumph

05:07:11.340 --> 05:07:13.760
by affording a wider scope for your revenge?

05:07:15.720 --> 05:07:21.880
How is this I must not be trifled with, and I demand an answer.

05:07:22.960 --> 05:07:27.020
If I have no ties and no affections, hatred and vice must be my portion.

05:07:27.820 --> 05:07:31.680
The love of another will destroy the cause of my crimes,

05:07:31.680 --> 05:07:36.760
and I shall become a thing of whose existence everyone will be ignorant.

05:07:38.080 --> 05:07:42.420
My vices are the children of a forced solitude that I abhor,

05:07:43.240 --> 05:07:49.640
and my virtues will necessarily arise when I live in communion with an equal.

05:07:50.560 --> 05:07:54.200
I shall feel the affections of a sensitive being

05:07:54.200 --> 05:07:58.680
and become linked to the chain of existence and events from which I am now excluded.

05:07:59.240 --> 05:08:02.500
I paused some time to reflect on all he had related

05:08:02.500 --> 05:08:05.180
and the various arguments which he had employed.

05:08:06.380 --> 05:08:10.740
I thought of the promise of virtues which he had displayed on the opening of his existence

05:08:10.740 --> 05:08:15.060
and the subsequent blight of all kindly feeling by the loathing and scorn

05:08:15.060 --> 05:08:17.540
which his protectors had manifested towards him.

05:08:18.780 --> 05:08:22.820
His power and threats were not omitted in my calculations.

05:08:23.440 --> 05:08:26.280
A creature who could exist in the ice caves of the glaciers

05:08:26.280 --> 05:08:30.660
and hide himself from pursuit among the ridges of inaccessible precipices

05:08:30.660 --> 05:08:34.680
was a being possessing faculties it would be vain to cope with.

05:08:35.560 --> 05:08:37.300
After a long pause of reflection,

05:08:38.080 --> 05:08:41.720
I concluded that the justice due both to him and my fellow creatures

05:08:41.720 --> 05:08:45.020
demanded of me that I should comply with his request.

05:08:46.100 --> 05:08:48.160
Turning to him, therefore, I said,

05:08:49.380 --> 05:08:53.540
I consent to your demand, on your solemn oath to quit Europe forever,

05:08:53.540 --> 05:08:56.240
and every other place in the neighborhood of man,

05:08:56.760 --> 05:09:01.060
as soon as I shall deliver into your hands a female who will accompany you in your exile.

05:09:01.960 --> 05:09:07.800
I swear, he cried, by the sun and by the blue sky of heaven

05:09:07.800 --> 05:09:10.860
and by the fire of love that burns my heart,

05:09:11.640 --> 05:09:18.020
that if you grant my prayer, while they exist, you shall never behold me again.

05:09:19.280 --> 05:09:21.720
Depart to your home and commence your labors.

05:09:21.720 --> 05:09:26.120
I shall watch their progress with unutterable anxiety,

05:09:27.320 --> 05:09:31.880
and fear not, but that when you are ready, I shall appear.

05:09:33.040 --> 05:09:34.720
Seeing this, he suddenly quitted me,

05:09:35.580 --> 05:09:37.560
fearful perhaps of any change in my sentiments.

05:09:38.460 --> 05:09:41.780
I saw him descend the mountain with greater speed than the flight of an eagle,

05:09:42.740 --> 05:09:46.460
and quickly lost among the undulations of the sea of ice.

05:09:47.980 --> 05:09:49.820
His tail had occupied the whole day,

05:09:49.820 --> 05:09:53.000
and the sun was on the verge of the horizon when he departed.

05:09:54.040 --> 05:09:57.100
I knew that I ought to hasten my descent towards the valley,

05:09:57.800 --> 05:09:59.920
as I should soon be encompassed in darkness.

05:10:01.000 --> 05:10:03.220
But my heart was heavy and my steps slow.

05:10:03.960 --> 05:10:06.580
The labor of winding among the little paths of the mountain,

05:10:07.260 --> 05:10:10.040
and fixing my feet firmly as I advanced, perplexed me,

05:10:10.960 --> 05:10:15.740
occupied as I was by the emotions which the occurrences of the day had produced.

05:10:16.680 --> 05:10:20.420
Night was far advanced when I came to the halfway resting place,

05:10:20.680 --> 05:10:22.480
and seated myself beside the fountain.

05:10:23.620 --> 05:10:27.540
The stars shone at intervals as the clouds passed from over them.

05:10:28.380 --> 05:10:30.920
The dark pines rose before me,

05:10:32.020 --> 05:10:34.900
and every here and there a broken tree lay on the ground.

05:10:35.820 --> 05:10:37.660
It was a scene of wonderful solemnity,

05:10:38.560 --> 05:10:40.800
and stirred strange thoughts within me.

05:10:41.700 --> 05:10:43.100
I wept bitterly,

05:10:44.020 --> 05:10:46.420
and clasping my hands in agony I exclaimed,

05:10:47.280 --> 05:10:49.800
Oh, stars and clouds and winds,

05:10:50.880 --> 05:10:53.220
you're all about to mock me.

05:10:53.460 --> 05:10:55.040
If you really pity me,

05:10:55.420 --> 05:10:59.380
crush sensation and memory that may become as nought.

05:10:59.900 --> 05:11:05.300
But if nought, depart, depart, and leave me in darkness.

05:11:06.580 --> 05:11:08.520
These were wild and miserable thoughts,

05:11:08.520 --> 05:11:13.060
but I cannot describe to you how the eternal twinkling of the stars weighed upon me,

05:11:13.120 --> 05:11:20.000
and how I listened to every blast of wind as if it were a dull, ugly siroc on its way to consume me.

05:11:20.720 --> 05:11:24.060
Morning dawned before I arrived at the village of Chamouni.

05:11:24.620 --> 05:11:27.160
I took no rest, but returned immediately to Geneva.

05:11:28.260 --> 05:11:31.620
Even in my own heart I could give no expression to my sensations.

05:11:32.620 --> 05:11:34.580
They weighed on me with a mountain's weight,

05:11:35.020 --> 05:11:37.920
and their excess destroyed my agony beneath them.

05:11:38.880 --> 05:11:43.260
Thus I returned home, and entering the house presented myself to the family.

05:11:44.540 --> 05:11:47.100
My haggard and wild appearance awoke intense alarm,

05:11:47.960 --> 05:11:49.320
but I answered no question.

05:11:49.760 --> 05:11:50.840
Scarcely did I speak.

05:11:51.560 --> 05:11:53.900
I felt as if I were placed under a ban,

05:11:54.440 --> 05:11:56.760
as if I had no right to claim their sympathies,

05:11:57.400 --> 05:12:01.660
as if never more might I enjoy companionship with them.

05:12:02.580 --> 05:12:05.600
Yet even thus I loved them to adoration,

05:12:05.600 --> 05:12:13.220
and, to save them, I resolved to dedicate myself to my most abhorred task.

05:12:14.260 --> 05:12:19.900
The prospect of such an occupation made every other circumstance of existence pass before me like a dream,

05:12:20.520 --> 05:12:24.740
and that thought only had to be the reality of life.

05:12:53.480 --> 05:12:57.780
Day after day, week after week, passed away on my return to Geneva,

05:12:59.040 --> 05:13:01.860
and I could not collect the courage to recommence my work.

05:13:03.020 --> 05:13:05.940
I feared the vengeance of the disappointed fiend,

05:13:06.400 --> 05:13:11.120
yet I was unable to overcome my repugnance to the task which was enjoined me.

05:13:11.1000 --> 05:13:14.480
I found that I could not compose a female,

05:13:15.240 --> 05:13:19.840
without again devoting several months to profound study and laborious disquisition.

05:13:20.440 --> 05:13:24.640
I had heard of some discoveries having been made by an English philosopher,

05:13:25.540 --> 05:13:27.980
the knowledge of which was material to my success,

05:13:28.840 --> 05:13:33.260
and I sometimes thought of obtaining my father's consent to visit England for this purpose,

05:13:34.100 --> 05:13:39.420
but I clung to every pretense of delay and shrank from taking the first step in an undertaking

05:13:39.420 --> 05:13:42.1000
whose immediate necessity began to appear less absolute to me.

05:13:43.1000 --> 05:13:46.160
A change indeed had taken place in me.

05:13:46.160 --> 05:13:50.720
My health, which had hitherto declined, was now much restored,

05:13:51.360 --> 05:13:58.160
and my spirits, when unchecked by the memory of my unhappy promise, rose proportionably.

05:13:59.460 --> 05:14:01.300
My father saw this change with pleasure,

05:14:01.660 --> 05:14:06.060
and he turned his thoughts towards the best method of eradicating the remains of my melancholy,

05:14:06.980 --> 05:14:09.540
which every now and then would return by fits,

05:14:10.400 --> 05:14:14.880
and with a devouring blackness overcast the approaching sunshine.

05:14:15.700 --> 05:14:20.100
At these moments I took refuge in the most perfect solitude.

05:14:21.680 --> 05:14:24.720
I passed whole days on the lake alone in a little boat,

05:14:25.480 --> 05:14:31.820
watching the clouds and listening to the rippling of the waves, silent and listless.

05:14:33.720 --> 05:14:37.840
But the fresh air and bright sun seldom failed to restore me to some degree of composure,

05:14:38.040 --> 05:14:44.240
and on my return I met the salutations of my friends with a readier smile and a more cheerful heart.

05:14:44.240 --> 05:14:50.300
It was after my return from one of these rambles that my father, calling me aside, thus addressed me.

05:14:50.680 --> 05:14:57.020
I am happy to remark, my dear son, that you have resumed your former pleasures and seem to be returning to yourself.

05:14:57.900 --> 05:15:01.840
And yet you are still unhappy and still avoid our society.

05:15:02.760 --> 05:15:06.040
For some time I was lost in conjecture as to the cause of this,

05:15:06.540 --> 05:15:12.600
but yesterday an idea struck me, and if it is well founded I conjure you to avow it.

05:15:12.600 --> 05:15:19.720
Reserve on such a point would be not only useless, but draw down treble misery on us all.

05:15:20.800 --> 05:15:25.460
I trembled violently at his exhortium, and my father continued,

05:15:26.500 --> 05:15:31.380
I confess, my son, that I have always looked forward to your marriage with our dear Elizabeth

05:15:31.380 --> 05:15:36.580
as the tie of our domestic comfort and the stay of my declining years.

05:15:37.080 --> 05:15:41.800
You were attached to each other from your earliest infancy, you studied together,

05:15:41.800 --> 05:15:46.360
and appeared in dispositions and tastes entirely suited to one another.

05:15:47.180 --> 05:15:56.340
But so blind is the experience of man that what I conceive to be the best assistance to my plan may have entirely destroyed it.

05:15:56.600 --> 05:16:02.620
You, perhaps, regarded her as your sister, without any wish that she might become your wife.

05:16:03.260 --> 05:16:09.180
Nay, you may have met with another whom you may love, and considering yourself as bound in honor to Elizabeth,

05:16:09.180 --> 05:16:14.040
this struggle may occasion the poignant misery which you appear to feel.

05:16:15.040 --> 05:16:20.280
My dear father, reassure yourself, I love my cousin tenderly and sincerely.

05:16:20.860 --> 05:16:27.180
I never saw any woman who excited, as Elizabeth does, my warmest admiration and affection.

05:16:27.860 --> 05:16:32.280
My future hopes and prospects are entirely bound up in the expectation of our union.

05:16:33.400 --> 05:16:40.840
The expression of your sentiments on this subject, my dear Victor, gives me more pleasure than I have for some time experienced.

05:16:41.220 --> 05:16:44.460
If you feel thus, we shall assuredly be happy.

05:16:44.920 --> 05:16:47.840
However, present events may cast a gloom over us.

05:16:48.580 --> 05:16:54.620
But it is this gloom which appears to have taken so strong a hold of your mind that I wish to dissipate.

05:16:55.260 --> 05:17:00.080
Tell me, therefore, whether you object to an immediate solemnization of the marriage.

05:17:00.080 --> 05:17:09.340
We have been unfortunate, and recent events have drawn us from that everyday tranquility befitting my years and infirmities.

05:17:09.1000 --> 05:17:15.180
You are younger, yet I do not suppose, possessed as you are of a competent fortune,

05:17:15.540 --> 05:17:22.340
that an early marriage would at all interfere with any future plans of honor and utility that you may have formed.

05:17:23.050 --> 05:17:27.340
Do not suppose, however, that I wish to dictate happiness to you,

05:17:27.340 --> 05:17:31.380
or that a delay on your part would cause me any serious uneasiness.

05:17:32.300 --> 05:17:38.360
Interpret my words with candor, and answer me, I conjure you, with confidence and sincerity.

05:17:39.460 --> 05:17:45.500
I listen to my father in silence, and remain for some time incapable of offering any reply.

05:17:46.200 --> 05:17:52.180
I revolved rapidly in my mind a multitude of thoughts, and endeavored to arrive at some conclusion.

05:17:53.040 --> 05:17:59.700
Alas, to me the idea of an immediate union with my Elizabeth was one of horror and dismay.

05:18:00.400 --> 05:18:07.040
I was bound by a solemn promise which I had not yet fulfilled, and dared not break.

05:18:07.520 --> 05:18:13.540
Or if I did, what manifold miseries might not impend over me and my devoted family?

05:18:14.320 --> 05:18:22.500
Could I enter into a festival with this deadly weight yet hanging round my neck and bowing me to the ground?

05:18:23.240 --> 05:18:28.120
I must perform my engagement, and let the monster depart with his mate,

05:18:28.880 --> 05:18:33.600
before I allowed myself to enjoy the delight of a union from which I expected peace.

05:18:34.260 --> 05:18:38.580
I remembered also the necessity imposed upon me of either journeying to England,

05:18:38.580 --> 05:18:42.600
or entering into a long correspondence with those philosophers of that country

05:18:42.600 --> 05:18:47.020
whose knowledge and discoveries were of indispensable use to me in my present undertaking.

05:18:48.620 --> 05:18:53.460
The latter method of obtaining the desired intelligence was dilatory and unsatisfactory.

05:18:54.620 --> 05:19:01.640
Besides, I had an insurmountable aversion to the idea of engaging myself in my loathsome task in my father's house,

05:19:02.520 --> 05:19:05.400
while in habits of familiar intercourse with those I loved.

05:19:06.360 --> 05:19:10.200
I knew that a thousand fearful accidents might occur,

05:19:10.820 --> 05:19:16.880
the slightest of which would disclose a tale to thrill all connected with me with horror.

05:19:18.020 --> 05:19:22.220
I was aware also that I should often lose all self-command,

05:19:22.920 --> 05:19:28.980
all capacity of hiding the harrowing sensations that would possess me during the progress of my unearthly occupation.

05:19:29.380 --> 05:19:34.160
I must absent myself from all I loved while thus employed.

05:19:35.400 --> 05:19:41.800
Once commenced, it would quickly be achieved, and I might be restored to my family in peace and happiness.

05:19:43.100 --> 05:19:47.360
My promise fulfilled, the monster would depart forever.

05:19:48.640 --> 05:19:55.020
Or, so my fond fancy imaged, some accident might meanwhile occur to destroy him,

05:19:55.740 --> 05:19:58.040
and put an end to my slavery forever.

05:19:59.320 --> 05:20:01.760
These feelings dictated my answer to my father.

05:20:01.760 --> 05:20:07.480
I expressed a wish to visit England, but concealing the true reasons of this request,

05:20:07.820 --> 05:20:11.920
I clothed my desires under a guise which excited no suspicion,

05:20:12.620 --> 05:20:17.720
while I urged my desire with an earnestness that easily induced my father to comply.

05:20:19.780 --> 05:20:25.500
After so long a period of an absorbing melancholy that resembled madness in its intensity and effects,

05:20:26.120 --> 05:20:30.020
he was glad to find that I was capable of taking pleasure in the idea of such a journey,

05:20:30.020 --> 05:20:38.420
and he hoped that change of scene and varied amusement would, before my return, have restored me entirely to myself.

05:20:39.700 --> 05:20:42.280
The duration of my absence was left to my own choice.

05:20:42.620 --> 05:20:46.540
A few months, or at most a year, was the period contemplated.

05:20:47.260 --> 05:20:51.780
One paternal kind precaution he had taken to ensure my having a companion.

05:20:52.920 --> 05:20:58.240
Without previously communicating with me, he had, in concert with Elizabeth,

05:20:58.240 --> 05:21:02.380
arranged that Clare Valle should join me at Strasbourg.

05:21:03.380 --> 05:21:07.360
This interfered with the solitude I coveted for the prosecution of my task.

05:21:08.460 --> 05:21:13.080
Yet at the commencement of my journey the presence of my friend could in no way be an impediment,

05:21:13.620 --> 05:21:19.200
and truly I rejoiced that thus I should be saved many hours of lonely, maddening reflection.

05:21:19.980 --> 05:21:24.240
Nay, Henry might stand between me and the intrusion of my foe.

05:21:24.240 --> 05:21:32.100
If I were alone, would he not at times force his abhorred presence on me to remind me of my task,

05:21:32.620 --> 05:21:34.300
or to contemplate its progress?

05:21:35.320 --> 05:21:37.220
To England, therefore, I was bound,

05:21:37.620 --> 05:21:42.080
and it was understood that my union with Elizabeth should take place immediately on my return.

05:21:42.920 --> 05:21:45.740
My father's age rendered him extremely averse to delay.

05:21:47.040 --> 05:21:51.740
For myself there was one reward I promised myself from my detested toils,

05:21:51.740 --> 05:21:56.280
one consolation for my unparalleled sufferings.

05:21:57.260 --> 05:22:03.360
It was the prospect of that day when, enfranchised from my miserable slavery,

05:22:04.100 --> 05:22:09.220
I might claim Elizabeth and forget the past in my union with her.

05:22:10.440 --> 05:22:12.300
I now made arrangements for my journey,

05:22:12.520 --> 05:22:17.340
but one feeling haunted me which filled me with fear and agitation.

05:22:18.320 --> 05:22:23.100
During my absence I should leave my friends unconscious of the existence of their enemy

05:22:23.100 --> 05:22:29.400
and unprotected from his attacks, exacerbated as he might be by my departure.

05:22:30.880 --> 05:22:35.680
But he had promised to follow me wherever I might go, and would he not accompany me to England?

05:22:36.840 --> 05:22:43.200
This imagination was dreadful in itself, but soothing inasmuch as it supposed the safety of my friends.

05:22:44.280 --> 05:22:49.760
I was agonized with the idea of the possibility that the reverse of this might happen.

05:22:50.900 --> 05:22:54.640
But through the whole period during which I was the slave of my creature,

05:22:55.200 --> 05:22:58.280
I allowed myself to be governed by the impulses of the moment,

05:22:59.160 --> 05:23:03.900
and my present sensation strongly intimated that the fiend would follow me

05:23:03.900 --> 05:23:07.200
and exempt my family from the danger of his machinations.

05:23:08.380 --> 05:23:12.960
It was in the latter end of September that I again quitted my native country.

05:23:13.760 --> 05:23:17.880
My journey had been my own suggestion, and Elizabeth therefore acquiesced.

05:23:18.320 --> 05:23:22.320
But she was filled with disquiet at the idea of my suffering away from her,

05:23:22.580 --> 05:23:24.560
the inroads of misery and grief.

05:23:25.300 --> 05:23:28.720
It had been her care which provided me a companion in Clareval,

05:23:29.600 --> 05:23:32.500
and yet a man is blind to a thousand minute circumstances

05:23:32.500 --> 05:23:35.480
which call forth a woman's sedulous attention.

05:23:36.140 --> 05:23:38.780
She longed to bid me haste in my return.

05:23:39.620 --> 05:23:45.180
A thousand conflicting emotions rendered her mute as she bade me a tearful, silent farewell.

05:23:46.220 --> 05:23:49.560
I threw myself into the carriage that was to convey me away,

05:23:50.460 --> 05:23:54.820
hardly knowing whither I was going, and careless of what was passing around.

05:23:55.560 --> 05:23:59.580
I remembered only, and it was with a bitter anguish that I reflected on it,

05:23:59.940 --> 05:24:03.570
to order that my chemical instruments should be packed to go with me.

05:24:04.530 --> 05:24:09.870
Filled with dreary imaginations, I passed through many beautiful and majestic scenes,

05:24:10.610 --> 05:24:12.750
but my eyes were fixed and unobserving.

05:24:13.690 --> 05:24:15.830
I could only think of the bourne of my travels,

05:24:16.290 --> 05:24:19.190
and the work which was to occupy me whilst they endured.

05:24:20.550 --> 05:24:25.390
After some days spent in listless indolence, during which I traversed many leagues,

05:24:25.950 --> 05:24:29.710
I arrived at Strasbourg, where I waited two days for Clareval.

05:24:30.310 --> 05:24:31.210
He came.

05:24:32.270 --> 05:24:35.030
Lass, how great was the contrast between us!

05:24:35.470 --> 05:24:40.770
He was alive to every new scene, joyful when he saw the beauties of the setting sun,

05:24:41.410 --> 05:24:44.750
and more happy when he beheld it rise and recommence a new day.

05:24:45.530 --> 05:24:49.830
He pointed out to me the shifting colours of the landscape and the appearances of the sky.

05:24:50.730 --> 05:24:55.910
This is what it is to live, he cried. How I enjoy existence!

05:24:55.910 --> 05:25:01.350
But you, my dear Frankenstein, wherefore are you desponding and sorrowful?

05:25:02.690 --> 05:25:05.450
In truth, I was occupied by gloomy thoughts,

05:25:05.830 --> 05:25:10.910
and neither saw the descent of the evening star nor the golden sunrise reflected in the Rhine.

05:25:11.950 --> 05:25:16.510
And you, my friend, would be far more amused with the journal of Clareval,

05:25:17.030 --> 05:25:19.990
who observed the scenery with an eye of feeling and delight,

05:25:20.670 --> 05:25:22.290
than in listening to my reflections.

05:25:23.070 --> 05:25:29.510
Ay, a miserable wretch, haunted by a curse that shut up every avenue to enjoyment.

05:25:31.290 --> 05:25:35.430
We had agreed to descend the Rhine in a boat from Strasbourg to Rotterdam,

05:25:36.750 --> 05:25:38.630
whence we might take shipping for London.

05:25:39.790 --> 05:25:44.870
During this voyage we passed many willowy islands and saw several beautiful towns.

05:25:45.510 --> 05:25:50.050
We stayed a day at Mannheim, and on the fifth from our departure from Strasbourg,

05:25:50.050 --> 05:25:51.590
arrived at Mains.

05:25:52.810 --> 05:25:57.070
The course of the Rhine below Mains becomes much more picturesque.

05:25:57.530 --> 05:26:04.050
The river descends rapidly and winds between hills, not high but steep, and of beautiful forms.

05:26:05.010 --> 05:26:08.850
We saw many ruined castles standing on the edges of precipices,

05:26:09.450 --> 05:26:12.910
surrounded by black woods, high and inaccessible.

05:26:14.010 --> 05:26:18.810
This part of the Rhine, indeed, presents a singularly variegated landscape.

05:26:18.810 --> 05:26:25.310
In one spot you view rugged hills, ruined castles overlooking tremendous precipices,

05:26:25.710 --> 05:26:27.890
with a dark Rhine rushing beneath.

05:26:28.630 --> 05:26:32.970
And on the sudden turn of a promontory, flourishing vineyards,

05:26:33.450 --> 05:26:38.270
with green sloping banks and a meandering river and populous towns occupy the scene.

05:26:39.730 --> 05:26:41.970
We travelled at the time of the vintage,

05:26:42.490 --> 05:26:45.830
and heard the song of the labourers as we glided down the stream.

05:26:45.830 --> 05:26:51.490
Even I, depressed in mind and my spirits continually agitated by gloomy feelings,

05:26:52.010 --> 05:26:53.310
even I was pleased.

05:26:54.230 --> 05:26:59.310
I lay at the bottom of the boat, and as I gazed on the cloudless blue sky,

05:27:00.150 --> 05:27:03.650
I seemed to drink in a tranquillity to which I had long been a stranger.

05:27:04.970 --> 05:27:08.190
And if these were my sensations, who could describe those of Henry?

05:27:08.190 --> 05:27:11.930
He felt as if he had been transported to Fairyland,

05:27:12.390 --> 05:27:14.870
and enjoyed a happiness seldom tasted by man.

05:27:15.550 --> 05:27:21.010
I have seen, he said, the most beautiful scenes of my own country.

05:27:21.390 --> 05:27:24.150
I have visited the lakes of Lucerne and Uri,

05:27:24.470 --> 05:27:28.610
where the snowy mountains descend almost perpendicularly to the water,

05:27:28.810 --> 05:27:31.230
casting black and impenetrable shades,

05:27:31.550 --> 05:27:36.070
which would cause a gloomy and mournful appearance were it not for the most verdant islands

05:27:36.070 --> 05:27:38.890
that believe the eye by their gay appearance.

05:27:40.030 --> 05:27:43.190
I have seen this lake agitated by a tempest,

05:27:43.370 --> 05:27:46.930
when the wind tore up whirlwinds of water and gave you an idea

05:27:46.930 --> 05:27:49.450
of what the waterspout must be on the great ocean,

05:27:49.930 --> 05:27:53.030
and the waves dash with fury the base of the mountain,

05:27:53.510 --> 05:27:56.970
where the priest and his mistress were overwhelmed by an avalanche,

05:27:57.010 --> 05:28:01.470
and where their dying voices are still said to be heard amid the pauses of the nightly wind.

05:28:02.410 --> 05:28:07.590
I have seen the mountains of La Vallée and the Pays-du-Vaux,

05:28:08.150 --> 05:28:13.110
but this country, Victor, pleases me more than all those wonders.

05:28:13.930 --> 05:28:17.230
The mountains of Switzerland are more majestic and strange,

05:28:17.970 --> 05:28:24.590
but there is a charm in the banks of this divine river that I never before saw equalled.

05:28:24.950 --> 05:28:28.090
Look at that castle which overhangs yon precipice,

05:28:28.090 --> 05:28:34.710
and that also on the island, almost concealed among the foliage of those beautiful trees,

05:28:35.590 --> 05:28:40.090
and now that group of laborers coming from among their vines,

05:28:40.410 --> 05:28:43.050
and that village half-hid in the recess of the mountain.

05:28:44.170 --> 05:28:50.570
Oh, surely the spirit that inhabits and guards this place has a soul more in harmony with man

05:28:50.570 --> 05:28:57.530
than those who pile the glacier or retire to the inaccessible peaks of the mountains of our own country.

05:28:59.110 --> 05:29:05.390
Clairvaux, beloved friend, even now it delights me to record your words

05:29:05.390 --> 05:29:09.150
and to dwell on the praise of which you are so eminently deserving.

05:29:10.070 --> 05:29:14.010
He was a being formed in the very poetry of nature.

05:29:14.690 --> 05:29:19.450
His wild and enthusiastic imagination was chastened by the sensibility of his heart.

05:29:20.270 --> 05:29:23.430
His soul overflowed with ardent affections,

05:29:23.430 --> 05:29:26.970
and his friendship was of that devoted and wondrous nature

05:29:26.970 --> 05:29:30.650
that the world-minded teach us to look for only in the imagination.

05:29:31.970 --> 05:29:35.610
But even human sympathies were not sufficient to satisfy his eager mind.

05:29:36.810 --> 05:29:43.850
The scenery of external nature, which others regard only with admiration, he loved with ardor.

05:29:44.670 --> 05:29:48.110
The sounding cataract haunted him like a passion.

05:29:48.110 --> 05:29:52.170
The tall rock, the mountain, and the deep gloomy wood,

05:29:52.430 --> 05:29:56.030
their colors and their forms were then to him an appetite,

05:29:56.690 --> 05:30:02.810
a feeling, and a love that had no need of a remoter charm by thought supplied

05:30:02.810 --> 05:30:05.990
or any interest unborrowed from the eye.

05:30:10.900 --> 05:30:13.010
And where does he now exist?

05:30:14.190 --> 05:30:16.690
Is this gentle and lovely being lost forever?

05:30:17.470 --> 05:30:22.410
Has this mind, so replete with ideas, imaginations, fanciful and magnificent,

05:30:23.010 --> 05:30:27.390
which formed a world whose existence depended on the life of its creator,

05:30:28.610 --> 05:30:30.190
has this mind perished?

05:30:30.990 --> 05:30:33.210
Does it now only exist in my memory?

05:30:34.190 --> 05:30:36.990
No, it is not thus.

05:30:37.750 --> 05:30:43.950
Your form, so divinely wrought and beaming with beauty, has decayed.

05:30:43.950 --> 05:30:49.990
But your spirit still visits and consoles your unhappy friend.

05:30:51.510 --> 05:30:53.130
Pardon this gush of sorrow.

05:30:54.450 --> 05:30:59.950
These ineffectual words are but a slight tribute to the unexampled worth of Henry.

05:31:01.070 --> 05:31:06.670
But they soothe my heart, overflowing with the anguish which his remembrance creates.

05:31:09.050 --> 05:31:10.690
I will proceed with my tale.

05:31:12.250 --> 05:31:14.950
Beyond Cologne we descended to the plains of Holland,

05:31:15.830 --> 05:31:18.470
and we resolved to post the remainder of our way,

05:31:18.750 --> 05:31:23.910
for the wind was contrary and the stream of the river was too gentle to aid us.

05:31:25.130 --> 05:31:28.570
Our journey here lost the interest arising from beautiful scenery,

05:31:29.110 --> 05:31:33.690
but we arrived in a few days at Rotterdam, whence we proceeded by sea to England.

05:31:34.470 --> 05:31:37.630
It was on a clear morning in the latter days of December

05:31:37.630 --> 05:31:40.590
that I first saw the white cliffs of Britain.

05:31:41.990 --> 05:31:44.550
The banks of the Thames presented a new scene.

05:31:45.650 --> 05:31:47.270
They were flat, but fertile,

05:31:47.770 --> 05:31:51.310
and almost every town was marked by the remembrance of some story.

05:31:52.290 --> 05:31:55.970
We saw Tilbury Fort and remembered the Spanish Armada,

05:31:56.730 --> 05:31:59.470
Gravesend, Woolwich and Greenwich,

05:32:00.650 --> 05:32:03.330
places which I had heard of even in my country.

05:32:03.330 --> 05:32:07.630
At length we saw the numerous steeples of London,

05:32:08.290 --> 05:32:10.430
St. Paul's towering above them all,

05:32:10.850 --> 05:32:13.790
and the Tower famed in English history.

05:32:27.170 --> 05:32:30.070
This reading by Megan Jane Daniels Suiyasu.

05:32:31.030 --> 05:32:32.990
Frankenstein by Mary Shelley.

05:32:35.650 --> 05:32:37.890
London was our present point of rest.

05:32:38.170 --> 05:32:42.850
We determined to remain several months in this wonderful and celebrated city.

05:32:43.470 --> 05:32:48.670
Clairvaux desired the intercourse of the men of genius and talent who flourished at this time.

05:32:49.190 --> 05:32:51.490
But this was with me a secondary object.

05:32:51.910 --> 05:32:56.190
I was principally occupied with the means of obtaining the information necessary

05:32:56.190 --> 05:32:58.110
for the completion of my promise,

05:32:58.450 --> 05:33:02.890
and quickly availed myself of the letters of introduction that I had brought with me,

05:33:03.030 --> 05:33:05.530
addressed to the most distinguished natural philosophers.

05:33:06.430 --> 05:33:10.210
If this journey had taken place during my days of study and happiness,

05:33:10.210 --> 05:33:13.390
it would have afforded me inexpressible pleasure.

05:33:14.270 --> 05:33:16.430
But a blight had come over my existence,

05:33:16.830 --> 05:33:21.190
and I only visited these people for the sake of the information they might give me

05:33:21.190 --> 05:33:24.550
on the subject in which my interest was so terribly profound.

05:33:25.390 --> 05:33:27.190
Company was irksome to me,

05:33:27.350 --> 05:33:31.270
when alone I could fill my mind with the sights of heaven and earth.

05:33:31.770 --> 05:33:33.950
The voice of Henry soothed me,

05:33:33.970 --> 05:33:37.070
and I could thus cheat myself into a transitory peace.

05:33:38.010 --> 05:33:43.370
But busy, uninteresting, joyous faces brought back despair to my heart.

05:33:44.010 --> 05:33:47.690
I saw an insurmountable barrier placed between me and my fellow men.

05:33:48.130 --> 05:33:51.670
This barrier was sealed with the blood of William and Justine,

05:33:52.010 --> 05:33:56.830
and to reflect on the events connected with those names filled my soul with anguish.

05:33:57.630 --> 05:34:01.030
But in Clairvaux I saw the image of my former self.

05:34:01.390 --> 05:34:04.890
He was inquisitive and anxious to gain experience and instruction.

05:34:05.590 --> 05:34:07.790
The difference of manners which he observed

05:34:07.790 --> 05:34:11.570
was to him an inexhaustible source of instruction and amusement.

05:34:12.350 --> 05:34:15.610
He was also pursuing at an object he had long had in view.

05:34:16.430 --> 05:34:18.410
His design was to visit India,

05:34:18.750 --> 05:34:22.130
in the belief that he had in his knowledge of its various languages,

05:34:22.690 --> 05:34:25.150
and in the views he had taken of its society,

05:34:25.730 --> 05:34:30.530
the means of materially assisting the progress of European colonisation and trade.

05:34:31.330 --> 05:34:34.770
In Britain only could he further the execution of his plan.

05:34:35.510 --> 05:34:36.910
He was forever busy,

05:34:37.290 --> 05:34:41.270
and the only check to his enjoyments was my sorrowful and dejected mind.

05:34:42.410 --> 05:34:44.990
I tried to conceal this as much as possible,

05:34:45.430 --> 05:34:48.370
that I might not debar him from the pleasures natural to one

05:34:48.370 --> 05:34:50.550
who is entering on a new scene of life,

05:34:51.190 --> 05:34:54.670
undisturbed by any care or bitter recollection.

05:34:55.170 --> 05:34:57.310
I often refused to accompany him,

05:34:57.550 --> 05:34:58.970
alleging another engagement,

05:34:58.970 --> 05:35:00.930
that I might remain alone.

05:35:01.970 --> 05:35:06.170
I now also began to collect the materials necessary for my new creation,

05:35:06.650 --> 05:35:09.970
and this was to me like the torture of single drops of water

05:35:09.970 --> 05:35:11.930
continually falling on the head.

05:35:12.590 --> 05:35:16.190
Every thought that was devoted to it was an extreme anguish,

05:35:16.510 --> 05:35:18.990
and every word that I spoke in allusion to it

05:35:18.990 --> 05:35:22.130
caused my lips to quiver and my heart to palpitate.

05:35:23.190 --> 05:35:25.310
After passing some months in London,

05:35:25.650 --> 05:35:27.990
we received a letter from a person in Scotland

05:35:27.990 --> 05:35:30.150
who had formerly been our visitor at Geneva.

05:35:30.750 --> 05:35:33.090
He mentioned the beauties of his native country

05:35:33.090 --> 05:35:35.890
and asked us if those were not sufficient allurements

05:35:35.890 --> 05:35:39.090
to induce us to prolong our journey as far north as Perth,

05:35:39.130 --> 05:35:41.010
where he resided.

05:35:41.290 --> 05:35:44.030
Clearville eagerly desired to accept this invitation,

05:35:44.410 --> 05:35:47.230
and I, although I abhorred society,

05:35:47.790 --> 05:35:50.030
wished to again view mountains and streams

05:35:50.030 --> 05:35:51.490
and all the wondrous works

05:35:51.490 --> 05:35:54.330
with which nature adorns her chosen dwelling places.

05:35:54.770 --> 05:35:57.610
We had arrived in England at the beginning of October

05:35:57.610 --> 05:35:59.170
and it was now February.

05:35:59.730 --> 05:36:02.210
We accordingly determined to commence our journey

05:36:02.210 --> 05:36:05.030
towards the north at the expiration of another month.

05:36:06.030 --> 05:36:07.150
In this expedition,

05:36:07.610 --> 05:36:10.330
we did not intend to follow the great road to Edinburgh,

05:36:10.770 --> 05:36:14.750
but to visit Windsor, Oxford, Matlock and the Cumberland Lakes,

05:36:15.170 --> 05:36:17.470
resolving to arrive at the completion of this tour

05:36:17.470 --> 05:36:18.730
about the end of July.

05:36:19.430 --> 05:36:21.610
I packed up my chemical instruments

05:36:21.610 --> 05:36:23.450
and the materials I had collected,

05:36:23.990 --> 05:36:27.230
resolving to finish my labours in some obscure nook

05:36:27.230 --> 05:36:29.170
in the northern highlands of Scotland.

05:36:30.410 --> 05:36:32.810
We quitted London on the 27th of March

05:36:32.810 --> 05:36:34.850
and remained a few days at Windsor,

05:36:35.070 --> 05:36:36.690
rambling in its beautiful forest.

05:36:37.290 --> 05:36:39.410
This was a new scene to us mountaineers.

05:36:39.630 --> 05:36:42.010
The majestic oaks, the quantity of game

05:36:42.010 --> 05:36:45.550
and the herds of stately deer were all novelties to us.

05:36:46.030 --> 05:36:47.970
From thence, we proceeded to Oxford.

05:36:48.530 --> 05:36:49.830
As we entered this city,

05:36:50.010 --> 05:36:52.490
our minds were filled with the remembrance of the events

05:36:52.490 --> 05:36:54.450
that had been transacted there

05:36:54.450 --> 05:36:56.430
more than a century and a half before.

05:36:57.330 --> 05:37:00.430
It was here that Charles I had collected his forces.

05:37:01.430 --> 05:37:03.470
This city had remained faithful to him

05:37:03.470 --> 05:37:06.050
after the whole nation had forsaken his cause

05:37:06.050 --> 05:37:08.370
to join the standard of parliament and liberty.

05:37:09.370 --> 05:37:12.210
The memory of that unfortunate king and his companions,

05:37:12.730 --> 05:37:15.210
the amiable Falkland, the insolent Goring,

05:37:15.450 --> 05:37:16.870
his queen and son,

05:37:17.210 --> 05:37:19.930
gave a peculiar interest to every part of the city

05:37:19.930 --> 05:37:22.210
which they might have supposed to have inhabited.

05:37:23.130 --> 05:37:26.050
The spirit of elder days found a dwelling here

05:37:26.050 --> 05:37:28.590
and we delighted to trace its footsteps.

05:37:29.530 --> 05:37:33.070
If these feelings had not found an imaginary gratification,

05:37:33.730 --> 05:37:36.110
the appearance of the city had yet in itself

05:37:36.110 --> 05:37:38.750
sufficient beauty to obtain our admiration.

05:37:39.550 --> 05:37:42.150
The colleges are ancient and picturesque,

05:37:42.410 --> 05:37:44.390
the streets are almost magnificent

05:37:44.390 --> 05:37:47.490
and the lovely Isis, which flows beside it

05:37:47.490 --> 05:37:49.330
through meadows of exquisite verdure,

05:37:49.330 --> 05:37:52.550
is spread forth into a placid expanse of waters

05:37:52.550 --> 05:37:55.770
which reflects its majestic assemblage of towers

05:37:55.770 --> 05:38:00.370
and spires and domes embossed among aged trees.

05:38:02.410 --> 05:38:03.890
I enjoyed this scene

05:38:04.450 --> 05:38:07.010
and yet my enjoyment was embittered

05:38:07.010 --> 05:38:08.830
both by the memory of the past

05:38:08.830 --> 05:38:11.210
and the anticipation of the future.

05:38:11.970 --> 05:38:14.510
I was formed for peaceful happiness.

05:38:15.310 --> 05:38:16.970
During my youthful days,

05:38:17.390 --> 05:38:19.350
disconsent never visited my mind

05:38:19.350 --> 05:38:22.030
and if ever I was overcome by an anui,

05:38:22.750 --> 05:38:24.750
the sight of what is beautiful in nature

05:38:24.750 --> 05:38:27.450
or the study of what is excellent and sublime

05:38:27.450 --> 05:38:28.830
in the productions of man

05:38:28.830 --> 05:38:30.750
could always interest my heart

05:38:30.750 --> 05:38:33.450
and communicate elasticity to my spirits.

05:38:34.450 --> 05:38:36.510
But I am a blasted tree.

05:38:37.150 --> 05:38:38.990
The bolt has entered my soul

05:38:38.990 --> 05:38:41.250
and I felt then that I should survive

05:38:41.250 --> 05:38:43.850
to exhibit what I shall soon cease to be.

05:38:44.370 --> 05:38:47.290
A miserable spectacle of wrecked humanity,

05:38:47.770 --> 05:38:51.070
pitiable to others and intolerable to myself.

05:38:52.030 --> 05:38:54.350
We passed a considerable period at Oxford,

05:38:54.650 --> 05:38:56.350
rambling amongst its environs

05:38:56.350 --> 05:38:58.630
and endeavouring to identify every spot

05:38:58.630 --> 05:39:01.250
which might relate to the most animating epoch

05:39:01.250 --> 05:39:02.430
of the English history.

05:39:03.310 --> 05:39:05.130
Our little voyages of discovery

05:39:05.130 --> 05:39:07.550
were often prolonged by the successive objects

05:39:07.550 --> 05:39:08.890
that presented themselves.

05:39:09.530 --> 05:39:12.210
We visited the tomb of the illustrious Hamden

05:39:12.210 --> 05:39:14.590
and the field on which that patriot fell.

05:39:15.350 --> 05:39:17.290
For a moment, my soul was elevated

05:39:17.290 --> 05:39:19.510
from its debasing and miserable fears

05:39:19.510 --> 05:39:22.870
to contemplate the divine ideas of liberty

05:39:22.870 --> 05:39:25.650
and self-sacrifice of which these sights

05:39:25.650 --> 05:39:28.010
were the monuments and the remembrances.

05:39:29.070 --> 05:39:31.710
For an instant, I dared to shake off my chains

05:39:31.710 --> 05:39:34.250
and look around me with a free and lofty spirit,

05:39:35.650 --> 05:39:38.230
but the iron had eaten into my flesh

05:39:38.230 --> 05:39:39.770
and I sank again,

05:39:39.770 --> 05:39:43.110
trembling and hopeless, into my miserable self.

05:39:43.870 --> 05:39:47.390
We left Oxford with regret and proceeded to Matlock,

05:39:47.650 --> 05:39:49.370
which was our next place of rest.

05:39:50.290 --> 05:39:52.210
The country in the neighbourhood of this village

05:39:52.210 --> 05:39:55.790
resembled, to a greater degree, the scenery of Switzerland,

05:39:56.310 --> 05:39:58.250
but everything is on a lower scale

05:39:58.250 --> 05:40:01.670
and the green hills want the crown of distant white alps,

05:40:01.830 --> 05:40:03.910
which always attend on the piney mountains

05:40:03.910 --> 05:40:05.210
of my native country.

05:40:05.970 --> 05:40:07.890
We visited the wondrous cave

05:40:07.890 --> 05:40:10.390
and the little cabinets of natural history

05:40:10.390 --> 05:40:13.250
where the curiosities are disposed in the same manner

05:40:13.250 --> 05:40:15.990
as in the collections at Servox and Chamonix.

05:40:17.050 --> 05:40:20.330
The latter name made me tremble when pronounced by Henry

05:40:20.330 --> 05:40:22.590
and I hastened to quit Matlock,

05:40:23.110 --> 05:40:26.410
with which that terrible scene was thus associated.

05:40:27.850 --> 05:40:30.630
From Derby, still journeying northwards,

05:40:30.910 --> 05:40:33.510
we passed two months in Cumberland and Westmoreland.

05:40:33.990 --> 05:40:37.590
I can now almost fancy myself amongst the Swiss mountains.

05:40:38.190 --> 05:40:39.590
The little patches of snow,

05:40:39.710 --> 05:40:42.370
which yet lingered on the northern sides of the mountains,

05:40:42.810 --> 05:40:45.730
the lakes and the dashing of the rocking streams

05:40:45.730 --> 05:40:48.390
were all familiar and dear sights to me.

05:40:49.690 --> 05:40:51.810
Here also we made some acquaintances

05:40:51.810 --> 05:40:55.150
who almost contrived to cheat me into happiness.

05:40:56.130 --> 05:40:59.490
The delight of Clevel was proportionately greater than mine.

05:40:59.850 --> 05:41:03.030
His mind expanded in the company of men of talent

05:41:03.030 --> 05:41:07.330
and he found in his own nature greater capacities and resources

05:41:07.330 --> 05:41:10.550
than he could have ever imagined himself to have possessed

05:41:10.550 --> 05:41:12.890
while he associated with his inferiors.

05:41:13.710 --> 05:41:16.070
I could pass my life here, he said to me,

05:41:16.310 --> 05:41:20.790
and among these mountains I should scarcely regret Switzerland and the Rhine.

05:41:21.250 --> 05:41:23.330
But he found that a traveller's life

05:41:23.330 --> 05:41:26.790
is one that includes much pain amidst its enjoyments.

05:41:27.370 --> 05:41:29.630
His feelings are forever on the stretch

05:41:29.630 --> 05:41:32.310
and when he begins to sink in to repose

05:41:32.310 --> 05:41:34.530
he finds himself obliged to quit

05:41:34.530 --> 05:41:37.310
that on which he rests in pleasure for something new

05:41:37.310 --> 05:41:39.710
which again engages his attention

05:41:39.710 --> 05:41:42.770
and which he also forsakes for other novelties.

05:41:43.810 --> 05:41:47.530
We had scarcely visited the various lakes of Cumberland and Westmoreland

05:41:47.530 --> 05:41:50.670
and conceived an affection for some of the inhabitants

05:41:50.670 --> 05:41:54.230
when the period of our appointment with our Scotch friend approached

05:41:54.230 --> 05:41:56.450
and we left them to travel on.

05:41:57.110 --> 05:41:59.410
For my own part, I was not sorry.

05:41:59.410 --> 05:42:02.930
I had now neglected my promise for some time

05:42:02.930 --> 05:42:06.010
and I feared the effects of the demon's disappointment.

05:42:07.310 --> 05:42:11.270
He might remain in Switzerland and wreak his vengeance on my relatives.

05:42:12.410 --> 05:42:15.710
This idea pursued me and tormented me at every moment

05:42:15.710 --> 05:42:18.930
from which I might otherwise have snatched repose and peace.

05:42:19.850 --> 05:42:22.590
I waited for my letters with feverish impatience.

05:42:23.210 --> 05:42:27.210
If they were delayed, I was miserable and overcome by a thousand fears

05:42:27.210 --> 05:42:31.570
and when they arrived and I saw the superscription of Elizabeth and my father

05:42:31.570 --> 05:42:35.010
I hardly dared to read and ascertain my fate.

05:42:35.610 --> 05:42:38.030
Sometimes I thought that the fiend followed me

05:42:38.030 --> 05:42:41.590
and might expedite my remissness by murdering my companion.

05:42:42.390 --> 05:42:44.090
When these thoughts possessed me

05:42:44.090 --> 05:42:46.290
I would not quit Henry for a moment

05:42:46.290 --> 05:42:48.530
but followed him as his shadow

05:42:48.530 --> 05:42:52.150
to protect him from the fancied range of his destroyer.

05:42:52.710 --> 05:42:55.610
I felt as if I had committed some great crime

05:42:55.610 --> 05:42:58.350
the consciousness of which haunted me.

05:42:58.810 --> 05:43:03.990
I was guiltless but I had indeed drawn down some horrible curse upon my head

05:43:03.990 --> 05:43:06.270
as mortal as that of crime.

05:43:07.310 --> 05:43:10.390
I visited Edinburgh with languid eyes and mind

05:43:10.390 --> 05:43:14.770
and yet that city might have interested the most unfortunate being.

05:43:15.750 --> 05:43:17.770
Clairvaux did not like it so well as Oxford

05:43:17.770 --> 05:43:21.470
for the antiquity of the latter city was more pleasing to him.

05:43:21.710 --> 05:43:24.870
But the beauty and regularity of the new town of Edinburgh

05:43:24.870 --> 05:43:28.130
its romantic castle and its environs

05:43:28.130 --> 05:43:32.070
the most delightful in the world Arthur's Seat, Sir Barnard's Whirl

05:43:32.070 --> 05:43:35.170
and the Pentland Hills compensated him for the change

05:43:35.170 --> 05:43:37.830
and filled him with cheerfulness and admiration.

05:43:38.630 --> 05:43:42.670
But I was impatient to arrive at the termination of my journey.

05:43:43.690 --> 05:43:45.330
We left Edinburgh in a week

05:43:45.330 --> 05:43:50.290
passing through Coupar, St Andrews and along the banks of the Tay to Perth

05:43:50.290 --> 05:43:51.710
where our friend greeted us.

05:43:51.710 --> 05:43:55.170
But I was in no mood to laugh and talk with strangers

05:43:55.170 --> 05:43:59.930
or enter into their feelings or plans with the good humour expected from a guest

05:43:59.930 --> 05:44:05.090
and accordingly I told Clairvaux that I wished to make the tour of Scotland alone.

05:44:05.670 --> 05:44:09.890
Do you, said I, enjoy yourself and let this be our rendezvous.

05:44:10.390 --> 05:44:12.430
I may be absent a month or two

05:44:12.430 --> 05:44:16.010
but do not interfere with my emotions, I entreat you.

05:44:16.850 --> 05:44:19.650
Leave me to peace and solitude for a short time

05:44:19.650 --> 05:44:23.050
and when I return I hope it will be with a lighter heart

05:44:23.050 --> 05:44:25.070
more congenial to your own temper.

05:44:27.070 --> 05:44:28.770
Henry wished to dissuade me

05:44:28.770 --> 05:44:32.470
but seeing me bend on this plan ceased to remonstrate.

05:44:33.130 --> 05:44:34.890
He entreated me to write often.

05:44:35.750 --> 05:44:38.010
I had rather be with you, he said,

05:44:38.490 --> 05:44:42.650
in your solitary rambles than with these Scotch people whom I do not know.

05:44:43.130 --> 05:44:45.330
Hasten then, dear friend, to return

05:44:45.330 --> 05:44:48.310
that I may again feel myself somewhat at home

05:44:48.310 --> 05:44:50.290
which I cannot do in your absence.

05:44:51.710 --> 05:44:53.230
Having parted from my friend

05:44:53.230 --> 05:44:56.270
I determined to visit some remote spot of Scotland

05:44:56.270 --> 05:44:58.450
and finish my work in solitude.

05:44:59.150 --> 05:45:01.870
I did not doubt but that the monster followed me

05:45:01.870 --> 05:45:04.950
and would discover himself to me when I should have finished

05:45:04.950 --> 05:45:07.270
that he might receive his companion.

05:45:08.510 --> 05:45:11.890
With this resolution I traversed the Northern Highlands

05:45:11.890 --> 05:45:15.870
and fixed on one of the remotest of the Orkneys as the scene of my labours.

05:45:15.870 --> 05:45:19.090
It was a place fitted for such a work

05:45:19.090 --> 05:45:23.930
being hardly more than a rock whose sides were continually beaten upon by the waves.

05:45:24.670 --> 05:45:26.010
The soil was barren

05:45:26.010 --> 05:45:28.990
scarcely affording pasture for a few miserable cows

05:45:28.990 --> 05:45:30.690
and oatmeal for its inhabitants

05:45:30.690 --> 05:45:35.270
which consisted of five persons whose gaunt and scraggly limbs

05:45:35.270 --> 05:45:37.390
gave tokens of their miserable fare.

05:45:38.330 --> 05:45:40.930
Vegetables and bread when they indulged in such luxuries

05:45:41.390 --> 05:45:45.150
and even fresh water was to be procured from the mainland

05:45:45.150 --> 05:45:47.550
which was about five miles distant.

05:45:48.130 --> 05:45:51.190
On the whole island there were but three miserable huts

05:45:51.190 --> 05:45:53.830
and one of these was vacant when I arrived.

05:45:54.470 --> 05:45:55.270
This I hired.

05:45:56.190 --> 05:46:00.050
It contained but two rooms and these exhibited all the squalidness

05:46:00.050 --> 05:46:02.130
of the most miserable pernery.

05:46:02.630 --> 05:46:05.950
The thatch had fallen in, the walls were unplastered

05:46:05.950 --> 05:46:07.510
and the door was off its hinges.

05:46:08.190 --> 05:46:11.050
I ordered it to be repaired, bought for some furniture

05:46:11.050 --> 05:46:12.410
and took possession.

05:46:13.370 --> 05:46:16.390
An incident which would doubtless have occasioned some surprise

05:46:16.390 --> 05:46:19.730
had not all the senses of the cottagers been benumbed by want

05:46:19.730 --> 05:46:20.930
and squalid poverty.

05:46:21.510 --> 05:46:24.630
As it was I lived ungazed and unmolested

05:46:24.630 --> 05:46:28.070
hardly thanked for the pittance of food and clothes which I gave

05:46:28.070 --> 05:46:32.330
so much does suffering blunt even the coarsest sensations of men.

05:46:32.970 --> 05:46:36.070
In this retreat I devoted the morning to labour

05:46:36.070 --> 05:46:38.550
but in the evening when the weather permitted

05:46:38.550 --> 05:46:42.390
I walked on the stony beach of the sea to listen to the waves

05:46:42.390 --> 05:46:44.490
as they roared and dashed at my feet.

05:46:45.210 --> 05:46:48.150
It was a monotonous yet ever-changing scene.

05:46:49.670 --> 05:46:50.770
I thought of Switzerland.

05:46:51.230 --> 05:46:54.650
It was far different from this desolate and appalling landscape.

05:46:55.470 --> 05:46:57.210
Its hills are covered with vines

05:46:57.210 --> 05:47:00.190
and its cottages are scattered thickly in the plains.

05:47:00.890 --> 05:47:03.770
Its fair lakes reflect a blue and gentle sky

05:47:03.770 --> 05:47:05.870
and when travelled by the winds

05:47:05.870 --> 05:47:08.990
their tumult is but the play of a lively infant

05:47:08.990 --> 05:47:11.550
when compared to the roaring of the giant ocean.

05:47:13.610 --> 05:47:14.530
In this manner

05:47:14.530 --> 05:47:17.910
I distributed my occupations when I first arrived

05:47:17.910 --> 05:47:20.250
but as I proceeded in my labour

05:47:20.710 --> 05:47:24.930
it became every day more horrible and irksome to me.

05:47:25.450 --> 05:47:27.530
Sometimes I could not prevail on myself

05:47:27.530 --> 05:47:29.810
to enter my laboratory for several days

05:47:29.810 --> 05:47:32.670
and at other times I toiled day and night

05:47:32.670 --> 05:47:34.250
in order to complete my work.

05:47:34.750 --> 05:47:38.470
It was indeed a filthy process in which I was engaged.

05:47:39.150 --> 05:47:40.690
During my first experiment

05:47:40.690 --> 05:47:43.530
a kind of enthusiastic frenzy had blinded me

05:47:43.530 --> 05:47:44.930
to the horror of my employment.

05:47:45.350 --> 05:47:48.490
My mind was intently fixed on the consummation of my labour

05:47:48.490 --> 05:47:51.670
and my eyes were shut to the horror of my proceedings.

05:47:52.390 --> 05:47:54.670
But now I went to it in cold blood

05:47:54.670 --> 05:47:57.890
and my heart often sickened at the work of my hands.

05:47:59.170 --> 05:48:00.530
Thus situated

05:48:00.530 --> 05:48:04.070
employed in the most detestable occupation

05:48:04.070 --> 05:48:06.190
immersed in a solitude

05:48:06.190 --> 05:48:09.230
where nothing could for an instant call my attention

05:48:09.230 --> 05:48:11.830
from the actual scene in which I was engaged

05:48:11.830 --> 05:48:14.230
my spirits became unequal.

05:48:14.230 --> 05:48:17.650
I grew restless and nervous.

05:48:17.870 --> 05:48:21.970
Every moment I feared to meet my persecutor.

05:48:22.190 --> 05:48:25.570
Sometimes I sat with my eyes fixed on the ground

05:48:25.570 --> 05:48:29.010
fearing to raise them lest they should encounter the object

05:48:29.010 --> 05:48:32.330
which I so much dreaded to behold.

05:48:32.970 --> 05:48:36.230
I feared to wander from the sight of my fellow creatures

05:48:36.230 --> 05:48:37.650
lest when alone

05:48:37.650 --> 05:48:40.370
he should come to claim his companion.

05:48:41.610 --> 05:48:43.670
In the meantime I worked on

05:48:43.670 --> 05:48:46.750
and my labour was already considerably advanced.

05:48:47.910 --> 05:48:49.990
I looked towards its completion

05:48:49.990 --> 05:48:51.910
with a tremulous and eager hope

05:48:51.910 --> 05:48:55.130
which I dared not trust myself to question

05:48:55.130 --> 05:48:57.930
but which was intermixed with obscure

05:48:57.930 --> 05:49:01.090
forebodings of evil that made my heart sicken

05:49:01.090 --> 05:49:02.090
in my bosom.

05:49:27.430 --> 05:49:29.270
I sat one evening in my laboratory.

05:49:29.870 --> 05:49:33.210
The sun had set and the moon was just rising from the sea.

05:49:33.720 --> 05:49:39.530
I had not sufficient light for my employment and I remained idle in a pause of consideration

05:49:39.530 --> 05:49:44.350
of whether I should leave my labour for the night or hasten its conclusion by an unremitting

05:49:44.350 --> 05:49:45.450
attention to it.

05:49:46.030 --> 05:49:51.850
As I sat, a train of reflection occurred to me which led me to consider the effects of

05:49:51.850 --> 05:49:53.170
what I was now doing.

05:49:53.750 --> 05:49:59.710
Three years before I was engaged in the same manner and had created a fiend whose unparalleled

05:49:59.710 --> 05:50:04.870
barbarity had desolated my heart and filled it forever with the bitterest remorse.

05:50:05.830 --> 05:50:11.450
I was now about to form another being of whose dispositions I was alike ignorant.

05:50:11.890 --> 05:50:17.370
She might become ten thousand times more malignant than her mate and delight for its own sake

05:50:17.370 --> 05:50:19.550
in murder and wretchedness.

05:50:20.210 --> 05:50:25.450
He had sworn to quit the neighbourhood of man and hide himself in deserts, but she had

05:50:26.130 --> 05:50:32.150
And she, who in all probability was to become a thinking and reasoning animal, might refuse

05:50:32.150 --> 05:50:34.810
to comply with a compact made before her creation.

05:50:35.310 --> 05:50:40.950
They might even hate each other, the creature who already lived loathed his own deformity,

05:50:41.330 --> 05:50:46.130
and might he not conceive a greater abhorrence for it when it came before his eyes in the

05:50:46.130 --> 05:50:47.010
female form?

05:50:47.730 --> 05:50:52.350
She might also turn with disgust from him to the superior beauty of man.

05:50:52.350 --> 05:50:58.930
She might quit him, and he, being again alone, exasperated by the fresh provocation of being

05:50:58.930 --> 05:51:01.190
deserted by one of his own species.

05:51:02.230 --> 05:51:07.250
Even if they were to leave Europe and inhabit the deserts of the New World, yet one of the

05:51:07.250 --> 05:51:12.710
results of those sympathies for which the demon thirsted would be children, and a race

05:51:12.710 --> 05:51:18.190
of devils would be propagated upon the earth who might make the very existence of the species

05:51:18.190 --> 05:51:21.550
of man a condition precarious and full of terror.

05:51:22.050 --> 05:51:27.750
Had I right, for my own benefit, to inflict this curse upon everlasting generations?

05:51:28.670 --> 05:51:32.790
I had been moved by the sophisms of the being I had created.

05:51:33.710 --> 05:51:39.510
I had been struck senseless by his fiendish threats, but now, for the first time, the

05:51:39.510 --> 05:51:41.950
wickedness of my promise burst upon me.

05:51:42.810 --> 05:51:47.750
I shuddered to think that future ages might curse me as their pest, whose selfishness

05:51:47.750 --> 05:51:53.370
had not hesitated to buy its own piece at the price, perhaps, of the existence of the

05:51:53.370 --> 05:51:54.850
whole human race.

05:51:55.790 --> 05:52:03.510
I trembled, and my heart felled within me when, on looking up, I saw by the light of

05:52:03.510 --> 05:52:05.770
the moon the demon at the casement.

05:52:06.590 --> 05:52:12.330
A ghastly grin wrinkled his lips as he gazed on me, where I sat fulfilling the task which

05:52:12.330 --> 05:52:13.950
he had allotted to me.

05:52:13.950 --> 05:52:20.990
Yes, he had followed me in my travels, he had loitered in forests, hid himself in caves,

05:52:21.370 --> 05:52:28.090
or taken refuge in wide and desert heaths, and now he came to mark my progress and claim

05:52:28.090 --> 05:52:29.970
the fulfilment of my promise.

05:52:30.870 --> 05:52:37.710
As I looked on him, his countenance expressed the utmost extent of malice and treachery.

05:52:37.710 --> 05:52:43.630
I thought with a sensation of madness on my promise of creating another like to him,

05:52:44.370 --> 05:52:49.130
and trembling with passion, tore to pieces the thing on which I was engaged.

05:52:49.770 --> 05:52:55.450
The wretch saw me destroy the creature, on whose future existence he depended for happiness,

05:52:56.050 --> 05:53:00.550
and with a howl of devilish despair and revenge, withdrew.

05:53:01.350 --> 05:53:07.790
I left the room and, locking the door, made a solemn vow in my own heart never to resume

05:53:07.790 --> 05:53:13.470
my labours, and then, with trembling steps, I sought my own apartment.

05:53:14.090 --> 05:53:19.630
I was alone, none were near me to dissipate the gloom and relieve me from the sickening

05:53:19.630 --> 05:53:22.430
oppression of the most terrible reveries.

05:53:23.450 --> 05:53:28.510
Several hours passed, and I remained near my window gazing on the sea.

05:53:28.510 --> 05:53:34.570
It was almost motionless, for the winds were hushed, and all nature opposed under the eye

05:53:34.570 --> 05:53:35.630
of the quiet moon.

05:53:36.350 --> 05:53:41.990
A few fishing vessels alone specked the water, and now and then the gentle breeze wafted

05:53:41.990 --> 05:53:45.130
the sound of voices as the fishermen called to one another.

05:53:46.090 --> 05:53:51.770
I felt the silence, although I was hardly conscious of its extreme profundity, until

05:53:51.770 --> 05:53:57.090
my ear was suddenly arrested by the paddling of oars near the shore, and a person landed

05:53:57.090 --> 05:53:58.490
close to my house.

05:53:59.970 --> 05:54:05.590
In a few minutes after, I heard the creaking of my door, as if someone endeavoured to open

05:54:05.590 --> 05:54:06.270
it softly.

05:54:06.990 --> 05:54:13.130
I trembled from head to foot, I felt a presentiment of who it was, and wished to where I was one

05:54:13.130 --> 05:54:18.930
of the peasants who dwelt in a cottage not far from mine, but I was overcome by the sensation

05:54:18.930 --> 05:54:24.890
of helplessness, so often felt in frightful dreams, when you in vain endeavoured to fly

05:54:24.890 --> 05:54:28.250
from an impending danger and was routed to the spot.

05:54:29.110 --> 05:54:35.170
Presently I heard the sound of footsteps along the passage, the door opened, and the

05:54:35.170 --> 05:54:38.550
wretch, whom I dreaded, appeared.

05:54:40.030 --> 05:54:44.630
Shutting the door, he approached me and said in a smothered voice,

05:54:45.430 --> 05:54:48.690
You have destroyed the work which you began.

05:54:49.310 --> 05:54:50.730
Was it that you intend?

05:54:51.750 --> 05:54:53.630
Do you dare to break your promise?

05:54:54.240 --> 05:54:56.870
I have endured toil and misery.

05:54:57.370 --> 05:54:59.230
I left Switzerland with you.

05:54:59.490 --> 05:55:04.770
I crept along the shores of the Rhine, among its willow islands, and over the summits of

05:55:04.770 --> 05:55:05.450
its hills.

05:55:05.990 --> 05:55:11.170
I have dwelt many months in the heaths of England, and among the deserts of Scotland.

05:55:11.710 --> 05:55:15.830
I have endured incalculable fatigue and cold, and hunger.

05:55:16.470 --> 05:55:18.490
Do you dare destroy my hopes?

05:55:19.990 --> 05:55:20.650
Be gone!

05:55:21.130 --> 05:55:22.850
I do break my promise.

05:55:22.850 --> 05:55:29.210
Never will I create another like yourself, equal in deformity and wickedness.

05:55:30.190 --> 05:55:37.190
Slave, I before reasoned with you, but you have proved yourself unworthy of my condescension.

05:55:38.170 --> 05:55:40.470
Remember that I have power.

05:55:41.130 --> 05:55:48.610
You believe yourself miserable, but I can make you so wretched that the light of day

05:55:48.610 --> 05:55:50.290
will be hateful to you.

05:55:51.030 --> 05:55:55.310
You are my creator, but I am your master.

05:55:55.850 --> 05:55:56.430
Obey!

05:55:58.310 --> 05:56:04.410
The hour of my irresolution is past, and the period of your power is arrived.

05:56:05.050 --> 05:56:11.490
Your threats cannot move me to do an act of wickedness, but they confirm in me a determination

05:56:11.490 --> 05:56:14.810
of not creating you a companion in vice.

05:56:15.250 --> 05:56:22.510
Shall I, in cold blood, set loose upon the earth a demon whose delight is in death and

05:56:22.510 --> 05:56:23.330
wretchedness?

05:56:23.950 --> 05:56:24.510
Be gone!

05:56:25.090 --> 05:56:29.710
I am firm, and your words only exasperate my rage.

05:56:31.270 --> 05:56:37.190
The monster saw my determination in my face, and gnashed his teeth in the impotence of

05:56:37.190 --> 05:56:37.630
anger.

05:56:38.350 --> 05:56:47.470
Shall each man, cried he, find a wife for his bosom, and each beast have his mate, and

05:56:47.470 --> 05:56:48.650
I be alone?

05:56:49.290 --> 05:56:55.630
I had feelings of affection, and they were requited by detestation and scorn.

05:56:56.230 --> 05:56:59.450
Man, you may hate, but beware!

05:57:00.070 --> 05:57:06.530
Your hours will pass in dread and misery, and soon the bolt will fall which must ravage

05:57:06.530 --> 05:57:08.410
you from your happiness forever.

05:57:09.450 --> 05:57:10.830
Are you to be happy?

05:57:11.110 --> 05:57:14.310
Will I grovel in the intensity of my wretchedness?

05:57:14.970 --> 05:57:22.730
You can blast my other passions, but revenge remains, revenge henceforth dearer than light

05:57:22.730 --> 05:57:23.610
or food.

05:57:24.330 --> 05:57:33.890
I may die, but first you, my tyrant and tormentor, shall curse the sun that gazes on your misery.

05:57:35.110 --> 05:57:39.430
Beware, for I am fearless, and therefore powerful.

05:57:40.170 --> 05:57:45.110
I will watch with the wiliness of a snake, that I may sting with its venom.

05:57:46.090 --> 05:57:50.530
Man, you shall repent of the injuries you inflict.

05:57:52.750 --> 05:57:58.190
Devil, cease, and do not poison the air with these sounds of malice.

05:57:58.190 --> 05:58:04.110
I have declared my resolution to you, and I am no coward to bend beneath words.

05:58:04.810 --> 05:58:07.370
Leave me, I am inexorable.

05:58:09.170 --> 05:58:17.730
It is well, I go, but remember, I shall be with you on your wedding night.

05:58:18.830 --> 05:58:21.810
I started forward and exclaimed,

05:58:22.490 --> 05:58:29.210
Villain, before you sign my death warrant, be sure that you yourself safe.

05:58:30.610 --> 05:58:36.490
I would have seized him, but he eluded me and quitted the house with precipitation.

05:58:37.630 --> 05:58:44.450
In a few moments I saw him in his boat, which shot across the waters with an arrow-y swiftness,

05:58:44.850 --> 05:58:47.130
and was soon lost amidst the waves.

05:58:48.010 --> 05:58:53.510
All was again silent, but his words rang in my ears.

05:58:54.430 --> 05:59:00.170
I burned with rage to pursue the murderer of my peace and precipitate him into the ocean.

05:59:01.210 --> 05:59:04.850
I walked up and down my room hastily and perturbed,

05:59:05.090 --> 05:59:10.290
while my imagination conjured up a thousand images to torment and sting me.

05:59:11.050 --> 05:59:15.230
Why had I not followed him and closed with him in mortal strife?

05:59:15.970 --> 05:59:21.770
But I had suffered him to depart, and he had directed his course towards the mainland.

05:59:24.030 --> 05:59:29.850
I shuddered to think who might be the next victim sacrificed to his insatiable revenge.

05:59:31.070 --> 05:59:33.530
And then I thought again of his words,

05:59:34.590 --> 05:59:37.750
I will be with you on your wedding night.

05:59:38.690 --> 05:59:43.650
That, then, was the period fixed for the fulfilment of my destiny.

05:59:44.430 --> 05:59:50.170
In that hour I should die and at once satisfy and extinguish his malice.

05:59:50.970 --> 05:59:56.870
The prospect did not move me to fear, yet when I thought of my beloved Elizabeth,

05:59:57.410 --> 06:00:04.210
of her tears and endless sorrow, when she should find her lover so barbariously snatched from her,

06:00:04.650 --> 06:00:10.530
tears, the first I had shed for many months, streamed from my eyes,

06:00:10.530 --> 06:00:15.110
and I resolved not to fall before my enemy without a bitter struggle.

06:00:18.930 --> 06:00:22.790
The night passed away, and the sun rose from the ocean.

06:00:23.510 --> 06:00:27.670
My feelings became calmer, if it may be called calmness,

06:00:27.730 --> 06:00:31.390
when the violence of rage sinks into the depths of despair.

06:00:32.270 --> 06:00:36.410
I left the house, the horrid scene of last night's contention,

06:00:36.410 --> 06:00:41.230
and walked on the beach of the sea, which I almost regarded as an

06:00:41.230 --> 06:00:44.630
insurmountable barrier between me and my fellow creatures.

06:00:45.090 --> 06:00:50.850
Nay, a wish that such should prove the fact stole across me.

06:00:51.730 --> 06:00:55.550
I desired that I might pass my life on that barren rock.

06:00:56.170 --> 06:01:01.510
Wearily, it is true, but uninterrupted by any sudden shock of misery.

06:01:02.310 --> 06:01:08.670
If I returned, it was to be sacrificed, or to see those whom I loved most

06:01:08.670 --> 06:01:13.130
die under the grasp of a demon whom I had myself created.

06:01:14.750 --> 06:01:17.510
I walked about the isle like a restless spectre,

06:01:18.470 --> 06:01:21.990
separated from all it loved and miserable in the separation.

06:01:22.950 --> 06:01:25.770
When it became noon and the sun rose higher,

06:01:26.410 --> 06:01:30.250
I lay down on the grass and was overpowered by a deep sleep.

06:01:31.510 --> 06:01:36.390
I had been awake the whole of the preceding night, my nerves were agitated,

06:01:37.030 --> 06:01:40.050
and my eyes inflamed by watching and misery.

06:01:41.170 --> 06:01:45.830
The sleep into which I now sank refreshed me, and when I awoke,

06:01:46.350 --> 06:01:50.830
I again felt as if I belonged to a race of human beings like myself,

06:01:51.390 --> 06:01:55.950
and I began to reflect upon what had passed with greater composure.

06:01:56.870 --> 06:02:02.410
Yet still, the words of the fiend rang in my ears like a death knell.

06:02:02.650 --> 06:02:08.170
They appeared like a dream, yet distinct and oppressive as a reality.

06:02:09.310 --> 06:02:13.770
The sun had far descended, and I sat still on the shore,

06:02:14.290 --> 06:02:19.210
satisfying my appetite, which had become ravenous, with an oaten cake.

06:02:19.750 --> 06:02:24.910
When I saw a fishing boat land close to me, and one of the men brought me a packet,

06:02:25.510 --> 06:02:30.630
it contained letters from Geneva and one from Clearville entreating me to join him.

06:02:30.810 --> 06:02:35.370
He said that he was wearing away his time fruitlessly where he was,

06:02:35.750 --> 06:02:40.050
that the letters from the friends he had formed in London desired his return

06:02:40.050 --> 06:02:45.010
to complete the negotiation they had entered into for his Indian enterprise.

06:02:45.770 --> 06:02:51.650
I could no longer delay his departure, but as his journey to London might be followed,

06:02:51.650 --> 06:02:56.350
even sooner than he now conjectured, by his longer voyage,

06:02:56.770 --> 06:03:01.470
he entreated me to bestow as much of my society on him as I could spare.

06:03:02.550 --> 06:03:08.010
He besought me, therefore, to leave my solitary isle and to meet him at Perth,

06:03:08.170 --> 06:03:10.330
that we might proceed southwards together.

06:03:11.330 --> 06:03:14.170
This letter in a degree recalled me to life,

06:03:14.550 --> 06:03:18.630
and I determined to quit my island at the expiration of two days.

06:03:19.510 --> 06:03:25.610
Yet before I departed, there was a task to perform, on which I shuddered to reflect.

06:03:26.390 --> 06:03:33.710
I must pack up my chemical instruments, and for that purpose, I must enter the room which had been

06:03:33.710 --> 06:03:41.430
the scene of my odious work, and I must handle those utensils, the sight of which was sickening

06:03:41.430 --> 06:03:49.050
me. The next morning, at daybreak, I summoned sufficient courage and unlocked the door of my

06:03:49.050 --> 06:03:56.850
laboratory. The remains of the half-finished creature, whom I had destroyed, laid scattered

06:03:56.850 --> 06:04:03.230
on the floor, and I almost felt as if I had mingled with the living flesh of a human being.

06:04:03.750 --> 06:04:07.750
I paused to collect myself, and then entered the chamber.

06:04:08.590 --> 06:04:15.650
With trembling hand, I conveyed the instruments out of the room, but I reflected that I ought

06:04:15.650 --> 06:04:20.810
not to leave the relics of my work to excite the horror and suspicion of the peasants,

06:04:21.150 --> 06:04:27.870
and I accordingly put them into a basket with a great quantity of stones, and laying them up,

06:04:27.870 --> 06:04:34.190
determined to throw them into the sea that very night. And in the meantime, I sat upon the beach,

06:04:34.190 --> 06:04:38.030
employed in cleaning and arranging my chemical apparatus.

06:04:39.950 --> 06:04:45.570
Nothing could be more complete than the alteration that had taken place in my feelings since the night

06:04:45.570 --> 06:04:52.710
of the appearance of the demon. I had before regarded my promise with gloomy despair as a

06:04:52.710 --> 06:05:00.130
thing that, with whatever consequences, must be fulfilled. But now I felt as if a film had been

06:05:00.130 --> 06:05:08.330
from before my eyes, and that I saw for the first time clearly. The idea of renewing my labors

06:05:08.330 --> 06:05:16.050
did not for one instant occur to me, the threat I had weighed upon my thoughts, but I did not reflect

06:05:16.050 --> 06:05:23.510
that a voluntary act of mine could avert it. I had resolved in my own mind that to create another

06:05:23.510 --> 06:05:29.770
like the fiend I had first made would be an act of the basest and most atrocious selfishness

06:05:29.770 --> 06:05:35.410
and I banished from my mind every thought that could lead to a different conclusion.

06:05:36.810 --> 06:05:43.070
Between two and three in the morning the moon rose, and I then, putting my basket aboard a little

06:05:43.070 --> 06:05:51.430
skiff, sailed out about four miles from the shore. The scene was perfectly solitary, a few boats were

06:05:51.430 --> 06:05:58.330
returning towards land, but I sailed away from them. I felt as if I was about the commission of

06:05:58.330 --> 06:06:04.390
dreadful crime and avoided with shuddering anxiety any encounter with my fellow creatures.

06:06:05.570 --> 06:06:12.270
At one time the moon, which had been before clear, was suddenly overspread by a thick cloud,

06:06:12.850 --> 06:06:19.370
and I took advantage of the moment of darkness and cast my basket into the sea. I listened to

06:06:19.370 --> 06:06:26.670
the gurgling sound as it sank and then sailed away from the spot. The sky became clouded,

06:06:26.670 --> 06:06:31.730
but the air was pure, although chilled by the northeast breeze that was then rising.

06:06:33.050 --> 06:06:38.830
But it refreshed me and filled me with such agreeable sensations that I resolved to prolong

06:06:38.830 --> 06:06:45.030
my stay on the water, and fixing the rudder in a direct position, stretched myself at the bottom

06:06:45.030 --> 06:06:53.090
of the boat. Clouds hid the moon, everything was obscure, and I heard only the sound of the boat as

06:06:53.090 --> 06:07:00.110
keel cut through the waves. The murmur lulled me, and in a short time I slept soundly.

06:07:01.010 --> 06:07:07.190
I do not know how long I remained in this situation, but when I awoke I found that the

06:07:07.190 --> 06:07:14.350
sun had already mounted considerably. The wind was high and the waves continually threatened the

06:07:14.350 --> 06:07:21.310
safety of my little skiff. I found the wind was northeast and must have driven me far from the

06:07:21.310 --> 06:07:27.370
coast from which I had embarked. I endeavored to change my course, but quickly found that if I

06:07:27.370 --> 06:07:33.730
again made the attempt the abode would instantly be filled with water. Thus situated, my only

06:07:33.730 --> 06:07:41.450
resource was to drive before the wind. I confess that I felt a few sensations of terror. I had no

06:07:41.450 --> 06:07:46.890
compass with me, and was so slenderly acquainted with the geography of this part of the world

06:07:46.890 --> 06:07:52.590
that the sun was of little benefit to me. I might be driven into the wild Atlantic

06:07:52.590 --> 06:07:58.710
and feel all the torches of starvation, or be swallowed up in the immeasurable waters that

06:07:58.710 --> 06:08:05.310
roared and buffeted around me. I had already been out many hours and felt the torment of a burning

06:08:05.310 --> 06:08:12.430
thirst, a prelude to my other sufferings. I looked upon the heavens which were covered by clouds that

06:08:12.430 --> 06:08:21.150
flew before the wind, only to be replaced by others. I looked upon the sea. It was to be my grave.

06:08:22.390 --> 06:08:31.290
Fiend! I exclaimed. Your task is already fulfilled. I thought of Elizabeth, of my father,

06:08:31.730 --> 06:08:38.430
and of Clairvaux, all left behind, on whom the monster might satisfy his sanctuary

06:08:38.430 --> 06:08:46.010
and merciless passions. This idea plunged me into a reverie so despairing and frightful

06:08:46.010 --> 06:08:53.210
that even now, when the scene is on the point of closing before me forever, I shudder to reflect on

06:08:53.210 --> 06:09:01.610
it. Some hours passed thus, but by degrees, as the sun declined towards the horizon,

06:09:01.610 --> 06:09:07.050
the wind died away into a gentle breeze and the sea became free from breakers.

06:09:08.090 --> 06:09:13.790
But these gave place to a heavy swell. I felt sick and hardly able to hold the rudder,

06:09:13.930 --> 06:09:20.850
when suddenly I saw a line of high land towards the south. Almost spent as I was,

06:09:21.190 --> 06:09:27.590
by fatigue and the dreadful suspense I had endured for several hours, this sudden certainty of life

06:09:27.590 --> 06:09:34.670
rushed like a flood of warm joy to my heart and tears gushed from my eyes. How mutable are our

06:09:34.670 --> 06:09:41.110
feelings and how strange it is that the clinging love we have of life, even in the excess of

06:09:41.110 --> 06:09:48.210
misery! I constructed another sail with a part of my dress and eagerly steered my course towards

06:09:48.210 --> 06:09:54.970
the land. It had a wild and rocky appearance, but as I approached nearer, I easily perceived

06:09:54.970 --> 06:10:01.970
traces of cultivation. I saw vessels near the shore and found myself suddenly transported

06:10:01.970 --> 06:10:08.270
back to the neighbourhood of civilised man. I carefully traced the windings of the land

06:10:08.270 --> 06:10:13.710
and hailed a steeple at which I at length saw issuing from behind a small promontory.

06:10:14.630 --> 06:10:21.470
As I was in a state of extreme debility, I resolved to sail towards the town as a place

06:10:21.470 --> 06:10:27.150
where I could most easily procure nourishment. Fortunately, I had money with me.

06:10:28.330 --> 06:10:34.970
As I turned the promontory, I perceived a small neat town and a good harbour which I entered,

06:10:35.430 --> 06:10:42.090
my heart bounding with joy at my unexpected escape. As I was occupied in fixing the boat

06:10:42.090 --> 06:10:48.670
and arranging the sails, several people crowded towards the spot. They seemed much surprised at

06:10:48.670 --> 06:10:55.550
my appearance, but instead of offering me any assistance, whispered together with gestures that

06:10:55.550 --> 06:11:00.770
at any other time might have produced in me a slight sensation of alarm.

06:11:01.590 --> 06:11:07.410
As it was, I merely remarked that they spoke English and I therefore addressed them in that

06:11:07.410 --> 06:11:14.770
language. My good friends, said I, will you be so kind as to tell me the name of this town

06:11:14.770 --> 06:11:22.230
and inform me where I am? You will know that soon enough, replied a man with a hoarse voice.

06:11:22.930 --> 06:11:26.870
Maybe you come to a place that will not prove much to your taste,

06:11:27.370 --> 06:11:31.410
but you will not be consulted as to your quarters, I promise you.

06:11:32.510 --> 06:11:38.990
I was exceedingly surprised on receiving so rude an answer from a stranger, and I was also

06:11:38.990 --> 06:11:44.110
disconcerted on the perceiving the frowning and angry countenances of his companions.

06:11:45.090 --> 06:11:51.590
Why do you answer me so roughly? I replied, surely it is not the custom of Englishmen to

06:11:51.590 --> 06:12:00.710
receive strangers so inhospitably. I do not know, said the man, what the custom of the English may be,

06:12:01.170 --> 06:12:07.910
but it is the custom of the Irish to hate villains. While this strange dialogue continued,

06:12:07.910 --> 06:12:15.410
I perceived the crowd rapidly increase. Their faces expressed a mixture of curiosity and anger,

06:12:16.090 --> 06:12:24.050
which annoyed and in some degree alarmed me. I inquired the way to the inn, but no one replied.

06:12:25.010 --> 06:12:31.750
I then moved forward and a murmuring sound arose from the crowd as they followed and surrounded me

06:12:31.750 --> 06:12:36.130
when an ill-looking man approaching tapped me on the shoulder and said,

06:12:36.690 --> 06:12:41.990
Come, sir, you must follow me to Mr. Kerwin's to give an account of yourself.

06:12:43.870 --> 06:12:50.170
Who is Mr. Kerwin? Why am I to give an account of myself? Is this not a free country?

06:12:51.530 --> 06:12:57.090
Aye, sir, free enough for honest folks. Mr. Kerwin is a magistrate,

06:12:57.510 --> 06:13:02.310
and you are to give an account of the death of a gentleman who was found murdered here last night.

06:13:03.430 --> 06:13:11.870
This answer startled me, but I presently recovered myself. I was innocent. That could easily be

06:13:11.870 --> 06:13:18.110
proved. Accordingly, I followed my conductor in silence and was led to one of the best houses in

06:13:18.110 --> 06:13:25.330
the town. I was ready to sink from fatigue and hunger, but being surrounded by a crowd,

06:13:25.910 --> 06:13:31.910
I thought it politic to rouse all my strength so that no physical debility might be construed into

06:13:31.910 --> 06:13:39.850
apprehension or conscious guilt. Little did I then expect the calamity that was in a few moments to

06:13:39.850 --> 06:13:48.890
overwhelm me and extinguish in horror and despair all fear of ignominy or death. I might pause here,

06:13:49.250 --> 06:13:55.410
for it requires all my fortitude to recall the memory of the frightful events which I am about

06:13:55.410 --> 06:13:59.250
to relate in proper detail to my recollection.

06:14:26.190 --> 06:14:30.590
I was soon introduced into the presence of the magistrate, an old benevolent man with

06:14:30.590 --> 06:14:35.970
calm and mild manners. He looked upon me, however, with some degree of severity, and

06:14:35.970 --> 06:14:42.490
then, turning towards my conductors, he asked to appear as witnesses on this occasion. About

06:14:42.490 --> 06:14:48.530
half a dozen men came forward, and, one being selected by the magistrate, he deposed that

06:14:48.530 --> 06:14:53.150
he had been out fishing the night before with his son and brother-in-law, Daniel Nugent,

06:14:53.590 --> 06:14:59.650
when, about ten o'clock, they observed a strong northerly blast rising, and they accordingly

06:14:59.650 --> 06:15:06.410
put in for port. It was a very dark night, as the moon had not yet risen. They did not land at the

06:15:06.410 --> 06:15:13.130
harbor, but, as they had been accustomed, at a creek about two miles below. He walked on first,

06:15:13.410 --> 06:15:19.050
carrying a part of the fishing tackle, and his companions followed him at some distance. As he

06:15:19.050 --> 06:15:23.970
was proceeding along the sands, he struck his foot against something and fell at his length on the

06:15:25.070 --> 06:15:30.170
His companions came up to assist him, and, by the light of their lantern, they found that he had

06:15:30.170 --> 06:15:36.990
fallen on the body of a man who was, to all appearance, dead. Their first supposition was

06:15:36.990 --> 06:15:42.050
that it was the corpse of some person who had been drowned and was thrown on shore by the waves,

06:15:42.070 --> 06:15:47.530
but, on examination, they found that the clothes were not wet and even that the body was not then

06:15:47.530 --> 06:15:53.410
cold. They instantly carried it to the cottage of an old woman near the spot and endeavored,

06:15:53.410 --> 06:16:00.170
but in vain, to restore it to life. It appeared to be a handsome young man about five and twenty

06:16:00.170 --> 06:16:06.470
years of age. He had apparently been strangled, for there was no sign of any violence except the

06:16:06.470 --> 06:16:13.350
black mark of fingers on his neck. The first part of this deposition did not in the least interest

06:16:13.350 --> 06:16:18.730
me, but when the mark of the fingers was mentioned, I remembered the murder of my brother and felt

06:16:18.730 --> 06:16:24.750
myself extremely agitated. My limbs trembled, and a mist came over my eyes, which obliged me

06:16:24.750 --> 06:16:30.170
to lean on a chair for support. The magistrate observed me with a keen eye and, of course,

06:16:30.270 --> 06:16:36.210
drew an unfavorable augury from my manner. The son confirmed his father's account,

06:16:36.470 --> 06:16:41.250
but when Daniel Nugent was called, he swore positively that just before the fall of his

06:16:41.250 --> 06:16:46.070
companion he saw a boat with a single man in it at a short distance from the shore,

06:16:46.070 --> 06:16:51.610
and as far as he could judge by the light of a few stars, it was the same boat in which I had just

06:16:51.610 --> 06:16:58.110
landed. A woman deposed that she lived near the beach and was standing at the door of her cottage,

06:16:58.530 --> 06:17:03.750
waiting for the return of the fisherman, about an hour before she heard of the discovery of the body,

06:17:04.050 --> 06:17:09.310
when she saw a boat with only one man in it push off from that part of the shore where the corpse

06:17:09.310 --> 06:17:15.210
was afterwards found. Another woman confirmed the account of the fisherman having brought the body

06:17:15.210 --> 06:17:21.390
into her house. It was not cold. They put it into a bed and rubbed it, and Daniel went to the town

06:17:21.390 --> 06:17:28.710
for an apothecary, but life was quite gone. Several other men were examined concerning my landing,

06:17:28.910 --> 06:17:34.290
and they agreed that, with the strong north wind that had arisen during the night, it was very

06:17:34.290 --> 06:17:39.290
probable that I had beaten about for many hours and had been obliged to return nearly to the same

06:17:39.290 --> 06:17:44.570
spot from which I had departed. Besides, they observed that it appeared that I had brought the

06:17:44.570 --> 06:17:49.870
body from another place, and it was likely that as I did not appear to know the shore, I might have

06:17:49.870 --> 06:17:54.770
put into the harbor, ignorant of the distance of the town of Blanc, from the place where I had

06:17:54.770 --> 06:18:02.090
deposited the corpse. Mr. Kerwin, on hearing this evidence, desired that I should be taken into the

06:18:02.090 --> 06:18:06.550
room where the body lay for interment, that it might be observed what effect the sight of it would

06:18:06.550 --> 06:18:12.950
produce upon me. This idea was probably suggested by the extreme agitation I had exhibited when the

06:18:12.950 --> 06:18:18.530
murder had been described. I was accordingly conducted by the magistrate and several other

06:18:18.530 --> 06:18:24.290
persons to the inn. I could not help being struck by the strange coincidences that had taken place

06:18:24.290 --> 06:18:29.410
during this eventful night, but, knowing that I had been conversing with several persons in the

06:18:29.410 --> 06:18:34.750
island I had inhabited about the time that the body had been found, I was perfectly tranquil as

06:18:34.750 --> 06:18:40.710
to the consequences of the affair. I entered the room where the corpse lay and was led up to the

06:18:40.710 --> 06:18:47.630
coffin. How can I describe my sensations on beholding it? I feel yet parched with horror,

06:18:47.950 --> 06:18:53.110
nor can I reflect on that terrible moment without shuddering and agony. The examination,

06:18:53.730 --> 06:18:58.310
the presence of the magistrate and witnesses, passed like a dream from my memory when I saw

06:18:58.310 --> 06:19:04.870
the lifeless form of Henry Clairvaux stretched before me. I gasped for breath, and throwing

06:19:04.870 --> 06:19:09.950
myself on the body, I exclaimed, Have my murderous machinations deprived you also,

06:19:09.950 --> 06:19:16.090
my dearest Henry, of life? Two I have already destroyed. Other victims await their destiny,

06:19:16.570 --> 06:19:24.350
but you, Clairvaux, my friend, my benefactor. The human frame could no longer support the agonies

06:19:24.350 --> 06:19:30.350
that I endured, and I was carried out of the room in strong convulsions. A fever succeeded to this.

06:19:30.770 --> 06:19:35.830
I lay for two months on the point of death. My ravings, as I afterward heard, were frightful.

06:19:35.830 --> 06:19:42.230
I called myself the murderer of William, of Justine, and of Clairvaux. Sometimes I entreated

06:19:42.230 --> 06:19:47.250
my attendants to assist me in the destruction of the fiend by whom I was tormented, and at others

06:19:47.250 --> 06:19:52.370
I felt the fingers of the monster already grasping my neck and screamed aloud with agony and terror.

06:19:53.610 --> 06:19:58.170
Fortunately, as I spoke my native language, Mr. Kerwin alone understood me,

06:19:58.330 --> 06:20:02.330
but my gestures and bitter cries were sufficient to affright the other witnesses.

06:20:03.330 --> 06:20:09.910
Why did I not die? More miserable than man ever was before, why did I not sink into forgetfulness

06:20:09.910 --> 06:20:15.630
and rest? Death snatches away many blooming children, the only hopes of their doting parents.

06:20:16.230 --> 06:20:19.870
How many brides and youthful lovers have been one day in the bloom of health and hope,

06:20:20.150 --> 06:20:25.970
and the next to pray for worms and the decay of the tomb? Of what materials was I made that I

06:20:25.970 --> 06:20:31.730
could thus resist so many shocks, which, like the turning of the wheel, continually renewed the

06:20:31.730 --> 06:20:38.630
torture? But I was doomed to live, and in two months found myself as awaking from a dream,

06:20:39.030 --> 06:20:45.130
in a prison, stretched on a wretched bed, surrounded by jailers, turnkeys, bolts, and all the

06:20:45.130 --> 06:20:51.210
miserable apparatus of a dungeon. It was morning, I remember, when I thus awoke to understanding.

06:20:52.190 --> 06:20:56.430
I had forgotten the particulars of what had happened, and only felt as if some great

06:20:56.430 --> 06:21:01.510
misfortune had suddenly overwhelmed me, but when I looked around and saw the barred windows and the

06:21:01.510 --> 06:21:06.890
swallowedness of the room in which I was, all flashed across my memory, and I groaned bitterly.

06:21:08.310 --> 06:21:13.130
This sound disturbed an old woman who was sleeping in a chair beside me. She was a

06:21:13.130 --> 06:21:18.710
hired nurse, the wife of one of the turnkeys, and her countenance expressed all those bad qualities

06:21:18.710 --> 06:21:25.150
which often characterized that class. The lines of her face were hard and rude, like that of

06:21:25.150 --> 06:21:31.370
persons accustomed to see without sympathizing in sights of misery. Her tone expressed her entire

06:21:31.370 --> 06:21:36.310
indifference. She addressed me in English, and the voice struck me as one that I had heard during

06:21:36.310 --> 06:21:44.190
my sufferings. Are you better now, sir? said she. I replied in the same language, with a feeble voice.

06:21:44.770 --> 06:21:50.710
I believe I am, but if it be all true, if indeed I did not dream, I am sorry that I am still alive

06:21:50.710 --> 06:21:57.710
to feel this misery and horror. For that matter, replied the old woman, if you mean about the

06:21:57.710 --> 06:22:02.150
gentleman you murdered, I believe that it were better for you if you were dead, for I fancy it

06:22:02.150 --> 06:22:07.630
will go hard with you. However, that's none of my business. I am sent to nurse you and get you well.

06:22:07.990 --> 06:22:11.910
I do my duty with a safe conscience. It were well if everybody did the same.

06:22:13.450 --> 06:22:18.390
I turned with loathing from the woman who could utter so unfeeling a speech to a person just saved

06:22:18.390 --> 06:22:23.370
on the very edge of death, but I felt languid and unable to reflect on all that had passed.

06:22:23.890 --> 06:22:28.830
The whole series of my life appeared to me as a dream. I sometimes doubted if indeed it were

06:22:28.830 --> 06:22:32.930
all true, for it never presented itself to my mind with the force of reality.

06:22:35.230 --> 06:22:40.630
As the images that floated before me became more distinct, I grew feverish. A darkness pressed

06:22:40.630 --> 06:22:46.630
around me. No one was near me who soothed me with a gentle voice of love. No dear hand supported me.

06:22:47.090 --> 06:22:51.510
The physician came and prescribed medicines, and the old woman prepared them for me,

06:22:51.510 --> 06:22:56.050
but utter carelessness was visible in the first, and the expression of brutality was

06:22:56.050 --> 06:23:01.030
strongly marked in the visage of the second. Who could be interested in the fate of a murderer

06:23:01.030 --> 06:23:07.370
but the hangman who would gain his fee? These were my first reflections, but I soon learned

06:23:07.370 --> 06:23:12.370
that Mr. Kerwin had shown me extreme kindness. He had caused the best room in the prison to be

06:23:12.370 --> 06:23:17.410
prepared for me. Richard indeed was the best, and it was he who had provided a physician and a nurse.

06:23:18.190 --> 06:23:22.970
It is true he seldom came to see me, for although he ardently desired to relieve

06:23:22.970 --> 06:23:27.150
the sufferings of every human creature, he did not wish to be present at the agonies

06:23:27.150 --> 06:23:32.230
and miserable ravings of a murderer. He came, therefore, sometimes to see that I was not

06:23:32.230 --> 06:23:38.190
neglected, but his visits were short and with long intervals. One day, while I was gradually

06:23:38.190 --> 06:23:43.710
recovering, I was seated in a chair, my eyes half open and my cheeks livid like those in death.

06:23:44.290 --> 06:23:48.870
I was overcome by gloom and misery, and often reflected I had better seek death

06:23:48.870 --> 06:23:53.010
than desire to remain in a world which to me was replete with wretchedness.

06:23:53.970 --> 06:23:59.010
At one time I considered whether I should not declare myself guilty and suffer the penalty of

06:23:59.010 --> 06:24:04.890
the law, less innocent than poor Justine had been. Such were my thoughts when the door of

06:24:04.890 --> 06:24:10.690
my apartment was opened and Mr. Kerwin entered. His countenance expressed sympathy and compassion.

06:24:10.690 --> 06:24:14.150
He drew a chair close to mine and addressed me in French.

06:24:14.910 --> 06:24:18.970
I fear that this place is very shocking to you. Can I do anything to make you more comfortable?

06:24:20.670 --> 06:24:23.730
I thank you, but all that you mention is nothing to me.

06:24:24.050 --> 06:24:27.130
On the whole earth there is no comfort which I am capable of receiving.

06:24:29.310 --> 06:24:33.250
I know that the sympathy of a stranger can be but of little relief to one born down as

06:24:33.250 --> 06:24:37.970
you are by so strange a misfortune. But you will, I hope, soon quit this melancholy abode,

06:24:37.970 --> 06:24:42.070
for doubtless evidence can easily be brought to free you from the criminal charge.

06:24:43.670 --> 06:24:49.310
That is my least concern. I am, by a course of strange events, become the most miserable of

06:24:49.310 --> 06:24:55.070
mortals. Persecuted and tortured as I am and have been, can death be any evil to me?

06:24:57.270 --> 06:25:01.110
Nothing indeed could be more unfortunate and agonizing than the strange chances that have

06:25:01.110 --> 06:25:06.350
lately occurred. You were thrown by some surprising accident on this shore, renowned for its

06:25:06.350 --> 06:25:11.370
vitality, seized immediately, and charged with murder. The first sight that was presented to

06:25:11.370 --> 06:25:16.210
your eyes was the body of your friend, murdered in so unaccountable a manner, and placed, as it

06:25:16.210 --> 06:25:23.090
were, by some fiend across your path. As Mr. Curwen said this, notwithstanding the agitation

06:25:23.090 --> 06:25:28.450
I endured on this retrospect of my sufferings, I also felt considerable surprise at the knowledge

06:25:28.450 --> 06:25:33.970
he seemed to possess concerning me. I suppose some astonishment was exhibited in my countenance,

06:25:33.970 --> 06:25:35.770
for Mr. Curwen hastened to say,

06:25:36.370 --> 06:25:40.670
Immediately upon your being taken ill, all the papers that were on your person were brought to

06:25:40.670 --> 06:25:45.490
me, and I examined them that I might discover some trace by which I could send to your relations in

06:25:45.490 --> 06:25:50.930
account of your misfortune and illness. I found several letters, and among others one which I

06:25:50.930 --> 06:25:55.950
discovered from its commencement to be from your father. I instantly wrote to Geneva. Nearly two

06:25:55.950 --> 06:26:00.870
months have elapsed since the departure of my letter. But you are ill. Even now you tremble.

06:26:00.870 --> 06:26:03.230
You are unfit for agitation of any kind.

06:26:05.510 --> 06:26:08.670
The suspense is a thousand times worse than the most horrible event.

06:26:09.190 --> 06:26:12.870
Tell me what new scene of death has been acted, and whose murderer I am now to lament.

06:26:14.590 --> 06:26:17.950
Your family is perfectly well, said Mr. Curwen, with gentleness.

06:26:18.570 --> 06:26:21.370
And someone, a friend, is come to visit you.

06:26:22.730 --> 06:26:27.750
I know not by what chain of thought the idea presented itself, but it instantly darted into

06:26:27.750 --> 06:26:32.750
my mind that the murderer had come to mock at my misery and taunt me with the death of Clairvaux,

06:26:33.210 --> 06:26:36.230
as a new incitement for me to comply with his hellish desires.

06:26:37.030 --> 06:26:39.710
I put my hand before my eyes and cried out in agony,

06:26:40.070 --> 06:26:44.490
Oh, take him away! I cannot see him! For God's sake, do not let him enter!

06:26:46.210 --> 06:26:50.150
Mr. Curwen regarded me with a troubled countenance. He could not help regarding

06:26:50.150 --> 06:26:53.970
my exclamation as a presumption of my guilt and said in rather a severe tone,

06:26:53.970 --> 06:26:57.790
I should have thought, young man, that the presence of your father would have been welcome

06:26:57.790 --> 06:27:00.190
instead of inspiring such violent repugnance.

06:27:01.430 --> 06:27:06.230
My father, cried I, while every feature and every muscle was relaxed from anguish to pleasure.

06:27:06.830 --> 06:27:12.830
Is my father indeed come? How kind, how very kind! But where is he? Why does he not hasten to me?

06:27:14.230 --> 06:27:17.170
My change of manner surprised and pleased the magistrate.

06:27:17.710 --> 06:27:21.510
Perhaps he thought that my former exclamation was a momentary return of delirium,

06:27:21.510 --> 06:27:24.450
and now he instantly resumed his former benevolence.

06:27:24.910 --> 06:27:29.070
He rose and quitted the room with my nurse, and in a moment my father entered it.

06:27:30.670 --> 06:27:35.110
Nothing at this moment could have given me greater pleasure than the arrival of my father.

06:27:35.830 --> 06:27:40.790
I stretched out my hand to him and cried, Are you then safe at Elizabeth and Ernest?

06:27:41.810 --> 06:27:46.170
My father calmed me with assurances of their welfare and endeavoured by dwelling on these

06:27:46.170 --> 06:27:51.430
subjects so interesting to my heart to raise my desponding spirits. But he soon felt that a

06:27:51.430 --> 06:27:56.970
prison cannot be the abode of cheerfulness. What a place is this that you inhabit, my son,

06:27:57.070 --> 06:28:01.210
said he, looking mournfully at the barred windows and wretched appearance of the room.

06:28:01.830 --> 06:28:06.470
You travel to seek happiness, but a fatality seems to pursue you. And poor Clairvaux!

06:28:07.690 --> 06:28:12.470
The name of my unfortunate and murdered friend was an agitation too great to be endured in my weak

06:28:12.470 --> 06:28:20.030
state. I shed tears. Alas, yes, my father, replied I. Some destiny of the most horrible kind hangs

06:28:20.030 --> 06:28:24.790
over me, and I must live to fulfil it, or surely I should have died on the coffin of Henry.

06:28:26.710 --> 06:28:31.590
We were not allowed to converse for any length of time, for the precarious state of my health

06:28:31.590 --> 06:28:37.450
rendered every precaution necessary that could ensure tranquillity. Mr. Kerwin came in and

06:28:37.450 --> 06:28:42.230
insisted that my strength should not be exhausted by too much exertion, but the appearance of my

06:28:42.230 --> 06:28:49.150
father was to me like that of my good angel, and I gradually recovered my health. As my sickness

06:28:49.150 --> 06:28:54.290
quitted me, I was absorbed by a gloomy and black melancholy that nothing could dissipate.

06:28:54.950 --> 06:29:01.450
The image of Clairvaux was forever before me, ghastly and murdered. More than once the agitation

06:29:01.450 --> 06:29:06.430
into which these reflections threw me made my friends dread a dangerous relapse. Alas,

06:29:06.670 --> 06:29:11.630
why did they preserve so miserable and detested a life? It was surely that I might fulfil my

06:29:11.630 --> 06:29:18.430
destiny, which is now drawing to a close. Soon, oh very soon, will death extinguish these throbbings

06:29:18.430 --> 06:29:23.670
and relieve me from the mighty weight of anguish that bears me to the dust, and in executing the

06:29:23.670 --> 06:29:29.730
award of justice I shall also sink to rest. Then the appearance of death was distant,

06:29:30.090 --> 06:29:34.590
although the wish was ever present to my thoughts, and I often sat for hours motionless

06:29:34.590 --> 06:29:39.830
and speechless, wishing for some mighty revolution that might bury me and my destroyer in its ruins.

06:29:41.450 --> 06:29:46.370
The season of the assesies approached. I had already been three months in prison,

06:29:46.370 --> 06:29:51.710
and although I was still weak and in continual danger of a relapse, I was obliged to travel

06:29:51.710 --> 06:29:57.670
nearly a hundred miles to the country town where the court was held. Mr. Kerwin charged himself

06:29:57.670 --> 06:30:02.930
with every care of collecting witnesses and arranging my defence. I was spared the disgrace

06:30:02.930 --> 06:30:07.670
of appearing publicly as a criminal, as the case was not brought before the court that decides on

06:30:07.670 --> 06:30:13.210
life and death. The grand jury rejected the bill, on its being proved that I was on the Orkney

06:30:13.210 --> 06:30:17.830
Islands at the hour the body of my friend was found, and a fortnight after my removal

06:30:17.830 --> 06:30:24.190
I was liberated from prison. My father was enraptured on finding me freed from the vexations

06:30:24.190 --> 06:30:28.730
of a criminal charge, that I was again allowed to breathe the fresh atmosphere and permitted

06:30:28.730 --> 06:30:34.290
to return to my native country. I did not participate in these feelings, for to me the

06:30:34.290 --> 06:30:41.510
walls of a dungeon or a palace were alike hateful. The cup of life was poisoned forever, and although

06:30:41.510 --> 06:30:47.470
the sun shone upon me, as upon the happy and gay of heart, I saw around me nothing but a dense and

06:30:47.470 --> 06:30:52.800
frightful darkness, penetrated by no light but the glimmer of two eyes that glared upon me.

06:30:53.990 --> 06:30:59.770
Sometimes they were the expressive eyes of Henry, languishing in death, the dark orbs nearly covered

06:30:59.770 --> 06:31:05.170
by the lids and the long black lashes that fringed them. Sometimes it was the watery,

06:31:05.410 --> 06:31:10.210
clouded eyes of the monster as I first saw them in my chamber at Ingolstadt.

06:31:11.830 --> 06:31:17.470
My father tried to awaken in me the feelings of affection. He talked of Geneva, which I should

06:31:17.470 --> 06:31:24.410
soon visit, of Elizabeth and Ernest, but these words only drew deep groans from me. Sometimes,

06:31:24.430 --> 06:31:29.210
indeed, I felt a wish for happiness, and thought with melancholy delight of my beloved cousin,

06:31:29.530 --> 06:31:36.130
or longed, with a devouring malady du pays, to see once more the blue lake and rapid roan

06:31:36.130 --> 06:31:41.230
that had been so dear to me in early childhood. But my general state of feeling was a torpor

06:31:41.230 --> 06:31:46.810
in which a prison was as welcome a residence as the divinest scene in nature, and these fits were

06:31:46.810 --> 06:31:53.170
seldom interrupted but by paroxysms of anguish and despair. At these moments I often endeavored to

06:31:53.170 --> 06:31:58.170
put an end to the existence I loathed, and it required unceasing attendance and vigilance to

06:31:58.170 --> 06:32:04.050
restrain me from committing some dreadful act of violence. Yet one duty remained to me, the

06:32:04.050 --> 06:32:09.070
recollection of which finally triumphed over my selfish despair. It was necessary that I should

06:32:09.070 --> 06:32:14.070
return without delay to Geneva, there to watch over the lives of those I so fondly loved,

06:32:14.350 --> 06:32:19.030
and to lie in wait for the murderer, that if any chance led me to the place of his concealment,

06:32:19.250 --> 06:32:25.350
or if he dared again to blast me by his presence, I might, with unfailing aim, put an end to the

06:32:25.350 --> 06:32:30.710
existence of the monstrous image which I had endued with the mockery of a soul still more

06:32:30.710 --> 06:32:37.430
monstrous. My father still desired to delay our departure, fearful that I could not sustain the

06:32:37.430 --> 06:32:42.610
teagues of a journey, for I was a shattered wreck, the shadow of a human being. My strength

06:32:42.610 --> 06:32:48.150
was gone, I was a mere skeleton, and fever night and day preyed upon my wasted frame.

06:32:49.150 --> 06:32:53.330
Still, as I urged our leaving Ireland with such inquietude and impatience,

06:32:53.670 --> 06:32:58.810
my father thought it best to yield. We took our passage on board a vessel bound for Havre de

06:32:58.810 --> 06:33:05.030
Grasse, and sailed with a fair wind from the Irish shores. It was midnight. I lay on the deck

06:33:05.030 --> 06:33:09.610
looking at the stars and listening to the dashing of the waves. I hailed the darkness

06:33:09.610 --> 06:33:14.630
that shut Ireland from my sight, and my pulse beat with a feverish joy when I reflected that

06:33:14.630 --> 06:33:19.770
I should soon see Geneva. The past appeared to me in the light of a frightful dream,

06:33:20.350 --> 06:33:24.690
yet the vessel in which I was, the wind that blew me from the detested shore of Ireland,

06:33:25.110 --> 06:33:29.430
and the sea which surrounded me told me too forcibly that I was deceived by no vision,

06:33:29.670 --> 06:33:34.370
and that Clairvaux, my friend and dearest companion, had fallen a victim to me and the

06:33:34.370 --> 06:33:40.790
monster of my creation. I re-passed in my memory my whole life, my quiet happiness while residing

06:33:40.790 --> 06:33:46.950
with my family in Geneva, the death of my mother, and my departure for Ingolstadt. I remembered,

06:33:47.170 --> 06:33:51.730
shuddering, the mad enthusiasm that hurried me on to the creation of my hideous enemy,

06:33:52.070 --> 06:33:57.930
and I called to mind the night in which he first lived. I was unable to pursue the train of thought.

06:33:57.930 --> 06:34:04.350
A thousand feelings pressed upon me, and I wept bitterly. Ever since my recovery from the fever

06:34:04.350 --> 06:34:08.650
I had been in the custom of taking every night a small quantity of laudanum,

06:34:08.790 --> 06:34:13.110
for it was by means of this drug only that I was enabled to gain the rest necessary for

06:34:13.110 --> 06:34:17.730
the preservation of life. Oppressed by the recollection of my various misfortunes,

06:34:18.030 --> 06:34:21.850
I now swallowed double my usual quantity, and soon slept profoundly.

06:34:22.570 --> 06:34:25.690
But sleep did not afford me respite from thought and misery.

06:34:26.250 --> 06:34:29.180
My dreams presented a thousand objects that scared me.

06:34:30.210 --> 06:34:35.450
Towards morning I was possessed by a kind of nightmare. I felt the fiend's grasp in my neck

06:34:35.450 --> 06:34:42.470
and could not free myself from it. Groans and cries rang in my ears. My father, who was watching over

06:34:42.470 --> 06:34:48.510
me, perceiving my restlessness, awoke me. The dashing waves were around, the cloudy sky above,

06:34:48.510 --> 06:34:54.370
the fiend was not here. A sense of security, a feeling that a truce was established between

06:34:54.370 --> 06:35:00.050
the present hour and the irresistible disastrous future, imparted to me a kind of calm forgetfulness

06:35:00.050 --> 06:35:04.230
of which the human mind is by its structure peculiarly susceptible.

06:35:07.790 --> 06:35:14.250
The voyage came to an end. We landed and proceeded to Paris.

06:35:14.970 --> 06:35:19.810
I soon found that I had overtaxed my strength and that I must repose before I could continue

06:35:19.810 --> 06:35:26.390
my journey. My father's care and attentions were indefatigable, but he did not know the origin of

06:35:26.390 --> 06:35:32.370
my sufferings and sought erroneous methods to remedy the incurable ill. He wished me to seek

06:35:32.370 --> 06:35:39.530
amusement in society. I abhorred the face of man. Oh, not abhorred! They were my brethren,

06:35:39.530 --> 06:35:45.190
my fellow beings, and I felt attracted to even the most repulsive among them as to creatures of an

06:35:45.190 --> 06:35:50.490
angelic nature and celestial mechanism. But I felt that I had no right to share their intercourse.

06:35:51.150 --> 06:35:56.710
I had unchained an enemy among them whose joy it was to shed their blood and to revel in their

06:35:56.710 --> 06:36:02.210
groans. How they would each and all abhor me and hunt me from the world did they know my

06:36:02.210 --> 06:36:08.910
unhallowed acts and the crimes which had their source in me. My father yielded at length to my

06:36:08.910 --> 06:36:15.490
desire to avoid society and strove by various arguments to banish my despair. Sometimes he

06:36:15.490 --> 06:36:19.490
thought that I felt deeply the degradation of being obliged to answer a charge of murder,

06:36:19.630 --> 06:36:27.050
and he endeavored to prove to me the futility of pride. Alas, my father, said I, how little do you

06:36:27.050 --> 06:36:32.990
know me? Human beings, their feelings and passions would indeed be degraded if such a wretch as I

06:36:32.990 --> 06:36:39.290
pride. Justine, poor unhappy Justine, was as innocent as I, and she suffered the same charge.

06:36:39.630 --> 06:36:45.290
She died for it, and I am the cause of this. I murdered her. William, Justine, and Henry,

06:36:45.530 --> 06:36:52.970
they all died by my hands. My father had often, during my imprisonment, heard me make the same

06:36:52.970 --> 06:36:58.010
assertion. When I thus accused myself, he sometimes seemed to desire an explanation,

06:36:58.010 --> 06:37:03.410
and at others he appeared to consider it as the offspring of delirium, and that, during my illness,

06:37:03.850 --> 06:37:09.370
some idea of this kind had presented itself to my imagination, the remembrance of which I preserved

06:37:09.370 --> 06:37:16.270
in my convalescence. I avoided explanation and maintained a continual silence concerning the

06:37:16.270 --> 06:37:22.070
wretch I had created. I had a persuasion that I should be supposed mad, and this in itself would

06:37:22.070 --> 06:37:28.310
forever have chained my tongue. But, besides, I could not bring myself to disclose a secret

06:37:28.310 --> 06:37:33.950
which would fill my hearer with consternation, and make fear and unnatural horror the inmates

06:37:33.950 --> 06:37:40.550
of his breast. I checked, therefore, my impatient thirst for sympathy, and was silent when I would

06:37:40.550 --> 06:37:46.590
have given the world to have confided the fatal secret. Yet still words like those I have recorded

06:37:47.570 --> 06:37:53.330
uncontrollably from me. I could offer no explanation of them, but their truth in part relieved the

06:37:53.330 --> 06:37:59.310
burden of my mysterious woe. Upon this occasion, my father said, with an expression of unbounded

06:37:59.310 --> 06:38:05.170
wonder, My dearest Victor, what infatuation is this? My dear son, I entreat you never to

06:38:05.170 --> 06:38:12.050
make such an assertion again. I am not mad, I cried energetically. The sun and the heavens

06:38:12.050 --> 06:38:16.950
which have viewed my operations can bear witness of my truth. I am the assassin of those most

06:38:16.950 --> 06:38:22.490
innocent victims. They died by my machinations. A thousand times would I have shed my own blood,

06:38:22.630 --> 06:38:27.810
drop by drop, to have saved their lives. But I could not, my father. Indeed, I could not sacrifice

06:38:27.810 --> 06:38:34.170
the whole human race. The conclusion of this speech convinced my father that my ideas were

06:38:34.170 --> 06:38:38.510
deranged, and he instantly changed the subject of our conversation and endeavored to alter the

06:38:38.510 --> 06:38:43.590
my thoughts. He wished as much as possible to obliterate the memory of the scenes that

06:38:43.590 --> 06:38:48.710
had taken place in Ireland, and never alluded to them or suffered me to speak of my misfortunes.

06:38:51.170 --> 06:38:57.010
As time passed away, I became more calm. Misery had her dwelling in my heart, but I no longer

06:38:57.010 --> 06:39:02.210
talked in the same incoherent manner of my own crimes. Sufficient for me was the consciousness

06:39:02.210 --> 06:39:08.350
of them. By the utmost self-violence, I curbed the imperious voice of wretchedness, which sometimes

06:39:08.350 --> 06:39:12.810
desired to declare itself to the whole world, and my manners were calmer and more composed

06:39:12.810 --> 06:39:18.370
than they had ever been since my journey to the Sea of Ice. A few days before we left Paris on

06:39:18.370 --> 06:39:21.830
our way to Switzerland, I received the following letter from Elizabeth.

06:39:24.050 --> 06:39:29.090
My dear friend, it gave me the greatest pleasure to receive a letter from my uncle dated at Paris.

06:39:29.450 --> 06:39:33.910
You are no longer at a formidable distance, and I may hope to see you in less than a fortnight.

06:39:33.910 --> 06:39:39.190
My poor cousin, how much you must have suffered! I expect to see you looking even more ill than

06:39:39.190 --> 06:39:44.130
when you quitted Geneva. This winter has been passed most miserably, tortured as I have been

06:39:44.130 --> 06:39:48.770
by anxious suspense, yet I hope to see peace in your countenance and to find that your heart

06:39:48.770 --> 06:39:54.790
is not totally void of comfort and tranquility. Yet I fear that the same feelings now exist that

06:39:54.790 --> 06:40:00.470
made you so miserable a year ago, even perhaps augmented by time. I would not disturb you at

06:40:00.470 --> 06:40:05.510
period when so many misfortunes weigh upon you, but a conversation that I had with my uncle

06:40:05.510 --> 06:40:11.530
previous to his departure renders some explanation necessary before we meet. Explanation? You may

06:40:11.530 --> 06:40:17.310
possibly say, what can Elizabeth have to explain? If you really say this, my questions are answered

06:40:17.310 --> 06:40:22.370
and all my doubts satisfied. But you are distant from me, and it is possible that you may dread

06:40:22.370 --> 06:40:27.750
and yet be pleased with this explanation. And in a probability of this being the case, I dare not

06:40:27.750 --> 06:40:32.770
any longer postpone writing what, during your absence, I have often wished to express to you,

06:40:32.850 --> 06:40:38.610
but have never had the courage to begin. You well know, Victor, that our union had been the

06:40:38.610 --> 06:40:43.410
favorite plan of your parents ever since our infancy. We were told this when young and taught

06:40:43.410 --> 06:40:48.430
to look forward to it as an event that would certainly take place. We were affectionate playfellows

06:40:48.430 --> 06:40:54.450
during childhood and, I believe, dear and valued friends to one another as we grew older. But as

06:40:54.450 --> 06:40:58.310
brother and sister often entertain a lively affection towards each other without desiring a

06:40:58.310 --> 06:41:05.030
more intimate union, may not such also be our case? Tell me, dearest Victor. Answer me. I

06:41:05.030 --> 06:41:11.310
conjure you by our mutual happiness with simple truth. Do you not love another? You have traveled,

06:41:11.470 --> 06:41:15.350
you have spent several years of your life at Ingolstadt, and I confess to you, my friend,

06:41:15.370 --> 06:41:20.290
that when I saw you last autumn so unhappy, flying to solitude from the society of every creature,

06:41:20.290 --> 06:41:25.130
I could not help supposing that you might regret our connection and believe yourself bound in honor

06:41:25.130 --> 06:41:29.870
to fulfill the wishes of your parents, although they opposed themselves to your inclinations.

06:41:30.430 --> 06:41:35.570
But this is false reasoning. I confess to you, my friend, that I love you and that in my airy

06:41:35.570 --> 06:41:40.910
dreams of futurity you have been my constant friend and companion. But it is your happiness

06:41:40.910 --> 06:41:45.570
I desire as well as my own when I declared to you that our marriage would render me eternally

06:41:45.570 --> 06:41:51.350
miserable unless it were the dictate of your own free choice. Even now I weep to think that,

06:41:51.450 --> 06:41:57.490
born down as you are by the cruelest misfortunes, you may stifle, by the word honor, all hope of

06:41:57.490 --> 06:42:03.290
that love and happiness which would alone restore you to yourself. I, who have so disinterested

06:42:03.290 --> 06:42:08.050
in affection for you, may increase your miseries tenfold by being an obstacle to your wishes.

06:42:08.870 --> 06:42:13.630
Ah, Victor, be assured that your cousin and playmate has too sincere a love for you

06:42:13.630 --> 06:42:19.530
not to be made miserable by this supposition. Be happy, my friend, and if you obey me in this

06:42:19.530 --> 06:42:24.430
one request, remain satisfied that nothing on earth will have the power to interrupt my tranquility.

06:42:25.410 --> 06:42:30.630
Do not let this letter disturb you. Do not answer tomorrow or the next day or even until you come

06:42:30.630 --> 06:42:35.850
if it will give you pain. My uncle will send me news of your health, and if I see but one

06:42:35.850 --> 06:42:41.090
smile on your lips when we meet, occasioned by this or any other exertion of mine, I shall need

06:42:41.090 --> 06:42:47.810
no other happiness. Elizabeth Levenza, Geneva, May 18th, 17 blank.

06:42:50.970 --> 06:42:55.770
This letter revived in my memory what I had before forgotten, the threat of the fiend.

06:42:56.370 --> 06:43:02.430
I will be with you on your wedding night. Such was my sentence, and on that night would the

06:43:02.430 --> 06:43:07.190
demon employ every art to destroy me and tear me from the glimpse of happiness which promised

06:43:07.190 --> 06:43:13.750
partly to console my sufferings. On that night he determined to consummate his crimes by my death.

06:43:14.990 --> 06:43:20.670
Well, be it so. A deadly struggle would then assuredly take place in which if he were victorious

06:43:20.670 --> 06:43:27.170
I should be at peace and his power over me be at an end. If he were vanquished I should be a free man.

06:43:27.950 --> 06:43:33.410
Alas, what freedom! Such as the peasant enjoys when his family have been massacred before his

06:43:33.410 --> 06:43:39.910
cottage burnt, his lands laid waste, and he is turned adrift, homeless, penniless, and alone,

06:43:40.230 --> 06:43:45.470
but free. Such would be my liberty, except that in my Elizabeth I possessed a treasure,

06:43:45.850 --> 06:43:50.650
alas, balanced by those horrors of remorse and guilt which would pursue me until death.

06:43:52.790 --> 06:43:58.010
Sweet and beloved Elizabeth, I read and re-read her letter, and some softened feelings stole into

06:43:58.010 --> 06:44:04.750
my heart, and dared to whisper paradisiacal dreams of love and joy. But the apple was already eaten,

06:44:05.050 --> 06:44:10.850
and the angel's arm bared to drive me from all hope. Yet I would die to make her happy.

06:44:11.510 --> 06:44:17.570
If the monster executed his threat, death was inevitable. Yet, again, I considered whether my

06:44:17.570 --> 06:44:22.570
marriage would hasten my fate. My destruction might indeed arrive a few months sooner,

06:44:22.650 --> 06:44:27.330
but if my torturer should suspect that I postponed it, influenced by his menaces,

06:44:27.330 --> 06:44:31.170
he would surely find other and perhaps more dreadful means of revenge.

06:44:32.510 --> 06:44:37.510
He had vowed to be with me on my wedding night, yet he did not consider that threat as binding

06:44:37.510 --> 06:44:42.490
him to peace in the meantime, for as if to show me that he was not yet satiated with blood,

06:44:42.890 --> 06:44:46.770
he had murdered Clairvaux immediately after the enunciation of his threats.

06:44:48.230 --> 06:44:54.230
I resolved, therefore, that if my immediate union with my cousin would conduce either to hers or my

06:44:54.230 --> 06:45:00.350
father's happiness, my adversary's designs against my life should not retard it a single hour.

06:45:02.330 --> 06:45:07.450
In this state of mind I wrote to Elizabeth. My letter was calm and affectionate.

06:45:08.210 --> 06:45:13.250
I fear, my beloved girl, I said, little happiness remains for us on earth.

06:45:13.730 --> 06:45:20.050
Yet all that I may one day enjoy is centered in you. Chase away your idle fears. To you alone do

06:45:20.050 --> 06:45:25.270
I consecrate my life and my endeavors for contentment. I have one secret, Elizabeth,

06:45:25.810 --> 06:45:31.330
a dreadful one. When revealed to you, it will chill your frame with horror, and then, far from

06:45:31.330 --> 06:45:35.570
being surprised at my misery, you will only wonder that I survive what I have endured.

06:45:36.250 --> 06:45:41.350
I will confide this tale of misery and terror to you the day after our marriage shall take place.

06:45:41.770 --> 06:45:45.610
For, my sweet cousin, there must be perfect confidence between us.

06:45:45.610 --> 06:45:50.550
But until then, I conjure you, do not mention or allude to it.

06:45:50.850 --> 06:45:53.790
This I most earnestly entreat, and I know you will comply.

06:45:57.210 --> 06:46:01.610
In about a week after the arrival of Elizabeth's letter we returned to Geneva.

06:46:02.510 --> 06:46:07.330
The sweet girl welcomed me with warm affection, yet tears were in her eyes as she beheld my

06:46:07.330 --> 06:46:13.790
emaciated frame and feverish cheeks. I saw a change in her also. She was thinner and had lost

06:46:13.790 --> 06:46:18.650
much of that heavenly vivacity that had before charmed me, but her gentleness and soft looks of

06:46:18.650 --> 06:46:23.170
compassion made her a more fit companion for one blasted and miserable as I was.

06:46:24.130 --> 06:46:29.430
The tranquility which I now enjoy did not endure. Memory brought madness with it,

06:46:29.550 --> 06:46:34.950
and when I thought of what had passed a real insanity possessed me. Sometimes I was furious

06:46:34.950 --> 06:46:42.070
and burnt with rage, sometimes low and despondent. I neither spoke nor looked at anyone, but sat

06:46:42.070 --> 06:46:45.410
motionless, bewildered by the multitude of miseries that overcame me.

06:46:47.930 --> 06:46:52.730
Elizabeth alone had the power to draw me from these fits. Her gentle voice would soothe me

06:46:52.730 --> 06:46:56.850
when transported by passion and inspire me with human feelings when sunk in torpor.

06:46:57.870 --> 06:47:04.330
She wept with me and for me. When reason returned she would remonstrate and endeavor to inspire me

06:47:04.330 --> 06:47:10.970
with resignation. Ah, it is well for the unfortunate to be resigned, but for the guilty there is no

06:47:10.970 --> 06:47:16.990
peace. The agonies of remorse poison the luxury that is otherwise sometimes found in indulging

06:47:16.990 --> 06:47:23.110
the excess of grief. Soon after my arrival my father spoke of my immediate marriage with

06:47:23.110 --> 06:47:32.190
Elizabeth. I remained silent. Have you then some other attachment? None on earth. I love

06:47:32.190 --> 06:47:37.090
Elizabeth and look forward to our union with delight. Let the day therefore be fixed and on

06:47:37.090 --> 06:47:41.090
it I will consecrate myself in life or death to the happiness of my cousin.

06:47:43.070 --> 06:47:47.850
My dear Victor, do not speak thus. Heavy misfortunes have befallen us, but let us

06:47:47.850 --> 06:47:52.630
only cling closer to what remains and transfer our love for those whom we have lost to those who yet

06:47:52.630 --> 06:47:58.350
live. Our circle will be small but bound close by the ties of affection and mutual misfortune,

06:47:58.430 --> 06:48:03.530
and when time shall have softened your despair new and dear objects of care will be born

06:48:03.530 --> 06:48:06.570
to replace those of whom we have been so cruelly deprived.

06:48:08.590 --> 06:48:13.030
Such were the lessons of my father, but to me the remembrance of the threat returned.

06:48:13.650 --> 06:48:18.110
Nor can you wonder that, omnipotent as the fiend had yet been in his deeds of blood,

06:48:18.530 --> 06:48:22.870
I should almost regard him as invincible, and that when he had pronounced the words

06:48:22.870 --> 06:48:28.530
I shall be with you on your wedding night I should regard the threatened fate as unavoidable.

06:48:29.270 --> 06:48:33.510
But death was no evil to me if the laws of Elizabeth were balanced with it,

06:48:33.830 --> 06:48:38.430
and I therefore with a contented and even cheerful countenance agreed with my father

06:48:38.430 --> 06:48:42.450
that if my cousin would consent the ceremony should take place in ten days,

06:48:42.990 --> 06:48:46.230
and thus put, as I imagined, the seal to my fate.

06:48:48.130 --> 06:48:52.790
Great God, if for one instant I had thought what might be the hellish intention of my fiendish

06:48:52.790 --> 06:48:58.270
adversary I would rather have banished myself forever from my native country and wandered a

06:48:58.270 --> 06:49:04.290
cast over the earth than have consented to this miserable marriage. But, as if possessed of magic

06:49:04.290 --> 06:49:09.510
powers, the monster had blinded me to his real intentions, and when I thought that I had prepared

06:49:09.510 --> 06:49:17.270
only my own death I hastened that of a far dearer victim. As the period fixed for our marriage drew

06:49:17.270 --> 06:49:23.630
nearer, whether from cowardice or a prophetic feeling, I felt my heart sink within me. But I

06:49:23.630 --> 06:49:27.970
concealed my feelings by an appearance of hilarity that brought smiles and joy to the countenance of

06:49:27.970 --> 06:49:32.930
my father, but hardly deceived the ever watchful and nicer eye of Elizabeth.

06:49:35.370 --> 06:49:39.730
She looked forward to our union with placid contentment, not unmingled with a little fear,

06:49:40.070 --> 06:49:44.990
which past misfortunes had impressed that what now appeared certain and tangible happiness might

06:49:44.990 --> 06:49:49.830
soon dissipate into an airy dream and leave no trace but deep and everlasting regret.

06:49:51.290 --> 06:49:55.430
Preparations were made for the event, congratulatory visits were received,

06:49:55.430 --> 06:50:01.310
and all wore a smiling appearance. I shut up, as well as I could, in my own heart,

06:50:01.690 --> 06:50:07.230
the anxiety that prayed there, and entered with seeming earnestness into the plans of my father,

06:50:07.590 --> 06:50:10.630
although they might only serve as the decorations of my tragedy.

06:50:12.090 --> 06:50:16.170
Through my father's exertions a part of the inheritance of Elizabeth had been restored to

06:50:16.170 --> 06:50:24.990
her by the Austrian government. A small possession on the shores of Como belonged to her. It was

06:50:24.990 --> 06:50:30.410
to spend our first days of happiness beside the beautiful lake near which it stood.

06:50:32.070 --> 06:50:36.270
In the meantime, I took every precaution to defend my person in case the fiend should

06:50:36.270 --> 06:50:42.710
openly attack me. I carried pistols and a dagger constantly about me and was ever on the watch to

06:50:42.710 --> 06:50:49.570
prevent artifice, and by these means gained a greater degree of tranquility. Indeed, as the

06:50:49.570 --> 06:50:54.830
period approached, the threat appeared more as a delusion, not to be regarded as worthy to disturb

06:50:54.830 --> 06:51:00.610
my peace, while the happiness I hoped for in my marriage wore a greater appearance of certainty as

06:51:00.610 --> 06:51:05.630
the day fixed for its solemnization drew nearer, and I heard it continually spoken of as an

06:51:05.630 --> 06:51:12.790
occurrence which no accident could possibly prevent. Elizabeth seemed happy. My tranquil demeanor

06:51:12.790 --> 06:51:18.450
contributed greatly to calm her mind. But on the day that was to fulfill my wishes and my destiny

06:51:18.450 --> 06:51:24.290
she was melancholy, and a presentiment of evil pervaded her. And perhaps also she thought of

06:51:24.290 --> 06:51:27.790
the dreadful secret which I had promised to reveal to her on the following day.

06:51:28.890 --> 06:51:32.710
My father was in the meantime overjoyed and in the bustle of preparation

06:51:32.710 --> 06:51:36.910
only recognized in the melancholy of his niece the diffidence of a bride.

06:51:38.890 --> 06:51:43.710
After the ceremony was performed a large party assembled at my father's, but it was agreed that

06:51:43.710 --> 06:51:49.010
Elizabeth and I should commence our journey by water, sleeping that night at Evian and continuing

06:51:49.010 --> 06:51:55.930
our voyage on the following day. The day was fair, the wind favorable, all smiled on our nuptial

06:51:55.930 --> 06:52:03.270
embarkation. Those were the last moments of my life during which I enjoyed the feeling of happiness.

06:52:04.110 --> 06:52:09.970
We passed rapidly along, the sun was hot, but we were sheltered from its rays by a kind of canopy,

06:52:10.390 --> 06:52:15.250
while we enjoyed the beauty of the scene, sometimes on one side of the lake, where we saw Mount

06:52:15.250 --> 06:52:20.530
Salève, the pleasant banks of Mont-Alegre, and at a distance surmounting all, the beautiful

06:52:20.530 --> 06:52:26.050
Mont Blanc and the assemblage of snowy mountains that in vain endeavored to emulate her. Sometimes

06:52:26.050 --> 06:52:30.950
coasting the opposite banks we saw the mighty Jura opposing its dark side to the ambition that

06:52:30.950 --> 06:52:35.630
would quit its native country, and an almost insurmountable barrier to the invader who should

06:52:35.630 --> 06:52:43.550
wish to enslave it. I took the hand of Elizabeth. You are sorrowful, my love. Ah, if you knew what

06:52:43.550 --> 06:52:47.710
I have suffered and what I may yet endure, you would endeavor to let me taste the quiet and

06:52:47.710 --> 06:52:53.810
freedom from despair that this one day at least permits me to enjoy. Be happy, my dear Victor,

06:52:54.110 --> 06:52:59.650
replied Elizabeth. There is, I hope, nothing to distress you, and be assured that if a lively joy

06:52:59.650 --> 06:53:05.810
is not painted in my face, my heart is contented. Something whispers to me not to depend too much

06:53:05.810 --> 06:53:11.590
on the prospect that is opened before us, but I will not listen to such a sinister voice. Observe

06:53:11.590 --> 06:53:16.590
how fast we move along, and how the clouds, which sometimes obscure and sometimes rise above the

06:53:16.590 --> 06:53:21.590
dome of Mont Blanc, render this scene of beauty still more interesting. Look also at the

06:53:21.590 --> 06:53:25.750
innumerable fish that are swimming in the clear waters, where we can distinguish every pebble

06:53:25.750 --> 06:53:31.330
that lies at the bottom. What a divine day! How happy and serene all nature appears!

06:53:33.250 --> 06:53:38.290
Thus Elizabeth endeavored to divert her thoughts and mind from all reflection upon melancholy

06:53:38.290 --> 06:53:43.570
subjects. But her temper was fluctuating, joy for a few instants shown in her eyes,

06:53:43.730 --> 06:53:47.010
but it continually gave place to distraction and reverie.

06:53:48.470 --> 06:53:54.110
The sun sank lower in the heavens. We passed the river Drance and observed its path through the

06:53:54.110 --> 06:53:59.790
chasms of the higher and the glens of the lower hills. The Alps here come closer to the lake,

06:53:59.870 --> 06:54:03.970
and we approached the amphitheater of mountains which formed its eastern boundary.

06:54:04.790 --> 06:54:09.730
The spire of Evian shone under the woods that surrounded it and the range of mountain above

06:54:09.730 --> 06:54:16.070
mountain by which it was overhung. The wind, which had hitherto carried us along with amazing

06:54:16.070 --> 06:54:22.510
rapidity, sank at sunset to a light breeze. The soft air just ruffled the water and caused a

06:54:22.510 --> 06:54:27.530
pleasant motion among the trees as we approached the shore, from which it wafted the most delightful

06:54:27.530 --> 06:54:34.310
scent of flowers and hay. The sun sank beneath the horizon as we landed, and as I touched the

06:54:34.310 --> 06:54:41.190
shore I felt those cares and fears revive which soon were to clasp me and cling to me forever.

06:55:10.250 --> 06:55:16.870
It was eight o'clock when we landed. We walked for a short time on the shore, enjoying the

06:55:16.870 --> 06:55:23.170
transitory light, and then retired to the inn and contemplated the lovely scene of waters,

06:55:23.790 --> 06:55:29.250
woods and mountains, obscured in darkness yet still displaying their black outlines.

06:55:32.350 --> 06:55:37.990
The wind, which had followed in the south, now rose with great violence in the west.

06:55:38.480 --> 06:55:44.990
The moon had reached her summit in the heavens and was beginning to descend. The clouds swept

06:55:44.990 --> 06:55:51.430
across it swifter than the flight of the vulture and dimmed her rays, while the lake reflected

06:55:51.430 --> 06:55:58.010
the scene of the busy heavens, rendered still busier by the restless waves that were beginning

06:55:58.010 --> 06:56:06.870
to rise. Suddenly a heavy storm of rain descended. I had been calm during the day,

06:56:06.870 --> 06:56:14.150
but so soon as night obscured the shapes of objects, a thousand fears rose in my mind.

06:56:14.610 --> 06:56:21.570
I was anxious and watchful, while my right hand grasped the pistol which was hidden in my bosom.

06:56:22.610 --> 06:56:30.670
Every sound terrified me, but I resolved that I would sell my life dearly and not shrink from

06:56:30.670 --> 06:56:35.830
the conflict until my own life or that of my adversary was extinguished.

06:56:38.170 --> 06:56:43.570
Elizabeth observed my agitation for some time in timid and fearful silence,

06:56:44.010 --> 06:56:49.330
but there was something in my glance which communicated terror to her and trembling,

06:56:49.610 --> 06:56:55.070
she asked. What is it that agitates you, my dear Victor? What is it you fear?

06:56:56.310 --> 06:57:02.530
Oh, peace, peace, my love, I replied. This night and all will be safe,

06:57:02.530 --> 06:57:11.310
but this night is dreadful, very dreadful. I passed an hour in this state of mind when

06:57:11.310 --> 06:57:17.410
suddenly I reflected how fearful the combat which I momentarily expected would be to my wife,

06:57:18.830 --> 06:57:23.930
and earnestly I entreated her to retire, resolving not to join her until I had

06:57:23.930 --> 06:57:27.030
obtained some knowledge as to the situation of my enemy.

06:57:28.850 --> 06:57:34.930
She left me, and I continued some time walking up and down the passages of the

06:57:34.930 --> 06:57:40.530
house and inspecting every corner that might afford a retreat to my adversary,

06:57:41.650 --> 06:57:47.370
but I discovered no trace of him and was beginning to conjecture that some fortunate

06:57:47.370 --> 06:57:54.200
chance had intervened to prevent the execution of his menaces, when suddenly I heard a shrill and

06:57:54.200 --> 06:58:00.980
fearful scream. It came from the room into which Elizabeth had retired. As I heard it,

06:58:00.1000 --> 06:58:06.120
the whole truth rushed into my mind, my arms dropped, the motion of every muscle and fiber

06:58:06.120 --> 06:58:12.020
was suspended. I could feel the blood trickling in my veins and tingling in the extremities of

06:58:12.020 --> 06:58:19.620
my limbs. The state lasted but for an instant. The scream was repeated, and I rushed into the room.

06:58:21.060 --> 06:58:28.180
Great God, why did I not then expire? Why am I here to relate the destruction of the best hope

06:58:28.180 --> 06:58:34.020
and the purest creatures of earth? She was there, lifeless and inanimate, thrown across the bed,

06:58:34.160 --> 06:58:38.980
her head hanging down and her pale and distorted features half covered by her hair.

06:58:41.900 --> 06:58:47.880
Everywhere I turn I see the same figure, her bloodless arms in relaxed form, flung by the

06:58:47.880 --> 06:58:58.440
murderer on its bridled rear. Could I behold this and live? Alas, life is obstinate and clings

06:58:58.440 --> 06:59:06.860
closest where it is most hated. For a moment only did I lose recollection. I fell senseless on the

06:59:06.860 --> 06:59:14.240
ground. When I recovered I found myself surrounded by the people of the inn, their countenance

06:59:14.240 --> 06:59:21.760
expressed a breathless terror. But the horror of others appeared only as a mockery, a shadow

06:59:21.760 --> 06:59:30.240
of the feelings that oppressed me. I escaped from them to the room where lay the body of Elizabeth,

06:59:30.380 --> 06:59:38.780
my love, my wife, so lately living, so dear, so worthy. She had been moved from the posture in

06:59:38.780 --> 06:59:45.140
which I had first beheld her, and now as she lay, her head upon her arms and a handkerchief

06:59:45.140 --> 06:59:53.260
thrown across her face and neck, I might have supposed her asleep. I rushed towards her and

06:59:53.260 --> 06:59:59.960
embraced her with ardor, but the deadly languor and coldness of the limbs told me that what I

06:59:59.960 --> 07:00:06.540
now held in my arms had ceased to be the Elizabeth whom I had loved and cherished. Their murderous

07:00:06.540 --> 07:00:13.160
mark of the fiend's grasp was on her neck, and the breath had ceased to issue from her lips.

07:00:16.840 --> 07:00:23.360
While I still hung over her in the agony of despair, I happened to look up. The windows

07:00:23.360 --> 07:00:29.300
of the room had before been darkened, and I felt a kind of panic on seeing the pale yellow light

07:00:29.300 --> 07:00:36.520
of the moon illuminate the chamber. The shutters had been thrown back, and with a sensation of

07:00:36.520 --> 07:00:42.920
horror not to be described, I saw at the open window a figure the most hideous and abhorred.

07:00:43.720 --> 07:00:49.260
A grin was on the face of the monster. He seemed to jeer as with his fiendish finger

07:00:49.260 --> 07:00:55.460
he pointed towards the corpse of my wife. I rushed towards the window and, drawing pistol

07:00:55.460 --> 07:01:02.360
from my bosom, fired, but he eluded me, leapt from his station and running with the swiftness of

07:01:02.360 --> 07:01:11.040
plunged into the lake. The report of the pistol brought a crowd into the room. I pointed to the

07:01:11.040 --> 07:01:17.680
spot where he had disappeared, and we followed the track with boats. Nets were cast but in vain.

07:01:19.140 --> 07:01:26.300
After passing several hours, we returned. Hopeless, most of my companions believing

07:01:26.300 --> 07:01:33.520
it to have been a form conjured up by my fancy. After having landed, they proceeded to search

07:01:33.520 --> 07:01:41.120
the country, parties going in different directions among the woods and vines. I attempted to accompany

07:01:41.120 --> 07:01:47.740
them and proceed the short distance from the house, but my head whirled round. My steps were

07:01:47.740 --> 07:01:55.020
like those of a drunken man, and I felt at last in a state of utter exhaustion. A film covered my

07:01:55.020 --> 07:02:02.240
eyes and my skin was parched with the heat of fever. In this state, I was carried back and placed

07:02:02.240 --> 07:02:08.980
on a bed, hardly conscious of what had happened. My eyes wandered round the room as if to seek

07:02:08.980 --> 07:02:16.360
something that I had lost. After an interval, I rose and, as if by instinct, crawled into the

07:02:17.050 --> 07:02:27.740
my beloved lay. There were women weeping around. I hung over it and joined my sad tears to theirs.

07:02:29.540 --> 07:02:35.500
All this time, no distinct idea presented itself to my mind, but my thoughts rambled to their

07:02:35.500 --> 07:02:45.220
various subjects, reflecting confusedly on my misfortunes and their cause. I was bewildered

07:02:45.220 --> 07:02:52.220
in a cloud of wonder and horror. The death of William, the execution of Justine, the murder

07:02:52.220 --> 07:02:59.960
of Clairvaux, and lastly of my wife. Even at that moment, I knew not that my only remaining friends

07:02:59.960 --> 07:03:07.600
were safe from the malignity of the fiend. My father, even now, might be writhing under his

07:03:07.600 --> 07:03:14.820
grasp, and Ernest might be dead at his feet. This idea made me shudder and recalled me to

07:03:14.820 --> 07:03:20.780
action. I started up and resolved to return to Geneva with all possible speed.

07:03:25.580 --> 07:03:34.580
There were no horses to be procured, and I must return by the lake, but the wind was unfavorable

07:03:34.580 --> 07:03:41.700
and the rain fell in torrents. However, it was hardly morning, and I might reasonably hope to

07:03:41.700 --> 07:03:49.680
arrive by night. I hired men to row and took my oar myself, where I had always experienced relief

07:03:49.680 --> 07:03:58.860
from mental torment and bodily exercise. But the overflowing misery I now felt and the excess of

07:03:58.860 --> 07:04:07.420
agitation that I endured rendered me incapable of any exertion. I threw down the oar, and leaning

07:04:07.420 --> 07:04:16.120
my head upon my hands gave way to every gloomy idea that arose. If I looked up, I saw scenes

07:04:16.120 --> 07:04:22.180
which were familiar to me in my happier time, and which I had contemplated but the day before in

07:04:22.180 --> 07:04:30.780
the company of her who was now but a shadow and a recollection. Tears streamed from my eyes. The

07:04:30.780 --> 07:04:36.060
rain had ceased for a moment, and I saw the fish play in the waters as they had done a few hours

07:04:36.060 --> 07:04:48.120
before. They had then been observed by Elizabeth. Nothing is so painful to the human mind as a great

07:04:48.120 --> 07:04:55.380
and sudden change. The sun might shine or the crowds might lure, but nothing could appear to

07:04:55.380 --> 07:05:02.160
me as it had done the day before. A fiend had snatched from me every hope of future happiness.

07:05:03.080 --> 07:05:09.380
No creature had ever been so miserable as I was. So frightful an event is single in the history of

07:05:09.380 --> 07:05:17.220
man. But why should I dwell upon the incidents that followed this last overwhelming event?

07:05:18.400 --> 07:05:26.170
Mine has been a tale of horrors. I have reached their acme, and what I must now relate can be

07:05:26.930 --> 07:05:39.170
tedious to you. Know that one by one my friends were snatched away. I was left desolate. My own

07:05:39.170 --> 07:05:44.810
strength is exhausted, and I must tell in a few words what remains of my hideous narration.

07:05:48.250 --> 07:05:55.810
I arrived at Geneva. My father and Ernest yet lived, but the former sunk under the tidings

07:05:55.810 --> 07:06:03.090
I bore. I see him now, excellent and venerable old man, his eyes wandered in vacancy, for they

07:06:03.090 --> 07:06:08.930
had lost their charm and their delight. He is Elizabeth, his more than daughter, whom he

07:06:08.930 --> 07:06:14.930
doted on with all that affection which a man feels, who in the decline of life, having few

07:06:14.930 --> 07:06:23.090
affections, clings more earnestly to those that remain. Cursed be the fiend that brought

07:06:23.090 --> 07:06:30.150
misery on his grey hairs and doomed him to waste and wretchedness. He could not live under the

07:06:30.150 --> 07:06:37.710
horrors that were accumulated around him. The springs of existence suddenly gave way. He was

07:06:37.710 --> 07:06:47.510
unable to rise from his bed, and in a few days he died in my arms. What then became of me? I

07:06:47.510 --> 07:06:53.550
know not. I lost sensation, and chains and darkness were the only objects that pressed

07:06:53.550 --> 07:07:00.610
upon me. Sometimes, indeed, I dreamt that I wandered in flowery meadows and pleasant

07:07:00.610 --> 07:07:08.570
bales with the friends of my youth, but I awoke and found myself in a dungeon. Melancholy followed,

07:07:08.650 --> 07:07:14.090
but by degrees I gained a clear conception of my miseries and situation, and was then

07:07:14.090 --> 07:07:19.970
released from my prison, for they had called me mad, and during many months, as I understood,

07:07:20.310 --> 07:07:31.310
a solitary cell had been my habitation. Liberty, however, had been a useless gift to me, had I

07:07:31.310 --> 07:07:39.230
not, as I awakened to reason, at the same time awakened to revenge. As the memory of my past

07:07:39.770 --> 07:07:46.170
pressed upon me, I began to reflect on their cause, the monster whom I had created, the

07:07:46.170 --> 07:07:55.170
miserable demon whom I had sent abroad into the world for my destruction. I was possessed

07:07:55.170 --> 07:08:00.750
by a maddening rage when I thought of him, and desired and ardently prayed that I might

07:08:00.750 --> 07:08:08.270
have him within my grasp to wreak a great and single revenge on his cursed head.

07:08:11.270 --> 07:08:18.310
Nor did my hate long confine itself to useless wishes. I began to reflect on the best means

07:08:18.310 --> 07:08:25.290
of securing him, and for this purpose, about a month after my release, I repaired to a criminal

07:08:26.030 --> 07:08:33.610
and told him that I had an accusation to make, that I knew the destroyer of my family, and that

07:08:33.610 --> 07:08:37.910
I required him to exert his whole authority for the apprehension of the murderer.

07:08:39.830 --> 07:08:47.490
The magistrate listened to me with attention and kindness. Be assured, sir, he said. No pains or

07:08:47.490 --> 07:08:50.210
exertion on my part shall be spared to discover the villain.

07:08:51.490 --> 07:09:00.570
Thank you, I replied. Listen therefore to the deposition that I have to make. It is indeed a

07:09:00.570 --> 07:09:06.200
tale so strange that I should fear you would not credit it were it not something in truth which,

07:09:07.630 --> 07:09:15.870
however wonderful, forces conviction. The story is too connected to be mistaken for a dream,

07:09:16.430 --> 07:09:24.030
and I have no motive for falsehood. My manner, as I thus addressed him,

07:09:24.190 --> 07:09:31.970
was impressive but calm. I had formed in my own heart a resolution to pursue my destroyer to death,

07:09:32.690 --> 07:09:39.050
and this purpose quieted my agony, and for an interval reconciled me to life.

07:09:39.050 --> 07:09:46.450
I now relate my history briefly but with firmness and precision, marking the dates

07:09:46.450 --> 07:09:52.350
with accuracy and never deviating into invective or exclamation.

07:09:54.810 --> 07:09:57.910
The magistrate appeared at first perfectly incredulous,

07:09:58.030 --> 07:10:01.550
but as I continued he became more attentive and interested.

07:10:04.830 --> 07:10:10.090
I saw him sometimes shudder with horror, and others a lively surprise,

07:10:10.490 --> 07:10:14.010
unmingled with disbelief, was painted on his countenance.

07:10:15.450 --> 07:10:20.510
When I had concluded my narration, I said, This is the being whom I accuse,

07:10:21.110 --> 07:10:25.590
and for whose seizure and punishment I call upon you to exert your whole power.

07:10:26.210 --> 07:10:31.110
It is your duty as magistrate, and I believe and hope that your feelings as a man will not

07:10:31.110 --> 07:10:34.910
revolt from the execution of those functions on this occasion.

07:10:37.710 --> 07:10:43.150
The address caused a considerable change in the physiognomy of my own auditor.

07:10:44.370 --> 07:10:50.210
He had heard my story with that half kind of belief that is given to a tale of spirits

07:10:50.210 --> 07:10:55.050
and supernatural events, but when he was called upon to act officially in consequence,

07:10:55.050 --> 07:10:58.270
the whole tide of his incredulity returned.

07:10:59.850 --> 07:11:06.110
He, however, answered mildly, I would willingly afford you every aid in your pursuit,

07:11:06.750 --> 07:11:11.930
but the creature of whom you speak appears to have powers which would put all my exertions

07:11:11.930 --> 07:11:16.810
to defiance. Who can follow an animal which can traverse the sea of ice,

07:11:17.070 --> 07:11:20.650
and inhabit caves and dens where no man would venture to intrude?

07:11:21.790 --> 07:11:28.890
Besides, some months have elapsed since the commission of his crimes,

07:11:29.410 --> 07:11:34.270
and no one can conjecture to what place he has wandered or what region he may now inhabit.

07:11:37.810 --> 07:11:42.810
I do not doubt that he hovers near the spot which I inhabit, and if he has indeed taken

07:11:42.810 --> 07:11:49.210
refuge in the Alps he may be hunted like the Chamois and destroyed as a beast of prey,

07:11:49.850 --> 07:11:53.270
but I perceive your thoughts. You do not credit my narrative,

07:11:53.810 --> 07:11:58.530
and do not intend to pursue my enemy with the punishment which is his desert.

07:11:59.930 --> 07:12:05.090
As I spoke, rage sparkled in my eyes. The magistrate was intimidated.

07:12:05.230 --> 07:12:08.910
You are mistaken, said he. I will exert myself,

07:12:10.030 --> 07:12:15.090
and if it is in my power to seize the monster, be assured that he shall suffer punishment

07:12:15.090 --> 07:12:22.290
proportionate to his crimes, but I fear from what you have yourself described to be his properties

07:12:22.290 --> 07:12:27.730
that this will prove impracticable, and thus while every proper measure is pursued,

07:12:28.170 --> 07:12:35.570
you should make up your mind to disappointment. That cannot be, but all that I can say will be

07:12:35.570 --> 07:12:42.290
of little avail. My revenge is of no moment to you, yet while I allow it to be a vice,

07:12:42.290 --> 07:12:49.090
I confess that it is the devouring and only passion of my soul. My rage is unspeakable.

07:12:50.050 --> 07:12:55.030
When I reflect that the murderer whom I have turned loose upon society still exists,

07:12:55.710 --> 07:12:59.990
you refuse my just demand. I have but one resource, and I devote myself,

07:13:00.750 --> 07:13:03.650
either in my life or death, to his destruction.

07:13:06.710 --> 07:13:12.550
I trembled with excess of agitation as I said this. There was a frenzy in my manner,

07:13:12.890 --> 07:13:18.110
and something, I doubt not, of that haughty fierceness which the martyrs of old are said

07:13:18.110 --> 07:13:24.410
to have possessed. But to a German magistrate whose mind was occupied by far other ideas

07:13:24.410 --> 07:13:30.110
than those of devotion and heroism, this elevation of mine had much the appearance of madness.

07:13:30.970 --> 07:13:37.210
He endeavoured to soothe me as a nurse, as a child, and reverted to my tale as the effects

07:13:37.210 --> 07:13:46.090
of delirium. Man, I cried, how ignorant art thou in thy pride of wisdom! Cease! You know

07:13:46.090 --> 07:13:54.150
not what it is you say. I broke from the house angry and disturbed, and retired to meditate.

07:13:55.270 --> 07:14:02.570
I broke from the house angry and disturbed, and retired to meditate on some other mode of action.

07:14:26.630 --> 07:14:28.810
Frankenstein by Mary Shelley.

07:14:36.430 --> 07:14:42.210
My present situation was one in which all voluntary thought was swallowed up and lost.

07:14:43.250 --> 07:14:45.110
I was hurried away by fury.

07:14:45.790 --> 07:14:49.410
Revenge alone endowed me with strength and composure.

07:14:50.330 --> 07:14:54.890
It molded my feelings and allowed me to be calculating and calm.

07:14:55.650 --> 07:15:00.270
At periods when otherwise delirium or death would have been my portion.

07:15:02.930 --> 07:15:05.710
My first resolution was to quit Geneva forever.

07:15:06.370 --> 07:15:13.810
My country, which when I was happy and beloved was dear to me, now in my adversity became hateful.

07:15:14.970 --> 07:15:21.710
I provided myself with a sum of money, together with a few jewels which had belonged to my mother, and departed.

07:15:23.590 --> 07:15:28.830
And now my wanderings began, which are to cease but with life.

07:15:30.830 --> 07:15:39.490
I have traveled a vast portion of the earth and have endured all the hardships which travelers in deserts and barbarous countries are wont to meet.

07:15:40.810 --> 07:15:42.670
How I have lived I hardly know.

07:15:43.610 --> 07:15:49.710
How many times I stretched my failing limbs upon the sandy plain and prayed for death.

07:15:50.650 --> 07:15:52.850
But revenge kept me alive.

07:15:53.790 --> 07:15:57.930
I dare not die and leave my adversary in being.

07:16:00.030 --> 07:16:08.190
When I quitted Geneva, my first labor was to gain some clue by which I might trace the steps of my fiendish enemy.

07:16:10.350 --> 07:16:18.950
But my plan was unsettled, and I wandered many hours round the confines of the town, uncertain what path I should pursue.

07:16:20.790 --> 07:16:27.970
As night approached, I found myself at the entrance of the cemetery where William, Elizabeth, and my father reposed.

07:16:29.250 --> 07:16:33.110
I entered it and approached the tomb which marked their graves.

07:16:35.450 --> 07:16:41.490
Everything was silent, except the leaves of the trees which were gently agitated by the wind.

07:16:42.290 --> 07:16:49.730
The night was nearly dark, and the scene would have been solemn and affecting even to an uninterested observer.

07:16:52.170 --> 07:17:03.290
The spirits of the departed seemed to flit around and to cast shadow, which was felt but not seen around the head of the mourner.

07:17:04.910 --> 07:17:10.510
The deep grief which this scene had at first excited quickly gave way to rage and despair.

07:17:11.490 --> 07:17:14.390
They were dead, and I lived.

07:17:15.770 --> 07:17:22.150
Their murderer also lived, and to destroy him I must drag out my weary existence.

07:17:23.670 --> 07:17:27.990
I knelt on the grass and kissed the earth, and with quivering lips exclaimed,

07:17:28.910 --> 07:17:34.530
By the sacred earth on which I kneel, by the shades that wander near me,

07:17:34.530 --> 07:17:40.270
By the deep and eternal grief that I feel, I swear, and by thee, O night,

07:17:41.050 --> 07:17:46.990
And the spirits that preside over thee, to pursue the demon who caused this misery,

07:17:47.430 --> 07:17:54.070
Until he or I shall perish in mortal conflict, for this purpose I will preserve my life.

07:17:54.570 --> 07:18:01.450
To execute this dear revenge will I again behold the sun and tread the green herbage of earth,

07:18:01.450 --> 07:18:07.990
Which otherwise should vanish from my eyes forever, and I call on you, spirits of the dead,

07:18:08.510 --> 07:18:13.650
And on you wandering ministers of vengeance to aid and conduct me in my work.

07:18:14.750 --> 07:18:19.130
Let the cursed and hellish monster drink deep of agony.

07:18:20.190 --> 07:18:23.730
Let him feel the despair that now torments me.

07:18:25.590 --> 07:18:31.470
I had begun my adjuration with solemnity, and an awe which almost assured me

07:18:31.470 --> 07:18:36.730
That the shades of my murdered friends heard and approved my devotion.

07:18:38.830 --> 07:18:43.810
But the furies possessed me, as I concluded, and rage choked my utterance.

07:18:46.410 --> 07:18:50.810
I was answered through the stillness of the night by a loud and fiendish laugh.

07:18:50.810 --> 07:18:56.510
It rang on my ears long and heavily. The mountains re-echoed it,

07:18:57.110 --> 07:19:00.810
And I felt as if all hell surrounded me with mockery and laughter.

07:19:02.290 --> 07:19:05.530
Surely in that moment I should have been possessed by frenzy,

07:19:05.990 --> 07:19:10.190
And have destroyed my miserable existence, but that my vow was heard,

07:19:10.970 --> 07:19:12.950
And that I was reserved for vengeance.

07:19:13.990 --> 07:19:16.010
The laughter died away.

07:19:17.490 --> 07:19:21.290
When a well-known and abhorred voice, apparently close to my ear,

07:19:21.630 --> 07:19:23.650
Addressed me in an audible whisper.

07:19:24.770 --> 07:19:31.730
I am satisfied, miserable wretch. You have determined to live, and I am satisfied.

07:19:34.050 --> 07:19:39.250
I darted towards a spot from which the sound proceeded, but the devil eluded my grasp.

07:19:40.270 --> 07:19:45.850
Suddenly the broad disk of the moon arose, and shone full upon his ghastly and distorted shape,

07:19:46.290 --> 07:19:48.310
As he fled with more than mortal speed.

07:19:49.270 --> 07:19:53.570
I pursued him, and for many months this has been my task.

07:19:54.530 --> 07:19:59.170
Guided by a slight clue, I followed the windings of the Rhône, but vainly.

07:20:00.570 --> 07:20:05.470
The blue Mediterranean appeared, and by a strange chance I saw the fiend enter by night,

07:20:05.470 --> 07:20:09.570
And hide himself in a vessel band bound for the Black Sea.

07:20:10.550 --> 07:20:15.730
I took my passage in the same ship, but he escaped, I know not how.

07:20:17.550 --> 07:20:24.090
Amidst the wilds of Tartary and Russia, although he still evaded me, I have ever followed in his track.

07:20:24.930 --> 07:20:30.750
Sometimes the peasants, scared by this horrid apparition, inform me of his path.

07:20:30.750 --> 07:20:39.310
Sometimes he himself, who feared that if I lost all trace of him, I should despair and die, left some mark to guide me.

07:20:40.590 --> 07:20:46.050
The snows descended on my head, and I saw the print of his huge step on the white plain.

07:20:48.090 --> 07:20:53.090
To you first entering on life, to whom care is new and agony unknown,

07:20:53.810 --> 07:20:56.810
How can you understand what I have felt and still feel?

07:20:56.810 --> 07:21:03.370
Cold, want, and fatigue, were the least pains of which I was destined to endure.

07:21:04.570 --> 07:21:09.550
I was cursed by some devil, and carried about with me my eternal hell.

07:21:10.770 --> 07:21:16.210
Yet still a spirit of good followed and directed my step, and when I most murmured,

07:21:17.190 --> 07:21:20.990
Would suddenly extricate me from seemingly insurmountable difficulties.

07:21:22.850 --> 07:21:27.310
Sometimes, when nature, overcome by hunger, sunk under the exhaustion,

07:21:28.110 --> 07:21:33.170
A repast was prepared for me in the desert, that restored and inspirited me.

07:21:34.890 --> 07:21:38.970
The fair was indeed coarse, such as the peasants of the country ate,

07:21:39.690 --> 07:21:45.250
But I will not doubt that it was set there by the spirits that I had invoked to aid me.

07:21:45.250 --> 07:21:50.870
Often, when all was dry, the heavens cloudless, and I was parched by thirst,

07:21:51.810 --> 07:21:57.550
A slight cloud would bedim the sky, and shed a few drops that revived me and vanished.

07:22:00.450 --> 07:22:06.490
I followed, when I could, the courses of the rivers, but the demon generally avoided these,

07:22:06.990 --> 07:22:10.310
As it was here that the population of the country chiefly collected.

07:22:11.010 --> 07:22:18.510
In other places human beings were seldom seen, and I generally subsisted on the wild animals that crossed my path.

07:22:19.210 --> 07:22:24.310
I had money with me, and gained the friendship of the villagers by distributing it,

07:22:24.770 --> 07:22:29.730
While I brought with me some food that I had killed, which after taking small part,

07:22:30.290 --> 07:22:34.670
I always presented to those who had provided me with fire and utensils for cooking.

07:22:35.850 --> 07:22:39.570
My life, as it passed thus, was indeed hateful to me,

07:22:39.690 --> 07:22:44.310
And it was during sleep alone that I could taste joy. Oh, blessed sleep!

07:22:45.430 --> 07:22:50.590
Often, when most miserable, I sank to repose, and my dreams lulled me even to rapture.

07:22:51.610 --> 07:22:56.450
The spirits that guarded me had provided these moments, or rather hours, of happiness,

07:22:56.530 --> 07:23:00.370
That I might retain strength to fulfill my pilgrimage.

07:23:02.230 --> 07:23:07.030
Deprived of this respite, I should have sunk under my hardships.

07:23:09.050 --> 07:23:12.690
During the day I was sustained and inspirited by the hope of night,

07:23:13.030 --> 07:23:17.580
For in sleep I saw my friends, my wife, and my beloved country.

07:23:19.730 --> 07:23:26.570
Again I saw the benevolent countenance of my father, heard the silver tones of my Elizabeth's voice,

07:23:26.570 --> 07:23:30.730
And beheld Clerval, enjoying health and youth.

07:23:32.550 --> 07:23:38.770
Often, when wearied by a toilsome march, I persuaded myself that I was dreaming until night should come,

07:23:39.190 --> 07:23:44.210
And that I should then enjoy reality in the arms of my dearest friends.

07:23:46.290 --> 07:23:52.570
What agonizing fondness did I feel for them? How did I cling to their fears, to their...

07:23:56.210 --> 07:24:02.490
What agonizing fondness did I feel for them? How did I cling to their dream forms,

07:24:02.610 --> 07:24:07.790
As sometimes they haunted even my waking hours, and persuade myself that they still lived?

07:24:10.090 --> 07:24:14.730
At such moments, vengeance, that burned within me, died in my heart,

07:24:15.110 --> 07:24:18.270
And I pursued my path towards the destruction of the demon,

07:24:19.150 --> 07:24:21.310
More as a task enjoined by heaven,

07:24:21.310 --> 07:24:25.610
As the mechanical impulse of some power of which I was unconscious,

07:24:26.770 --> 07:24:28.990
Than as the ardent desire of my soul.

07:24:33.090 --> 07:24:36.410
What his feelings were whom I pursued I cannot know.

07:24:37.590 --> 07:24:41.470
Sometimes, indeed, he left marks in writing on the bark of the trees,

07:24:41.610 --> 07:24:45.710
Or cut in stone that guided me and instigated my fury.

07:24:46.950 --> 07:24:48.870
My reign is not yet over.

07:24:50.650 --> 07:24:53.890
These words were legible in one of these inscriptions.

07:24:54.490 --> 07:24:58.010
You live, and my power is complete. Follow me.

07:24:58.850 --> 07:25:01.810
I seek the everlasting ices of the north,

07:25:02.270 --> 07:25:06.710
Where you will feel the misery of cold and frost to which I am impassive.

07:25:07.750 --> 07:25:12.510
You will find near this place, if you follow not too tardily, a dead hare.

07:25:13.090 --> 07:25:16.530
Eat and be refreshed. Come on, my enemy.

07:25:17.470 --> 07:25:20.190
We have yet to wrestle for our lives,

07:25:21.230 --> 07:25:24.490
But many hard and miserable hours must you endure,

07:25:25.270 --> 07:25:27.290
Until that period shall arrive.

07:25:30.270 --> 07:25:33.850
Scoffing devil, again do I vow vengeance,

07:25:34.710 --> 07:25:39.150
Again do I devote thee, miserable fiend to torture and death.

07:25:40.410 --> 07:25:43.930
Never will I give up my search until he or I perish,

07:25:43.930 --> 07:25:47.630
And then with what ecstasy shall I join my Elizabeth

07:25:47.630 --> 07:25:51.010
And my departed friends who even now prepare for me

07:25:51.010 --> 07:25:54.970
The reward of my tedious toil and horrible pilgrimage.

07:25:56.710 --> 07:26:01.350
As I still pursued my journey to the northward, the snows thickened,

07:26:01.350 --> 07:26:05.410
And the cold increased in a degree almost too severe to support.

07:26:07.370 --> 07:26:10.070
The peasants were shut up in their hovels,

07:26:10.070 --> 07:26:14.110
And only a few of the most hardy ventured forth to seize the animals

07:26:14.110 --> 07:26:18.210
Whom starvation had forced from their hiding places to seek for prey.

07:26:20.170 --> 07:26:24.270
The rivers were covered with ice, and no fish could be procured,

07:26:25.190 --> 07:26:28.450
And thus I was cut off from my chief article of maintenance.

07:26:30.410 --> 07:26:34.530
The triumph of my enemy increased with the difficulty of my labors.

07:26:35.910 --> 07:26:38.490
One inscription that he left was in these words,

07:26:39.410 --> 07:26:42.210
Prepare, your toil is only begin.

07:26:43.210 --> 07:26:48.050
Wrap yourself in furs, and provide food, for we shall soon enter

07:26:48.050 --> 07:26:53.650
Upon a journey where your sufferings will satisfy my everlasting hatred.

07:26:56.810 --> 07:27:01.110
My courage and perseverance were invigorated by these scoffing words.

07:27:01.950 --> 07:27:06.890
I resolved not to fail in my purpose, and calling on heaven to support me,

07:27:06.890 --> 07:27:10.890
I continued with unabated fervour to traverse immense deserts,

07:27:11.590 --> 07:27:16.610
Until the ocean appeared at a distance, and formed the utmost boundary of the horizon.

07:27:18.450 --> 07:27:22.450
Oh, how unlike it was to the blue seasons of the south!

07:27:23.330 --> 07:27:29.830
Covered with ice, it was only to be distinguished from land by its superior wildness and ruggedness.

07:27:30.890 --> 07:27:36.290
The Greeks wept for joy when they beheld the Mediterranean from the hills of Asia,

07:27:36.290 --> 07:27:40.010
And hailed with rapture the boundary of their toils.

07:27:42.850 --> 07:27:49.580
I did not weep, but I knelt down, and with a full heart thanked my guiding spirits for conducting me

07:27:49.910 --> 07:27:56.310
In safety to the place where I hoped, not withstanding my adversary's jibe,

07:27:56.610 --> 07:27:59.110
To meet and grapple with him.

07:28:01.830 --> 07:28:07.170
Some weeks before this period I had procured a sled and dogs,

07:28:07.470 --> 07:28:10.610
And thus traversed the snows with inconceivable speed.

07:28:11.650 --> 07:28:16.470
I know not whether the fiend possessed the same advantages, but I found that as before

07:28:16.470 --> 07:28:21.190
I had daily lost ground in the pursuit I now gained on him,

07:28:21.410 --> 07:28:26.330
So much so that when I first saw the ocean he was but one day's journey in advance,

07:28:26.330 --> 07:28:30.110
And I hoped to intercept him before he should reach the beach.

07:28:32.570 --> 07:28:38.810
With new courage therefore I pressed on, and in two days arrived at a wretched hamlet on the seashore.

07:28:39.850 --> 07:28:45.390
I inquired of the inhabitants concerning the fiend and gained accurate information.

07:28:47.050 --> 07:28:53.770
A gigantic monster, they said, had arrived the night before, armed with a gun and many pistols,

07:28:53.770 --> 07:28:59.890
Putting to flight the inhabitants of a solitary cottage through fear of his terrific appearance.

07:29:00.470 --> 07:29:07.430
He had carried off their store of winter food and, placing it in a sledge, to draw,

07:29:08.290 --> 07:29:12.210
Which he had seized on a numerous drove of trained dogs.

07:29:12.930 --> 07:29:18.870
He had harnessed them, and the same night, to the joy of the horror-struck villagers,

07:29:18.870 --> 07:29:23.650
Had pursued his journey across the sea in a direction that led to no land,

07:29:24.570 --> 07:29:31.870
And they conjectured that he must speedily be destroyed by the breaking of the ice frozen by the eternal frosts.

07:29:34.210 --> 07:29:38.070
On hearing this information I suffered a temporary access of despair.

07:29:39.230 --> 07:29:44.370
He had escaped me, and I must commence a destructive and almost endless journey

07:29:44.370 --> 07:29:50.750
Across the mountainous ices of the ocean, amidst cold that few of the inhabitants could long endure,

07:29:51.070 --> 07:29:56.690
And which I, the native of a genial and sunny climate, could not hope to survive.

07:29:58.410 --> 07:30:04.450
Yet at the idea that the fiend should live and be triumphant, my rage and vengeance returned,

07:30:05.070 --> 07:30:08.630
And, like a mighty tide, overwhelmed every other feeling.

07:30:09.450 --> 07:30:14.190
After a slight repose, during which the spirits of the dead hovered round,

07:30:14.670 --> 07:30:18.970
And instigated me to toil in revenge, I prepared for my journey.

07:30:21.050 --> 07:30:26.650
I exchanged my land-sledge for one fashioned for the inequalities of the frozen ocean,

07:30:27.250 --> 07:30:29.870
And purchasing a plentiful stock of presisions.

07:30:32.690 --> 07:30:34.630
I departed from land.

07:30:36.770 --> 07:30:40.150
I cannot guess how many days have passed since then,

07:30:40.330 --> 07:30:46.130
But I have endured misery which nothing but the eternal sentiment of a just retribution,

07:30:46.510 --> 07:30:49.690
Burning within my heart, could have enabled me to support.

07:30:50.930 --> 07:30:56.110
Immense and rugged mountains of ice often barred up my passage,

07:30:56.370 --> 07:31:00.930
And I often heard the thunder of the ground sea, which threatened my destruction.

07:31:01.690 --> 07:31:06.990
But again the frost came and made the paths of the sea secure.

07:31:09.190 --> 07:31:15.530
By the quantity of provision which I had consumed, I should guess that I had passed three weeks in this journey,

07:31:16.050 --> 07:31:21.770
And the continual protraction of hope returning back upon the heart,

07:31:22.470 --> 07:31:27.070
Often wrung bitter drops of despondency and grief from my eyes.

07:31:28.290 --> 07:31:32.250
Despair had indeed almost secured her prey,

07:31:32.750 --> 07:31:35.550
And I should soon have sunk beneath this misery.

07:31:37.930 --> 07:31:45.370
Once after the poor animals that conveyed me had with incredible toil gained the summit of a sloping ice mountain,

07:31:45.970 --> 07:31:52.070
And one, sinking under his fatigue, died, I viewed the expanse before me with anguish,

07:31:52.470 --> 07:31:56.230
When suddenly my eye caught a dark speck upon the dusky plain.

07:31:57.070 --> 07:32:00.670
I strained my sight to discover what it could be,

07:32:01.150 --> 07:32:05.050
And uttered a wild cry of ecstasy when I distinguished a sledge,

07:32:05.450 --> 07:32:08.790
And the distorted proportions of a well-known form within.

07:32:10.370 --> 07:32:14.670
Oh, with what burning gush did hope revisit my heart,

07:32:15.170 --> 07:32:19.330
Warm tears filled my eyes, which I hastily wiped away,

07:32:19.970 --> 07:32:23.730
That they might not intercept the view I had of the demon.

07:32:24.450 --> 07:32:28.450
But still my sight was dimmed by the burning drops,

07:32:28.830 --> 07:32:33.690
Until, giving way to the emotions that oppressed me, I wept aloud.

07:32:36.910 --> 07:32:39.970
But this was not the time for delay.

07:32:41.270 --> 07:32:44.330
I disencumbered the dogs of their dead companion,

07:32:44.850 --> 07:32:47.170
Gave them a plentiful portion of food,

07:32:47.370 --> 07:32:50.690
And after an hour's rest, which was absolutely necessary,

07:32:50.690 --> 07:32:54.550
And yet, which was bitterly irksome to me, I continued my route.

07:32:56.250 --> 07:33:00.630
The sledge was still visible, nor did I again lose sight of it,

07:33:00.790 --> 07:33:03.510
Except at the moment when, for a short time,

07:33:03.570 --> 07:33:07.110
Some ice rock concealed it with its intervening crags.

07:33:08.310 --> 07:33:10.750
I indeed perceptibly gained on it,

07:33:10.750 --> 07:33:13.330
And when, after nearly two days' journey,

07:33:13.710 --> 07:33:17.490
I beheld my enemy at no more than a mile distant,

07:33:17.490 --> 07:33:20.110
My heart bounded within me.

07:33:21.510 --> 07:33:25.590
But now, when I appeared almost within grasp of my foe,

07:33:25.710 --> 07:33:27.530
My hopes were suddenly extinguished,

07:33:27.550 --> 07:33:31.270
And I lost all trace of him more utterly than I had ever done before.

07:33:32.490 --> 07:33:35.450
A ground sea was heard, the thunder of its progress

07:33:35.450 --> 07:33:38.150
As the waters rolled and swelled beneath me,

07:33:38.390 --> 07:33:40.890
Became every moment more ominous and terrific.

07:33:41.650 --> 07:33:43.270
I pressed on, but in vain.

07:33:43.750 --> 07:33:46.230
The wind rose and the sea roared,

07:33:46.230 --> 07:33:49.350
And, as with the mighty shock of an earthquake,

07:33:49.570 --> 07:33:53.590
It split and cracked with a tremendous and overwhelming sound.

07:33:54.490 --> 07:33:56.070
The work was soon finished.

07:33:56.530 --> 07:34:00.710
In a few minutes a tumultuous sea rolled between me and my enemy,

07:34:00.990 --> 07:34:03.630
And I was left drifting on a scattered piece of ice

07:34:03.630 --> 07:34:05.490
That was continually lessening,

07:34:05.690 --> 07:34:08.290
And thus preparing for me a hideous death.

07:34:10.690 --> 07:34:14.070
In this manner many an appalling hours passed.

07:34:14.070 --> 07:34:16.050
Several of my dogs died,

07:34:16.430 --> 07:34:20.070
And I myself was about to sink under the accumulation of distress

07:34:20.070 --> 07:34:22.710
When I saw your vessel riding at anchor,

07:34:23.370 --> 07:34:26.410
And holding forth to me hopes of succor and life.

07:34:28.210 --> 07:34:31.470
I had no conception that vessels ever came so far north

07:34:31.470 --> 07:34:33.050
And was astounded at the sight.

07:34:33.950 --> 07:34:37.170
I quickly destroyed part of my sledge to construct oars,

07:34:37.390 --> 07:34:40.510
And by these means was enabled, with infinite fatigue,

07:34:40.690 --> 07:34:43.210
To move my ice raft in the direction of your ship.

07:34:44.450 --> 07:34:47.370
I had determined, if you were going southward,

07:34:47.570 --> 07:34:50.450
Still to trust myself to the mercy of the seas

07:34:50.450 --> 07:34:52.230
Rather than abandon my purpose.

07:34:53.310 --> 07:34:56.550
I hoped to induce you to grant me a boat

07:34:57.290 --> 07:34:59.430
With which I could pursue my enemy,

07:35:00.270 --> 07:35:02.090
But your direction was northward.

07:35:02.650 --> 07:35:05.310
You took me on board when my vigor was exhausted,

07:35:06.090 --> 07:35:09.510
And I should soon have sunk under my multiple-eyed hardships

07:35:09.510 --> 07:35:11.330
Into a death which I still dread,

07:35:11.330 --> 07:35:13.450
For my task is unfulfilled.

07:35:16.370 --> 07:35:19.770
Oh, when will my guiding spirit in conducting me to the demon

07:35:19.770 --> 07:35:21.990
Allow me the rest I so much desire,

07:35:22.730 --> 07:35:26.270
Or must I die, and he yet live?

07:35:27.590 --> 07:35:31.990
If I do, swear to me, Walton, that he shall not escape,

07:35:32.970 --> 07:35:36.710
That you will seek him and satisfy my vengeance in his death.

07:35:37.590 --> 07:35:40.650
And do I dare to ask of you to undertake my pilgrimage

07:35:40.650 --> 07:35:42.830
To endure the hardships that I have undergone?

07:35:43.670 --> 07:35:46.610
No, I am not so selfish.

07:35:47.550 --> 07:35:49.570
Yet when I am dead, if he should appear,

07:35:50.110 --> 07:35:52.990
If the ministers of vengeance should conduct him to you,

07:35:53.150 --> 07:35:54.910
Swear that he shall not live,

07:35:55.690 --> 07:35:59.650
Swear that he shall not triumph over my accumulated woes,

07:36:00.350 --> 07:36:03.010
And survive to add to the list of his dark crimes.

07:36:04.010 --> 07:36:06.270
He is eloquent and persuasive,

07:36:06.750 --> 07:36:10.210
And once his words had even power over my heart,

07:36:10.210 --> 07:36:15.230
But trust him not, his soul is as hellish as his form,

07:36:15.550 --> 07:36:19.610
Full of treachery and fiendlike malice.

07:36:20.550 --> 07:36:21.310
Hear him not.

07:36:23.150 --> 07:36:25.430
Call on him the mains of William, Justine,

07:36:26.430 --> 07:36:29.390
Clairvaux, Elizabeth, my father and the wretched Victor,

07:36:30.130 --> 07:36:32.010
And thrust your sword into his heart.

07:36:33.010 --> 07:36:36.630
I will hover near and direct the steel aright.

07:36:40.190 --> 07:36:42.130
Walton, in continuation.

07:36:43.110 --> 07:36:46.290
August 26th, 17 something.

07:36:50.650 --> 07:36:53.870
You have read this strange and terrific story, Margaret.

07:36:55.850 --> 07:36:58.690
And do you not feel your blood congeal with horror,

07:36:59.030 --> 07:37:01.130
Like that which even now curdles mine?

07:37:02.950 --> 07:37:05.270
Sometimes, seized with sudden agony,

07:37:05.270 --> 07:37:07.370
He could not continue his tale.

07:37:07.910 --> 07:37:10.450
At others his voice broken, yet piercing,

07:37:11.110 --> 07:37:14.090
Uttered with difficulty the words so replete with anguish.

07:37:15.130 --> 07:37:19.470
His fine and lovely eyes were now lighted up with indignation,

07:37:20.010 --> 07:37:22.270
Now subdued to downcast sorrow,

07:37:22.950 --> 07:37:25.510
And quenched in infinite wretchedness.

07:37:27.030 --> 07:37:30.390
Sometimes he commanded his countenance and tones,

07:37:31.190 --> 07:37:34.570
And related the most horrible incidents with a tranquil voice,

07:37:34.570 --> 07:37:36.990
Suppressing every mark of agitation.

07:37:38.090 --> 07:37:40.190
Then, like a volcano bursting forth,

07:37:40.390 --> 07:37:44.150
His face would suddenly change to an expression of the wildest rage,

07:37:44.710 --> 07:37:45.660
As he shrieked out,

07:37:46.890 --> 07:37:48.910
Impreciations on his persecutor.

07:37:51.290 --> 07:37:52.590
His tale is connected,

07:37:52.970 --> 07:37:55.470
And told with an appearance of the simplest truth.

07:37:56.390 --> 07:37:59.910
Yet I own to you that the letters of Felix and Saffy,

07:38:00.090 --> 07:38:01.230
Which he showed me,

07:38:01.330 --> 07:38:04.090
And the apparition of the monster seen from our ship,

07:38:04.090 --> 07:38:07.350
Brought to me a greater conviction of the truth of his narrative

07:38:07.350 --> 07:38:09.090
Than his assertiveness,

07:38:10.550 --> 07:38:12.370
However earnest and connected.

07:38:15.070 --> 07:38:17.310
Such a monster has, then, real existence.

07:38:18.110 --> 07:38:19.090
I cannot doubt it.

07:38:19.930 --> 07:38:22.270
Yet I am lost in surprise and admiration.

07:38:23.830 --> 07:38:26.970
Sometimes I endeavored to gain from Frankenstein

07:38:26.970 --> 07:38:29.310
The particulars of his creature's formation,

07:38:29.570 --> 07:38:31.090
But on this point he was impenetrable.

07:38:32.610 --> 07:38:35.370
Are you mad, my friend, said he,

07:38:35.750 --> 07:38:38.630
Or whither does your senseless curiosity lead you?

07:38:38.910 --> 07:38:42.710
Would you also create for yourself and the world a demonical enemy?

07:38:43.090 --> 07:38:44.110
Peace, peace!

07:38:44.790 --> 07:38:47.750
Learn my miseries and do not seek to increase your own.

07:38:49.650 --> 07:38:52.690
Frankenstein discovered that I made notes concerning his history.

07:38:53.450 --> 07:38:54.790
He asked to see them,

07:38:55.110 --> 07:38:58.390
And then himself corrected and augmented them in many places,

07:38:59.010 --> 07:39:00.970
But principally in giving me the life

07:39:00.970 --> 07:39:04.590
And spirit to the conversations he held with his enemy.

07:39:06.070 --> 07:39:08.790
Since you have preserved my narration, said he,

07:39:09.330 --> 07:39:14.190
I would not that a mutilated one should go down to posterity.

07:39:15.910 --> 07:39:17.430
Thus has a week passed away

07:39:17.430 --> 07:39:19.530
While I have listened to the strangest tale

07:39:19.530 --> 07:39:21.230
That ever imagination formed.

07:39:23.070 --> 07:39:25.210
My thoughts and every feeling of my soul

07:39:25.210 --> 07:39:27.910
Have been drunk up by the interest of my guest,

07:39:27.910 --> 07:39:32.870
Which this tale and his own elevated and gentle manners have created.

07:39:34.250 --> 07:39:37.230
I wish to soothe him, yet I can counsel one

07:39:37.230 --> 07:39:39.230
So indefinitely miserable,

07:39:40.970 --> 07:39:44.310
So destitute of every hope and consolation.

07:39:46.690 --> 07:39:49.910
Frankenstein discovered that I made notes concerning his history.

07:39:50.530 --> 07:39:51.870
He asked to see them,

07:39:52.090 --> 07:39:55.470
And then himself corrected and augmented them in many places,

07:39:55.470 --> 07:39:57.790
But principally in giving me the life

07:39:57.790 --> 07:40:00.430
And spirit to the conversations he held with his enemy.

07:40:02.290 --> 07:40:05.370
Since you have preserved my narration, said he,

07:40:05.770 --> 07:40:09.950
I would not that a mutilated one should go down to posterity.

07:40:11.670 --> 07:40:13.190
Thus has a week passed away

07:40:13.190 --> 07:40:15.310
While I have listened to the strangest tale

07:40:15.310 --> 07:40:17.090
That ever imagination formed.

07:40:17.910 --> 07:40:20.110
My thoughts and every feeling of my soul

07:40:20.110 --> 07:40:22.750
Have been drunk up by the interest of my guest,

07:40:22.750 --> 07:40:26.770
Which this tale and his own elevated gentle manners have created.

07:40:28.430 --> 07:40:31.710
I wish to soothe him, yet I can counsel one

07:40:31.710 --> 07:40:33.210
So infinitely miserable,

07:40:33.530 --> 07:40:36.410
So destitute of every hope and consolation to live.

07:40:37.770 --> 07:40:40.710
Oh no, the only joy that he can now know

07:40:40.710 --> 07:40:43.370
Will be when he composes his shattered spirit

07:40:43.370 --> 07:40:44.810
To peace and death.

07:40:46.310 --> 07:40:47.810
Yet he enjoys one comfort,

07:40:48.250 --> 07:40:50.930
The offspring of solitude and delirium.

07:40:50.930 --> 07:40:55.750
He believes that when in dreams he holds converse with his friends

07:40:55.750 --> 07:40:59.910
And derives from that communion consolation for his miseries

07:40:59.910 --> 07:41:01.690
Or excitements to his vengeance,

07:41:02.310 --> 07:41:04.630
That they are not the creations of his fancy,

07:41:05.010 --> 07:41:09.630
But the beings themselves who visit from the regions of a remote world.

07:41:10.530 --> 07:41:14.470
This faith gives a solemnity to his reveries

07:41:14.470 --> 07:41:18.350
That render them to me almost as imposing and interesting as truth.

07:41:20.950 --> 07:41:23.510
Our conversations are not always confined

07:41:23.870 --> 07:41:26.350
To his own history and misfortunes.

07:41:28.030 --> 07:41:31.990
On every point of general literature he displays unbounded knowledge

07:41:31.990 --> 07:41:34.430
And a quick and piercing apprehension.

07:41:35.450 --> 07:41:37.510
His eloquence is forcible and touching,

07:41:38.230 --> 07:41:41.530
Nor can I hear him when he relates a pathetic incident

07:41:41.530 --> 07:41:46.510
Or endeavors to move the passions of pity or love without tears.

07:41:47.090 --> 07:41:50.730
What a glorious creature must he have been in the days of his prosperity

07:41:51.030 --> 07:41:54.330
When he is thus noble and godlike in ruin.

07:41:54.870 --> 07:41:58.930
He seems to feel his own worth in the greatness of his fall.

07:42:01.530 --> 07:42:06.330
When younger, said he, I believe myself destined for some great enterprise.

07:42:06.930 --> 07:42:08.230
My feelings are profound,

07:42:08.490 --> 07:42:12.910
But I possessed a coolness of judgment that fitted me for illustrious achievements.

07:42:13.510 --> 07:42:17.550
This sentiment of worth, of my nature, supported me

07:42:17.550 --> 07:42:19.590
When others would have been oppressed.

07:42:20.590 --> 07:42:23.650
For I deemed it criminal to throw away in useless grief

07:42:23.650 --> 07:42:26.870
Those talents that might be useful to my fellow creatures.

07:42:28.570 --> 07:42:30.690
When I reflected on the work I had completed

07:42:30.690 --> 07:42:36.230
No less than one, no lesser one than the creation of a sensitive and rational animal.

07:42:36.830 --> 07:42:40.070
I could not rank myself with the herd of common projectors.

07:42:40.070 --> 07:42:45.690
But this thought, which supported me in my commencement of my career,

07:42:46.130 --> 07:42:48.830
Now serves only to plunge me lower in the dust.

07:42:50.030 --> 07:42:53.210
All my speculations and hopes are as nothing and,

07:42:53.790 --> 07:42:57.810
Like the archangel who aspired to omnipotence,

07:42:58.390 --> 07:43:00.130
I am chained to an eternal hell.

07:43:01.270 --> 07:43:03.090
My imagination was vivid,

07:43:03.930 --> 07:43:06.910
Yet my powers of analysis and application were intense.

07:43:07.730 --> 07:43:11.230
By the union of these qualities I conceived the idea

07:43:11.230 --> 07:43:13.750
And executed the creation of a man.

07:43:16.050 --> 07:43:18.630
Even now I cannot recollect, without passion,

07:43:19.090 --> 07:43:21.330
My reveries while the work was incomplete.

07:43:22.290 --> 07:43:24.310
I trod heaven in my thoughts,

07:43:24.690 --> 07:43:28.510
Now exulting in my powers, now burning with the idea of their effects.

07:43:29.490 --> 07:43:33.750
From my infancy I was imbued with high hopes and lofty ambition.

07:43:34.790 --> 07:43:36.510
But how I am sunk.

07:43:38.210 --> 07:43:40.970
Oh, my friend, if you had known me as I once was,

07:43:41.210 --> 07:43:43.870
You would not recognize me in this state of degradation.

07:43:45.170 --> 07:43:47.270
Despondency rarely visited my heart.

07:43:48.090 --> 07:43:51.230
A high destiny seemed to bear me on until I fell,

07:43:51.690 --> 07:43:53.410
Never, never again to rise.

07:43:57.250 --> 07:44:00.270
Must I then lose this admirable being?

07:44:00.270 --> 07:44:02.610
I have longed for a friend.

07:44:03.110 --> 07:44:06.330
I have sought one who would sympathize with and love me.

07:44:06.690 --> 07:44:09.670
Behold, on these desert seas I have found such a one.

07:44:10.190 --> 07:44:13.450
But I have fear I have gamed him

07:44:13.450 --> 07:44:15.970
Only to know his value and lose him.

07:44:16.810 --> 07:44:19.150
I would reconcile him to life.

07:44:20.090 --> 07:44:21.750
But he repulses the idea.

07:44:22.890 --> 07:44:24.710
I thank you, Walton, he said,

07:44:25.150 --> 07:44:28.290
For your kind intentions towards so miserable a wretch.

07:44:28.290 --> 07:44:32.270
But when you speak of new tides and fresh affections,

07:44:34.050 --> 07:44:36.850
Think you that any can replace those who are gone.

07:44:37.210 --> 07:44:40.570
Can any man be to me as Clairvaux was,

07:44:41.190 --> 07:44:42.910
Or any woman another Elizabeth?

07:44:44.530 --> 07:44:46.910
Even where the affections are not strongly moved

07:44:46.910 --> 07:44:48.510
By any superior excellence,

07:44:49.230 --> 07:44:52.370
The companions of our childhood always possess

07:44:52.370 --> 07:44:54.290
A certain power over our minds,

07:44:54.290 --> 07:44:57.490
Which hardly any later friend can obtain.

07:44:59.010 --> 07:45:02.750
They know our infinite dispositions,

07:45:02.750 --> 07:45:06.090
Which, however they may be afterwards modified,

07:45:06.330 --> 07:45:07.570
Are never eradicated.

07:45:08.250 --> 07:45:09.870
They can judge of our actions

07:45:09.870 --> 07:45:11.630
With more certain conclusions

07:45:12.290 --> 07:45:14.350
As to the integrity of our motives.

07:45:16.170 --> 07:45:18.130
A sister or a brother can never,

07:45:18.250 --> 07:45:21.070
Unless indeed such symptoms have been shown early,

07:45:21.070 --> 07:45:24.270
Suspect the other of fraud or false dealings,

07:45:24.470 --> 07:45:27.730
When another friend, however strongly he may be attached,

07:45:28.430 --> 07:45:29.810
May, in spite of himself,

07:45:30.390 --> 07:45:32.050
Be contemplated with suspicion.

07:45:34.450 --> 07:45:36.910
But I enjoyed friends dear not only

07:45:36.910 --> 07:45:38.670
Through habit and association,

07:45:39.070 --> 07:45:40.370
But from their own merits.

07:45:41.330 --> 07:45:44.390
And wherever I am, the soothing voice of my Elizabeth

07:45:44.390 --> 07:45:47.510
And the conversations of Clairvaux

07:45:47.510 --> 07:45:50.170
Will ever be whispered in my ear.

07:45:51.170 --> 07:45:52.110
They are dead,

07:45:52.710 --> 07:45:55.510
But one feeling in such a solitude

07:45:55.510 --> 07:45:57.970
Can persuade me to preserve my life.

07:45:59.430 --> 07:46:02.150
If I were engaged in any high undertaking

07:46:03.010 --> 07:46:04.370
Or design,

07:46:05.470 --> 07:46:07.570
Fraught with extensive utility

07:46:07.570 --> 07:46:08.970
To my fellow creatures,

07:46:09.490 --> 07:46:11.210
Then I could live to fulfill it,

07:46:11.210 --> 07:46:12.830
But such is not my destiny.

07:46:13.290 --> 07:46:15.610
I must pursue and destroy the being

07:46:15.610 --> 07:46:17.430
To whom I have gave existence.

07:46:18.290 --> 07:46:21.750
Then my lot on earth will be fulfilled,

07:46:22.690 --> 07:46:23.750
And I may die.

07:46:27.790 --> 07:46:28.990
September 2nd.

07:46:28.990 --> 07:46:30.030
My beloved sister,

07:46:30.930 --> 07:46:33.110
I write to you encompassed by peril

07:46:33.110 --> 07:46:36.190
And ignorant whether I am ever doomed to see again

07:46:36.190 --> 07:46:39.030
My dear England and the dearer friends that inhabit it.

07:46:39.350 --> 07:46:42.250
I am surrounded by mountains of ice which admit of no escape

07:46:42.250 --> 07:46:44.810
And threaten every moment to crush my vessel.

07:46:45.790 --> 07:46:48.310
The brave fellows who I have persuaded to be

07:46:48.310 --> 07:46:51.230
My companions look towards me for aid,

07:46:51.610 --> 07:46:53.110
But I have none to bestow.

07:46:53.970 --> 07:46:56.350
There is something terribly appalling in our situation,

07:46:56.430 --> 07:46:58.830
Yet my courage and hopes do not desert me.

07:46:59.270 --> 07:47:02.130
Yet it is terrible to reflect that the lives of all these men

07:47:02.130 --> 07:47:03.730
Are endangered through me.

07:47:04.250 --> 07:47:07.550
If we are lost, my mad, mad schemes are the cause.

07:47:10.830 --> 07:47:11.830
And what, Margaret,

07:47:11.850 --> 07:47:13.310
Will be the state of your mind?

07:47:13.670 --> 07:47:15.430
You will not hear of my destruction,

07:47:15.710 --> 07:47:17.790
And you will anxiously await my return.

07:47:18.330 --> 07:47:20.910
Years will pass and you will have visiting of despair

07:47:20.910 --> 07:47:22.450
And yet be tortured by hope.

07:47:23.250 --> 07:47:26.450
Oh, my beloved sister, the sickening failing

07:47:26.450 --> 07:47:29.170
Of your heartfelt expectations is in prospect

07:47:29.170 --> 07:47:31.270
More terrible to me than my own death,

07:47:31.910 --> 07:47:33.930
But you have a husband and lovely children.

07:47:34.250 --> 07:47:38.050
You may be happy. Heaven bless you and make you so.

07:47:39.390 --> 07:47:41.310
My unfortunate guest regards me

07:47:41.310 --> 07:47:42.670
With a tenderest compassion.

07:47:43.510 --> 07:47:46.530
He endeavours to fill me with hope and talks as if life

07:47:46.530 --> 07:47:48.090
Were a possession which he valued.

07:47:48.770 --> 07:47:51.610
He reminds me how often the same accidents have happened

07:47:51.610 --> 07:47:54.570
To other navigators who have attempted this sea.

07:47:55.250 --> 07:47:57.830
And in spite of myself, he fills me with cheerful

07:47:58.890 --> 07:47:59.450
Auguries.

07:48:00.470 --> 07:48:02.850
Even the sailors feel the power of his eloquence.

07:48:03.090 --> 07:48:04.890
When he speaks, they no longer despair.

07:48:05.550 --> 07:48:09.050
He rouses their energies, and while they hear his voice,

07:48:09.170 --> 07:48:12.750
They believe these vast mountains of ice

07:48:12.750 --> 07:48:16.350
Are molehills which will vanish before the resolutions

07:48:16.350 --> 07:48:17.270
Of man.

07:48:17.270 --> 07:48:19.670
These feelings are transitory.

07:48:19.990 --> 07:48:23.830
Each day of expectation delayed fills them with fear.

07:48:24.430 --> 07:48:27.190
And I almost dread a mutiny caused by this despair.

07:48:30.470 --> 07:48:31.670
September 5th.

07:48:31.670 --> 07:48:34.330
A scene has just passed of such uncommon interest

07:48:34.330 --> 07:48:37.430
That although it is highly probable that these papers

07:48:37.430 --> 07:48:40.490
May never reach you, yet I cannot forbear recording it.

07:48:41.350 --> 07:48:43.430
We are still surrounded by mountains of ice,

07:48:43.430 --> 07:48:46.530
Still in imminent danger of being crushed in their conflict.

07:48:47.190 --> 07:48:50.530
The cold is excessive, and many of my unfortunate

07:48:50.530 --> 07:48:53.130
Comrades have already found a grave amidst this

07:48:53.130 --> 07:48:54.510
Scene of desolation.

07:48:55.530 --> 07:48:57.710
Frankenstein has daily declined in health.

07:48:58.110 --> 07:49:00.730
A feverish fire still glimmers in his eyes.

07:49:00.910 --> 07:49:04.210
But he is exhausted, and when suddenly roused to any

07:49:04.210 --> 07:49:07.310
Exertion, he speedily sinks again into apparent

07:49:07.310 --> 07:49:08.170
Lifelessness.

07:49:09.170 --> 07:49:11.550
I mentioned in my last letter the fears

07:49:11.550 --> 07:49:13.050
I entertained of a mutiny.

07:49:13.670 --> 07:49:16.790
This morning as I sat, watching the wan countenance

07:49:16.790 --> 07:49:19.730
Of my friend, his eyes half closed and his limbs

07:49:19.730 --> 07:49:23.150
Hanging listlessly, I was roused by half a dozen

07:49:23.150 --> 07:49:25.810
Of the sailors who demanded admission into the cabin.

07:49:26.710 --> 07:49:28.790
They entered, and their leader addressed me.

07:49:29.250 --> 07:49:32.010
He told me that he and his companions had been chosen

07:49:32.010 --> 07:49:34.770
By the other sailors to come in deputation to me,

07:49:34.770 --> 07:49:37.990
To make a requisition, which injustice I could not

07:49:37.990 --> 07:49:38.690
Refuse.

07:49:39.690 --> 07:49:43.290
We were immured in ice, and should probably never

07:49:43.290 --> 07:49:46.510
Escape, but they feared that if, as was possible,

07:49:46.570 --> 07:49:49.590
The ice should dissipate and a free passage be opened,

07:49:49.830 --> 07:49:52.210
I should be rash enough to continue my voyage,

07:49:52.510 --> 07:49:55.510
And lead them into fresh dangers, after which they

07:49:55.510 --> 07:49:57.470
Might happily have surmounted this.

07:49:59.010 --> 07:50:01.630
They insisted, therefore, that I should engage with

07:50:01.630 --> 07:50:04.630
A solemn promise that if the vessel should be freed,

07:50:05.110 --> 07:50:07.650
I would instantly direct my course southward.

07:50:08.750 --> 07:50:10.450
Their speech troubled me.

07:50:11.030 --> 07:50:13.810
I had not despaired, nor had I yet conceived

07:50:13.810 --> 07:50:15.790
The idea of returning if set free.

07:50:16.310 --> 07:50:19.410
Yet I could injustice, yet could I injustice,

07:50:19.650 --> 07:50:22.110
Or even impossibility, refuse this demand.

07:50:23.170 --> 07:50:25.230
I hesitated before I answered,

07:50:25.930 --> 07:50:28.770
When Frankenstein, who had at first been silent

07:50:28.770 --> 07:50:32.370
And indeed appeared hardly to have force enough to attend,

07:50:32.790 --> 07:50:34.050
Now roused himself.

07:50:34.830 --> 07:50:37.690
His eyes sparkled, and his cheeks flushed with momentary

07:50:37.690 --> 07:50:38.250
Vigor.

07:50:39.130 --> 07:50:42.270
Turning towards the men, he said, What do you mean?

07:50:42.910 --> 07:50:44.910
What do you demand of your captain?

07:50:45.670 --> 07:50:48.190
Are you then so easily turned from your design?

07:50:48.930 --> 07:50:51.170
Did you not call this a glorious expedition?

07:50:51.750 --> 07:50:53.510
And wherefore was it glorious?

07:50:53.510 --> 07:50:58.030
Not because the way was smooth and placid as a southern sea,

07:50:58.410 --> 07:51:01.070
But because it was full of dangers and terror,

07:51:01.510 --> 07:51:03.010
Because at every new incident,

07:51:03.530 --> 07:51:06.550
Your fortitude was to be called forth,

07:51:06.850 --> 07:51:08.650
And your courage exhibited,

07:51:09.210 --> 07:51:11.410
Because danger and death surrounded it,

07:51:11.570 --> 07:51:13.710
And these you were to brave and overcome.

07:51:15.150 --> 07:51:18.070
For this it was glorious, and for this it was

07:51:18.070 --> 07:51:19.270
An honorable undertaking.

07:51:19.270 --> 07:51:22.290
You were hereafter to be hailed

07:51:22.290 --> 07:51:24.150
As the benefactors of your species,

07:51:24.690 --> 07:51:28.070
Your names adored as belonging to the brave men

07:51:28.070 --> 07:51:30.310
Who encountered death for honor,

07:51:30.650 --> 07:51:32.070
And the benefit of mankind.

07:51:32.730 --> 07:51:36.030
And now, behold, with the first imagination of danger,

07:51:36.230 --> 07:51:39.710
Or, if you will, the first mighty and terrific trial

07:51:39.710 --> 07:51:42.010
Of your courage, you shrink away,

07:51:42.150 --> 07:51:44.650
And are content to be handed down as men

07:51:44.650 --> 07:51:47.810
Who had not strength enough to endure cold imperil.

07:51:48.950 --> 07:51:51.390
And so poor souls were chilly

07:51:51.390 --> 07:51:53.830
And returned to their warm firesides.

07:51:54.630 --> 07:51:57.110
Why, that requires not this preparation.

07:51:57.610 --> 07:51:59.350
Ye need not have come thus far,

07:51:59.450 --> 07:52:01.970
And dragged your captain to the shame of a defeat,

07:52:02.230 --> 07:52:03.950
Merely to prove yourself cowards.

07:52:04.630 --> 07:52:07.450
Oh, be men, or be more than men.

07:52:07.750 --> 07:52:10.590
Be steady to your purposes, and firm as a rock.

07:52:10.590 --> 07:52:13.650
This ice is not made of such stuff

07:52:13.650 --> 07:52:15.230
As your hearts may be.

07:52:15.770 --> 07:52:18.210
It is mutable and cannot withstand you.

07:52:18.590 --> 07:52:22.130
If you say that it shall not, do not return to your families

07:52:22.130 --> 07:52:24.950
With the stigma of disgrace marked on your brows.

07:52:25.270 --> 07:52:28.110
Return as heroes who have fought and conquered,

07:52:28.830 --> 07:52:32.070
And who know not what it is to turn back,

07:52:33.130 --> 07:52:34.590
Turn their backs on the foe.

07:52:36.430 --> 07:52:38.170
He spoke this with a voice

07:52:38.170 --> 07:52:40.830
So modulated to the different feelings

07:52:40.830 --> 07:52:43.110
Expressed in his speech, with an eye

07:52:43.110 --> 07:52:45.950
So full of lofty design and heroism,

07:52:46.650 --> 07:52:48.730
That can you wonder that these men were moved?

07:52:49.250 --> 07:52:52.350
They looked at one another and were unable to reply.

07:52:53.130 --> 07:52:53.850
I spoke.

07:52:54.890 --> 07:52:57.830
I told them to retire and consider of what had been said,

07:52:58.250 --> 07:52:59.890
That I would not lead them farther north

07:52:59.890 --> 07:53:02.050
If they strenuously desired the contrary,

07:53:02.050 --> 07:53:04.250
But that I hoped that, with reflection,

07:53:04.390 --> 07:53:05.730
Their courage would return.

07:53:07.570 --> 07:53:10.650
They retired, and I turned towards my friend,

07:53:10.770 --> 07:53:13.850
But he was sunk in languor,

07:53:14.710 --> 07:53:16.330
And almost deprived of life.

07:53:17.830 --> 07:53:20.130
How all this will terminate, I know not.

07:53:21.310 --> 07:53:23.550
But I had rather die than return shamefully,

07:53:23.890 --> 07:53:25.290
My purpose unfulfilled.

07:53:26.270 --> 07:53:27.990
Yet I fear such will be my fate.

07:53:27.990 --> 07:53:31.390
The men, unsupported by ideas of glory and honor,

07:53:31.630 --> 07:53:33.970
Can never willingly continue to endure

07:53:33.970 --> 07:53:35.090
Their present hardship.

07:53:38.390 --> 07:53:40.710
September 7th. The die is cast.

07:53:41.190 --> 07:53:43.770
I have consented to return if we are not destroyed.

07:53:44.410 --> 07:53:47.290
Thus are my hopes blasted by cowardice and indecision.

07:53:47.990 --> 07:53:50.430
I come back ignorant and disappointed.

07:53:51.450 --> 07:53:54.290
It requires more philosophy than I possess

07:53:54.290 --> 07:53:56.510
To bear this injustice with patience.

07:54:01.950 --> 07:54:03.070
September 12th.

07:54:03.070 --> 07:54:03.810
It is past.

07:54:03.930 --> 07:54:05.170
I am returning to England.

07:54:05.530 --> 07:54:07.710
I have lost my hopes of utility and glory.

07:54:08.150 --> 07:54:09.290
I have lost my friend.

07:54:10.070 --> 07:54:13.810
But I will endeavor to detail these bitter circumstances to you,

07:54:13.830 --> 07:54:16.810
My dear sister, and while I am wafted towards England

07:54:16.810 --> 07:54:19.170
And towards you, I will not despond.

07:54:20.430 --> 07:54:22.870
September 9th. The ice began to move,

07:54:22.870 --> 07:54:25.870
And roarings like thunder were heard at a distance,

07:54:26.810 --> 07:54:28.910
As the island split and cracked

07:54:29.950 --> 07:54:31.330
In every direction.

07:54:34.570 --> 07:54:36.350
We were in the most imminent peril,

07:54:36.670 --> 07:54:38.230
But as we could only remain passive,

07:54:38.330 --> 07:54:41.470
My chief attention was occupied by my unfortunate guest,

07:54:41.670 --> 07:54:43.950
Whose illness increased in such a degree

07:54:43.950 --> 07:54:46.570
That he was entirely confined to his bed.

07:54:47.670 --> 07:54:50.210
The ice cracked behind us and was driven

07:54:50.210 --> 07:54:52.570
With force towards the north.

07:54:53.230 --> 07:54:54.970
A breeze sprung from the west,

07:54:55.650 --> 07:54:58.690
And on the 11th the passage towards the south

07:54:59.210 --> 07:55:00.610
Became perfectly free.

07:55:01.090 --> 07:55:04.530
When the sailors saw this, and that their return to the native country

07:55:04.530 --> 07:55:07.510
Was apparently assured, a shout of tumultuous joy

07:55:07.510 --> 07:55:10.030
Broke from them, loud and long continued.

07:55:11.090 --> 07:55:13.690
Frankenstein, who was dozing, awoke and asked

07:55:13.690 --> 07:55:14.990
The cause of the tumult.

07:55:14.990 --> 07:55:18.370
They shout, I said, because they will soon

07:55:18.370 --> 07:55:19.330
Return to England.

07:55:21.130 --> 07:55:22.710
Do you then really return?

07:55:23.690 --> 07:55:26.270
Alas, yes, I cannot withstand their demands.

07:55:26.470 --> 07:55:28.870
I cannot lead them unwillingly to danger.

07:55:29.010 --> 07:55:29.910
I must return.

07:55:31.010 --> 07:55:32.870
Do so, if you will, but I will not.

07:55:33.650 --> 07:55:36.490
You may give up your purpose, but mine is assigned to me

07:55:36.490 --> 07:55:37.950
By heaven, and I dare not.

07:55:37.950 --> 07:55:41.990
I am weak, but surely the spirits who assist my vengeance

07:55:41.990 --> 07:55:44.190
Will endow me with sufficient strength.

07:55:45.590 --> 07:55:47.910
Saying this, he endeavored to spring from the bed,

07:55:48.130 --> 07:55:49.930
But the exertion was too great for him.

07:55:50.270 --> 07:55:52.470
He fell back and fainted.

07:55:53.910 --> 07:55:55.950
It was not long before he was restored,

07:55:56.110 --> 07:55:59.530
And I often thought that life was entirely extinct.

07:56:02.130 --> 07:56:04.030
At length he opened his eyes,

07:56:04.370 --> 07:56:07.350
He breathed with difficulty, and was unable to speak.

07:56:07.350 --> 07:56:10.430
The surgeon gave him a composing draft,

07:56:11.470 --> 07:56:13.730
And ordered us to leave him undisturbed.

07:56:14.070 --> 07:56:16.950
In the meantime, he told me that my friend

07:56:16.950 --> 07:56:19.070
Had certainly not many hours to live.

07:56:20.810 --> 07:56:22.650
His sentence was pronounced,

07:56:22.910 --> 07:56:25.650
And I could only grieve and be patient.

07:56:26.710 --> 07:56:28.470
I sat by his bed, watching him.

07:56:28.650 --> 07:56:31.010
His eyes were closed, and I thought he slept.

07:56:32.090 --> 07:56:34.630
But presently he called to me in a feeble voice,

07:56:35.950 --> 07:56:38.010
And bidding me come near, said,

07:56:38.470 --> 07:56:42.810
Alas, the strength I relied on is gone.

07:56:43.570 --> 07:56:45.990
I feel that I soon shall die,

07:56:46.590 --> 07:56:48.890
And he, my enemy and persecutor,

07:56:49.090 --> 07:56:50.390
May still be in being.

07:56:51.470 --> 07:56:54.210
Think not, Walton, that in the last moments

07:56:54.210 --> 07:56:57.210
Of my existence I feel that burned hatred

07:56:57.210 --> 07:57:00.550
And ardent desire of revenge I once expressed,

07:57:00.890 --> 07:57:03.530
But I feel myself justified in desiring

07:57:03.530 --> 07:57:04.930
The death of my adversary.

07:57:06.010 --> 07:57:08.010
During these last days I have been occupied

07:57:08.010 --> 07:57:09.930
In examining my past conduct,

07:57:11.030 --> 07:57:12.530
Nor do I find it blamable.

07:57:14.290 --> 07:57:16.730
In a fit of enthusiastic madness I created

07:57:16.730 --> 07:57:19.810
A rational creature and was bound towards him

07:57:19.810 --> 07:57:21.910
To assure, as far as was in my power,

07:57:21.970 --> 07:57:23.750
His happiness and well-being.

07:57:24.490 --> 07:57:27.130
This was my duty, but there was another

07:57:27.130 --> 07:57:29.370
Still paramount to that.

07:57:30.070 --> 07:57:32.870
My duties towards the beings of my own species

07:57:32.870 --> 07:57:34.770
Had greater claims to my attention,

07:57:35.270 --> 07:57:37.210
Because they included a greater proportion

07:57:37.210 --> 07:57:39.110
Of happiness or misery.

07:57:40.850 --> 07:57:43.550
Urged by this view, I refused,

07:57:43.810 --> 07:57:46.770
And did right in refusing to create a companion

07:57:46.770 --> 07:57:47.970
For the first creature.

07:57:49.070 --> 07:57:51.630
He showed unparalleled malignity

07:57:51.630 --> 07:57:54.390
And selfishness in evil.

07:57:56.970 --> 07:57:58.210
He destroyed my friends.

07:57:59.250 --> 07:58:00.630
He devoted to destruction

07:58:00.630 --> 07:58:03.850
Beings who possessed exquisite sensations,

07:58:04.170 --> 07:58:05.290
Happiness and wisdom.

07:58:05.930 --> 07:58:08.950
Nor do I know where this thirst for vengeance may end,

07:58:09.410 --> 07:58:12.750
Miserable himself, that he may render no other wretched.

07:58:13.270 --> 07:58:14.290
He ought to die.

07:58:15.010 --> 07:58:18.170
The task of this destruction was mine, but I have failed.

07:58:18.170 --> 07:58:22.310
When actuated by selfish and vicious motives,

07:58:23.810 --> 07:58:25.130
I asked you to undertake

07:58:25.130 --> 07:58:26.810
My unfinished work,

07:58:27.170 --> 07:58:29.630
And I renew this request now,

07:58:29.910 --> 07:58:33.030
When I am only induced by reason and virtue.

07:58:38.370 --> 07:58:40.450
Yet I cannot ask you to renounce

07:58:40.450 --> 07:58:43.490
Your country and friends to fulfill this task.

07:58:44.310 --> 07:58:46.250
And now that you are returning to England,

07:58:48.130 --> 07:58:50.990
You will have little chance of meeting with him,

07:58:51.310 --> 07:58:53.310
But the consideration of these points

07:58:53.310 --> 07:58:56.150
And the well-balancing of what you may esteem

07:58:56.150 --> 07:58:57.950
Your duties, I leave to you.

07:58:58.450 --> 07:59:01.050
My judgment and ideas are already disturbed

07:59:01.050 --> 07:59:02.590
By the near approach of death.

07:59:03.450 --> 07:59:06.190
I dare not ask you to do what I think right,

07:59:06.710 --> 07:59:08.950
For I may still be misled by passion.

07:59:10.650 --> 07:59:13.210
That he should live to be an instrument of mischief

07:59:13.210 --> 07:59:15.970
Disturbs me in other respects this hour,

07:59:16.430 --> 07:59:18.650
When I momentarily expect my release

07:59:18.650 --> 07:59:21.850
Is the only happy one which I have enjoyed for several years.

07:59:22.910 --> 07:59:24.570
The forms of the beloved dead

07:59:24.570 --> 07:59:27.290
Flip before me, and I hasten to their arms.

07:59:27.910 --> 07:59:29.190
Farewell, Walton.

07:59:30.290 --> 07:59:32.110
Seek happiness in the tranquility,

07:59:32.870 --> 07:59:35.350
And avoid ambition, even if it be only

07:59:35.350 --> 07:59:38.050
The apparently innocent one of distinguishing yourself

07:59:38.050 --> 07:59:39.350
In science and discoveries.

07:59:40.430 --> 07:59:41.950
Yet why do I say this?

07:59:42.610 --> 07:59:45.030
I have myself been blasted in these hopes.

07:59:46.050 --> 07:59:47.350
Yet another may succeed.

07:59:49.590 --> 07:59:51.890
His voice became faint as he spoke,

07:59:52.070 --> 07:59:54.030
And at length, exhausted by his effort,

07:59:54.250 --> 07:59:55.610
He sunk into silence.

07:59:56.510 --> 07:59:58.510
About half an hour afterwards,

07:59:58.650 --> 08:00:00.750
He attempted again to speak, but was unable.

08:00:00.750 --> 08:00:03.110
He pressed my hand feebly,

08:00:03.790 --> 08:00:05.390
And his eyes closed forever,

08:00:06.070 --> 08:00:08.390
While the irradiation of a gentle smile

08:00:08.390 --> 08:00:10.090
Passed away from his lips.

08:00:11.850 --> 08:00:13.810
Margaret, what comment can I make

08:00:13.810 --> 08:00:16.530
On the untimely extinction of this glorious spirit?

08:00:17.230 --> 08:00:18.930
What can I say that will enable you

08:00:18.930 --> 08:00:20.770
To understand the depth of my sorrow?

08:00:21.650 --> 08:00:23.090
All that I should express

08:00:23.090 --> 08:00:24.710
Would be inadequate and feeble.

08:00:25.350 --> 08:00:26.330
My tears flow.

08:00:27.250 --> 08:00:29.270
My mind is overshadowed by a cold,

08:00:29.370 --> 08:00:30.610
A cloud of disappointment.

08:00:31.790 --> 08:00:33.470
But I journey towards England,

08:00:34.270 --> 08:00:36.350
And I may there find consolation.

08:00:38.590 --> 08:00:41.350
I am interrupted. What do these sounds pretend?

08:00:41.930 --> 08:00:44.190
It is midnight, the breeze blows fairly,

08:00:44.730 --> 08:00:47.010
And the watch on deck scarcely stir.

08:00:48.230 --> 08:00:50.610
Again there is a sound as of a human voice,

08:00:50.730 --> 08:00:53.170
But horser. It comes from the cabin

08:00:53.170 --> 08:00:55.510
Where the remains of Frankenstein still lie.

08:00:56.150 --> 08:00:58.870
I must arise and examine. Good night, my sister.

08:01:00.770 --> 08:01:03.350
Great God, what a scene has just taken place!

08:01:03.830 --> 08:01:05.950
I am yet dizzy with remembrance of it.

08:01:07.290 --> 08:01:09.330
I hardly know whether I shall have the power

08:01:09.330 --> 08:01:12.250
To detail it, yet the tale which I have recorded

08:01:12.250 --> 08:01:14.170
Would be incomplete without this final

08:01:14.170 --> 08:01:17.130
And wonderful catastrophe. I enter the cabin

08:01:17.130 --> 08:01:20.590
Where lay the remains of my ill-fated and admirable friend.

08:01:22.530 --> 08:01:24.310
Over him hung a form

08:01:24.310 --> 08:01:26.510
Which I cannot find words to describe,

08:01:26.950 --> 08:01:29.310
Gigantic in stature, yet uncouth

08:01:29.310 --> 08:01:31.030
And distorted in its proportions.

08:01:31.830 --> 08:01:34.530
As he hung over the coffin his face was concealed

08:01:34.530 --> 08:01:38.030
By long locks of ragged hair, but one vast hand

08:01:38.030 --> 08:01:40.730
Was extended in colour and apparent texture

08:01:40.730 --> 08:01:43.650
Like that of a mummy. When he heard the sound

08:01:43.650 --> 08:01:45.930
Of my approach he ceased to utter exclamations

08:01:45.930 --> 08:01:48.530
Of grief and horror and sprung towards the window.

08:01:49.310 --> 08:01:52.190
Never before did I behold a vision

08:01:52.190 --> 08:01:55.750
So horrible as his face, of such loathsome

08:01:55.750 --> 08:01:58.250
Yet appalling hideousness.

08:01:58.790 --> 08:02:02.190
I shut my eyes involuntarily and endeavoured

08:02:02.190 --> 08:02:04.950
To recollect what were my duties with regard

08:02:04.950 --> 08:02:08.190
To this destroyer. I called on him to stay.

08:02:08.190 --> 08:02:11.210
He paused, looking on me with wonder

08:02:11.210 --> 08:02:13.690
And again turning towards the lifeless form

08:02:13.690 --> 08:02:17.030
Of his creator, he seemed to forget my presence

08:02:17.030 --> 08:02:20.390
And every feature and gesture seemed instigated

08:02:20.390 --> 08:02:23.190
By the wildest rage of some uncontrollable

08:02:23.790 --> 08:02:24.310
Passion.

08:02:26.310 --> 08:02:29.190
That is also my victim, he exclaimed.

08:02:31.130 --> 08:02:32.830
In his murder my crimes

08:02:32.830 --> 08:02:35.770
Are consummated. The miserable series

08:02:35.770 --> 08:02:38.990
Of my being is wound to its close.

08:02:42.010 --> 08:02:43.570
That is also my victim,

08:02:43.570 --> 08:02:46.490
He exclaimed. In his murder

08:02:46.490 --> 08:02:48.950
My crimes are consummated.

08:02:49.890 --> 08:02:52.290
The miserable series of my being

08:02:52.290 --> 08:02:54.030
Is wound to its close.

08:02:55.350 --> 08:02:56.950
O Frankenstein,

08:02:57.550 --> 08:02:59.950
Generous and self-devoted being,

08:03:01.190 --> 08:03:02.410
What does it avail

08:03:02.410 --> 08:03:06.570
That I now ask thee to pardon me?

08:03:07.070 --> 08:03:09.450
I, who irretrievably

08:03:09.450 --> 08:03:12.450
Destroyed thee by destroying all thou lovest,

08:03:13.590 --> 08:03:15.830
Alas, he is cold.

08:03:16.870 --> 08:03:18.690
He cannot answer me.

08:03:20.430 --> 08:03:22.270
His voice seemed suffocated

08:03:22.270 --> 08:03:25.070
And my first impulses, which had suggested

08:03:25.070 --> 08:03:27.870
To me the duty of obeying the dying request

08:03:27.870 --> 08:03:30.350
Of my friend in destroying his enemy

08:03:30.350 --> 08:03:32.450
Were now suspended by a mixture

08:03:32.450 --> 08:03:34.170
Of curiosity and compassion.

08:03:35.410 --> 08:03:36.990
I approached this tremendous being.

08:03:37.230 --> 08:03:39.790
I dared not again raise my eyes to his face.

08:03:40.010 --> 08:03:42.170
There was something so scarring and unearthly

08:03:42.170 --> 08:03:43.330
In its ugliness.

08:03:45.910 --> 08:03:48.870
I attempted to speak, but the words

08:03:48.870 --> 08:03:51.370
Died away on my lips. The monster continued

08:03:51.370 --> 08:03:54.350
To utter wild and incoherent self-reproaches.

08:03:54.350 --> 08:03:57.730
At length I gathered resolution

08:03:57.730 --> 08:04:00.730
To address him in a pause of the tempest

08:04:00.730 --> 08:04:01.570
Of his passion.

08:04:03.670 --> 08:04:06.650
Your repentance, I said, is now superfluous.

08:04:06.950 --> 08:04:09.010
If you had listened to the voice of conscience

08:04:09.010 --> 08:04:11.070
And heeded the strings of remorse

08:04:11.070 --> 08:04:14.010
Before you had urged your diabolical vengeance

08:04:14.010 --> 08:04:16.930
To this extremity, Frankenstein would yet have lived.

08:04:19.210 --> 08:04:20.710
And do you dream?

08:04:20.710 --> 08:04:21.690
Said the demon.

08:04:23.030 --> 08:04:25.870
Do you think that I was then dead to agony and remorse?

08:04:26.610 --> 08:04:29.070
He, he continued pointing to the corpse,

08:04:29.770 --> 08:04:32.570
He suffered not in the consummation of the deed.

08:04:33.070 --> 08:04:36.430
Oh, not the ten thousandth portion

08:04:36.430 --> 08:04:38.730
Of the anguish that was mine during the lingering

08:04:38.730 --> 08:04:40.350
Detail of its execution.

08:04:42.030 --> 08:04:44.350
A frightful selfishness hurried me on

08:04:44.350 --> 08:04:48.190
While my heart was poisoned with remorse.

08:04:49.990 --> 08:04:52.070
Think you that the groans

08:04:52.070 --> 08:04:55.030
Of Clairvaux were music to my ears?

08:04:56.850 --> 08:04:58.490
My heart was fashioned

08:04:58.490 --> 08:05:01.530
To be susceptible of love

08:05:01.530 --> 08:05:04.670
And sympathy, and when wretched

08:05:04.670 --> 08:05:06.890
By the misery of vice and hatred

08:05:06.890 --> 08:05:10.350
It did not endure the violence of the charred change

08:05:10.350 --> 08:05:13.670
Without torture such as you cannot even imagine.

08:05:15.290 --> 08:05:16.950
After the murder of Clairvaux

08:05:16.950 --> 08:05:19.730
While I returned to Switzerland heartbroken and overcome,

08:05:19.990 --> 08:05:23.330
I pitied Frankenstein, my pity amounted to horror.

08:05:23.950 --> 08:05:25.290
I abhorred myself.

08:05:26.130 --> 08:05:29.110
But when I discovered that he, the author at once

08:05:29.110 --> 08:05:32.410
Of my existence and of its unspeakable torments

08:05:32.410 --> 08:05:34.070
Dared to hope for happiness,

08:05:34.630 --> 08:05:38.190
That while he accumulated wretchedness and despair upon me

08:05:38.190 --> 08:05:41.350
He sought his own enjoyment in feelings and passions

08:05:41.350 --> 08:05:45.130
From the indulgence of which I was forever barred,

08:05:45.130 --> 08:05:48.210
Then impotent envy and bitter indignation

08:05:48.210 --> 08:05:52.090
Filled me with an insatiable thirst for vengeance.

08:05:53.470 --> 08:05:54.950
I recollected my threat

08:05:55.870 --> 08:05:58.410
And resolved that it should be accomplished.

08:05:59.190 --> 08:06:01.090
I knew that I was preparing myself

08:06:01.090 --> 08:06:03.950
For a deadly torture, but I was the slave

08:06:03.950 --> 08:06:07.430
Not the master of an impulse

08:06:07.430 --> 08:06:10.410
Which I detested, yet I could not disobey.

08:06:11.970 --> 08:06:14.630
Yes, when she died,

08:06:15.030 --> 08:06:16.550
Nay, then I was not miserable.

08:06:17.710 --> 08:06:20.830
I had cast off all feelings, subdued all anguish

08:06:20.830 --> 08:06:23.250
To riot in the excess of my despair.

08:06:24.610 --> 08:06:26.830
Evil, thencefore, became my good.

08:06:28.770 --> 08:06:31.770
Urged thus far, I had no choice

08:06:31.770 --> 08:06:34.190
But to adapt my nature to an element

08:06:34.190 --> 08:06:35.970
Which I had willingly chosen.

08:06:36.790 --> 08:06:39.430
The completion of my demonical design

08:06:39.430 --> 08:06:43.110
Became an insatiable passion, and now it has ended.

08:06:43.730 --> 08:06:45.790
There is my last victim.

08:06:48.950 --> 08:06:52.190
I was at first touched by the expression of his misery,

08:06:53.030 --> 08:06:55.170
Yet when I called to mind what Frankenstein

08:06:55.170 --> 08:06:58.130
Had said of his powers of eloquence and persuasion,

08:06:58.910 --> 08:07:01.150
And when I again cast my eyes

08:07:01.150 --> 08:07:03.390
On the lifeless form of my friend,

08:07:04.190 --> 08:07:06.430
Indignation was rekindled within me.

08:07:07.330 --> 08:07:09.670
Wretch, I said, it is well that you come here

08:07:09.670 --> 08:07:12.050
To whine over the desolation that you have made.

08:07:12.510 --> 08:07:14.810
You throw a torch into a pile of buildings,

08:07:15.350 --> 08:07:17.610
And when they are consumed you sit among the ruins

08:07:17.610 --> 08:07:20.490
And lament the fall, hypocritical fiend.

08:07:20.870 --> 08:07:24.870
If he whom you mourn still lived, still would he be the object.

08:07:25.070 --> 08:07:27.070
Again would he become the prey

08:07:27.070 --> 08:07:29.050
Of your accursed vengeance.

08:07:29.730 --> 08:07:31.850
It is not pity that you feel.

08:07:32.330 --> 08:07:35.990
You lament only because the victim of your malignity

08:07:35.990 --> 08:07:38.150
Is withdrawn from your power.

08:07:41.010 --> 08:07:42.850
Oh, it is not thus,

08:07:43.110 --> 08:07:45.170
Not thus interrupted the being.

08:07:46.190 --> 08:07:48.830
Yet such must be the impression conveyed to you

08:07:48.830 --> 08:07:51.970
By what appears to be the purport of my actions.

08:07:52.790 --> 08:07:55.410
Yet I seek not a fellow feeling in my misery.

08:07:56.230 --> 08:07:58.210
No sympathy may I ever find.

08:08:00.350 --> 08:08:03.730
When I first sought it, it was the love of virtue,

08:08:04.530 --> 08:08:06.550
The feelings of happiness and affection,

08:08:07.490 --> 08:08:09.130
With which my whole being overflowed

08:08:09.650 --> 08:08:11.390
That I wished to be participated.

08:08:12.710 --> 08:08:15.550
But now that virtue has become to me a shadow,

08:08:16.070 --> 08:08:18.090
And that happiness and affection are turned

08:08:18.090 --> 08:08:19.850
Into bitter and loathing despair,

08:08:20.450 --> 08:08:22.230
In what should I seek for sympathy?

08:08:23.190 --> 08:08:25.130
I am content to suffer alone,

08:08:25.130 --> 08:08:27.870
While my suffering shall endure.

08:08:28.570 --> 08:08:31.070
When I die, I am well satisfied

08:08:31.070 --> 08:08:33.410
That abhorrence and opprobrium

08:08:33.910 --> 08:08:35.210
Should load my memory.

08:08:37.550 --> 08:08:39.950
Once my fancy was soothed

08:08:39.950 --> 08:08:43.190
With dreams of virtue, of fame, and of enjoyment.

08:08:43.930 --> 08:08:46.690
Once I falsely hoped to meet with beings who,

08:08:46.890 --> 08:08:49.450
Pardoning my outward form, would love me

08:08:49.450 --> 08:08:50.850
For the excellent qualities

08:08:50.850 --> 08:08:52.830
Which I was capable of unfolding.

08:08:53.790 --> 08:08:56.990
I was nourished with high thoughts of honor and devotion.

08:08:57.950 --> 08:08:59.790
But now crime has degraded me

08:08:59.790 --> 08:09:01.370
Beneath the meanest animal.

08:09:01.890 --> 08:09:04.270
No guilt, no mischief,

08:09:04.730 --> 08:09:06.590
No malignity, no misery

08:09:06.590 --> 08:09:09.450
Can be found comparable to mine.

08:09:10.630 --> 08:09:13.390
When I run over the frightful catalogue of my sins,

08:09:13.450 --> 08:09:15.710
I cannot believe that I am the same creature

08:09:15.710 --> 08:09:18.310
Whose thoughts were once filled with sublime

08:09:18.310 --> 08:09:21.210
And transcendent visions of the beauty

08:09:21.210 --> 08:09:22.650
And the majesty of goodness.

08:09:23.690 --> 08:09:25.850
But it is even so.

08:09:26.750 --> 08:09:29.230
The fallen angel becomes a malignant devil.

08:09:30.350 --> 08:09:33.050
Yet even that enemy of God and man

08:09:33.050 --> 08:09:36.510
Had friends and associates in his desolation.

08:09:37.630 --> 08:09:39.150
I am alone.

08:09:41.070 --> 08:09:43.630
You who call Frankenstein your friend

08:09:43.630 --> 08:09:46.730
Seem to have a knowledge of my crimes and his misfortunes.

08:09:47.590 --> 08:09:50.090
But in the detail which he gave you

08:09:50.090 --> 08:09:53.170
Of them he could not sum up the hours

08:09:53.170 --> 08:09:55.850
And months of misery which I endured

08:09:55.850 --> 08:09:58.090
Wasting in impotent passions.

08:09:58.930 --> 08:10:00.830
For while I destroyed his hopes

08:10:00.830 --> 08:10:03.150
I did not satisfy my own desires.

08:10:04.110 --> 08:10:06.750
They were forever ardent and craving.

08:10:08.530 --> 08:10:10.930
Still I desired love

08:10:10.930 --> 08:10:12.490
And fellowship.

08:10:13.890 --> 08:10:16.650
And I was still spurned.

08:10:17.610 --> 08:10:19.410
Was there no injustice in this?

08:10:20.430 --> 08:10:22.350
Am I to be thought the only criminal

08:10:22.880 --> 08:10:26.110
When all humankind simmed against me?

08:10:27.510 --> 08:10:29.030
Why do you not hate Felix

08:10:29.030 --> 08:10:32.930
Who drove his friend from the door with contumely?

08:10:34.030 --> 08:10:35.310
Why do you not execrate

08:10:35.310 --> 08:10:37.150
The rustic who sought to destroy

08:10:37.150 --> 08:10:39.010
The savior of his child?

08:10:39.510 --> 08:10:43.010
Nay, these are virtuous and immaculate beings.

08:10:43.190 --> 08:10:45.470
I, the miserable and the abandoned

08:10:45.470 --> 08:10:48.430
Am an abortion to be spurned at,

08:10:48.770 --> 08:10:51.650
Kicked and trampled on.

08:10:54.030 --> 08:10:55.730
Even now my blood boils

08:10:55.730 --> 08:10:57.550
At the recollection of this injustice.

08:10:58.510 --> 08:11:00.370
But it is true that I am a wretch.

08:11:00.590 --> 08:11:02.750
I have murdered the lovely and the helpless.

08:11:02.750 --> 08:11:05.330
I have strangled the innocent as they slept

08:11:05.330 --> 08:11:07.550
And grasped to death his throat

08:11:07.550 --> 08:11:11.530
Who never injured me or any other living thing.

08:11:13.550 --> 08:11:14.870
I have devoted my creator

08:11:14.870 --> 08:11:17.930
The select specimen of all that is worthy of love

08:11:17.930 --> 08:11:20.050
And admiration among men to misery.

08:11:20.790 --> 08:11:22.370
I have pursued him

08:11:22.370 --> 08:11:26.290
Even to that irredeemable ruin.

08:11:27.150 --> 08:11:30.150
There he lies, white and cold in death.

08:11:30.150 --> 08:11:33.930
You hate me, but your abhorrence cannot equal

08:11:33.930 --> 08:11:35.950
That with which I regard myself.

08:11:36.670 --> 08:11:39.450
I look on the hands which executed the deed

08:11:39.450 --> 08:11:40.750
I think of the heart

08:11:41.490 --> 08:11:44.630
In which the imagination of it was conceived

08:11:45.150 --> 08:11:48.490
And long for the moment when these hands will meet my eyes

08:11:48.490 --> 08:11:52.530
When that imagination will haunt my thoughts no more.

08:11:53.170 --> 08:11:54.930
Fear not that I shall be instrument

08:11:54.930 --> 08:11:56.290
Of future mischief.

08:11:56.290 --> 08:11:58.570
My work is nearly complete.

08:11:59.130 --> 08:12:02.230
Neither yours nor any man's death

08:12:02.230 --> 08:12:05.290
Is needed to consummate the series of my being

08:12:05.290 --> 08:12:08.310
And accomplish that which must be done.

08:12:08.590 --> 08:12:10.090
But it requires my own.

08:12:12.370 --> 08:12:14.890
Do not think that I shall be slow

08:12:14.890 --> 08:12:16.670
To perform this sacrifice.

08:12:17.510 --> 08:12:20.190
I shall quit your vessel on the ice raft

08:12:20.190 --> 08:12:21.670
Which brought me thither

08:12:21.670 --> 08:12:25.050
And shall seek the most northern extremity of the globe.

08:12:25.390 --> 08:12:27.090
I shall collect my funeral pile

08:12:27.490 --> 08:12:30.850
And consume to ashes this miserable frame

08:12:31.210 --> 08:12:32.730
That it remains.

08:12:33.570 --> 08:12:36.750
Its remains may afford no light to any curious

08:12:36.750 --> 08:12:39.650
And unhallowed wretch who would create

08:12:39.650 --> 08:12:41.170
Such another as I have been.

08:12:41.990 --> 08:12:45.530
I shall die. I shall no longer feel the agonies

08:12:45.530 --> 08:12:47.070
Which now consume me

08:12:47.070 --> 08:12:51.350
Or be the prey of feelings unsatisfied yet unquenched.

08:12:52.390 --> 08:12:53.250
He is dead

08:12:53.250 --> 08:12:55.290
Who called me into being

08:12:55.970 --> 08:12:57.710
And when I shall be no more

08:12:57.710 --> 08:13:01.630
The very remembrance of us both will speedily vanish.

08:13:02.750 --> 08:13:04.930
I shall no longer see the sun or stars

08:13:04.930 --> 08:13:07.870
Or feel the winds play on my cheeks.

08:13:08.570 --> 08:13:12.010
Light, feeling and sense will pass away

08:13:12.750 --> 08:13:14.470
And in this condition

08:13:15.250 --> 08:13:17.350
Must I find my happiness.

08:13:20.690 --> 08:13:21.770
Some years ago

08:13:21.770 --> 08:13:22.930
When the images

08:13:23.470 --> 08:13:26.750
Which this world affords first opened upon me

08:13:26.750 --> 08:13:29.250
When I felt the cheering warmth of summer

08:13:29.250 --> 08:13:33.030
And heard the rustling of the leaves and the warbling of the birds

08:13:33.030 --> 08:13:35.410
And these were all to me

08:13:35.410 --> 08:13:37.530
I should have wept to die.

08:13:38.310 --> 08:13:40.790
Now it is my only consolation

08:13:40.790 --> 08:13:44.650
Polluted by crimes and torn by the bitterest remorse

08:13:44.650 --> 08:13:48.070
Where can I find rest but in death?

08:13:50.370 --> 08:13:50.970
Farewell

08:13:51.610 --> 08:13:55.250
I leave you and in the last of the humankind

08:13:55.970 --> 08:13:57.670
Whom these eyes

08:13:57.670 --> 08:13:59.510
Will ever behold.

08:14:00.290 --> 08:14:01.810
Farewell, Frankenstein

08:14:01.810 --> 08:14:06.110
If thou were yet alive and yet cherished a desire of revenge against me

08:14:06.110 --> 08:14:10.090
It would be better satiated in my life than in my destruction

08:14:10.090 --> 08:14:12.410
But it was not so

08:14:12.410 --> 08:14:14.570
Thou didst not seek my extinction

08:14:14.970 --> 08:14:17.610
That I might not cause greater wretchedness

08:14:17.610 --> 08:14:21.410
And if yet in some mode unknown to me thou hadst not ceased

08:14:21.410 --> 08:14:24.990
To think and feel thou wouldst not desire against me

08:14:24.990 --> 08:14:27.250
A vengeance greater than that which I feel

08:14:28.090 --> 08:14:29.650
Blasted as thou wert

08:14:29.650 --> 08:14:33.270
My agony was still superior to thine

08:14:33.270 --> 08:14:35.430
For the bitter sting of remorse

08:14:35.430 --> 08:14:38.230
Will not cease to rankle in my wounds until death

08:14:38.230 --> 08:14:39.750
Shall I close them forever

08:14:42.030 --> 08:14:45.250
But soon, he cried with sad and solemn enthusiasm

08:14:45.250 --> 08:14:47.250
I shall die

08:14:47.250 --> 08:14:49.550
And what I now feel

08:14:50.530 --> 08:14:52.470
Be no longer felt

08:14:53.410 --> 08:14:56.910
Soon these burning miseries will be extinct

08:14:57.670 --> 08:15:00.670
I shall ascend my funeral pile

08:15:01.510 --> 08:15:02.150
Triumphantly

08:15:03.290 --> 08:15:07.050
And exult in the agony of the torturing flames

08:15:09.450 --> 08:15:11.850
The light of that conflagration

08:15:13.070 --> 08:15:14.870
Will fade away

08:15:15.590 --> 08:15:18.530
My ashes will be swept into the sea by the winds

08:15:18.530 --> 08:15:21.690
My spirit will sleep in peace

08:15:21.690 --> 08:15:23.770
Or if it thinks

08:15:24.670 --> 08:15:26.950
It will not surely think thus

08:15:28.410 --> 08:15:28.970
Farewell

08:15:31.710 --> 08:15:34.030
He sprung from the cabin window

08:15:34.030 --> 08:15:36.950
As he said this, upon the ice raft

08:15:36.950 --> 08:15:38.550
Which lay close to the vessel

08:15:39.650 --> 08:15:42.050
He was soon borne away by the waves

08:15:42.050 --> 08:15:44.710
And lost in darkness and distance

08:15:47.610 --> 08:15:48.730
The end

08:15:58.470 --> 08:15:58.550
Thanks for watching
